<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Webpage_Construct.html</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BACKGROUND="../Gifs/whtmarb.jpg"><H1><CENTER>Welcome to the Webpage Construction page<BR><IMG SRC="../Gifs/cynus2.GIF" WIDTH="185" HEIGHT="80" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"ALIGN="BOTTOM"> </CENTER></H1><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="../Gifs/eyeslineleft.gif2" WIDTH="582" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER><H4><CENTER><A NAME="anchor138405"></A><TABLE BORDER=5 WIDTH="80%" HEIGHT="5" CELLPADDING=5 CELLSPACING=3><TR> <TD ALIGN = "CENTER"><A HREF="#anchor120206">Preview</A></TD> <TD ALIGN = "CENTER"><A HREF="#anchor26259">Step1 - Download Programs</A></TD> <TD ALIGN = "CENTER"><A HREF="#anchor116054">Step2 - Prewrite</A></TD> </TR> <TR> <TD ALIGN = "CENTER"><A HREF="#anchor139220">Step3 - Drafting</A></TD> <TD ALIGN = "CENTER"><A HREF="#anchor139603">Step4 - Edit</A></TD> <TD ALIGN = "CENTER"><A HREF="#anchor139891">Step 5 -Publish</A></TD> </TR> </TABLE> </CENTER></H4><P><CENTER><BR><IMG SRC="../Gifs/eyeslineright.gif" WIDTH="582" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER><H1><CENTER><A NAME="anchor120206"></A>Preview of this site</CENTER></H1><B>This site describes how to create a web page for your developmental program.Included are five steps from <A HREF="#anchor26259">getting the software</A>you need, to <A HREF="#anchor116054">prewriting</A>, to <A HREF="#anchor139220">drafting</A>,to <A HREF="#anchor139603">editing</A>, to <A HREF="#anchor139891">publishing</A>.Included are several sites to download software, utilities, and resourcesto build effective web pages.</B> <H1><CENTER><HR>Web Page Construction</CENTER></H1><B>The following are useful steps to help you construct a Web page. Realizethat you don't have to download all of these files/programs. Only downloadthose that are relevant to your needs.</B> <BR><HR><H2><A NAME="anchor26259"></A>Step 1 - Get all the Programs you will need</H2><H3>Examples of WWW in action</H3><DL>  <DD>There are lots of applications where the WWW has been used in highereducation. Go visit some <A HREF="http://moss.sonic.net/comprod/business_solutions/education/stories/index.html">examples</A>of these at the <I>Netscape Navigator</I> homepage. </DL><H3>Public domain and shareware</H3><DL>  <DD>Begin with downloading public domain and shareware for Mac and IBM-PC(and compatible) hardware. These sites contain those utilities you willneed particuarly compression programs (e.g., Stuffit Expander or DeZip)that are typically necessary when downloading software from the WWW. <BR><BR>  <DD>- for <A HREF="http://ftp.sunet.se/ftp/pub/mac/">Mac</A> <BR>- for <A HREF="http://ftp.sunet.se/ftp/pub/pc/">IBM-PC</A> (and compatibles)  <DD>- general <A HREF="http://ftp.sunet.se/">archived</A> collection ofMac and PC software </DL><H3>Browsers </H3><DL>  <DD>You will need to download a browser. I assume you have one if youare looking at this screen. There are non-graphical browsers like <I>Lynx</I>and graphical browsers like<I> Netscape Navigator</I> or <I>Internet Explorer</I>, among others. <BR><BR>  <DD>- <A HREF="http://moss.sonic.net/comprod/business_solutions/education/products_pricing/free_software.html">NetscapeNavigator 3.0 </A>(free to educational institutions) <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.microsoft.com/ie/msie.htm">Internet Explorer 2.0</A>(free to educational institutions) <BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Netscape Helper Programs</H3><DL>  <DD>Next, you will need what are called helper programs to be able toview <B>graphic</B> (GIF, JPEG), <B>audio</B> (AU, .WAV, or AIFF), and <B>video</B>(MPEG, AVI, or QT) files you find on the WWW. A great overview of all typesof helper files is located at<A HREF="http://www.matisse.net/files/formats.html">Common Internet file formats.</A> Also, an excellent overview of which multimediayou need for the PC is <A HREF="http://ac.dal.ca/~dong/contents.html">MultimediaFormats on the Internet </A>by Allison Zang. These acronyms represent: </DL><UL>  <LI>GIF (Graphical Interface Format for graphic images)   <LI>JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group - graphic files which are smallerin size and usually better quality)   <LI>AU (poorest quality audio usually at 8 bit though 11 bit is available;for both platforms)   <LI>.WAV (Microsoft Widows' audio file format)   <LI>AIFF (Mac audio file format, though not common on WWW)   <LI>MPEG (like JPEG, good quality video, though memory intensive)   <LI>AVI (Microsoft Widows' video file format)   <LI>QT (Apple's QuickTime available for both platforms) </UL><H3>Graphics: </H3><DL>  <DD>You will need to download a helper program to view graphic files.Download the appropriate one for your platform:<BR><BR>  <DD>- excellent list of lists of graphic icons is located at <A HREF="http://gagme.wwa.com/~boba/masters1.html#10">WebMasters</A><BR>- <A HREF="http://dragon.acadiau.ca/~giles/HTML_Editor/Documentation.html">GIFConverter</A> for Mac<BR>- <A HREF="http://www.med.cornell.edu/jpegview.html">JPEGview</A> for Mac  <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/PCTOOLS/pc_helpers.html">LviewPro</A> for PC <BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Audio: </H3><DL>  <DD>You will also need to download a helper program to hear audio files.Download the appropriate one for your platform:<BR><BR>- <A HREF="http://voyager.paramount.com/VoyagerMenu.html">Star Trek Voyager</A>- nice example of audio and video on the WWW   <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.realaudio.com/products/player2.0.html">RealAudio</A>for both platforms   <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.support.apple.com/pub/apple_sw_updates/US/Macintosh/system_sw/Other%20System%20Software/Sound_Manager_3.1.hqx">SoundManager</A> for Mac   <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/PCTOOLS/pc_helpers.html">SpeakerDriver</A> for PC   <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/PCTOOLS/pc_helpers.html">wplany</A>for PC   <DD>- audio <A HREF="http://www.netaxs.com/people/dmorgen/audio.html?">software</A>for PC </DL><H3>Video: </H3><DL>  <DD>You will need to download a helper program to view video files. Downloadthe appropriate one for your platform:<BR><BR>- go to Rob's Multimedia Lab for <A HREF="http://www.acm.uiuc.edu/rml/">software</A>for Mpeg, QT sample <A HREF="http://www.acm.uiuc.edu/rml/">weather</A> GIFsand movies, as well as sample <A HREF="http://www.neog.com/mbc/teg.html">TV</A>clips <BR>- several helper files including Sparkle, Fetch, Eudora, JPEGView, StuffitExpander can be found at the <A HREF="http://www.info.globalvillag.com/gcweb/software.mac.internet.html#300">GlobalVillage</A> page<BR>- <A HREF="http://qtvr.quicktime.apple.com/sw/sw.html">QuickTime VR</A>is available for either platform - also nice examples of virtual reality  <DD>- <A HREF="http://hyperarchive.lcs.mit.edu/HyperArchive/Archive/gst/mov/sparkle-245.hqx">Sparkle</A>for Mac   <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/PCTOOLS/pc_helpers.html">MPEGPLAY</A>for PC <BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Overview of the World Wide Web (WWW)</H3><DL>  <DD>Now you are ready to begin creating your web pages. If you haven'texplored the WWW, you might want to start with these nice overviews documentingthe history of the WWW, how it has grown, and its various components. Hereare a few overviews.<BR><BR>  <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/intro_tools.html">Universityof Toronto</A> <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.webcom.com/html/starting_www.html">Web Communications'</A>Guide to Publishing on the Web <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.learnthenet.com/">Essential Internet Home Page </A><BR>- <A HREF="http://www.eit.com/web/www.guide/">A Guide to CyberSpace</A></DL><H3>Web Page Templates</H3><DL>  <DD>A useful place to start building Web pages is to use templates. Filling-in-the-blanksyou can create a web page. <BR><BR>  <DD>- <A HREF="http://www-pcd.stanford.edu/mogens/intro/templates.html#TEMPLATES">StanfordUniversity</A> templates <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.utexas.edu/model">University of Texas </A>model homepages <BR>- Bob Allison's <A HREF="http://gagme.wwa.com/%7Eboba/masters1.html">WebMasters</A> is an excellent overview of constructing a web page <BR>- as is the University of Minnesota's Web 66 <A HREF="http://web66.coled.umn.edu/Cookbook/contents.html">ClassroomInternet Cookbook Server</A> <BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Introduction to HTML</H3><DL>  <DD>If you decide to use html editors, you will need to understand thehtml code. The following are tutorials on the html language. <BR><BR>  <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/intro_tools.html">Universityof Toronto</A> <BR>- <A HREF="http://www-pcd.stanford.edu/mogens/intro/tutorial.html">StanfordUniversity</A> <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.paradesa.com/teionline/home/home.html">Essential InternetHome Page</A> <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.webcom.com/html/tutor/html_overview.html">The Languageof the Web </A>- Web Communications HTML <BR>- <A HREF="http://wwwhome.elysian.net/~jglass/tutor/main.htm">HTML LearningCenter</A> <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.pcweek.com/eamonn/crash_course.html">Crash Coursein HTML - </A>Tutorial on multimedia hardware, software, and nice collectionsof audio and video files </DL><H3>HTML Editors</H3><DL>  <DD>If you decide to use a html editor to create your web pages, thereare several choices at the following sites. <BR><BR>  <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers/World_Wide_Web/HTML_Editors/">Yahoo</A><BR>- <A HREF="http://Akebono.stanford.edu/yahoo/Computers/World_Wide_Web/HTML_Editors/">StanfordUniversity <BR></A>- <A HREF="http://dragon.acadiau.ca/~giles/HTML_Editor/Documentation.html">HTMLEditor</A>, one html editor we would recommend for the Mac<BR>- <A HREF="http://137.143.111.3/web.weaver/about.html">WebWeaver</A>, anotherhtml editor we would recommend for the Mac <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.sausage.com/">HotDog</A>, one html editor we wouldrecommend for the PC <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.sq.com/products/hotmetal/hm-ftp.htm">HotMetal</A>,another html editor for the PC or Mac<BR>- many more editors with descriptions for both platforms are located at<A HREF="http://web.canlink.com/webdesign/#TEN">The Web Design</A> page<BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>HTML Converters</H3><DL>  <DD>If you have a word processor or a database, you might want to createmost of your web page on it and then save it as a &quot;html readable&quot;document. The following are available as shareware add-ons to your wordprocessor or database. Moreover, most of the latest versions of word processorsin either platform (like <B>MicroSoft's Word</B>,<B> Works</B>,<B> ClarisWorks</B>,<B>Hypercard</B>, <B>Word Perfect</B>,<B> etc</B>) allow you to save a fileas a &quot;html readable&quot; document. <BR><BR>  <DD>- from <A HREF="http://www.gatech.edu/word_html/release.htm">MicrosoftWord 6.0</A> <BR>- from <A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/MACTOOLS/mac_doc_man.html">QuarkXPress3.3</A> <BR>- from <A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/MACTOOLS/mac_doc_man.html">Excel</A><BR>- from<A HREF="http://www.utirc.utoronto.ca/HTMLdocs/MACTOOLS/mac_doc_man.html">a Rich Text Format</A> document <BR>- excellect collection of converters are located at <A HREF="http://web.canlink.com/webdesign/#TEN">TheWeb Design</A> page </DL><H3>Special HTML Characters (@, &#182;)</H3><DL>  <DD>Sometimes you need to use special characters to your text that youreditor/authoring program won't allow. Below is a list of the html code fora variety of special characters.   <DD><BR>  <DD>- listing of <A HREF="http://www.uni-passau.de/~ramsch/iso8859-1.html">specialcharacters</A> and html code <BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Buttons, lines, GIFs, and Image Mapping</H3><DL>  <DD>Buttons sometime are useful to navigate within and between your webpage rather than using only text links. Lines help separate major partsof your web pages. Graphic images (GIFs, JPEGs, etc) dress up your web pagesenhancing the points you are making. Image mapping allow you to link froma part of a graphic. Make sure you read the <A HREF="http://www.bham.wednet.edu/default.htm">Tenetson Web Page Design</A> as it is easy to go overboard with these. Below arecollections of buttons, lines, and graphic images.<BR><BR>- <A HREF="http://www.itec.sfsu.edu/multimedia/multimedia.html">San FranciscoState University</A>   <DD>- <A HREF="http://mech02.me.scarolina.edu/images/gifs/index.html">Universityof South Carolina</A> <BR>- nice tutorial on <A HREF="http://www.yahoo.com/Computers_and_Internet/Internet/World_Wide_Web/Programming/Imagemaps/">ImageMapping</A><BR>- <A HREF="http://ericir.syr.edu/Virtual/">AskERIC Virtual Library</A> isa nice example of Image Mapping </DL><H3>Tables</H3><DL>  <DD>Tables are a useful means of displaying information, like links toyour various web pages. Realize, however, that a table created for one browserdoes not necessarily allow it to be viewed on another browser.<BR><BR>  <DD>- tutorial on <A HREF="http://www.netscape.com/assist/net_sites/tables.html">Tables</A>from Netscape<BR>- drag and drop <A HREF="http://www.missouri.edu/~c588349/tablemaker-application.html">Tablemaker</A>for Mac <BR>- fill-in-the-blanks <A HREF="http://www.missouri.edu/~c588349/tablemaker.html">tablemaker</A>for either platform <BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Backgrounds</H3><DL>  <DD>Backgrounds enhance the look of your web pages. There are collectionsof GIF and JPEG files to use in your background at these locations.<BR><BR>- overview of html on <A HREF="http://www.netscape.com/assist/net_sites/bg/index.html">background</A>from Netscape<BR>- overview of <A HREF="http://gagme.wwa.com/%7Eboba/masters1.html#14">backgrounds</A>from Bob Allison's Web Masters <BR>- <A HREF="http://www.netcreations.com/patternland/index.html">Pattern Land</A><BR>- <A HREF="//www.meat.com/textures">Texture Land </A><BR>- <A HREF="http://www.netscape.com/assist/net_sites/bg/index.html">Solidcolor backgrounds</A> and an <A HREF="http://www.infi.net/wwwimages/colorindex.html">index</A>of the color codes for backgrounds and text </DL><H3>Forms</H3><DL>  <DD>A form allows you to get feedback or information from those viewingyour web pages. The information supplied in the form then can be added toa database to be evaluated by you and even your users. The WYSIWYG programsprovide an easy way to construct forms. The tutorials below give you a foundationon both constructing the form within a html editor, inputing the data toa data base, and making the database available to others to search.<BR><BR>- Carlos' <A HREF="http://robot0.ge.uiuc.edu/~carlosp/cs317/cft.html">tutorial</A>on forms<A HREF="http://www.webcom.com/webcom/html/tutor/forms/intro.html"><BR></A>- Stanford Univeristy tutorial on <A HREF="http://www-cs.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/mail-form">forms</A>construction <BR>- <A HREF="http://web.canlink.com/webdesign/#TEN">The Web Design</A> pagehas an excellect tutorial on tables including samples <BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Web Page Tools for HTML</H3><DL>  <DD>Other tools are useful to enhance your web pages:<A HREF="http://www.w3.org/pub/WWW/Tools/"><BR></A><BR>- excellent collection of <A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/Tools/">webpage construction tools</A> are located at W3C HTML Tools page<BR>- make your GIF images <A HREF="http://dragon.jpl.nasa.gov/~adam/transparent.html">transparent</A>here <BR>- have an introduction to transparent with downloadable programs at <A HREF="http://gagme.wwa.com/%7Eboba/masters1.html#11">WebMasters</A><BR>- adjusting the color of your text or create calendars for your web page:<A HREF="http://web.canlink.com/webdesign/tools.html">The Web Design Tools</A>page </DL><H3>CGI and Perl </H3><DL>  <DD>CGI (Common Gateway Interface) and Perl (Practical Extraction andReport Language) are hypermedia scripts that extend the capabilities ofyour browser. These allow you to add counters, searchable databases, guestbooks,calendars, etc. to your web pages. Many scripts are already written andprovided as public domain or shareware downloadable at the following locations:<BR><BR>- <A HREF="http://www.catt.ncsu.edu/users/bex/www/tutor/index.html">Tutorial</A>on CGI and Perl <BR>- nice <A HREF="http://hoohoo.ncsa.uiuc.edu/cgi/overview.html">overview</A>of CGI and a tutorial<BR>- excellect collection of CGI scripts are located at <A HREF="http://web.canlink.com/webdesign/#TEN">TheWeb Design</A> page<BR>- also for Mac at the <A HREF="http://www.macworld.com/cgi-bin/softads.pl/software/index.shtml">MacWorld</A>page<BR>- <A HREF="http://worldwidemart.com/scripts/">Matt's Script Archive</A>also has a lot of scripts that are free to download <BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Frames</H3><DL>  <DD>Frames allow you to create separate windows within your large <B>NetscapeNavigator</B> window. For example, you might want to have a table of contentsbe stationary while you scroll through another window. <BR><BR>- <A HREF="http://www.missouri.edu/~c588349/frameshop/index.html">FrameShop</A>is a frame maker from Sam Choukri<BR>- <A HREF="http://sharky.nomius.com/frames/menu.htm">Tutorial</A> on creatingframes in Netscape 2.0 <BR>- a list of tutorials on creating frames is located on the <A HREF="http://web.canlink.com/webdesign/#TEN">WebDesign</A> page </DL><H3>Java</H3><DL>  <DD><B>Java</B> is a computer language created by Sun Microsystems thatallows you to open software applications from within browsers or even whenthe applications are not physically located on your computer. <BR><BR>- <A HREF="http://www.javaworld.com/jw-04-1996/jw-04-javascript.html">JavaScript and frames <BR><BR></A><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H3>Animation</H3><DL>  <DD>A variety of software allows you to create animated buttons. Thereis even a tutorial on how to create animations. <B>Shockwave</B> allow youto create animations in <B>Macromedia Director </B>and import them to yourweb pages. <BR><BR>- Guidelines/ <A HREF="http://www.sun.com/951201/columns/alertbox/">benefits</A>of animation, video, and audio with samples<BR>- very nice <A HREF="http://members.aol.com/royalef/gifmake.htm">Animationtutorial<BR></A>- Netscape overview of <A HREF="http://www.netscape.com/assist/net_sites/bg/index.html">Animation<BR></A>- useful shareware animation program called <A HREF="http://www.macworld.com/cgi-bin/software.pl/Graphics/Software.614.html">GifBuilder</A>for Mac or <A HREF="http://pandasw.com/gifcon.htm">GIF Construction Set</A>for Windows based PCs<BR>- Windows or Mac versions of <A HREF="http://www-1.macromedia.com/Tools/Shockwave/Plugin/plugin.cgi">Shockwave</A>software </DL><H3>FTP file transfer</H3><DL>  <DD>FTP (File Transfer Protocol) provides your users the opportunity todownload software or documents from your web pages.<BR><BR>- Web Communications' <A HREF="http://www.webcom.com/webcom/help/ftp/welcome.html">tutorialon FTP </A>using their server <BR><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H4><CENTER><HR></CENTER></H4><H2><A NAME="anchor116054"></A>Step 2 - Prewrite your web pages </H2><DL>  <DD>As you begin writing your web pages, consider good design principles.A nice description are located at:<BR><BR>  <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.bham.wednet.edu/default.htm">Tenets</A> forweb page design <BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H2><HR><A NAME="anchor139220"></A>Step 3 - Draft your pages with WYSIWYGAuthoring tools</H2><DL>  <DD>Perhaps the simplest and fastest way to create web pages is to usea WYSIWYG (What You See Is What You Get) Web Page Construction Program.There are several available, but we would recommend:<BR><BR>- <A HREF="http://www.adobe.com/prodindex/sitemill/main.html">SiteMill</A>or <A HREF="http://www.adobe.com/prodindex/pagemill/main.html">PageMill</A>which is available for either platform <BR>- Web 3D or Internet Publishing Kit for PCs <BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><H4><HR></H4><H2><A NAME="anchor139603"></A>Step 4 - Edit your pages </H2><DL>  <DD>When you have a useful draft, you should check your spelling (withyour word processor or online HTML spelling checkers) and to see all yourlinks are valid. Some places you can check your links are:<A HREF="http://www-dsed.llnl.gov/documents/WWWtest.html"><BR><BR></A>- online <A HREF="http://www.unipress.com/weblint/index.html#form">spellingchecke</A>r by Weblint<BR>- <A HREF="http://www-dsed.llnl.gov/documents/WWWtest.html">Browser testpage</A> <BR>- HTML <A HREF="http://www.halsoft.com/html-val-svc/">validation</A> services<BR>- Checking <A HREF="http://www.ics.uci.edu/WebSoft/MOMspider">links</A><BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><HR><H2><A NAME="anchor139891"></A>Step 5 - Publishing your web pages</H2><DL>  <DD>Finally, you should publish your web pages. Where you do it dependsupon whether you have your own server or whether you have a commercial server.<BR><BR>- <A HREF="http://www.webcom.com/help/ftp/welcome.html%20">Uploading</A>to a commercial server   <DD>- <A HREF="http://www.submit-it.com/">Submit-It </A>to publish yourweb pages accessible by several search engines <BR><BR>  <DD><A HREF="#anchor138405"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/return.back.button.GIF"WIDTH="24" HEIGHT="25" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> return back</A></DL><HR><H5><IMG SRC="../Gifs/cynus2.GIF" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="14" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">back to <A HREF="Whole_Language.html">Whole LanguageCollege Reading Homepage</A></H5><HR><H2><CENTER>Send comments to Webmaster:</CENTER></H2><H5><CENTER><A HREF="mailto:DC02@SWT.edu"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/home.button.GIF"WIDTH="40" HEIGHT="40" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>click here to send comments</A></CENTER></H5><ADDRESS><CENTER><B>Webmaster: David C. Caverly, Ph.D.; DC&Oslash;2@SWT.edu<BR>November, 1996</B></CENTER></ADDRESS><P><CENTER></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
