<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Mission and History</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><BR><BR><IMG SRC="Images/image21.gif" WIDTH="469" HEIGHT="184" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR><BR><A HREF="DEVGRP">Home | </A><A HREF="Degreeout.html">Degree Outline | </A><A HREF="admcrit.html">AdmissionsCriteria |</A> <A HREF="finsup.html">Financial Support |</A> <A HREF="news.html">News|</A> <A HREF="Profemp.html">Professional/Employment Opportunity |</A> <A HREF="faculty.html">Faculty|</A> <A HREF="studdir.html">Student Directory |</A><BR><BR><BR><B>&quot;MISSION STATEMENT&quot; <BR><BR></B>The mission of the graduate program in Developmental and Adult Educationis to prepare graduate students to teach and lead effectively in a varietyof developmental and adult education programs in the 21st century, includingat-risk youth programs, adult basic and secondary education, and collegelearning assistance, in a way that provides graduates with tools to:<BR><BR>* Accurately and astutely assess educational and related needs,<BR><BR>* Design, implement, manage, and evaluate programs and services to effectivelyaddress those needs,<BR><BR>* Structure participatory programs involving collaboration, development,and <BR>ownership of educational ends and means by the learners themselves, and<BR><BR>* Model excellence in learning and leadership as well as in personal, professional,and<BR>community networking and development,<BR><BR>so that Developmental and Adult Education program participants can meettheir educational and <BR>related needs and goals; aspire to excellence in lifelong learning, criticalthinking, and creative <BR>problem solving; and improve the quality of their lives. <BR><BR><BR><B>Overview of M.A. Program in Developmental and Adult Education<BR><BR></B>The Developmental and Adult Education Master of Arts program prepareseducators for the administration of developmental education programs andservices. The program, offered by the Department of Educational Administrationand Psychological Services, is interdepartmental. It includes courses fromeducational administration, educational psychology, curriculum and instruction,English, reading education, mathematics, and psychology.<BR><BR>The 39-hour master's program includes 3 semester hours of supervised internshippracticum (150 clock hours minimum) in a developmental education settingin a junior/community college, four-year college/university, adult educationcenter, or industry.<BR><BR>Students in the M.A. program must write and defend a master's thesis ona developmental education topic. Graduate faculty will supervise the thesisproject.<BR><BR><BR><B>A chronology of American developmental education</B><BR><BR>1828 Yale Review laments the admission of underprepared students<BR>1836 First how-to-study manual published<BR>1849 University of Wisconsin establishes its Preparatory Department<BR>1865 Of 331 students at the University of Wisconsin, only 41 attend regularclasses<BR>1870s Preparatory departments proliferate on American campuses<BR>1894 Wellesley College establishes the first formal college developmentalcourse<BR>1916 The first How to Study course<BR>1938 Harvard and Dartmouth establish remedial reading courses<BR>1950s Large influx of underprepared students to colleges after WWII. Collegesrespond to meet their needs with college reading courses<BR>1952 Oscar Causey becomes the first president of the Southwest Reading Conference<BR>(later the National Reading Conference), exclusively devoted to collegereading<BR>1960s Open admissions policies lead to a second great influx of underpreparedstudents<BR>1970s Peer tutoring programs begin in California community colleges, leadingto formal<BR>learning centers by the end of the decade<BR>1980s Developmental courses widespread in 4-year-institutions<BR><BR>Wyatt, M. (1992). The past, present, and future need for college readingcourses<BR>in the U.S. Journal of Reading, 36 (1), 10-20.<BR><BR>From this brief history, you can see that underprepared learners have beenpresent in American post-secondary institutions for some time. The needsof these learners are being met through college preparatory and developmentalstudies programs. Another segment of society seeking developmental programsare adult learners who want to improve their skills in reading, writing,math, computers, etc. History supports an increasing need for developmentaland adult education programs. <BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><A HREF="DEVGRP">Home | </A><A HREF="Degreeout.html">Degree Outline | </A><A HREF="admcrit.html">AdmissionsCriteria |</A> <A HREF="finsup.html">Financial Support |</A> <A HREF="news.html">News|</A> <A HREF="Profemp.html">Professional/Employment Opportunity |</A> <A HREF="faculty.html">Faculty|</A> <A HREF="studdir.html">Student Directory |</A><BR><BR></BODY></HTML>
