<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>News</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><IMG SRC="Images/image26.gif" WIDTH="429" HEIGHT="175" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR><BR><A HREF="DEVGRP">Home |</A> <A HREF="deved1.html">Mission and History |</A><A HREF="Degreeout.html">Degree Outline | </A><A HREF="admcrit.html">AdmissionsCriteria |</A> <BR><A HREF="finsup.html">Financial Support |</A> <A HREF="Profemp.html">Professional/EmploymentOpportunity |</A> <A HREF="faculty.html">Faculty |</A> <A HREF="studdir.html">StudentDirectory |</A> <H3>What's New</H3>Issues in Developmental Education &amp; Adult Learning Spring 1996 Newsletterof the Graduate Program in Developmental and Adult Education <BR><BR><B>Graduate Assistantship Positions for Fall</B><BR><BR>Graduate assistantships are available for students majoring in programsin the Department of Educational Administration and Psychological Services(EAPS). Pick up the application forms from the departmental office.<BR><BR>Graduate assistant applications are due <B>annually in April</B>. Call 245-2575for further information.<BR><BR>Minimum requirements include having completed a minimum a) 12 hours of courseworkin the Developmental and Adult Education program, b) GPA of 3.5 for 12 ormore hours of Developmental and Adult Education program courses, and c)900 on the GRE (Quantitative + Verbal).<BR><BR>Graduate assistants work 10 hours per week and earn $362.00 per month. Flexiblehours are required.<BR><BR><B>Advance Registration Summer I, II, and Fall 1996</B><BR><BR>Advance registration for Summer I, II, and Fall 1996 semesters will runfrom Monday, April 1, through Friday, April 26.<BR><BR>If you have not already done so, pick up the Summer and Fall 1996 Scheduleof Classes from the Registrar's Office in J. C Kellam (JCK) or from theParking and Traffic booth on Moon Street at the entrance to JCK southsideparking.<BR><BR>Please contact me for advising as soon as possible. My office telephonenumber is 512-245-2650.<BR><BR><B>Master's Degree Candidate Sheet</B><BR><BR>Students planning for graduation in the next two semesters should pick upthe Master's Degree Candidate Sheet from the Graduate School.<BR><BR><B>Thesis Handbook/Guide</B><BR><BR>Developmental and Adult Education majors embarking on the master's thesisneed to pick up the SWT Thesis Handbook available from the Graduate School.A Developmental and Adult Education Program thesis guide is in the processof being produced. Look for an announcement of its availability in the comingweeks.<BR><BR><B>Important Dates </B><BR><BR>Registration and other important dates are listed below (Please consultthe Summer and Fall 1996 Schedule of Classes to verify all information):<BR>Early Registration - Summer I, II and Fall 1996 April 1 - April 26<BR><BR>Late Registration and Early Schedule Changes<BR><BR>Summer II June 28 - July 3<BR>Fall August 19 -27 (Late Registration)<BR>August 20 -24 (Early schedule Changes)<BR><BR>Holidays: <BR>Summer II Independence Day-Th., July 4<BR>Fall Labor Day, Monday, September 2<BR>Thanksgiving, Th-Su, Nov 27-Dec 1<BR>Finals Break, Tuesday, December 10<BR><BR>Schedule Changes:<BR>Summer II July 5 - 8<BR>Fall August 29 - Sept 3<BR><BR>Classes Begin: <BR>Summer II July 5 (EDP/EDA Classes)<BR>July 5 (same for other classes)<BR>Fall August 28 (at 5:00 p.m.)<BR><BR>Final Exams<BR>Summer I July 3 (EDP/EDA classes)<BR>July 1 (other classes)<BR>Summer II August 7 (EDP/EDA classes)<BR>August 7 (same for other classes)<BR>Fall December 11 - December 16 <BR><BR><B>Minors in Developmental Education</B><BR><BR>I welcome the opportunity to advise Developmental and Adult Education minorsconcerning the sequence for the minor and the career options made possibleas a result of this program of study. Please call: 512-245-2650<BR><BR><B>Internship<BR></B><BR>Any student who plans to begin an internship in Summer II or Fall 1996 mustsee me before registering for approval of internship plans and to removeholds on registration for internship. The same is true for anyone planningto begin a thesis during the coming 1996 semesters.<BR><BR><B>Course Listings for Summer II, Fall 1996</B><BR><BR>Below are lists of Developmental and Adult Education related courses forSummer II and Fall 1996 so that you can quickly become familiar with offerings.For the most complete and accurate information for registration, pleaseconsult the Summer and Fall 1996 Schedule of Classes.<BR><BR><BR><B>Summer II Developmental and Adult Education Related Courses<BR>Pg Course No Abbrevation Title Days/Times</B><BR>72 EDP 5399A Thesis ARR<BR>72 EDP 53299B Thesis ARR<BR>78 PE 5346 Lit &amp; Research All 2:15 - 4:15<BR>(Above section meets 7/8 to 8/2)<BR>Various electives also available (see advisor)<BR><BR><B>Fall Developmental and Adult Education Related Courses<BR>Pg Course No Abbreviation Title Days/times</B><BR>101 EDP 5371 Tch Lrng Strats M 3:30 -6:15<BR>101 EDP 5375 Underprep Lrnr M 6:30 - 6:15<BR>145 RDG 5395 Rdg to Older St W 6:30 - 6:15<BR>101 EDA 5389B Intern ARR<BR><BR><B>News!</B><BR><BR>Our e-mail addresses are EP02 (Emily Payne) and BL01 (Barbara Lyman) orEP02 al.swt.edu and BL01@ al.swt.edu.<BR><BR>Congratulations to Susan Gunn who has accepted a fellowship for doctoralstudy in English at Kent State University.<BR><BR>Watch for announcements about CASP (Conference on Academic Support Program)to be held in Austin in October. I recommend that you attend and participateas session moderators and /or presenters.<BR><BR>The second National Conference on Research in Developmental Education willbe held in Charlotte, NC this fall. May 1 is the deadline for proposals.Those of you who have completed thesis are urged to submit. See me and/or Emily Payne to obtain forms and discuss proposals for presentations.We need to showcase the excellent research being produced by our program.<BR>Developmental Education Majors, watch for a notice later concerning alternativeto the traditional required written comprehensive exam.<BR><BR>Graduate students are invited to participate as moderators in the 1996 CASP(College Academic Skills Program) conference. The conference will be heldWednesday , October 2 and Friday, October 4 in the Driskill Hotel in Austin,Texas. This will be a great opportunity to gain experience and meet peoplein the field. Responsibilities of moderators during conference sessions:introduction of self and speaker, distribution of materials, and maintainpresenters' environmental requirements. If you are interested contact LorriePowdrill at (512) 448-3301 or email at <B>1.powdrill@mail.utexas.edu</B>.<I></I>We welcome your participation.<BR><BR>Ask me about membership forms for joining state and national professionalorganizations in adult education and developmental studies. These associationsoffer research and professional development awards of up $500 each year.Join now and you will be eligible to apply for such awards to support yourthesis research.<BR><BR>Spread the word about the Graduate Program in Developmental and Adult Education.Word of mouth is our best advertising. Thank you.<BR><BR>Barbara Lyman, Ph.D<BR>Developmental and Adult Education Program<BR>Coordinator &amp; Graduate Advisor <BR><BR><BR><A HREF="DEVGRP">Home |</A> <A HREF="deved1.html">Mission and History |</A><A HREF="Degreeout.html">Degree Outline | </A><A HREF="admcrit.html">AdmissionsCriteria |</A> <BR><A HREF="finsup.html">Financial Support |</A> <A HREF="Profemp.html">Professional/EmploymentOpportunity |</A> <A HREF="faculty.html">Faculty |</A> <A HREF="studdir.html">StudentDirectory |</A> </BODY></HTML>
