</DOCHDR>
<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#fffdc0" TEXT="#900b0b"><A HREF="Mainpage.html"><IMG SRC="Graphics/image3.gif" WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="36" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=middle BORDER="0">Main page</A> | <A HREF="Background.html">Background</A>| <A HREF="Criteria.html">Criteria </A>| <A HREF="Information.html">Information</A>| <A HREF="Nominations.html">Nominations </A>| <A HREF="Winner.html">Winner</A>| <A HREF="http://www.swt.edu/">SWT page</A> <H1><CENTER><IMG SRC="Graphics/image24.gif" WIDTH="468" HEIGHT="117" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=bottom></CENTER></H1><H2><CENTER><IMG SRC="Graphics/image2.gif" WIDTH="201" HEIGHT="275" ALIGN=bottom NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>TOMAS RIVERA</CENTER></H2><B>The Tom&aacute;s Rivera Mexican American Children's Book Award<BR><BR></B>Tom&aacute;s Rivera, a native of Crystal City, Texas, is the first MexicanAmerican to have been selected Distinguished Alumnus at Southwest TexasState University. Graduating with a M.Ed. in Educational Administration(1964) after having received his B.S. degree in English (1958), both fromSWT, he went on to the University of Oklahoma where he received his Ph.D.in Romance Languages and Literature in 1969. Within ten years after receivinghis Ph.D., he quickly rose to become Chancellor of the University of California,Riverside in 1979. During this time, he published extensively in variouslocations, including his landmark novel...y no se lo trag&oacute; la tierral...<I>Andthe Earth Did Not Part </I>(1971), short stories and poetry posthumouslygathered in <I>The Harvest/la cosecha, </I>and <I>The Searchers: CollectedPoetry, </I>respectively. All of his works are now found collected withhis essays in <I>Tom&aacute;s Rivera: The Complete Works, </I>edited byJuli&aacute;n Olivares in 1992.<BR>While his life as an educator and university administrator would take himaway from his creative writing, he nevertheless traveled extensively, readingand promoting Mexican American Literature throughout the United States,Mexico, and Europe. Indeed, during his adulthood he became known as theDean of Mexican American Literature wherever he went. His writings, in bothEnglish and Spanish, mainly deal with the difficult lives of Mexican Americanmigrant farm workers, but what he emphasizes most is their enduring, highlyresilient human spirit. It should also be noted that his writings mainlyfocus on the lives of Mexican American farm working children, as his foremostand unswerving concerns were for their education and liberation from oppressiveliving conditions. As he once said, &quot;The different <I>planes </I>thatwere evolved {in the Chicano community and literature} called for the establishmentand betterment of the Chicano community above all else.&quot;<BR>Tom&aacute;s Rivera's writings have provided tremendous hope for generationsof migrants who had previously not had their lives inscribed and valorizedin literature, ensuring with his literature that their lives were not livedin vain or forgotten. His enduring presence through his literature willlong stand in the United States as an example of what the Mexican Americancommunity is capable of nurturing, educating, and producing. About our education,he said, &quot;A highly quality education provided at all levels for theHispanic communities will insure stronger individuals, and in turn a strongercommunity. This type of education must be one of our constant and basicdemands. We can only insure this education if we lead, if we become involvedin getting it, if we have in it, and most importantly, if we make it partof our prophesy.&quot;<BR>The creation of this <I>Tom&aacute;s Rivera Mexican American Children'sBook Award</I> in his honor goes a long way towards keeping alive the prophesyhe saw as part of our legacy as members of a healthy and responsible community.This children's book award will also work towards sustaining the visionhe saw for the education of Mexican Americans in the Southwest and the greaterUnited States. It is therefore unquestionably right and proper that thisaward be given in his name, his honor, his prophesy. <H2><BR>Establishing the Award</H2><BR>Although a few books about Mexican Americans are beginning to appear, theactual number is inadequate to address the needs of the children in theclassroom. It is for this reason that several faculty went last Spring (1995)to visit with John Beck, Dean of our College of Education, about establishingan award to encourage writers and authors to produce more books that authenticallyreflect the Mexican American experience so that all children may have anaccurate representation of the lives of Mexican Americans.<BR>With his support, a steering committee was formed to establish the award.The steering committee consisted of representatives from departments acrosscampus: curriculum and instruction, reading, bilingual education, educationadministration, English, children's literature, and the Center for the Studyof the Southwest. The steering committee clarified issues related to theaward and established a regional committee to determine the finalists forthe award. The regional committee consists of college and public schooleducators, community members, and students. The majority of the RegionalCommittee is Mexican American. The books chosen as finalists by this committeewill be forwarded to a National Committee of Mexican American literatureexperts for final determination of a winner. <H2>History</H2><BR>The award was established in 1995 by Southwest Texas State University toencourage authors, illustrators and publishers of books that authenticallyreflect the lives of Mexican American children and young adults in the Southwesternregion of the United States.<BR><BR>The first award for books published in 1995 is scheduled for September 16,1996.<BR><BR>Chronology of award<BR>Several individuals wrote Dean John Beck about the need to encourage greaterproduction of Mexican American literature and to explore the possibilitiesof establishing such an award.<BR><BR>Dr. Beck encouraged the pursuit of this goal and helped establish a steeringcommittee to establish parameters.<BR><BR>Individuals serving on the initial steering committee included: JenniferBattle, Mark Busby, Blandina Cardenas-Ramirez, Charles Dolezal, Judy Leavell,Jaime Mejia, Velma Menchaca, Claudia Nelson, Marilyn Olson, Cynthia Peterson,Nancy Ramos, Patrice Werner<BR><BR>The initial steering committee established a Regional Committee to screeninital recommendations of books. They also established a National Committeeto make the final choice.<BR><BR>Member of the Regional Committee included:<BR><BR>Dr. Mauricio Charpenal U.T.S.A. Professor specializing in folklore of the<BR>Southwest and children's literature, retired<BR><BR>Ms. Oralia Cortez Librarian, San Antonio Central Library<BR><BR>Ms. Lucila Garza Classroom teacher<BR><BR>Mr. Jonathan Flores SWT student <BR><BR>Mr. Ruben Garza Southside Community Center, School Board Chairman<BR><BR>Ms. Rosemary Garza Central Office, Bilingual Education, San Marcos CISD<BR><BR>Ms. Maria Garza Southwest Texas Student <BR><BR>Ms. Ofelia Vasquez Philo Former School board member<BR><BR>Mr. Phil Mendez Educator (teacher and principal), retired<BR><BR>SWT faculty regional committee members include:<BR>Jennifer Battle, Dick Holland, Judy Leavell, Sandra McCollister, Jamie Mejia,Velma Menchaca, Claudia Nelson, Nancy Ramos and Patrice Werner<A HREF="Mainpage.html"><BR><BR><IMG SRC="Graphics/image3.gif" WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="36" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0"ALIGN=middle BORDER="0">Main page</A> | <A HREF="Background.html">Background</A>| <A HREF="Criteria.html">Criteria </A>| <A HREF="Information.html">Information</A>| <A HREF="Nominations.html">Nominations </A>| <A HREF="Winner.html">Winner</A>| <A HREF="http://www.swt.edu/">SWT page</A> </BODY></HTML>
