<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#fffbbe" TEXT="#9e1211"><A HREF="Mainpage.html"><IMG SRC="Graphics/image3.gif" WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="36" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=middle BORDER="0">Main page</A> | <A HREF="Background.html">Background</A>| <A HREF="Criteria.html">Criteria </A>| <A HREF="Information.html">Information</A>| <A HREF="Nominations.html">Nominations </A>| <A HREF="Winner.html">Winner</A>| <A HREF="http://www.swt.edu/">SWT page</A> <BR><IMG SRC="Graphics/image23.gif" WIDTH="468" HEIGHT="127" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=bottom><BR><B>The Need for Mexican American Children's Literature<BR></B><BR>Multiethnic literature reflects the contributions, lifestyles, and valuesof different ethnic groups. Literature about one's own culture or ethnicgroup, helps children have a better understanding of who they are and whatcontributions the can make to this country. This type of literature alsobenefits members of other ethnic backgrounds by helping them appreciateand understand America's various racial and ethnic groups.<BR>The number of excellent books reflecting the culture, heritage, and contemporaryexperiences of America's minority population is very small. Hispanic literaturehas focused on a conglomerate of cultures from Central and South America,Cuba, Puerto Rico, Mexico, the United States and other Spanish speakingcountries. Many children's books that have focused on Hispanics are aboutthe Puerto Rican Experience and of these, many are &quot;pervaded by sexism,racism, and ethnocentric colonialism&quot;(p.6)( Nieto, 1982). Often, theauthors of these children's books were not Puerto Rican .<BR>Contemporary books about Mexican Americans are even more rare and have beenstereotypical in nature (Ramirez and Ramirez, 1994). In fact, the very fewbooks written about Mexican Americans tended to be written with the aimof helping white children sympathize with, empathize with, and tolerateMexican Americans (Wagoner, 1982). Mexican American characters mostly displayedtraditional Mexican male-female roles and lived in rural or impoverishedcircumstances. In 1967, a book was written about Spanish speaking Americans.It was titled Good Boy, Bad Boy. The message was that speaking Spanish interferedwith one's ability to become a functioning member of American Society. <BR>It is important that children see themselves represented in books. Bookssend very strong messages to children about who they are and what they canbecome. These books affect children's attitudes, beliefs and achievement.<H3>To make nominations:</H3><BR>Submissions for future awards are currently being received. Send submissionsfor books first published in 1996 to:<BR><BR>The Tom&aacute;s Rivera Mexican American Children's Book Award<BR>SWT School of Education<BR>2001 Education Building<BR>601 University<BR>San Marcos, Texas 78666<BR><BR><BR><BR><A HREF="Mainpage.html"><IMG SRC="Graphics/image3.gif" WIDTH="32" HEIGHT="36" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN=middle BORDER="0">Main page</A> | <A HREF="Background.html">Background</A>| <A HREF="Criteria.html">Criteria </A>| <A HREF="Information.html">Information</A>| <A HREF="Nominations.html">Nominations </A>| <A HREF="Winner.html">Winner</A>| <A HREF="http://www.swt.edu/">SWT page</A> </BODY></HTML>
