<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>A garden of Ideas</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#eeb7f5"><H2></H2><H2><CENTER>A Garden of Ideas<IMG SRC="Images/image6.gif" WIDTH="142" HEIGHT="109" ALIGN=middle NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><B>Helpful Hints From Teacher Fellows </B></CENTER><P>* <B>Cindy</B>: Use &quot;shower board&quot; (found at home improvementstores) as dry-erase boards.<BR><BR>* <B>Bill</B>: Keep in contact with your students' parents by sending homeweekly newsletters.<BR><BR>* <B>Kate</B>: Keep an index card for each child with the names and numbersof parents in a recipe box. Use the card to note the date and topic of eachphone conversation. <BR><BR>* <B>Lesli</B>: Use bright paper wrist bands to send notes home to parents.Staple them as bracelets around each student's wrist. <BR><BR>* <B>Shannon</B>: Use foil baking pans or other trays to hold supplies whenteaching in cooperative groups. Have these ready before the lesson. It saveslots of time! <BR><BR>*<B>Paula</B>: Let one of the student jobs be &quot;parliamentarian.&quot;This person reminds students of the rules all week.<BR><BR>*<B>Melissa</B>: At the end of every day, have the students write a sentenceor two describing exciting things about the day. Write them in a class bookand bind one each month as a class journal.<BR><BR>*<B>Jennifer</B>: Keep a baggy full of Band Aids and sterile wipes in yourteacher desk, to save kids unnecessary trips to the nurse's office. <BR><BR>*<B>Terri</B>: Let your students be responsible for taking attendance andfiling graded student papers.<BR><BR>*<B>Ashley</B>: Have your class make a &quot;community quilt.&quot; Eachchild draws a picture of what will help to make a good community, laminatethe pictures, and then string them together. Each morning you can focuson one of the areas. <BR><BR>*<B>Kim</B>: Alleviate unwanted or negative baggage to help your mind stayclear and focused.<BR><BR>*<B>David</B>: Make time for yourself. Involve yourself in activities thatYOU enjoy.<BR><BR>*<B>Margaret</B>: Make a rotating line order for your students. This keepsthe same children from always straggling in the back. The line leader ofthe day will be the caboose the next day. <H4><CENTER><BR><A HREF="FellowsHome">Home</A><A HREF="fellows%20home"> </A>/ <A HREF="Gardens">Garden</A>/ <A HREF="sprouting">Sprout</A> / <A HREF="grape">Grapevine</A> / <A HREF="Sunnydays">Sunshine</A></CENTER></H4></BODY></HTML>
