<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>PLAN</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><BODY BGCOLOR="#0015FF" TEXT="#FFFF22" LINK="#4DC1FF" VLINK="#FF0000"><H1><CENTER><IMG SRC="bookandworld.gif" WIDTH="48" HEIGHT="48" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A NAME="anchor213753"></A> P.L.A.N.</CENTER></H1><H5><CENTER><A HREF="#anchor48375">Caverly, Mandeville, &amp; Nicholson</A>,(1995)</CENTER></H5><P><CENTER><HR></CENTER><H3>P = Preview</H3><DL>  <DD>Before you begin reading, you should always PREVIEW (or survey) thetext by reading the title, subtitles, highlighted words, charts, maps, tables,and pictures, as well as the summary. As you are previewing, create a tentativesemantic map of the concepts you are finding as you see I did in the samplemap.</DL><H5><CENTER><A HREF="PLAN_text"><IMG SRC="bookandworld.gif" WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="20" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">sample text</A> <A HREF="#anchor272229"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/search.gif" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">examplesummary</A> <A HREF="PLAN_map2"><IMG SRC="../NADE/home.return.gif" WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="17" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">sample map </A></CENTER></H5><P><CENTER><HR></CENTER><H3>L = Locate</H3><DL>  <DD>Next, LOCATE on this map those concepts that you think you alreadyknow and place a checkmark next to them. Also, locate on this map thoseconcepts that you don't know and place a question mark (?) next to thoseconcepts. Again, see the example in the third window. </DL><H5><CENTER><A HREF="PLAN_text"><IMG SRC="bookandworld.gif" WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="20" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">sample text</A> <A HREF="#anchor272229"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/search.gif" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">examplesummary</A> <A HREF="#anchor213753"><IMG SRC="return.back.button.GIF" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">back to the beginningof instruction</A> <A HREF="PLAN_map2"><IMG SRC="../NADE/home.return.gif"WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="17" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">sample map </A></CENTER></H5><P><CENTER><HR></CENTER><H4>A = Add</H4><DL>  <DD>Now, you have something to read for; that is, you can read to findwhat you don't know and confirm what you do know. <BR><BR>As you are reading, ADD new branches onto your map for those ideas you didn'tknow and confirm those branches for those ideas you thought you knew. Ifyou cannot add or confirm a branch, re-read that section of text again.See how we have added branches onto this example map in the third window.</DL><H5><CENTER><A HREF="PLAN_text"><IMG SRC="bookandworld.gif" WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="20" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">sample text</A> <A HREF="#anchor272229"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/search.gif" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">examplesummary</A> <A HREF="#anchor213753"><IMG SRC="return.back.button.GIF" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">back to the beginningof instruction</A> <A HREF="PLAN_map2"><IMG SRC="../NADE/home.return.gif"WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="17" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">sample map </A></CENTER></H5><P><CENTER><HR></CENTER><H4>N = Note</H4><DL>  <DD>After reading the entire text, you should NOTE whether you satifiedyour task or purpose for reading. If you read to be able to reproduce informationon a test, try re-creating the map from memory. Check back to see whichbranches and sub-branches you left off and then try to reproduce it onceagain until you are fairly accurate.   <DD><BR>  <DD>If your purpose for reading was to reconstruct the text on an essay,then try to create a summary of the entire text in your own words. Again,check the completeness and conciseness of your summary against your map.Continue to see an example summary. </DL><H5><CENTER><A HREF="PLAN_text"><IMG SRC="bookandworld.gif" WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="20" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">sample text</A> <A HREF="#anchor272229"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/search.gif" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">examplesummary</A> <A HREF="#anchor213753"><IMG SRC="return.back.button.GIF" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">back to the beginningof instruction</A> <A HREF="PLAN_map2"><IMG SRC="../NADE/home.return.gif"WIDTH="17" HEIGHT="17" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">sample map </A></CENTER></H5><P><CENTER><HR></CENTER><H5><A NAME="anchor48375"></A>Caverly, D.C., Mandeville, T.F., &amp; Nicholson,S.A. (1995). PLAN: A study reading strategy for informational text. <I>Journalof Adolescent and Adult Literacy,39 </I>(3), 190-199.</H5><HR><H3><A NAME="anchor45233"></A><A NAME="anchor272229"></A>Summary of Article</H3><DL>  <DD>There are three philosophical positions from which you could teachcollege reading: rationalist, empiricist, or phenomenologicalist. The firstargues all knowledge about reading is already in the student's head. Alla teacher need do is provide the opportunity to discover it through freeinquiry. Thus, instruction occurs through the environment created by theteacher and the good will of the student.   <DD>The second position, empiricist, believes the mind is a blank slateinto which the teacher is to add all the &quot;correct&quot; skills thestudent needs to have to succeed. The student does not contribute to his/hereducation other than being an active recipient of information transmittedfrom the teacher. Moreover, the student has no choice as to which skillsto learn as the teacher knows best. Unless, the student learns all the necessaryskills, in order, success will not be achieved.   <DD>The third position, phenomenologicalist, argues the student will constructtheir own, personal understanding of the reading process through an opportunityto construct tentative knowledge, to compare that knowledge to other students'knowledge to adapt and confirm it, then to develop one's personal understandingof that knowledge that best fits their needs. </DL><H5><CENTER><A HREF="#anchor213753"><IMG SRC="return.back.button.GIF" WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="18" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">back to the beginningof instruction</A></CENTER></H5><H5><HR></H5><BR><BR></BODY></HTML>
