<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN"><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>GS1100 Syllabus</TITLE>   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="User-Agent: Mozilla/3.0b7Gold (Macintosh; I; PPC)"></HEAD><BODY BACKGROUND="../Gifs/whtmarb.jpg"><H2 ALIGN=CENTER><!-- Date: Saturday, September 21, 1996  5:33 PM -->FreshmanSeminar<BR>General Studies 1100<BR>Fall, 1996</H2><H4>Professor: David C. Caverly, Ph.D.<BR>Office Phone: (512) 245-3100<BR>Office: Education: 2034<BR>Office Hours: M or W, 9-10, or by appointment</H4><P>Text Required: Gordon, J. (1995). <I>The university in your life</I>.Brown &amp; Benchmark.<BR><BR><HR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Overview</H2><DD>The purpose of General Studies 1100 (Freshman Seminar) is to allowyou a chance to begin finding out <B>who </B>you are, <B>where </B>youare, <B>what </B>you will find here, and most importantly <B>why </B>youare here. In other words, at the beginning of your college experience,we have found it useful to help you come to understand our goals, yourgoals, and how the two can and must come together. To accomplish this,you will be reading, writing, and discussing a variety of issues pertinentto your needs and ours. You will be expected to spend at least six (6)hours of preparation time outside of class. This will include reading andthen writing to peers on e-mail three times per week. Together, we willcollaborate on what college can and will be for you.</DD><CENTER><P><HR></P></CENTER><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Course Objectives</H2><UL><LI>To help you discover the value for your life and the lives of thoseyou affect for having a broad liberal arts education.</LI><LI>To expand your vision of the nature and purposes of a university.</LI><LI>To awaken you to the connection between a university education andthe development of your identity as a person.</LI></UL><DL><P><HR></P></DL><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Attendance</H2><P>Since most of the information you will learn will be garnered from discussionsin class, you must attend class to do well. Toward that e, the attendancepolicy is as follows:</P><DL><DD>- 5 points for each class missed</DD><DD>+5 points for attending all classes</DD></DL><P><HR></P><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Schedule and Assignments</H2><DL><DT>This class is designed to be a collaborative discussion of outsidereadings. Without an understanding of the readings, you will not be ableto contribute to this collaboration. Late assignments will not be acceptedwithout documentation of extenuating circumstances.</DT><CENTER><DT><ALIGN=CENTER></DT></CENTER><CENTER><TABLE BORDER=3 CELLSPACING=3 CELLPADDING=3 ><CAPTION></CAPTION><TR><TD><B>class</B></TD><TD><B>topic</B></TD><TD><B>reading/assignments</B></TD></TR><TR><TD>1</TD><TD>Introduction, syllabus, requirements</TD><TD>get copy of student ID</TD></TR><TR><TD>2</TD><TD>Why GS 1100?</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Whitman (p. 1), Schmitt (p. 12)</TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>3</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>How do you access the information highway?</TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>meet in EDU 2051</ALIGN=CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>4,5</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>How do you develop a sense of self?</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Saroyan, Hampl, Value Shield paper, Practice Journal1 due</ALIGN=CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>6</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>What does it mean to think?</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Clinchy, Morgan, Journal 2</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><CENTER><P><BR></P></CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>7</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Sex, Drugs, and Rock and Roll?</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>McInerney, Olds</ALIGN=CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>8, 9</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>What is the world going to be like?</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Daggett, LeGuin, Journal 3</ALIGN=CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>10, 11</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>How might you assimilate others' values with yours?</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Longo, Steele, hooks, Journal 4</ALIGN=CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>12, 13</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>How does a university education change you?</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Hutchins, Peterson, Interview paper, journal 5</ALIGN=CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>14, 15</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Why do you need to be a lifelong learner?</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Conroy, Sellers, journal 6</ALIGN=CENTER></TD></TR><TR><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>16</ALIGN=CENTER></TD><TD><ALIGN=CENTER>Final</ALIGN=CENTER></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER></DL><CENTER><P><HR></P></CENTER><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Grading:</H2><DL><P><BR>Your grade in this course will be based upon the following:</P></DL><UL><LI>assignment point value Participation in class discussions ------------------20</LI><LI>Attendance------------------------------------------------------------------------10</LI><LI>Weekly Journals</LI><BLOCKQUOTE><LI>journal response-------------------------------------------------------10</LI><LI>journal reaction -------------------------------------------------------10</LI><LI>journal feedback-------------------------------------------------------10</LI><LI>Value Shield Paper----------------------------------------------------10</LI><LI>Interviews Paper------------------------------------------------------10</LI><LI>Final--------------------------------------------------------------------20</LI></BLOCKQUOTE></UL><DL><DD>total---100</DD><DD>A = 94-100</DD><DD>B = 84-93</DD><DD>C = 75-83</DD><DD>D = 65-74</DD><DD>F = &lt;65</DD></DL><CENTER><P><BR><HR></P></CENTER><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Class Participation</H2><DL><DT>Since this class centers around collaborative class discussions, youwill be expected to participate in these discussions. Your grade for thissection will be based upon the following:</DT></DL><H4>18-20 pts</H4><P>Actively participating in the class discussion; asking and answeringquestions; leading the discussion; relating the discussion to your life,your values, and your other classes; demonstrating both connected and separateknowing.</P><H4>16-17 pts</H4><P><BR>Actively participating in the class discussion; asking and answering questions;relating the discussion to your life, your values, and your other classes.</P><H4>14-15 pts</H4><P>Participating in the class discussion; relating the discussion to yourlife, your values, and your other classes.</P><H4>12-13pts</H4><P>Participating sporadically in the discussion; relating the discussionto your life, your values, and your other classes.</P><H4>&lt;11 pts</H4><P>Occasionally participating in the class discussion.<BR></P><CENTER><P><HR></P></CENTER><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Weekly Journal</H2><P><BR>You will write a weekly journal for this class. You will be respondingthree ways: First, you will be asked to respond to a weekly prompt aboutthe readings and discussion that week over e-mail. This first journal responsewill be sent to your journal group and cc: to me at my e-mail address (DC&Oslash;2).<BR><BR>Second, you will be asked to react to what your journal group wrote intheir response. This second entry will be a reaction to what your journalgroup wrote compared to what you wrote. It, too, will be cc: to me at mye-mail address (DC&Oslash;2).<BR><BR>Third, you will be asked to give feedback on your journal group's reactionby sending feedback to them. This feedback should evaluate (both positivelyand negatively) their reaction to your journal prompt and the level ofthinking in which they are engaged. It, too, will be cc: to me at my e-mailaddress (DC&Oslash;2).<BR><BR>These journal entries will: &amp;sdot; be signed on a first name basisonly, &amp;sdot; be completed on the SWT mainframe computer's e-mail system,&amp;sdot; be a thoughtful discussion of the week's topic, including whatyou have read, what you have thought, and how this fits in with your on-goingexperiences in your other classes, &amp;sdot; be a penpal discussion withyour journal group (other freshmen from another section of GS 1100) andmonitored by me (thus the copy to me).</P><P><HR></P><H3>Your grade for this journal activity will be based upon the followingcriteria:</H3><H4>27-30 pts</H4><P>Actively participating in the journal discussion; answering the promptand asking further questions; relating your answer to your life, your values,and your other classes; responding supportively to your journal group inboth the reaction and the feedback demonstrating both connected and separateknowing. 24-26 pts Actively participating in the journal discussion; relatingyour answer to your life, your values, and your other classes; respondingsupportively to your journal group in both the reaction and the feedback.</P><H4>21-23 pts</H4><P>Participating in the journal discussion; relating the discussion toyour life, your values, and your other classes; responding dispassionatelyto your journal group.</P><H4>18-20pts</H4><P>Participating sporadically in the journal discussion; relating the discussionto your life, your values, and your other classes.</P><H4>&lt;17 pts</H4><P>Occasionally participating in the journal discussion.<BR></P><CENTER><P><HR></P></CENTER><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Value Shield Paper</H2><P><BR>You will write a paper completing the value shield in the following way:<BR></P><CENTER><P><IMG SRC="../Gifs/image1.gif" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" HEIGHT=153 WIDTH=357 ALIGN=BOTTOM></P></CENTER><P>Reproduce this shield on a sheet of blank paper. Then, in spaces 1-4create a symbol to represent each of the following items: # Then, in space5 write out your life motto. Finally, in connected prose write an introductionparagraph, at least one paragraph explaining/discussing your selected symbolsand motto, and then a conclusion paragraph. This paper must be typed orbetter yet word processed.</P><P><HR></P><H3>Your grade for this paper will be based upon the following:</H3><H4>9-10 pts</H4><P>A thoughtful consideration in your selection of the symbols and motto;a thoughtful discussion of each of the symbols and your motto in your writing;coherent and cohesive discussion; free of spelling, grammar, and punctuationerrors.</P><H4>8 pts</H4><P>A thoughtful consideration in your selection of the symbols and motto;a discussion of each of the symbols and your motto in your writing; freeof spelling, grammar, and punctuation errors.</P><H4>7 pts</H4><P>A consideration in your selection of the symbols and motto; a discussionof each of the symbols and your motto in your writing; a few spelling,grammar, or punctuation errors.</P><H4>6 pts</H4><P>A selection of the symbols and motto; a discussion of each of the symbolsand your motto in your writing; several spelling, grammar, or punctuationerrors.</P><H4>&lt;5 pts</H4><P>A selection of the symbols and motto or a discussion of each of thesymbols and motto in your writing; several spelling, grammar, or punctuationerrors.<BR></P><CENTER><P><HR></P></CENTER><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Interviews Paper</H2><P><BR>A second paper you will be asked to write will be based on an interviewof a professor and of an upperclass student (either a junior or senior)and their answers to the following questions:</P><H3>Professor Questions:</H3><DL><DD>1) How did he/she choose his/her academic discipline?</DD><DD>2) What motivated him/her to teach on a college campus?</DD><DD>3) What type of student does he/she regard as &quot;ideal?&quot;</DD><DD>4) What type of students irritates him/her the most?</DD><DD>5) What is his/her &quot;philosophy of teaching&quot; or &quot;preferredteaching style?&quot;</DD></DL><H3>Upperclass student Questions:</H3><DL><DD>1) What is his/her major?</DD><DD>2) What motivated him/her to go and stay in college?</DD><DD>3) What &quot;type&quot; of professor does he/she regard as ideal?</DD><DD>4) What irritates him/her about SWT professors?</DD><DD>5) What does he/she think is most important to &quot;get out&quot;of college?</DD></DL><P><BR>After completing these interviews, complete a short paper (2-3 typewrittenor better yet word processed pages) that summarizes what each person said,how they compare and contrast, and describe what you learned in light ofthe topics discussed in this course.</P><P><HR></P><H3>Your grade for this paper will be based upon the following:</H3><H4>9-10 pts</H4><P>A thoughtful summary and comparison/contrast of the answers given byboth the student and the professor; a thoughtful discussion of their answerscompared to what you are learning in this course; coherent and cohesivediscussion; free of spelling, grammar, and punctuation errors.</P><H4>8 pts</H4><P>A summary and comparison/contrast of the answers given by both the studentand the professor; a discussion of their answers compared to what you arelearning in this course; free of spelling, grammar, and punctuation errors.</P><H4>7 pts</H4><P>A summary and comparison/contrast of the answers given by both the studentand the professor; some spelling, grammar, and punctuation errors.</P><H4>6 pts</H4><P>A summary of the answers given by both the student and the professor;several spelling, grammar, and punctuation errors.</P><H4>&lt;5 pts</H4><P>A summary of the answers given by both the student and the professor;extensive spelling, grammar, and punctuation errors.<BR></P><CENTER><P><HR></P></CENTER><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Final</H2><P><BR>The final in this course will be comprehensive and will measure your knowledgeof and reflections on the following: &amp;sdot; vocabulary from the variousreadings &amp;sdot; substantive ideas discussed in the various readings&amp;sdot; conclusions discussed in class &amp;sdot; what you have learnedin this course &amp;sdot; where you will go from here<BR><BR><HR></P><H5><IMG SRC="../Gifs/cynus2.GIF" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" HEIGHT=18 WIDTH=36 ALIGN=TOP>backto <A HREF="../../Whole_Language.html">Whole Language College Reading Homepage</A></H5><ADDRESS><HR></ADDRESS><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Send comments to Webmaster:</H2><H5 ALIGN=CENTER><A HREF="mailto:DC02@SWT.edu"><IMG SRC="../Gifs/home.button.GIF" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" HEIGHT=40 WIDTH=40 ALIGN=BOTTOM></A><BR><A HREF="mailto:DC02@SWT.edu">click here to send comments</A></H5><CENTER><ADDRESS><B>Webmaster: David C. Caverly, Ph.D.; DC&Oslash;2@SWT.edu<BR>November, 1996</B></ADDRESS></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
