<HEAD>

<TITLE>BOARD OF CENSORS</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/PARCH.GIF">

<P><B>
<HR><P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Times New Roman">BOARD OF CENSORS
<P><HR></B>
<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE=4> The Board of Censors of the Medical
Association of the State of Alabama is made up of fifteen physicians:
seven members, one from each Congressional District and five at-large
members, plus MASA's President-elect, President and Immediate
Past President.  Other officers are the Vice President, Speaker
and Vice Speaker of the College of Counsellors and House of Delegates.
 They along with the chairmen from MASA's special sections, are
encouraged to attend the Board meetings and have the privilege
of entering into discussions.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman" SIZE=4> The Board of Censors, by statute,
serves as the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners.  The seven District
Censors and the five At-Large Censors, plus the chairmen of the
four Health Department Councils also serve as the Alabama State
Committee of Public Health.  These Boards meet in Montgomery on
the third Wednesday of each month and the preceding Tuesday to
conduct business.  On the first day, the Boards break out into
three subcommittees to discuss and consider, in-depth, the items
before them.  They then make recommendations to their respective
Board and the recommendations are  voted on during the Board meeting
on the next day.  The Subcommittee on Association Affairs is made
up of five Board members and the Vice President; the Credentials
Committee of the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners is made up
of five Board members; and the State Subcommittee of Public Health
is made up of four Board members, plus the four Council chairmen.
 The Chairman of MASA's Board is free to sit-in on the Subcommittee
of his choice.</FONT>
<P><CENTER><H4>Back to <A HREF="ADM.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">Association Affairs</A></H4></CENTER>
