<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>A BRIEF HISTORY OF ALABAMA MEDICINE AND</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../pics/PARCH.GIF">

<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Times New Roman">A BRIEF HISTORY OF ALABAMA MEDICINE AND<br>
THE MEDICAL ASSOCIATION OF THE STATE OF ALABAMA
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<B>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	As far back as 1818, when Alabama was still a territory, an Indian scout from Monroe County petitioned the Territorial Assembly to establish a board of physicians to regulate medical practice.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Only a few years later, in 1823, the new Alabama General Assembly passed the first Medical Practice Act, and then met on Christmas Eve at the State Capitol in Cahaba to select the first members of the medical licensing board. This Act established the long standing Alabama tradition of physician control of the licensing function. Active physician involvement in Alabama politics was evident from the outset; William Bibb, Alabama's first Governor was a physician, as was Henry Chambers, who was elected the state's first Senator. Unfortunately, he died enroute to Washington and never took office.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Early efforts to organize Alabama's physicians were spearheaded by the Alabama Medical Society of Selma; meeting late in 1846, they passed a resolution urging a state gathering of physicians.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Dr. Albert G. Mabry, Secretary of this society subsequently wrote to the President of the Mobile Medical Society inviting them to participate in such a gathering to develop a Code of Ethics, improve medical education and establish a state lunatic asylum. It appears that only Selma and Mobile had organized medical societies at that time.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Mobile responded very favorably and sponsored the organizational meeting of 21 physicians on December 1, 1847. The group adopted a Constitution, elected officers and declared itself the Medical Association of the State of Alabama.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Selma hosted the first regular meeting of the Association in 1848 -  the same year that ten members represented Alabama at the Baltimore meeting of the recently formed American Medical Association.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	The Association was formally incorporated in 1850 by the Alabama General Assembly; members were to be known as Fellows of the Association.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	For the next several years, the Association held regular meetings and pressed on with its efforts to rid the state of quacks, establish a hospital for the insane and also a medical school. Organizing the physicians was not an easy task. MD's were widely dispersed around the state and travel was primitive and very difficult on crude roads and navigable rivers. Then, as now, physicians were an independent lot, difficult to recruit into an organization. Chronic financial problems, the collecting of dues, etc. plagued the early organizational leaders.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	In 1855, the Association published 1500 copies of its transactions to sell and hopefully stimulate potential member interest. Unfortunately, this proved to be a financial disaster. 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	The Association was pretty much dormant from 1855-1868 due to the civil war. Many physicians did serve in the Confederate forces. 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Long-term efforts of the Association to construct a state hospital for the insane at Tuscaloosa finally succeeded in 1860 with an Act of the Alabama General Assembly. Dr. Peter Bryce served as its first superintendent and his leadership and humane methods of treatment of patients became a national model.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Selma physicians again provided the leadership to reorganize the Association in 1868 when remnants of the Selma, Montgomery, Mobile and Greensboro societies met together. 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Foremost in leadership to revive and create a strong centralized organization was Dr. Jerome Cochran. Through his persistent efforts, the Constitution was completely rewritten and the Association reorganized to achieve this goal. His plan was adopted in 1873 and much of it is still found in the current Constitution and Bylaws of the Association.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	A state law implementing this plan was passed by the Alabama General Assembly in 1875. Of particular importance was the creation of state and county Boards of Health, with the Association constituted as the State Board of Health with control over county Boards. Two years later, the state's second Medical Practice Act was passed which required a Certificate of Qualification from a Board of Medical Examiners to practice medicine. The state and county Boards of Censors of the Association were designated as the Board of Medical Examiners and the Standards of Medical Practice were to be determined by the physicians in the Association. 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	In 1879, the first state appropriation for public health  ($3000) was made, and Dr. Jerome Cochran was appointed as the first state health officer. Thus in just a few years, by legislative decree, members of the Association were granted major responsibilities in setting medical standards for practice and supervising public health functions. This responsibility continues today!
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	By 1888, all county medical societies had been chartered by the Association and the last four counties had organized county health departments. 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	From a shaky start and a major reorganization, the Association grew and prospered. Membership rolls reach 1,100 by 1893.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	To honor the memory of Dr. Jerome Cochran (who died in 1896) the Association established the Jerome Cochran Lecture, to be given annually as part of the Annual Session. Since 1899, this tradition has continued and honored presenters include the famous of American medicine - the Mayo Brothers, Alton Ochsner, Paul Dudley White, Tinsley Harrison, and many others. 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	The successful structure of the Association became a national model, emulated by other medical societies. Dr. Charles Reed, AMA President in 1901 cited it as the:&quot;Incomparable Alabama Plan.&quot; 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Naturally, all political and economic interests did not approve of physician control of the licensing and public health functions and the Act was challenged in Court; however, it was upheld by the Alabama Supreme Court in 1903.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	By 1907, it was evident that there was a need to consolidate the medical examine function under one Board, rather than separate Boards for each county. The Legislature enacted this change.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	The first full-time county health department (the second in the U.S.) was established in Walker County in 1914 by Dr. Carl Grote, Sr. 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	The first issue of the Journal of the Association was published in July 1931, and since then it has served as a major source of scientific knowledge for Alabama physicians. The &quot;bon voyage&quot; box on the first page expressed hopes for a successful future; these have been certainly fulfilled.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	From the beginning of the Association, many members worked hard to develop medical educational institutions in Alabama. Today the splendid results can be seen at the University of Alabama School of Medicine in Birmingham and the University of South Alabama College of Medicine in Mobile.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	This has been a brief chronology of the Association. A history wouldn't be complete however, without a brief mention of members who have made a significant contribution to the Association.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	Our Association is proud of seven members who have served as President of the American Medical Association: Charles Pope (1854); William Baldwin (1869); J. Marion Sims (1876); John Wyeth (1902); William Gorgas (1909); Edward Cary (1932) and James McLester (1935). Many members have been leaders in various fields of medicine: 
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">J. Marion Sims - A pioneer in gynecologic surgery, particularly the repair of vesicovaginal fistula.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Josiah Nott - A noted Mobile surgeon and early advocate of the theory that yellow fever was caused by a living organism.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">William Gorgas - Conqueror of yellow fever in the building of the Panama Canal and Surgeon General of the U.S. Army.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">L. L. Hill - Montgomery surgeon who performed the first successful suture of a human heart in the United States.
<P>
</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Tinsley Harrison -  Great teacher and writer in internal medicine at the University of Alabama School of Medicine.

<P></FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">John Kirklin - World famous pioneer in the use of heart-lung machine in open heart surgery.

<P></FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	As the Association faces the future, it can look back on a remarkable record of service and achievement. Perhaps this quotation from Dr. Howard Holley's recent book,  A History of Medicine in Alabama  best sums it up:

<P></FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">	&quot;The Medical Association of the State of Alabama has remained the bastion against poorly trained practitioners, ill-advised health laws, and non-ethical practitioners. It has freely fulfilled the dreams of Dr. Jerome Cochran and his colleagues who formulated the basic Constitution more than a century ago.&quot;

<P></FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Additional References on the history of the ALabama Medicine and the Association:

<P></FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">1.	Howard Holley, MD, A History of Medicine in Alabama, University of Alabama Press, 1982

<P></FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">2.	Douglas L. Cannon, MD &quot;History of the Medical Association of the State of Alabama&quot; A series of three articles (Jan-Mar 1977) in the Journal of the Medical Association of the State of Alabama

<P></FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">3.	Howard Holley, MD, &quot;Highlights of Nineteenth Century Medicine in Alabama&quot;,  Alabama Journal of Medical Sciences, Vol.20 No.3, 1983

<P></FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">4.	Video Tape - The Association has prepared a 1/2&quot; VHS videocassette tape presenting this information in a visual format with music, pictures and narration. this tape is available for free checkout from the Association's Education Department (1-800-239-MASA) for use at medical gatherings or personal review.</FONT>
</B>
<P>
<CENTER><H4>Back to <A HREF="ADM.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">Association Affairs</A></H4></CENTER>
<SCRIPT Language = "VBScript">
<!--
