<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Weekly News</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER></P><B><FONT SIZE=6>Medical News Week<BR>
</FONT>The Medical Association of the State of Alabama</P> </B></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>News Clips</FONT>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>December 16th and 23rd<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>State's health chief seeks funding boost</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- The head of the Alabama Department of Public Health said that
he is planning to request a $13 million increase in state funds
for his department's 1988 budget. <B>Montgomery Advertiser <BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Medicaid care program called landmark</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- A landmark Medicaid program the agency calls a first step toward
managed care could dramatically alter the way the state Health
Department operates, the state health officer said. <B>Birmingham
News<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Home health care firms to merge</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- Alabama's largest home health care company is affiliating with
another home health care provider, but the move should not change
the care that thousands of patients receive throughout the state.
<B>Birmingham News <BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Medical company expands services</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- MedPartners Inc. flexed its muscles Tuesday in its international
business and some of its specialty medical services. <B>Birmingham
News 12/4<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Study: Medicaid's slowing growth means less need
for major change</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> -- The Medicaid program
may not need major changes, according to a new study that predicts
the program's growth will continue to slow into the next century.
<B>Huntsville Times 12/4<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Carraway network will bring new telemedicine to
Winfield hospital</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> -- When a doctor in
Winfield needs an immediate opinion on what a specialist sees
in a patient's X-ray, he will soon be able to have an answer within
minutes without leaving his office. <B>Journal Record 12/4<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>UAB sets purchase of Triton from JBL </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>--
The University of Alabama at Birmingham, to &quot;unify leadership
and direction of its health care enterprise,&quot; plans to purchase
the managed-care company it formed with health care executive
Jim Little. <B>Birmingham Post Herald 12/6<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Training program for doctors in need of funds,
director says</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> -- The director of Montgomery's
only training program for young doctors said the project needs
funds and he is asking the city for help to the tune of $300,000.
<B>Montgomery Advertiser 12/6<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>AMA again pushing for Medicare reform</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- The American Medical Association is unwrapping the Medicare
reform proposal that it had packed away for the 1996 election
campaign in hopes that a new Congress and a re-elected president
might be more receptive in '97. <B>Huntsville Times 12/6<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>$1M malpractice award cut to $250,000</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- The Alabama Supreme Court upheld part of a medical malpractice
judgment against a northwest Alabama doctor , but cut the damage
award from $1 million to $250,000. <B>Huntsville Times 12/7 <BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Money drives surge in home health care</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- The world revolves around money and so does health care. Insurance,
and the income it generates, says Merrill Matthews Jr., is why
home health care has shown such rapid growth in recent years.
<B>Decatur Daily 12/9<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Mandate care sparks a debate</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- It's easy to see the benefits in Congress' decision to require
insurance companies to pay for 48 hours in the hospital after
mothers give birth. Less obvious are the costs. <B>Birmingham
News 12/11<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Medicare will be a large obstacle for Clinton</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- We've all heard the old adage of &quot;what goes around, comes
around.&quot; Well, what is coming around for the Clinton administration
is Medicare reform. <B>Andalusia Star News 12/11 <BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Health panel again denies Southside surgery center</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- A proposed Southside ambulatory surgery center that wanted
to specialize in colon and rectal endoscopy was voted down Tuesday
by a state health board.<B> Birmingham News 12/11<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Study eyes heart attack treatment</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- A national study of 220,000 Medicare patients - including Alabamians
- found that heart attack victims are more likely to survive if
treated by cardiologists rather than general doctors. <B>Mobile
Press Register 12/19<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Pain relief and the law: Let doctors be doctors</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- On January 8, the U.S. Supreme Court will hear arguments on
the constitutionality of state laws that prohibit physicians from
assisting in suicides. This editorial is only indirectly about
physician assisted suicide. <B>Mobile Press Register 12/19 <BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Survey on tobacco ads questioned</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- An advertiser group and a huge tobacco company are questioning
the significance of a new survey that says most advertising agency
executives believe cigarette marketers target teens. <B>Mobile
Press Register 12/19<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Health plan: Too good to be true? </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>--
They promised that Mobile's Medicaid patients could see physicians
more often and stay healthier without spending any more taxpayer
money. <B>Mobile Press Register 12/22<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Group targets teen pregnancies</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- A group that lobbies on issues affecting the poor wants Alabama
to do more to prevent teen-age pregnancies and help teen-age mothers.
<B>Montgomery Advertiser 12/24<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>UAB names John Davis to run its HMO</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- The University of Alabama at Birmingham, which bought out its
health maintenance organization from a former Complete Health
executive, has named another ex-Complete Health executive to run
the business. <B>Birmingham Post Herald 12/24<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Health care by number may add up to patient, privacy
problems</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> -- Millions of doctors, hospitals,
health insurers and players in the medical field will be issued
a federal identification code starting next ;year as part of a
government effort to fight fraud and to simplify payments. <B>Montgomery
Advertiser 12/26<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Coalition insurance plan starts next week</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- A business coalition's closely watched new health insurance
plan will launch next week with 30,000 members. <B>Birmingham
News 12/27<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Kids having Kids</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> -- Far
too many unmarried Alabama teen-agers are having babies at great
cost to their own futures and to the state. <B>Montgomery Advertiser
12/27<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Troubling torts</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2> -- Many
commentators, including myself, have been critical over the years
of the punitive damages problem in Alabama. Much of this criticism
has derived from anecdotes - single large verdicts, sometimes
sets of large verdicts. <B>Birmingham News 12/29<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Doctor indicted again on Medicaid fraud charges</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- A Perry County doctor accused of trying to defraud the federal
government over Medicaid billings has been indicted for a second
time and his attorneys want the charges thrown out of court. <B>Montgomery
Advertiser 1/3<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>UAB offers health option</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>
-- A health maintenance organization run by the University of
Alabama at Birmingham has begun offering a new product that allows
patients to see doctors outside the HMO network. <B>Birmingham
Post Herald 1/6<BR>
</P></B></FONT>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4>Provided by<BR>
<B>Public Relations Department<BR>
</B>For copies of articles call<BR>
<B>1-800-239-6272</B></FONT> </P></CENTER>
