<HEAD>
<TITLE>Health Reform 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<CENTER><H1>THE HEALTH INSURANCE PORTABILITY AND ACCOUNTABILITY ACT OF 1996</H1>
<H2>PUBLIC LAW 104-191<BR>
(FORMERLY H.R. 3103)</H2><P></CENTER><B>
On August 28, President Clinton signed "The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996" into law.  You may have heard of the bill by its previous names during its course through the legislature, such as S. 1028, H.R. 3103, and the Kassebaum-Kennedy Bill.  The Act represents a number of important goals for the profession, including insurance portability, limitations on pre-existing condition clauses, liability protection for physician volunteers, greatly improved fraud and abuse provisions, and an MSA pilot project.<P>
You can hyperlink here to documents that are provided to improve your understanding of the bill and its impact on the practice of medicine in the United States.  We suggest first looking at the table summarizing the reform bills as they were amended in Congress.  This best illustrates the highlights of the final bill.  The Table of Contents outlines the content of the final conference report without links to the original document, giving a quick overview of the bill.  You can also view the final conference report in its entirety, complete with the AMA's comments on critical points.<P>
<A HREF="GOVKKTAB.HTM"><IMG SRC="../pics/BUTTON2.GIF" ALIGN=MIDDLE></A><A HREF="GOVKKTAB.HTM">Table Comparison of the Health Insurance Reform Bills</A><P>
<A HREF="GOVKKTOC.HTM"><IMG SRC="../pics/BUTTON2.GIF" ALIGN=MIDDLE></A><A HREF="GOVKKTOC.HTM">Public Law 104-191 Table of Contents </A>- condensed and without links.<P>
<A HREF="GOVKK.HTM"><IMG SRC="../pics/BUTTON2.GIF" ALIGN=MIDDLE></A><A HREF="GOVKK.HTM">Public Law 104-191 Final Conference Report&#42;</A> - fully expanded.<P>
<FONT SIZE=6>&#42;WARNING! </FONT>The conference report is very large and may take up to three minutes to load depending on your web browser and modem.  We suggest that after it has completely loaded you use the File Save option on your browser to save it to a file on your computer.  You may then view it while not connected to the internet by using the File Open option on your browser.  It will appear complete with a Table of Contents that will allow you to traverse the document rapidly, saving you money in connection time and preventing the further waste of paper by not having to print the contents.</B><HR>
<I>Special thanks to Jon Burkhart at the AMA for providing the original documentation for web coding by MASA!</I><HR>
