<HEAD>
<TITLE>CME CALENDAR - 1996</TITLE>
</head>
<BODY background="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<HR>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>
<I>INFOSOLUTIONS</I> AGREEMENT MODIFIED: LIABILITY
QUESTIONS REMAIN<BR></FONT>
</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<font size=3><b>
<P>
Following a series of meetings with MASA's Third Party Grievance
Task Force and representatives of the state chapter of Medical
Group Management Association, Blue Cross/Blue Shield has announced
changes to the InfoSolutions contract and medical database regulations
designed to implement the medical records database portion of
the InfoSolutions medical information network. The medical records
database will receive, store and make available to subsequent
treating physicians medical information from other treatment providers,
pharmacies, laboratories and hospitals. (See related article,
<I><B>Alabama MD</B></I> November 30, 1995)
<P>
Modifications to the provider contract include the addition of
specific responsibilities on the Company for database security;
details on the composition and utilization of an advisory group
for establishing policies and procedures on operational aspects
of the database; modification of the 60 day termination provision
to allow termination of a physician only for substantive breach
of contract or database regulations or any tort or criminal act
related to the InfoSolutions agreement; an agreement that the
Company will not provide patient or provider specific names or
addresses to any catalog, clearing house, or other commercial
marketing entity for the purpose of establishing a customer or
client relationship; and provisions for appeals mechanisms through
binding arbitration. Changes to the database regulations include
provisions for certification of vendor software systems; a three
year maintenance period for requests and response activity within
the InfoSolutions database; an agreement that Blue Cross will
retain all historical medical information within the medical database;
an agreement to provide at least one year notification prior to
ceasing support for previously released software formats standards
to the database; adoption by Blue Cross of the National Bureau
of Standard's Data Encryption Standard as the encryption algorithm
for the database; an agreement to periodically conduct independent
data security and controls review of the database and report the
findings to the advisory group; and an agreement to receive advice
and input from the advisory group for developing reporting methodologies.
<P>
Liability and risk management concerns voiced by physician representatives
were not specifically addressed in the modifications to the provider
agreement or database regulations. Under the general provisions
of the InfoSolutions contract, each party is responsible for compliance
with the database regulations, including the prevention of unauthorized
access and unauthorized disclosure of database information. In
addition, each party is responsible for acts or omissions of its
own agents or employees but not those of the other party to the
contract. Each party is responsible for any claim or legal proceeding
against it including costs and legal fees. 
<P>
Company officials worked with Mutual Assurance to develop release
forms and patient information to address liability concerns. In
a January letter to Blue Cross/Blue Shield officials, Mutual Assurance
stated:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
We have reviewed the proposed InfoSolutions physician-patient
letter (copy attached) and the &quot;Medical Data Base Authorization
and Acknowledgment Form&quot; printed on the reverse side thereof.
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
Based on our review of these items and our several discussions
with you and Mr. Dick Jones, it is our judgment that the professional
liability coverage provided by Mutual Assurance to physicians
will not be adversely affected by an insured's participation in
this InfoSolutions program, provided the physician-patient letter
is tendered to each patient and the consent form (i.e. the &quot;Authorization&quot;
form) is executed by each of the participating physician's patients
prior to treatment. Consequently, from the standpoint of professional
liability insurance coverage for our insureds, Mutual Assurance
has no objection to this program. 
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
In a further effort to attempt to assess a physician's potential
exposure to liability under this contract and the availability
of insurance coverage, the Task Force directed the following question
to each of the principle medical malpractice insurers in the state:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
Would a physician insured by your company who is sued for damages
arising out of allegations of breach of confidential relations,
unauthorized release of medical information or other acts related
to his or her participation in the InfoSolutions program be afforded
a defense and coverage for any resulting judgment? Please assume
for the purposes of the question that the physician insured has
complied with all obligations under the InfoSolutions contract
and database regulations, provided all the recommended patient
information and secured the necessary patient consents. 
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
In further response to the question posed by the Task Force, Mutual
Assurance stated:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
Our insurance coverage... is not adversely affected.... by the
medical records storage medium be it microfiche, paper, or electronic.
While we cannot definitively address hypothetical coverage questions,
we would anticipate that most such disputes would arise in a situation
in which the patient has voluntarily and appropriately provided
the insured with access to confidential medical information. In
that situation, coverage would turn on whether the insured's alleged
breach of confidentiality occurred in the course of delivering
medical care.
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
Coastal Insurance Enterprises provided the following response:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
Any legal liability assumed by a physician or others protected
under our policy as a result of any contract or agreement is <U>specifically
excluded</U>. The only exception is where a physician has agreed
to hold an entity harmless for liability resulting from the physician's
conduct. In this situation, we can provide coverage for the hold
harmless language in the contract for an additional fee. However,
we do not cover any other provision in any contract other than
those arising out of the practice of medicine. 
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
In reviewing Blue Cross/Blue Shield's InfoSolutions contract,
this is strictly a contract drafted for their benefit. It has
nothing to do with the practice of medicine which we cover. It
appears that the contract has been created mainly for the benefit
of Blue Cross to gather information. If Blue Cross is concerned
about its liability, it should purchase a policy to cover it for
actions arising out of this contract. It appears that Blue Cross
wants the physicians to supply the information to Blue Cross,
pay for all liability coverage with Blue Cross incurring no risk.
Our answer to (MASA'S) question is no.
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
A preliminary reply from St. Paul Fire and Marine Insurance Company
to the Task Force's question is as follows:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
...an insured physician who is sued for allegations of breach
of confidential relations, unauthorized release of medical information
or other acts related to his or her participation in InfoSolutions
would be afforded both a defense and coverage for any resulting
judgments. The only qualification being that the inappropriate
disclosure be considered a professional service within the definition
included with our policy. It would be difficult to envision a
set of circumstances where that would not be the case. 
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
St. Paul indicated that it was having the contract documents reviewed
by their Loss Control and Legal Departments and would be providing
the Association with a formal response in the near future. 
<P>
MAG Mutual Insurance Company, a Georgia based malpractice insurer
which recently began offering policies in Alabama, responded to
the Task Force question in the following manner:
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
Under MAG Mutual's hysician and surgeons professional liability
policy (&quot;Policy&quot;) an insured is covered: 1.) for his/her
direct liability for providing or withholding medical professional
services to patients; and 2.) for his/her vicarious liability
for the providing or withholding of medical professional services
to patients by any person for whose acts the physician is legally
responsible. 
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>
Inherit in the treatment of patients are requests for release
of medical records or information. Therefore, the release of medical
information is considered a medical professional service for which
we would provide coverage based on the allegations as stated above.
However, whether or not we would cover allegations based on insureds'
&quot;other acts related to his or her participation in the InfoSolutions
program&quot; would depend on what these other acts are; i.e.,
what specific &quot;other acts&quot; were alleged and the facts
and circumstances surrounding such acts. An example of a possible
related &quot;other act&quot; which is not covered under our policy
is fee-for-service quality assurance activities. Therefore, an
insured who is paid by Blue Cross/Blue Shield to assist in quality
of insurance activities such as developing applicable guidelines
for the InfoSolutions program, may not have coverage for any claims
based on these activities.
</I></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
At the February 21, 1996 meeting of the Board of Censors, Blue
Cross/Blue Shield's CEO, Gene Thrasher confirmed that participation
in InfoSolutions, including the medical records database, is a
requirement for participation in the Company's new statewide primary
care network. Mr. Thrasher told the Board that the efficiencies
which the Company hopes will be generated by the medical records
database are important to maintain the Company's competitive position
as new managed care alternatives enter the market place. He announced
that invitations directed to primary care physicians to participate
in the statewide PCN will be mailed in the near future. Currently,
approximately 120 physicians are enrolled in the Mobile area and
144 primary care physicians serve beneficiaries in the Auburn/Opelika
and Tuscaloosa areas. 
<P>
The modifications which resulted from the series of meetings with
Blue Cross representatives were generally viewed by the Task Force
as a positive response to physicians' concerns. Nevertheless,
physicians are encouraged to carefully study the InfoSolutions
contract and the accompanying database regulations as well as
other information provided by Blue Cross about the program. Implementation
of the requirements imposed by the InfoSolutions contract will
affect each physician or group of physicians in a different manner,
depending upon size, specialty and the degree to which the practice
has begun a conversion to electronic medical records. For these
reasons, it is important that physicians and physician groups
make individual decisions concerning participation in the InfoSolutions
medical records database. The Medical Association neither endorses
nor opposes physician participation. Because there continue to
be questions which remain unanswered concerning potential liability
and malpractice insurance coverage, physicians are encouraged
to direct coverage questions to their individual malpractice or
other insurance carriers.
</b></font><P>
