<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>RETENTION OF PHYSICIAN OFFICE MEDICAL RECORDS IN ALABAMA
</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<hr>
<P>
<CENTER><B><font size=5>RETENTION OF PHYSICIAN OFFICE<br>
 MEDICAL RECORDS IN ALABAMA
</font></B></CENTER>
<p>
<hr>
<P>
<font size=4>
A physician should retain his or her office medical records for
as long as necessary to treat the patient and to insure the record
is available in the event of a liability claim.  The Association's
general recommendation is that office medical records be retained
for a period of ten (10) years from the date that the patient
was last treated.  The physician may choose to maintain his or
her office medical records for a longer period of time.  The statute
of limitation for medical liability claims in Alabama, as currently
interpreted by the courts, provides a bar to medical liability
claims after a period of two (2) years, or two years from the
date of the discovery of the injury, but not more than four (4)
years, except in the case of minors for whom the statute of limitations
may be up to eight (8) years.
<P>
Physicians who transfer their records on retirement or in connection
with the sale of a medical practice should insure by an agreement
in writing that they will be permitted access to the record in
the event of a medical liability claim.
</font><P>
