<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Current News</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<SCRIPT Language = "VBScript"><!--
SUB ClickMe_OnClick()
   parent.mainup.location.href="LEGFRAM.HTM"
END SUB
--></SCRIPT><BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>MASA Joins in Opposing Physician-Assisted
Suicide<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
MASA has joined with the American Medical Association, the American
Nurses Association, the American Psychiatric Association and forty-one
other medical organizations in a &quot;Friend of the Court&quot;
brief filed with the U.S. Supreme Court regarding two physician-assisted
suicide cases that will be decided next year. The appeal involves
decisions of the Ninth U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals and the Second
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals striking down laws which prohibit
physician-assisted suicide in Washington and New York. Among the
state medical societies joining MASA and the AMA on the brief
opposing physician-assisted suicide are Arkansas, Georgia, Louisiana,
Mississippi, Tennessee, and North Carolina. Specialty organizations
include the American Academy of Pain Medicine, the American Academy
of Orthopedic Surgeons, the American Academy of Neurology and
the College of American Pathologists. 
<P>
In the introduction to the brief the AMA summarizes its fundamental
opposition to physician-assisted suicide as follows: 
<P>
&quot;The ethical prohibition against physician-assisted suicide
is a cornerstone of medical ethics. Its roots are as ancient as
the Hippocratic Oath that a physician 'will neither give a deadly
drug to anybody if asked for it, nor... make a suggestion to this
effect', and the merits of the ban have been debated repeatedly
in this nation since the late nineteenth century. More recently,
the AMA has re-examined and re-affirmed the ethical prohibition
against physician-assisted suicide in 1977, 1988, 1991, 1993 and
1996. Physician-assisted suicide remains 'fundamentally incompatible
with the physician's role as healer, would be difficult or impossible
to control, and would impose serious societal risks'..... Other
health care professions have similar tenants.... Physicians and
nurses have the ability to respond sensitively to the concerns
of serious ill and dying patients and can meet their patients'
needs without acceding to requests for suicide.&quot;
<P>
The case is expected to be argued before the U.S. Supreme Court
after the first of the year. <BR>
<H4 ALIGN=CENTER><CENTER>Back to <A HREF="LEG.HTM" TARGET="_parent">Legal Update</A></CENTER>
</H4>
