<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PRN Policy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<hr>
<P>
<CENTER><B><font size=6>
Physicians Recovery Network Policy
</font></B></CENTER>
<P>
<hr>
<P><B>
Impairment in physicians is an issue of sufficient importance to be 
addressed by organized medicine in order to assure accountability to
the public and to maintain high professional standards.  In 1982 MASA
created the Impaired Physicians Program, a confidential information and
referral service for physicians experiencing problems with alcohol abuse,
drug dependence or mental or physical illnesses that impair their ability
to practice medicine. 
<BR><BR>
In 1989, a contract was entered into between MASA and the State Board 
of Medical Examiners to develop the Alabama Impaired Physicians Program to 
operate under the direction of the Alabama Impaired Physicians Committee.  
Beginning October 1, 1991, a full-time medical director was appointed to the 
program.  In 1992, to reflect its positive goals, the program's name was 
changed to the Physicians Recovery Network (PRN).
<BR><BR>
<H2><I>
MASA's Position
</I></H2>
MASA believes that impairment among physicians is an illness deserving 
attention and that physicians have an ethical responsibility to take an active
role in helping their colleagues in this regard.  MASA supports the PRN for 
physicians experiencing problems of alcohol abuse, drug dependence, or mental
or physical illnesses and endorses the program to encourage physicians with 
such problems into an evaluation and treatment setting in lieu of disciplinary 
action as long as patient safety can be assured.  Physicians who are aware of 
a colleague's impairment have an ethical responsibility to refer him or her to
the PRN.
<BR><BR>
<H2><I>
History
</I></H2>
Adopted 1985 Annual Session. Revised 1995 Annual Session.
</B><P>
<CENTER><H4>Back to <A HREF="PRNX.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">Physicians Recovery Network.</A></H4></CENTER>
