<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PRN Education Programs</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<hr>
<P>
<CENTER><B><font size=6>
PRN Educational Programs<BR>
</font></B></CENTER>
<P>
<hr>
<p>
<B>
The Physicians Recovery Network promotes the early identification, 
evaluation, and treatment of physicians who may be impaired as a result of 
mental/emotional illness, or substance abuse/dependence.  The success rate of 
physicians returning to practice is in excess of 90%.  One of the mechanisms that 
helps PRN to achieve its goals is education.  PRN is available in Alabama to 
present the following educational programs:
<DL>
<DT><I>
1)  Recognizing Signs and Symptoms of Substance Abuse in the Physician</I>
<DD><B>
By the time job performance is affected, substance abuse/dependence is well 
advanced.  This program underscores the importance of heeding early 
warning signs.</B>
<DT><BR><I>
2)  Guidelines for the Development of Hospital Wellness Programs</I>
<DD><B>
Outlines the structure of hospital wellness programs and illustrates how they 
encourage confidential early referrals of physicians who may be getting into 
difficulty.<BR></B>
<DT><BR><I>
3)  Preventing Allegations of Professional Sexual Misconduct</I>
<DD><B>
Presents a surprising view into the patient's perception of what may be 
considered "inappropriate" as well as good-sense protocol to prevent 
"misunderstandings."<BR></B>
<DT><BR><I>
4)  Managing the Behaviorally Disruptive Physician </I>
<DD><B>
A confidential program designed to help hospital executive and credentialing 
committees deal productively with this difficult issue.<BR></B>
<DT><BR><I>
5)  Early Identification of the Impaired Physician and its Positive Impact 
on the Medical Marriage  </I>
<DD><B>
A program directed toward the Medical Alliance which illustrates how early 
identification of physician impairment significantly improves the affected 
marriage.<BR></B>
<DT><BR><I>
6)  Recognition of Patient Drug-Seeking Behavior</I>
<DD><B>
Inappropriate prescribing can cast a shadow over an otherwise good medical 
practice.  This program explains how to identify and contend with the 
drug-seeking patient.</DL><BR></B>
<P>                            
