<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fractal Medicine Essay</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
Alabama M.D. for 6/27. Essay, revised 6/26

<CENTER><H2><I>The Fractal Geometry <BR>Of Medical Practice</I></H2></CENTER> 

<H6 ALIGN=CENTER>By William H. McDonald</H6>
 
<BLOCKQUOTE>"We shape our tools; thereafter, they shape us."<P>

<I>- Marshall McLuhan (1911-1980),<BR>
 Communications Theorist.</I></BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>

Somewhere in East Africa 2,000,000 years ago, they say, homo habilis, a distant and extinct relative, fashioned the first crude stone tool.<P>  

The evolution of the opposable thumb made the feat possible;  the evolving brain's dissatisfactions with the status quo made it necessary. Tools enabled home habilis to alter what he/she perceived to be imperfections in the world.<P> 

The long march of human tinkering had begun. Stone Age, Bronze Age, Iron Age - all were labeled by the tool-making raw material discovered and exploited. Down through the centuries man's history has been shaped, as Professor McLuhan said, by the tools he invented - servant to master in no time at all.<P> 

Fast forward to the final moments of the 20th Century, the Information Age: half-serious anthropologists suggest a new subspecies is evolving - techno sapiens, machine man, the melding of the human brain and the computer. Never before in tool-making history has there been anything to compare with this powerful conjunction. The computer is shaping us faster than we dare admit.<P>

Ominous new signs in recent years have been affixed to some doors in the Pentagon: "Information Warfare." Military planners know that information, in all the protean applications of the word, is so vital that any advanced nation could be brought to its knees by a successful disruption of  its communications. And the United States, as the most advanced Information Age nation, is probably the most vulnerable.<P> 

During the Gulf War when Suddam Hussein frantically turned to the Internet for his emergency communications after F-10s and F-117s clobbered his local command & control systems, coalition strategists considered an unprecedented interdiction - knocking out the Internet (by techniques that remain top secret).<P>

The idea was swiftly rejected after the planners were warned that a disruption would bring down the banking system of Western Europe. Presumably that was adjudged to be unacceptable "collateral damage," that curious euphemism of modern warfare and its ingenious tools of destruction.<P>

This is an extreme example of the hazards of homo sapiens' precarious new niche, in cyberspace. On a more quotidian level for  physicians,  information technology is changing medical practice, directly and indirectly, with such rapidity that many doctors confess to sensory overload. No sooner have you turned your attention to one brand-new challenge than two others appear.  And you are certainly no stranger to Information Warfare.<P>

Computer power, constantly accelerating according to Moore's Law,  has altered not only the rate of change but the nature of change. Professor McLuhan was on the money: "We shape our tools; thereafter they shape us."<P>

No sector of the economy is immune: even in Silicon Valley, wherein the strange denizens have always plied their trade in a weird time-warp, the pace of change has recently accelerated to the point that the clock and the calendar are no longer adequate gauges of time. Harassed hardware and software developers now speak of "Web Time,"  referring to the preposterously rapid expansion of the World Wide Web, where a new site is appearing every three seconds.<P>

Change has become non-linear, a profound culture-shock. At an early age, children of the Western World  were taught to visualize change as occurring more or less sequentially, with A followed by B and then C in an orderly, linear progression. But much of the change physicians are experiencing in these turbulent times is irregular, lateral,  zig-zag, seemingly random, unpredicatable and unprojectable.<P>

When you were in the public schools wondering of what possible use in later life could be geometry, algebra, or trig,  there was always that officious and ubiquitous teacher to declaim that such disciplines would teach you to think.<P>

To think, that is, in an orderly, linear way - Euclidian fashion, where shapes and problems had been neatly formalized and formularized.  You were introduced to circles, squares, rectangles, spheres, triangles, parallelograms, rhombuses, cubes, truncated cones, tetrahedrons, polyhedrons, etc., etc. For each there was a precise formula for finding all those attributes you considered totally irrelevant to your future: area, volume, curvature, whatever.<P>

Even if you felt no powerful bonding with Euclid, the Greek mathematician of the third century B.C. who started it all, you were learning to think rationally, the teacher said.<P>

You didn't believe that then and you may not believe it now.  How many problems in your life since have been in the shape of polyhedron or a truncated cone? How did the knowledge of the rhombus help you in trying to reason with a teenage son?<P>

The rigid constraints of algebra and trig were similarly presented as molding cognitive ability. Now, how many patient encounters have you had in which the binomial theorem or quadratic equations assisted you in a difficult diagnosis?<P>

But, face it, the truth is that all these disciplines of long ago  unquestionably did help greatly in shaping and molding a logical mind. When searching for order in the disorder of disease processes, you are using, if only subconsciously, the intellectual tools first provided by these disciplines, idiotic as they may have seemed at the time.<P>

Similarly, intensive medical training inculcated orderly, predictable couplings of cause and effect.  You came to respect and revere the rigors of the scientific method. But modern life, physician and non-physician alike are discovering, has become non-Euclidian. Just as nature presents us with few problems shaped as true cones or tetrahedrons, so does everyday life often deny us straight lines from A to B, or problems that can be solved in four or five prescribed steps leading neatly to QED.<P>

Thus, from kindergarten through residency, you were conditioned to find and respect order. But now you are faced with  disorder wrought by, among other marauders, the invasion of the body-snatchers of managed care, whose sometimes bizarre treatment notions you must balance against equally rapid changes in the true science of medicine, newly defined and redefined by ever-changing guideliness and parameters.<P>

 (When Nobel physicist Murray Gell-Mann was asked at a conference to define "parameter," he quickly replied, to the appreciative laughter of his peers,   "a variable constant." Physicians wonder what was so funny: their daily lives are filled with variable constants.)<P>

The non-Euclidian path of modern life can best be described as fractal. The word was coined by mathematician Benoit Mandelbrot to describe the shapes that formal mathematics had ignored or abandoned: the irregular and unpredictable configurations of clouds, coastlines, lightning, the microscopic intertwining of blood vessels, the galactic clustering of stars - all those non-linear phenomena that you were never taught to address by formula, precisely because they were non-linear - dismissed as noise, static, turbulence,  chaos to minds schooled in the niceties of  Euclidian symmetry and order.  Hence the title of his best-selling book, The Fractal Geometry of Nature.*<P>

Behind most of this sudden disruption of linearity  is man's newest  tool, the computer, the product of 2,000,000 years of  increasingly clever engines to reshape the world more to the heart's desire.<P>

The Luddites (1811-16)  blindly fought new textile machinery of the Industrial Revolution by sabotage, fire and pillage. They lost. And physicians will lose too if they elect to ignore what is now believed to be a true paradigm shift in the 
dissemination of knowledge: the computer and its progeny, particularly the Internet.<P>

More than  one graduation speaker this year noted the rapid transformation of world society into two classes,  the computer-literate and the computer-illiterate, the updated version of the haves and have-nots of history. Certainly no one in the knowledge-based professions, medicine being the most sensitive, can ignore this incredibly powerful engine of change.<P>

It might have been better if homo habilis had left well enough alone and kept his opposable thumb to himself. But he didn't and here we are. Managed care empires are waging relentless information  warfare against the physician. While you cannot hope to match their data-crunching firepower, the newly expanded capacity of the desktop computer,  linked to the data-rich Internet, can be effectively deployed as an electronic countermeasure, the physician's Great Equalizer.<P>

With these virtually boundless resources so readily at hand, you will  join  on-line discussions with other physicians across the nation; learn of the pitfalls in many forms of contracts now ensnaring physicians; study the experiences of your peers in states where the great revolution in medical economics has progressed much further than here in the Deep South.<P>

Not least, of course, you will learn to use Grateful Med and other doctor-friendly services of the National Library of Medicine, along with such advanced resources as Medical Matrix and the soon to be announced Healthtron, a Netscape spin-off.<P>

This is no drill; private practice is in a war of brute survival. To shorten your learning curve,  MASA is launching this site on the World Wide Web, and with it instructions on how Alabama doctors can join the ranks of the digitally correct. Quite apart from its function as defensive weaponry in medicine's struggle, the Internet is the door to a fascinating world out there, as will be seen in subsequent messages.</B><P>
  
<I>*In 1975, preparing his first major work on his shapes, dimensions and geometry, Mandelbrot needed a name for his lovely monstrosities. He was thumbing through his son's Latin dictionary when he came upon the adjective fractus, from the verb frangere, to break, two familiar English cognates being fracture and fraction.  Then and there, Mandelbrot created the word "fractal." Three years later he published his equation-filled book, Fractals, Chance and Dimension,  later incorporating this into the refined replacement work, The Fractal Geometry of Nature (1972, 1982, 1983, New York, W.H. Freeman & Co., ISBN 0-7167-1186-9).  The work has sold more copies than any book of high mathematics in the history of publishing.</I>
<P><CENTER><H4>Back to <A HREF="COM.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">Communications</A></H4></CENTER>
<SCRIPT Language = "VBScript">
