<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>AMA-YPS 1996 Interim Session</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND=../pics/PARCH.GIF><CENTER><img src="../pics/YPSLOGO.GIF" align=bottom width=349 height=113></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2><I>YOUNG PHYSICIANS ACHIEVE VICTORIES<BR>AT AMA INTERIM MEETING</I></H2></CENTER><P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><I><B>At the 1996 AMA Interim Meeting, the Young Physicians Section was successful in getting a number of its resolutions adopted.  Adoption means that the AMA acts to implement the policy.  The following is a summary of the most important issues debated.  Congratulations are to be extended to those delegates who represented the YPS on the House floor.  Young physicians can and do make a difference!</B></I></BLOCKQUOTE><P>

<H3>Physician Advocacy</H3>

<B>Restrictive Covenants During Training </B>- The AMA House
adopted an AMA-YPS resolution strongly urging that
residency and fellowship training programs that utilize
restrictive covenants provide written intent to impose
restrictions in advance of the interview process.  The
resolution also urges the Council on Ethical and Judicial
Affairs to consider strengthening its current opinion against
restrictive covenants, including elimination of restrictive
covenants for residents and fellows.

<H3>Patient Advocacy</H3>

<B>Coverage for Medically Necessary OTC Medications </B>- AMA
delegates concurred with a YPS resolution calling for an
AMA study on  the problem of patient reimbursement from
health care plans for appropriate medically necessary
over-the-counter medications, disposable medical
equipment, or durable medical equipment, with a
prescription from their physician.  The study will address
such issues as the exacerbation of illness when patients are
unable to afford medically necessary treatments; patients?
pressure on doctors to prescribe certain prescription
medications when over-the-counter medications are more
appropriate; increased paperwork and administration time
on the physician; the potentially onerous burden of certifying
as to the medical necessity of nonprescription medications;
potential cost-shifting; and possible increased numbers of
patient visits.<P>

<B>Caring for the Working Poor and their Dependents </B>- The
House voted to ratify this YPS resolution asking that the
AMA explore the development of partnerships with
corporations, non-profit organizations, and state and local
governments to address the need s of the working poor and
their dependents.  The AMA will widely disseminate the
lessons learned from the study.<P>

<B>Insurance Company Blanket Payment Refusals </B>- This
AMA-YPS resolution calls on the AMA to study the
practice of insurance companies and third party payors
sending out blanket refusals prospectively and
retrospectively for each of the different specialties and for
each insurance company and/or third party payor, and to
consider appropriate methods of informing current and
prospective patients on the use of this information in
choosing health care coverage.  The resolution further calls
on the AMA to oppose blanket refusals by third party
payors as detrimental to patients as an obstruction to their
obtaining needed medical care.<P>

<B>Community Mobility Device Prescription </B>- Delegates
referred to the AMA Board another YPS resolution asking
the AMA to work toward statutory changes that will result
in the Health Care Financing Administration allowing
reimbursement for electronic platform mobility devices for
patients who have achieved household mobility through
rehabilitation, but who are still limited in their community
mobility.  This anomaly is the result of conflicting federal
requirements.

<H3>Physician Payment</H3>

<B>Denial of Payment for Precertified Care </B>- Thanks to
adoption of an AMA-YPS resolution by AMA delegates,
existing AMA Policy was modified to read as follows:  The
AMA supports legislation and/or regulation that would
prevent the retrospective denial of payment for any claim
for services for which a physician had previously obtained
authorization, unless fraud was committed or incorrect
information provided at the time such prior approval was
obtained.

<H3>Environmental/Public Health</H3>

<B>Cellular Telephones and Medical Equipment</B> - As a result
of this AMA-YPS resolution, the AMA will continue its
collaboration with the FDA and the Association for the
Advancement of Medical Instrumentation in the following
areas:  (1) evaluating the potential for electronic
communications devices to interfere with the functioning of
medical equipment; (2) developing guidelines for the design,
manufacture, and use of communications devices and
medical equipment to maximize electromagnetic
compatibility and minimize electromagnetic interferences;
and (3) disseminating the findings and guidelines.<P>

<B>AMA Reducing and Recycling </B>- Thanks to adoption of this
AMA-YPS resolution, the AMA, where and when feasible,
will provide recycling bins for white colored paper in a
prominent place at the back of the meeting room for at least
the final day of AMA Section and House of Delegates
meetings, and all other AMA meetings.  The Chair,
Speaker, or some other appropriate individual will remind
delegates that they should recycle their papers in the bins if
they do not intend to keep them.

<H3>Physician Workforce/Supply</H3>

<B>Physician Supply and Antitrust </B>- This AMA-YPS resolution
was referred to the AMA Board for decision.  It asked the
AMA to support and/or initiate policies recognizing that
there is currently an oversupply of physicians in some
specialties and in some regions, and in the future there may
be an oversupply across specialties and regions.  It also
encouraged medical schools to align medical school class
sizes with current and future physician supply requirements.
 Finally, it asked AMA to seek appropriate antitrust relief so
organized medicine may work to better regulate physician
supply.<P>

<B>Graduate Medical Education </B>- This resolution called on the
AMA to aggressively implement AMA Policy 305.971,
?Discrimination Against Resident Candidates Based on
Graduate Medical Education Funding,? which states:  The
AMA (1) supports informing residents and medical students
about the COBRA 1986 regulations on residency training,
so that the restrictions may be incorporated into an
individual?s residency planning; 2) urges hospitals and
residency programs to use qualifications as a basic for filling
available positions, and not the status of the Medicare
component to graduate medical education funding; and (3)
continues to encourage and support legislation to maximize
graduate medical education funding.  Instead, AMA
delegates elected to adopt a recommendation #1 of Council
on Medical Education Report 5:  The AMA affirms current
policy for a Federal system of financing GME based on an
all payer contribution.

<H3>Leadership Development/Mainstreaming</H3>

<B>Increased YPS Delegate Representation for Unified Societies</B>
- AMA delegates voted to amend AMA-YPS bylaws to
grant an additional AMA-YPS delegate to each state
medical society and national medical specialty society
requiring unified membership with the AMA.  This creates
additional leadership opportunities for young physicians!<P>

<B>AMA-YPS 10th Anniversary </B>-- The 1996 interim meeting
marked the beginning of the AMA Young Physicians
Section 10th year in existence.  Throughout the AMA-HOD
and AMA-YPS meetings, current AMA-YPS
representatives, young AMA delegates under the age or 40,
and AMA-YPS wore special embroidered stickers honoring
the YPS.  These individuals shared with AMA delegates
and other individuals the goals and purposes of the Section
and talked about the victories and successes that the
Section has won during the last ten years.  10th anniversary
celebrations will be held throughout the next six months,
culminating in a anniversary party during the annual meeting
in June.  Your active participation and that of your fellow
young physicians in spreading the word about the AMA
and its Young Physicians Section is encouraged.<P>

If you have any questions or need more information,
please contact <A HREF="mailto:jon_burkhart@ama-assn.org">Jon Burkhart</A> at the AMA Department of
Young Physician Services, (312) 464-4748.  You are also encouraged
to e-mail YPS Chair <A HREF="mailto:spsolish@aol.com">Sam Solish, MD</A>.
<P><HR>
