<HEAD>
<TITLE> YPS Minutes </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/PARCH.GIF"><CENTER><a name="TOP"><img src="../pics/YPSLOGO.GIF" align=bottom width=349 height=113></a></CENTER><CENTER><H1>ALABAMA'S FIRST YPS ASSEMBLY</H1></CENTER><P>
The Alabama chapter of the Young Physicians Section of the American Medical Association held the first meeting of the Young Physicians Assembly at this year's 1996 Annual Session in Perdido on Thursday, April 18.  The Assembly included an educational session with an update on managed care, a presentation by the chief lobbyist from the AMA, and a discussion by MASA's lobbyist that focused on what Alabama physicians should do to change the makeup of the Supreme Court.<P>
A busy YPS delegation generated three late resolutions, all of which were heard by the reference committee on Friday and voted on by the House of Delegates on Saturday.  The first resolution proposed that physicians be compensated for telephone consultations with patients and be billed directly to the patient, or to insurance companies.  This was sufficiently controversial to make the front page of the Birmingham News the following day.<P>
A second resolution provided for the YPS to have a dedicated worldwide web site on the Internet, which was amended to provide for a dedicated site for the YPS within the Medical Association's home page.<P>
The last resolution proposed to amend the MASA bylaws in order to move the YPS meeting from Thursday to Friday of the Annual Session.<P>
The first two resolutions passed the House on Saturday, while the third--since it involves changing the bylaws--will be required to lay on the table for one year until the next Annual Session.<P>
In other business, Jo Lynne Herzog, MD, a dermatologist from Birmingham, was sworn in as YPS president for 1996-97.<P>
Certain YPS Assembly delegate positions are still open for next year's meeting.  If you are interested in becoming a delegate, or would like to nominate someone for a position, please contact Anne King, YPS Staff Representative, at the Medical Association in Montgomery.  Call 1-800-239-6272.<P><CENTER><H4>Back to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">Alabama YPS Home Page.</A></H4></CENTER>
