<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Information on the</TITLE>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<HR>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5>Information on the</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5> Network for Continuing Medical Education</FONT></B></CENTER>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=5> (NCME) Videocassette Service<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<B>
Welcome to a unique service offered to all physicians licensed
in the State of Alabama. This free check-out service is made possible
from funds provided through a contract for educational services
between the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners and the Medical
Association of the State of Alabama. A small portion of your annual
relicensure fee is used to provide a variety of educational activities
to physicians, including the purchase of these tapes. A few comments
on how the system operates:<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Information of Available Tapes<BR></FONT>
<P>
Approximately every 2-3 weeks, we receive new 1/2&quot; VHS format
tapes from NCME; the focus of subject material is clinical - aimed
at the primary care specialties although there are occasional
offerings on general topics of interest to all physicians or a
special one aimed at a particular specialty.<BR>
<P>
You can secure a listing of available tapes by calling the Medical
Association Education Department at (334) 263-6441 or 1-800-239-MASA
(Alabama only). New issues are also often publicized in the quarterly
BME Newsletter sent to all Alabama licensed physicians.<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
Check-out Procedures<BR></FONT>
<P>
Simply call the Medical Association Education Department and indicate
the tapes you desire by tape number (#437, #635, etc.).<BR>
<P>
To allow for maximum circulation, we limit check-out to <U>two
tapes at a time</U>, and allow you to <U>keep them for a two week
period</U>. Extensions can be granted for special circumstances
- call the Education Director if this is necessary.<BR>
<P>
The tapes will be sent to you (post free) in a bubble envelope
via UPS.<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
Return of Tapes<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
You are responsible for returning these tapes in good condition.
We suggest you reuse the bubble envelope to do this; it can be
sent either by UPS or US mail, and <U>should be insured for $75</U>.
If it is lost, you will be responsible for purchasing a replacement
tape.<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
CME Credit for Tapes<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Some of these tapes have been approved for AMA Category 1, AAFP
Prescribed and other forms of CME credit. The description of the
tape will indicate if this kind of credit is being granted.
<P>
Any CME credit granted will be done through the Network for CME
(<U>not</U> the Medical Association). Normally, such tapes will
have an accompanying booklet with it, which you should use as
you view the tape. Then complete the telecourse quiz and the Physician
Participation Record; <U>be sure your social security number</U>
and <U>our (Medical Association) hospital code #6022</U> are entered
so that your credit will be registered with NCME. Then tear off
the rear page with this information and send it to NCME, with
the mailing address provided. You may keep the rest of the study
booklet for your reference.<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
Physician Participation Records (For tapes #672 and above)
</FONT>
<P>
Please note that beginning with Videocassette #672, there will
no longer be a need to match a specific workbook with a program.
Physician Participation records will replace the old workbooks.
A universal format has been developed to allow physicians to record
their participation in any NCME credit program. Post-telecourse
quizzes for credit courses now will appear on the video at the
end of the program. Physicians simply record their answers on
one of the new Physician Participation Records. Programs numbered
671 and lower will still have specific workbooks.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
Expiration of Credit<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Generally, the period that tapes will be approved for CME credit
will for three years from the date of release. So if you want
credit, be sure to view these tapes in that period and get the
credit registered. This period for the credit may vary a bit from
tape to tape since the credit decision is made by the organization
originally developing the program.<BR>
<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>
CME Credit Record<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Should you ever need a transcript of the CME credit you earned
through NCME, you can write to NCME, One Harmon Plaza, Seacaucus
NJ 07094. Include your social security number and our hospital
code #6022. Post cards to do this are also available through our
Education Office.<BR>
<P>
We hope you find these videocassettes will be an interesting and
worthwhile addition to your professional education activities.
</B>
