<head>
<title>MASA Start Page</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFCECE">
<h1 align=center>Getting Started with MASALink</h1>
<h2 align=left>Welcome. . .</h2>
<blockquote>
<p align=left><b>If you are new to the Internet, we welcome you and hope this website provides you with the 
information you need about your Medical Association in a concise, easy to understand and 
environment-friendly format. Even if you are computer-wise, you may find the following tips useful 
when accessing this or other websites. Standards are constantly changing and the average website 
of today looks ill-designed when viewed with software written as recently as one year ago. 
<p align=left>This website is optimally viewed with Netscape Navigator 3.0 or Microsoft Internet Explorer 3.0. 
These web browsers command ninety percent of the IBM PC compatible market and are available 
for the Macintosh as well. AOL users will need to download the latest web browsing software available on AOL (which happens to be Internet Explorer 3.0). If you have an older browser or different computer (such as Amiga), you 
can still view this website but you will not be able to see the new interface. You 
can find out which version of Navigator or Internet Explorer by clicking on Help on the top menu 
bar and then clicking on About . . . 
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
<blockquote>
<h4 align=left>I'd like to download the latest version. Take me to <a href="http://home.netscape.com">Netscape</a> or <a href="http://www.microsoft.com">Microsoft</a>.</h4>
<h4 align=left><a href="index.html">Back me out of this now!</a> I don't have either and don't want to read further!</h4>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<h2 align=left>Before you begin. . .</h2>
<ol>
<li><p align=left><u>Make sure the resolution of your monitor is set at 800x600, not 640x480.</u> To do this in Windows 95, follow 
these easy steps:<p> 
<ol>
<li>Click on Start. 
<li>Move the mouse up to Settings and then over to Control Panel and click. 
<li>The Control Panel will display; double click on the Display icon. 
<li>A window will open across the top of which are page tabs. Click on Settings. 
<li>The section Desktop Area has a slider which you can move with the mouse to 800x600 or greater. 
Unless you have a large monitor (17&quot; or greater), do not move this higher as text may become too 
small to read. 
<li>Click on OK in the window and follow the directions. If your computer restarts and drops your internet 
connection, no harm is done. Simply re-login and access this screen again for the remainder of the 
directions. 
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>Caveat: If you are accessing the internet from a laptop, you may be forced to keep your 
resolution at 640x480 due to the small screen size. For Macintosh owners, you may refer to 
the manual provided with your operating system version. 
</blockquote>

<li><u>Netscape 3.0 Owners</u> - Netscape monopolizes thirty percent of the screen real estate with redundant help 
buttons. Reclaim your screen space right now:<p><ol>
<li>Click on Options on the menu bar at the top. The options menu will drop down. 
<li>Now click on Show Directory Buttons so that the checkmark is removed (you can always access the 
same information by clicking on Directory on the top menu bar). 
<li>Now click on General Preferences on the same options menu. 
<li>The Appearance page will come up first. Under the Toolbars section, click on Text. This reduces the 
big icon buttons to narrow text buttons. Congratulations! You've just created twenty percent more 
screen space. 
<li>You're not through yet. Under the Link Styles section on the same menu, click on Underlined so that 
the box is empty (underlining <U>off</U>). In the same section, set the Followed links to expire after 2 days. Now click on OK. 
This will save some space on your hard drive.
</ol>
<p>
<li><u>Internet Explorer 3.0 (and AOL) Owners</u> - A little more elegant than Netscape Navigator but needs some fine tuning:<p><ol>
<li>Click on View on the menu bar at the top. A menu will drop down. 
<li>Click on Options. 
<li>Under the Links section, click on the Underline links box so that the box does not have a check mark 
in it (underlining <U>off</U>). 
<li>In the same window, there are tabs across the top. Click on the one that says Navigation. 
<li>To save space on your hard drive, change the number to 2. 
<li>In the same window, click on the tab at the top that says Advanced. 
<li>Under the section that says Temporary Internet files, click on settings. 
<li>Move the slider on this page to about 2 percent. This will save a tremendous amount of disc 
space. 
<li>Click on OK at the bottom of the window and you are ready to go.
<li>This browser does not yet completely support frame HTML coding. Translated, if you find that you cannot backspace, click on the right mouse key inside the web browser window to bring up a menu box.  Then click on Refresh.</ol> 
</ol>Lastly, you may find that your web browser with time begins to run slower regardless of how good your connection might be.  This usually means the history and cache files have to be cleared which you can also find by strolling through the options.  If you cannot figure it out, email us and we'll be glad to tell you how.
<h2>A quick orientation. . .</h2>
<p>Navigating MASAlink is really quite simple. The main body of information that is present on the screen is always 
flanked on the left and on the bottom by clickable buttons that will let you quickly jump to a particular department at MASA 
or to the articles that you receive in the mail (often long before you will receive them).<p>

<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=2 width=100%>
<tr><td width=125><img src="pics/FRAME.GIF" align=left hspace=0 width=125 height=400 align="middle"></td><td width=500><strong>These are the departments at MASA. You will be able to click on the one 
you want to visit and examine documents that are pertinent to the 
Association as prepared by that particular department. Don't forget to 
check out some of Bill McDonald's essays in Communications!</strong></td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><br clear=left>
Icons across the bottom of the page allow you to jump directly to a periodical published by MASA or a particularly 
useful utility. These may change from time to time but you can bet on seeing these:
<p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=2 width=100%>
<tr><td align=center width=75><img src="pics/NEWSICON.GIF" align=bottom width=75 height=25></td><td width=575><b>Medical News Week is a quick summary of what major newspapers in Alabama had to say 
about health care for the preceding week. Published by the Public Relations Department.</b></td></tr>
<tr><td align=center width=75><img src="pics/PACICON.GIF" align=bottom width=75 height=25></td><td width=575><b>The Alabama Political Action Committee actively lobbies legislators to steer health care in the 
direction of a better future for doctors and patients alike. Sometimes they will let you know 
what they are doing here. An activity of Governmental Affairs.</b></td></tr>
<tr><td align=center width=75><img src="pics/ROTICON.GIF" align=bottom width=75 height=25></td><td width=575><b>The Rotunda is our watchdog on the government and it is here you will find the status of key 
health care related bills as they pass through Congress. Published by Governmental Affairs.</b></td></tr>
<tr><td align=center width=75><img src="pics/STATICON.GIF" align=bottom width=74 height=25></td><td width=575><b>Stat is often a formal call to arms for doctors to contact their legislators or other officials to 
help effect changes that preserve our best interest and the best interest of our patients. 
Published by Governmental Affairs.</b></td></tr>
<tr><td align=center width=75><img src="pics/AMDICON.GIF" align=bottom width=76 height=25></td><td width=575><b>You will quickly recognize the well known weekly <u>The Alabama MD</u> where you can also find 
archived Dr. Ernest Campbell's love of the Internet. Published by the Communications 
Department.</b></td></tr>
<tr><td align=center width=75><img src="pics/MAILICON.GIF" align=bottom width=75 height=25></td><td width=575><b>If you have a question or comment, you can email the Association directly by clicking here.</b></td></tr>
<tr><td align=center width=75><img src="pics/NETICON.GIF" align=bottom width=75 height=25></td><td width=575><b>A great compilation of World Wide Web Sites that are particularly useful to physicians. You 
can find here sites of a generally medical nature as well as those pertinent to individual 
specialties. Also, programs that help you search out information based on an idea or a few 
keywords can be accessed. Don't forget to check out the finance and home management 
section! Courtesy of the Webmaster.</b></td></tr></b>
</table>
</center></div>
<p>
<h2 align=center>I've seen enough, <a href="index.html" target="_top">let's get going!</a></h2>
