<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reform Bills Comparison</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../PARCH.GIF">
<FONT SIZE=2>AMA Division of Legislative Counsel - 8/2/96</FONT>
<CENTER><H1>COMPARISON OF HEALTH INSURANCE REFORM BILLS</H1></CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER CELLPADDING=5><TR><TH>Provision
<TH>House Bill<BR>
H.R. 3103 as adopted 3/28/96
<TH>Kassebaum-Kennedy Bill<BR>
H.R. 3103 (S. 1028) as adopted 4/23/96
<TH>Conference Report<BR>
(final)
<TR><TH COLSPAN=4><H3>INSURANCE REFORMS</H3>
<TR><TD>Portability
<TD>Prevents loss of group ins. coverage in job change w/ preex. limitation period reduced 1 mo. for each mo. of prior coverage w/o <U>60</U> day lapse.
<TD>Prevents loss of group ins. coverage in job changes, w/ preex. limitation period reduced 1 mo. for each mo. of coverage w/o <U>30</U> day lapse.
<TD>Prevents loss of group ins. coverage in job change w/ preex. lim. period reduced 1 mo. for each mo. of prior coverage w/o <U>63</U> day lapse.
<TR><TD>Preexisting<BR>
Conditions
<TD>No more than 12 mos limitation for condition diagnosed w/in 6 mos (18/6 rule for late entrants).
<TD>Same as House.
<TD>Same as House.
<TR><TD>Guaranteed<BR>Availability
<TD>Insurers must accept every small employer (2-50 employees) that applies for coverage.
<TD>Insurers must offer whole group coverage to any group that applies for coverage.
<TD>Same as House, with HHS coordinated study on large employer access to health insurance.  
<TR><TD>Guaranteed<BR>Renewability
<TD>Insurers must renew small and large group market.
<TD>Same as House.
<TD>Same as House.
<TR><TD>Individual Market<BR>Reform
<TD>Insurers must issue and renew coverage for individuals: 1) with 18 mos group coverage; 2) who have exhausted COBRA; and 3) who are ineligible for a group plan.  States can implement optional mechanisms to achieve goal.
<TD>Same as House, except that it also establishes rules to give individuals greater choice among health plans and to prevent risk selection against individuals purchasing individual coverage under this provision.
<TD>Same as House, except that insurers must also offer at least two different policies, with two different levels of benefit coverage within specified actuarial values of weighted average benefit. 
<TR><TD>Purchasing<BR>Groups
<TD>Expands voluntary group purchasing for small employers and assns, with stds developed by DOL.
<TD>State or DOL must certify voluntary HPPCs for purchasing individual or group health plans.
<TD>No voluntary HPPCs or MEWA provisions.
<TR><TH COLSPAN=4><H3>FRAUD AND ABUSE - ADMINISTRATIVE SIMPLIFICATION</H3>
<TR><TD>Criminal Intent<BR>Required
<TD>For new federal crimes (health care fraud and false statements) prosecution must show physician acted "knowingly," instead of "knowingly and willfully."  Acting with only a "knowing" intent could potentially catch physicians who made coding errors.
<TD>Sets standard at "knowingly and willfully."  This standard ensures that the practitioner knew what he was doing and knew that what he was doing was wrong.  Hence billing errors would not be enough to subject a physician to criminal prosecution.
<TD>Sets standard at "knowingly and willfully," as aggressively lobbied by AMA.
<TR><TD>Civil Monetary<BR>Penalties (CMP)
<TD>CMPs are imposed when a physician "knows or should know" that they are doing something not permitted by Medicare/Medicaid.  House bill clarified that "should know" means that one acted in deliberate ignorance of the truth or in reckless disregard of the truth.  Effect: makes it harder to impose CMPs for honest mistakes.
<TD>Contained no clarification of the "should know" standard.
<TD>Follows House version supported by AMA which defines "should know" standard as "reckless disregard for" or "deliberate indifference to" the truth in dealings with Medicare/Medicaid.
<TR><TD>Advisory Opinions
<TD>HHS to issue binding advis. opinions on what constitutes remuneration and whether an act would be grounds for sanctions.  NCVHS to advise HHS.
<TD>HHS IG to issue Interpretive Rulings (IRs) on what is considered prohibited conduct.  IRs not binding on parties.
<TD>Binding and mandatory favorable House advisory opinion language retained, but provisions sunset after four years.
<TR><TD>Bounty System
<TD>F&A Account would contain criminal fines, civil penalties and forfeited property derived from  enforcement efforts.  Account would be a part of the Hospital Insurance Trust Fund.
<TD>Same as House.
<TD>Same as House, and Comptroller General (GAO) to report to Congress on amts. deposited in fraud and abuse account. 
<TR><TD>Database
<TD>Database to report "final adverse actions" against practitioners. Would not include settlements or prof. liability claims.  Data available to fed and state agencies and health plans.
<TD>Same as House, except added "exclusions from federal and state health care programs" to definition of final adverse actions. 
<TD>Same as House, but added provision to avoid duplication with the reporting requirements established for Nat'l Practitioner Data Bank.
<TR><TD>CPT/Medical<BR>Records 
<TD>Problems include lack of physician input, "black box" edits, and potential copyright divestment.  Possible medical record confidentiality problems.
<TD>Same as House.
<TD>HHS Sec. to adopt code sets/stds. NUCC, NUBC and WEDI to advise std setting orgs on coding systems.  Congress to receive HHS recommendations on medical record confidentiality and adopt final regs if bill not passed within 36 mos.
<TR><TH COLSPAN=4><H3>OTHER PROVISIONS</H3>
<TR><TD>MSAs
<TD>MSAs ($2,000 ind, $4,000 family) are tax deductible with high deduct plan ($1,500 ind, $3,000 family). 10% excise tax on improper uses. 
<TD>Attempt to add MSAs defeated by 52-46 vote.  But, bill still includes provision encouraging MSAs to be added to health insurance legislation.
<TD>4 year pilot project is limited generally to 750,000 MSAs. Only available for self-employed and small biz (less than 51 employees). MSAs are tax deductible with high deductible plan ($1,500-2,250 ind, $3,000-4,500 family). Max. annual MSA contribution limited to 65% of above amts. for inds. and 75% for families. 15% excise tax on improper uses. Congress would have to vote to expand.
<TR><TD>Liability Reform
<TD>MICRA liability reforms, including $250,000 cap on non-economic damages.
<TD>Extends federal liability protection to medical volunteers who provide services to medically underserved persons.
<TD>MICRA reforms dropped.  Extends Fed. Tort Claims Act protections to physicians who provide volunteer health services to poor. 
<TR><TD>Tax Changes
<TD>Increases self-employed tax deduction to 50% by 2003.  Allows tax deduction for long-term care insurance.  Exempts from income tax state sponsored orgs that provide health coverage for high risk individuals.  Terminally or chronically ill may receive life. ins. on tax exempt basis.
<TD>Increases self-employed tax deduction to 80% by 2006.  Allows tax deduction for long-term care insurance.  Exempts from income tax state sponsored orgs that provide health coverage for high risk individuals.  Allows penalty-free IRA distributions for devastating medical expenses. Terminally or chronically ill may receive life. ins. on tax exempt basis. 
<TD>Same as Senate. 
<TR><TD>Patient Protection<BR>Provisions
<TD>No provisions.
<TD>Sense of Senate provisions against gag clauses (patient right to know) and in support of the need to insure children and pregnant women.  Mental health parity provision. HHS study of patient access to out-of-network providers. Ends ins. discrim. against domestic violence victims.
<TD>Senate mental health parity and anti-gag provisions dropped.  HHS study of patient access to out-of-network providers. Ends ins. discrim. against domestic violence victims.</TABLE><HR>
<CENTER>Back to the reform bill <A HREF="GOVKKINT.HTM">Main Page</A></CENTER>
</BODY>
