</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/GRYPARCH.GIF">
<CENTER><H3><A NAME="ABO">ABORTION</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>May a minor consent to an abortion?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, a minor (any person under the age of 18 years) who has not been married or has not by court order been legally freed from the care, custody and control of her parents, may not obtain an abortion without the written consent of a parent or legal guardian.  There are, however, exceptions to this general requirement of parental consent or permission:

<OL>
   <LI>If the pregnancy was caused by sexual intercourse with the minor's natural father, adoptive father, stepfather, or legal guardian, then written notice to the minor's mother by certified mail will be sufficient.
   <LI>A minor who elects not to seek parental consent may petition the juvenile court, on her own behalf, for a waiver of the parental consent requirement.
   <LI>Parental consent is not required when, in the clinical judgment of the attending physician, a medical emergency exists that compromises the health, safety or well-being of the minor so as to require an immediate abortion.  The physician must include in the minor's medical record clinical indications to support his or her decision.
</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the penalties for performing an abortion on a minor without proper consent?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Performing an abortion on a minor without complying with the specific consent requirements under Alabama law constitutes a Class A misdemeanor and could result in forfeiture of the physician's professional license.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What information can be disclosed by a physician?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Where parental consent has been obtained, a physician can disclose information concerning a minor's medical condition to her parents or legal guardian.  However, a physician treating a minor who has petitioned the juvenile court for a waiver of parental consent must follow special confidentiality requirements.  Under those circumstances, a physician should not disclose information regarding a minor's medical condition to her parents or legal guardian unless required to do so by the court.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="ABU">ABUSE REPORTING</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What are a physician's responsibilities in reporting suspected abuse?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Physicians are required to report any suspected physical abuse, neglect or exploitation of an adult or child to the appropriate county Department of Human Resources and/or law enforcement official.  Within three days after reporting the suspected abuse, an investigation will be conducted and a written report prepared.  Any person such as a physician who participates in the making of a report of suspected abuse or who participates in a judicial proceeding stemming from the report will be immune from all liability.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Does the physician/patient relationship bar a physician from reporting evidence of suspected abuse?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>No.  The doctrine of privileged communication which demands that in most cases a physician keep the medical condition of his patient confidential is not sufficient grounds for excluding evidence regarding a patient's injuries or the cause of the injuries in any report of suspected abuse or neglect.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="ADVD">ADVANCED DECLARATION</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is an advanced declaration?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Under Alabama law, adults have the fundamental right to control decisions relating to their own medical care, including the decision to have life-sustaining procedures withheld or withdrawn.  The Alabama legislature recognized this fundamental right by enacting the Natural Death Act, which allows an adult to make a written, advanced declaration instructing his or her physician to withhold or withdraw life-sustaining procedures in the event of a terminal condition.  See also, "Termination of Life Support."</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What is a terminal condition?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Under Alabama law, a patient is deemed to be terminally ill or terminally injured if the patient's death is imminent or his or her condition is hopeless unless artificially supported through life-sustaining procedures.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the specific requirements for a valid advanced declaration under Alabama law?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE><OL>
   <LI>The declaration must be in writing;
   <LI>The declaration must be signed by the person making the declaration, or by another person in the presence of the    person making the declaration and at the expressed direction of the person making the declaration;
   <LI>The declaration must be dated; and
   <LI>The declaration must be signed in the presence of two or more witnesses at least 19 years of age.</OL>

If the person making the declaration is pregnant, the advanced declaration has no effect during the course of the pregnancy.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Who may not be a witness to an advanced declaration?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A witness cannot be the same person who signed the declaration at the direction of the person making the declaration.  Further, a witness cannot be related to the person making the declaration by blood or marriage, or entitled to any portion of the estate of the declarant according to the Alabama laws of intestate succession which govern inheritance of possessions when there is no will, or under the declarant's will.  In addition, a witness must not be directly, financially responsible for the declarant's medical care.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>How is a physician notified of the existence of an advanced declaration?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The declarant is responsible for informing his or her attending physician that an advanced declaration has been signed, and the attending physician is required to place a copy of the advanced declaration in the patient's medical record.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May a physician lawfully refuse to comply with an advanced declaration?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  An attending physician may refuse to comply with a patient's advanced declaration without incurring liability.  However, the physician must transfer the patient to another physician who is willing to comply with the patient's advanced declaration.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Is a person required to complete an advanced declaration?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>No.  The completion of an advanced declaration is a voluntary act.  Further, no health care provider, health care service plan, health maintenance organization, or insurer issuing disability insurance may require a person to execute an advanced declaration as a condition for being insured for, or receiving, health care services.</BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPA.HTM#N">Appendix N</A>, Termination of Life Support).<P>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="ADV">ADVERTISING</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What advertisements are prohibited by the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Under Alabama Law, a physician is specifically prohibited from advertising any untruthful, deceptive or improbable statements concerning a physician's qualifications or the effects or results of his or her proposed treatment.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the penalties for a prohibited advertisement?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Medical Licensure Commission has the power to suspend or revoke a physician's license for intentionally or knowingly making a false, deceptive, or misleading statement in any advertisement for professional services.  Since it is sometimes difficult to determine whether an advertisement is deceptive or contains improbable statements, a physician may want to have a professional organization, such as the Medical Association of the State of Alabama, review the proposed advertisement.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="ADA">AMERICANS WITH DISABILITIES ACT ("ADA")</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the ADA?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The ADA is a federal statute designed to eliminate discrimination against individuals with disabilities in employment, and ensures access for the disabled to all public accommodations.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What does the ADA require?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Places of public accommodation, such as a physician's office, may not discriminate against individuals with disabilities.  These individuals must be given "the full and equal enjoyment of the goods and services of any private entity that serves the public."  As a result, physician's offices must make reasonable modifications in their policies, practices, or procedures to afford individuals with disabilities full and equal enjoyment of the physician's services, unless the physician can demonstrate that making modifications would fundamentally alter the nature of the goods or services offered or result in an undue hardship to the office.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>How does the ADA address architectural barriers?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A business serving the public must remove architectural and communication barriers in existing facilities where the removal would be "readily achievable."  The ADA defines "readily achievable" as easily accomplished and able to be carried out without much difficulty or expense.  The ADA also requires every newly designed and constructed business serving the public to be readily accessible to and usable by individuals with disabilities.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>How does the ADA affect physician practices?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The ADA affects physician practices just as it affects all public accommodations by requiring the removal of architectural and communication barriers.  The ADA may also affect a physician's employment practices by prohibiting discrimination against otherwise qualified individuals based on a disability.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the employment implications under the ADA?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The employment provisions of the ADA apply to physician practices that employ 15 or more employees.  Title I of the ADA provides that no employer may discriminate against a qualified individual with a disability in the terms and conditions of employment.  The ADA requires an employer to make reasonable accommodations for the known physical or mental limitations of a qualified job applicant with a disability.  If, however, an employer is able to show that a particular accommodation would impose an undue hardship on the operation of the business, the ADA would not require the employer to make such accommodation.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Who enforces the ADA and what are the potential penalties?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>An individual who believes that he or she has been subjected to discrimination in violation of the ADA may bring a private action against a physician's practice, and the United States Department of Justice may also bring suit to enforce the ADA.  Injunctive relief, attorney's fees and civil monetary penalties may be assessed against those who violate the ADA.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What should a physician do to avoid unlawful discrimination against individuals with disabilities?</I></B>

<OL>
   <LI>Inform employees about the ADA and provide training to employees who have occasion to work with disabled individuals.
   <LI>Review existing policies and procedures to ensure they do not single out or discriminate against individuals with disabilities, and revise where necessary.
   <LI>Review job application forms and verify that questions pertain only to an applicant's ability to perform the functions of the job.  In addition, remove any mandatory questions about the health of applicants or about possible disabilities.
   <LI>Review existing job descriptions.  They should list only essential job-related functions.  Also review job standards and criteria.  Employment requirements should be job-related and consistent with business necessity.
   <LI>Review employee benefit plans to ensure compliance with the ADA.
   <LI>Review office architectural and communication barriers for access by disabled individuals.</OL>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="AKS">ANTI-KICKBACK STATUTE</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the "anti-kickback" statute?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The federal "anti-kickback" statute is a broadly worded criminal statute which makes it illegal for anyone to knowingly and willfully solicit or receive (or offer or pay) any remuneration in return for referring an individual to a person (or to induce such person to refer an individual) for the furnishing (or arranging for the furnishing) of any item or service for which payment may be made by Medicare or Medicaid.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Who enforces the anti-kickback statute?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Office of Inspector General and the Federal Bureau of Investigation are the principal enforcement agencies.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What happens if a physician is found to be in violation of the anti-kickback statute?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A physician may be convicted of a felony, fined not more than $25,000 for each violation, or imprisoned for not more than five years, or both.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Are there any exceptions to the anti-kickback statute?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Several exceptions have been made to permit arrangements which would otherwise violate the anti-kickback statute.  These exceptions are known as "safe harbors."  The safe harbors currently adopted include:

<OL>
   <LI>Investment Interests
   <LI>Space Rental
   <LI>Equipment Rental
   <LI>Personal Services and Management Contracts
   <LI>Sale of Practice
   <LI>Referral Services
   <LI>Warranties
   <LI>Discounts
   <LI>Employees
   <LI>Group Purchasing Organizations
   <LI>Waiver of Beneficiary Coinsurance and Deductible Amounts
   <LI>Increased Coverage, Reduced Cost-Sharing Amounts, or Reduced Premium Amounts Offered by Health Plans
   <LI>Price Reductions Offered to Health Plans
   <LI>Waiver of Part A Deductible and Coinsurance Amounts Pursuant to an Agreement Between a Hospital and a Medicare SELECT Insurer</OL>


Additional safe harbors have been proposed and are likely to be adopted in the near future.  The proposed safe harbors include:

<OL>
   <LI>Investment Interests In Rural Areas
   <LI>Investment Interests In Ambulatory Surgical Centers
   <LI>Investment Interests In Group Practices Composed Exclusively of Active Investors
   <LI>Practitioner Recruitment
   <LI>Obstetrical Malpractice Insurance Subsidies
   <LI>Referral Agreements for Specialty Services
   <LI>Cooperative Hospital Service Organizations</OL>


Each safe harbor has its own set of criteria and requirements.  An attorney should be consulted before attempting to create any arrangement which may implicate the anti-kickback statute.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Do the enforcement agencies focus on any particular areas?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  The Office of Inspector General periodically publishes "Fraud Alerts," which describe certain fraudulent or abusive activities and/or arrangements within the health care industry.  The current Fraud Alerts address, among other things:

<OL>
   <LI>Joint venture arrangements
   <LI>Hospital incentives to physicians
   <LI>Prescription drug marketing schemes
   <LI>Arrangements for the provision of clinical lab services
   <LI>Home health fraud
   <LI>Fraud and abuse in the provision of medical supplies to nursing facilities</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>


(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPD.HTM">Appendix D</A>, Anti-Kickback Statute, <A HREF="LEGMDAPD.HTM#E">Appendix E</A>, Final Anti-Kickback Safe Harbor Regulations and <A HREF="LEGMDAPF.HTM">Appendix F</A>, Fraud Alerts).
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="ANTST">ANTITRUST</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What are the antitrust laws?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The antitrust laws were designed to protect competition, not individual competitors.  The Sherman Act, which is the first of the "antitrust laws," was passed in 1890 and prohibits monopolies and restraints of trade.<P>

Early on, the broad language of the Sherman Act led to enforcement problems.  Therefore, Congress passed the Clayton Act, which outlaws specific economic practices that could substantially lessen competition or tend to create a monopoly.  Congress also enacted the Federal Trade Commission Act (the "FTC Act") in 1914, which established a federal agency to investigate and challenge unfair trade practices, including antitrust violations.<P>  

The Sherman, Clayton, and FTC Acts form the core of what are generically referred to as the antitrust laws.  Over the last 100 years, certain industries have obtained special treatment such as the business of insurance under the McCarran-Ferguson Act, local government activity under the Local Government Antitrust Act, and health care peer review activity under the Health Care Quality Improvement Act.  In addition, enforcement mechanisms have been updated and penalties stiffened.  For example, the Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust Improvements Act of 1976 provides the government with advance notice of certain large mergers, so as to enable it to take action (if necessary) before the merger is consummated.<P>

The underlying theme of antitrust law is that free and unfettered competition is beneficial to society, and managed competition causes misallocation of economic resources.  Because of the structure of the health care industry, antitrust considerations play an important role.  Suppliers of health care services have increasingly found it necessary to join together to serve their mutual interests and/or to survive in the rapidly evolving health care industry.<P>  

While an extensive discussion of the antitrust laws is beyond the scope of this book, the basic antitrust prohibitions are set forth below.  If a potential problem is recognized, seek the advice of an attorney experienced in antitrust issues.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<I><U>The Sherman Act</U></I>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Section 1 - Section 1 of the Sherman Act prohibits (joint) action (i.e., contracts, combinations and conspiracies) that unreasonably restrains trade.<P>
Section 2 - Section 2 prohibits monopolization, attempted monopolization and conspiracies to monopolize.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<I><U>The Clayton Act</U></I>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Section 2 - Section 2 of the Clayton Act, as amended by the Robinson-Patman Act, prohibits price discrimination that may lessen competition.<P>
Section 3 - Section 3 prohibits specific activities when the effect may be substantially to lessen competition (for example, exclusive dealing arrangements, requirement contracts, and tying arrangements).<P>
Sections 7 and 7a - Section 7 prohibits mergers, acquisitions or joint ventures that may substantially lessen competition or tend to create a monopoly.  Section 7a requires the parties to certain large acquisitions and other transactions to file a prior notification with the FTC and the Department of Justice concerning the proposed transaction.<P>
Section 8 - Section 8 prohibits certain large companies from having interlocking boards of directors.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<I><U>The Federal Trade Commission Act</U></I>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Section 5 - Section 5 of the FTC Act prohibits unfair methods of competition and unfair or deceptive acts or practices.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What type of conduct generally violates the antitrust laws?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>In order to violate Section 1 of the Sherman Act, there must be an agreement between two or more individuals or entities which unreasonably restrains trade.  Conduct which constitutes an unreasonable restraint of trade includes:

<OL>
   <LI>An agreement between two or more individuals or entities regarding the price of services, commonly known as price fixing;
   <LI>An agreement between two or more individuals or entities to allocate territories or to restrict their own marketing activities, commonly known as market allocation; and
   <LI>An agreement between two or more individuals or entities to refuse to deal with a particular competitor, commonly known as group boycotts.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May a large physician group be considered a monopoly?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  When a physician group develops enough market power to increase and maintain prices above competitive levels, the group may constitute a monopoly.  However, merely having a monopoly does not violate the law.  Rather, the antitrust laws are implicated when a monopoly develops or increases in size through anticompetitive conduct or several competing medical practices merge and exercise monopoly power.  This may occur when most or all of the competing medical practices in an area merge into a single practice.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Are there any antitrust guidelines which address managed care organizations?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  The Department of Justice and the Federal Trade Commission issued a joint statement of enforcement policy and analytical principles relating to health care and antitrust on September 27, 1994.  The 1994 Policy Statement describes the agencies' enforcement policy with respect to physician network joint ventures, including independent practice associations and preferred provider organizations.  In addition, the Policy Statement sets forth various antitrust "safety zones" which describe conduct that generally will not be challenged by the agencies.</BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPG.HTM">Appendix G</A>, The 1994 Statement of Department of Justice and Federal Trade Commission Enforcement Policy on Physician Network Joint Ventures).
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="ASP">ASSET PROTECTION</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>In Alabama, what assets are protected from creditors?</I></B>

<OL>
   <LI>The homestead of an Alabama resident not exceeding $5,000 in value, and 160 acres in area;
   <LI>Personal burial plots and personal church pews;
   <LI>Personal property up to $3,000 (this sum is in addition to necessary clothing or apparel, family portraits or pictures, and family books);
   <LI>75% of wages or other compensation paid to laborers or employees for personal services;
   <LI>Proceeds and cash value of most life insurance policies;
   <LI>Public assistance benefits, including, but not limited to, welfare;
   <LI>Certain pension plans, profit sharing plans, and other retirement plans that meet the criteria set forth in the Internal Revenue Code for "qualified" pension plans; and
   <LI>Individual retirement accounts.</OL>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

<CENTER><H3><A NAME="APA">ASSISTANT TO PHYSICIANS</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>Who is an Assistant to a Physician?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>An Assistant to a Physician is a person who is a graduate of an approved program and is certified by the Alabama State Board of Medical Examiners to perform medical services under the supervision of a physician approved by the State Board of Medical Examiners.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What services may be performed by an Assistant to a Physician?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, an Assistant to a Physician may perform medical services under the supervision of a licensed physician or physicians approved by the Board of Medical Examiners.  However, there are specific limitations which apply to assistants supervised by ophthalmologists.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May an Assistant to a Physician prescribe drugs?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A properly certified and practicing Assistant to Physician may prescribe drugs subject to two conditions:

<OL>
   <LI>The drug type, dosage, quantity prescribed, and number of refills shall be authorized in an approved job description signed by the physicians to whom the assistant is certified.
   <LI>The drug must be on the formulary approved by the Board of Medical Examiners.</OL>

An Assistant to a Physician may not initiate a call-in prescription in the name of his or her physician for any drug which the assistant is not authorized to prescribe unless the drug is specifically ordered by the physician and the order is reduced to writing and signed by the physician within a time specified by the State Board of Medical Examiners.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May an Assistant to a Physician practice at remote sites?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The term supervision, as interpreted under Alabama law, does not require direct on-site supervision of the physician's assistant by a physician.  However, it does require professional oversight and direction as may be required by the regulations and guidelines of the State Board of Medical Examiners.</BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><I>Where can physicians obtain additional information about Assistants to Physicians?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Applications and information concerning certification of Assistants to Physicians are available from the Alabama State Board of Medical Examiners.</BLOCKQUOTE>

