<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/GRYPARCH.GIF">
<CENTER>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="BIL">BILLING</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>May a physician charge a late fee or interest on an unpaid
balance?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Yes. The AMA Ethical Guidelines indicate that although harsh or commercial
  collection practices are discouraged in the practice of medicine, a physician
  who has experienced problems with delinquent accounts may request that payment
  be made at the time of treatment or add interest or other reasonable charges
  to delinquent accounts. However, a physician must comply with state and federal
  laws and regulations applicable to the imposition of such charges. Patients
  must also be notified in advance of the interest or other reasonable finance
  or service charges by posting a notice in the physician's waiting room,
  distributing leaflets describing the office billing practices or appropriate
  notations on the billing statement.
  <P>
  The Council on Ethical and Judicial Affairs encourages physicians who choose
  to add an interest or finance charge to accounts not paid within a reasonable
  time to make exceptions in hardship cases.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>

  <H3>
    <A NAME="BIR">BIRTH AND DEATH CERTIFICATES</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>May a physician obtain a copy of a birth or death certificate?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Yes. The Alabama State Board of Health maintains procedures for the registration
  of births, deaths and stillbirths in the statewide central bureau of vital
  statistics. The records of a birth or death may be obtained for legitimate
  purposes, including determining personal and property rights of an individual,
  establishing age, birth place, parentage, identification, and cause of death.
  In addition, such records may be obtained for research purposes, but strict
  requirements must be met, including filing an application and undergoing
  a committee review for appropriate research procedures and confidentiality
  requirements.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>When must a birth certificate be filed?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A birth certificate must be filed with the local registrar of the district
  in which the birth occurs 5 days after the date of birth. This is unnecessary,
  however, if the infant's death occurs shortly after birth, unless a certificate
  is requested by the father or mother.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="CAN">CANCER REPORTING</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Physicians are required to report the presence of palpable lymph nodes and
  other related diagnostic or statistical information to the Alabama State
  Board of Health in order to obtain uniformity of examinations throughout
  the State and for statistical review and research. A physician must report
  such information on a standard examination and reporting form, and submit
  it to the State Department of Public Health Cancer Detection Program.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="CLI">CLINICS WITHOUT WALLS</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Clinics without walls are physician group practices organized as a professional
  association ("PA") wherein the physicians and/or employees practice in multiple
  offices rather than a single location. Each office is operated as a profit
  center. Generally, the revenue derived from the individual offices belongs
  to the group practice, but is distributed to shareholders in proportion to
  the individual office income.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="CONF">CONFIDENTIALITY OF MEDICAL INFORMATION</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>What sources of law affect medical records?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Federal law governs various confidentiality issues related to health care
  records through its regulation of such programs as Medicare, Medicaid, federal
  grants to substance abuse treatment facilities and other programs. The state
  legislature and state courts create laws and decisions which govern whether
  certain information is considered confidential. Courts in Alabama have also
  placed a duty of confidentiality on physicians which extends to their medical
  records, and legislation has provided for a psychotherapist-patient privilege
  from disclosure.
  <P>
  The Alabama State Board of Health is authorized to regulate certain aspects
  of health care in the State. As a result, regulations regarding the maintenance,
  disposal, and confidentiality of medical records in Alabama have been adopted.
  In addition, the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Hospital Organizations
  ("JCAHO"), requires that a hospital maintain medical records that are documented
  accurately and in a timely manner, are readily accessible, and permit prompt
  retrieval of information, including statistical data.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>Who owns the medical record?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  The question of who owns the medical record is complex and cannot be completely
  answered by identifying one person or entity. All states agree that the tangible,
  physical record -- the paper, strips, and other items where the information
  is recorded -- belongs to the practitioner or facility responsible for compiling
  and maintaining the information. Thus, in a case involving a physician who
  was a member of a professional corporation, a court has held that the
  corporation, and not the individual physician, owned the medical record.
  <P>
  However, the ownership of a medical record is not identical to the ownership
  interest in other tangible property. The owner of a medical record does not
  have unlimited rights with respect to the medical record, and is governed
  by limitations imposed by law and ethical standards.
  <P>
  Although courts have generally held that a patient's medical record is the
  property of the physician or facility that created it, courts have held that
  a patient has a limited property right to such record. This "right" essentially
  relates to access and privacy rather than to ownership.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>Does Alabama law treat medical records as privileged from
disclosure?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  No. Alabama law does not treat medical records as privileged from disclosure,
  therefore they are admissable in court. In the event that a party to a lawsuit
  requests production of a patient's medical records, and the records are properly
  disclosable (<I>i.e.</I>, express or implied consent has been obtained from
  the patient), a physician is required to produce the records, unless a court
  determines that such disclosure is an invasion of the patient's privacy,
  and the patient's right of privacy outweighs the evidentiary value of the
  records. However, Alabama law does treat psychiatric records as privileged
  from disclosure.
  <P>
  Although Alabama law does not treat medical records as privileged from
  disclosure, a physician may be liable for breach of fiduciary duty and/or
  breach of implied contract if he or she improperly discloses patient information
  acquired during the physician-patient relationship.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>When does a physician have an obligation to disclose information contained
in a medical record?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A physician's obligation to safeguard patient confidences is subject to certain
  exceptions which are ethically and legally justified because of overriding
  social considerations. Where a patient threatens to inflict serious bodily
  injury to another person and there is a reasonable probability that the patient
  may carry out the threat, the physician should take reasonable precautions
  for the protection of the intended victim, including notifying law enforcement
  authorities. However, before a physician discloses medical information without
  patient consent an attorney should be consulted.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>Can a patient waive his or her right to confidentiality?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Yes. A patient can expressly waive his or her right to confidentiality by
  signing a consent form authorizing the release of his or her medical records.
  Alabama courts have also held that a patient waives his or her right to
  confidentiality by implied consent when the patient files suit raising issues
  to which his or her medical records are relevant evidence. However, the release
  of medical records pursuant to implied consent can be problematic and may
  expose a physician to liability. Therefore, written consent is always preferred.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>When medical records are requested, who pays the copy costs?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A hospital, physician's office or other legal entity that maintains medical
  records may require the payment of reasonable copy costs prior to delivery
  of the records. This requirement applies to any person requesting medical
  records, except the State Board of Medical Examiners.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>How much can be charged for copying medical records?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  The reasonable cost of copying medical records can be charged, but no more
  than One Dollar ($1.00) per page for the first twenty-five (25) pages, no
  more than fifty cents ($.50) for each page in excess of twenty-five (25)
  pages, and a search fee of Five Dollars ($5.00). In addition, the person
  requesting the medical records can be charged a postage fee and the actual
  cost of reproducing x-rays and other special medical records.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What is a physician's duty to hold patient information in
confidence?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  According to the American Medical Association's Current Opinions of the Council
  on Ethical and Judicial Affairs, information disclosed to a physician during
  the course of the physician/patient relationship must be held in confidence
  to the greatest degree possible. The patient should feel free to make full
  disclosure of information to the physician so effective treatment can be
  provided. Therefore, a physician should not reveal confidential communications
  or patient information without the express or implied consent of the patient,
  unless required to do so by law.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPA.HTM#C2">Appendix C</A>, Sample Authorization for Release
of Medical Information and Records, and <A HREF="LEGMDAPH.HTM#K">Appendix
K</A>, Payment of Costs Associated with Medical Records Requests).
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="CONS">CONSENT TO TREATMENT</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>When is consent not required?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  If a patient is physically or mentally unable to consent to treatment and
  has no known relatives or legal guardian, consent is not required for a
  physician, psychiatrist or psychologist to render medical or mental health
  services. However, two or more physicians, psychiatrists or psychologists,
  after having consulted one another, must indicate in writing that medical
  services are necessary. Further, any attempt to secure consent from a court
  or to locate unknown relatives would delay treatment, thereby increasing
  the risk to the patient.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>When is consent of a missing husband or wife not required?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  The consent of a missing husband or wife is not required for a person (minor
  or adult) to consent to any medical, dental or mental health services when
  the person has not lived with his or her husband/wife for one year or longer
  and the location of the person's spouse is unknown.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>When may a physician treat a minor without parental consent?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A minor may give effective consent to any legally authorized medical, dental,
  or mental health service for himself or herself (and the consent of a parent
  or legal guardian is unnecessary) if the minor:
  <OL>
    <LI>
      Is 14 years of age or older;
    <LI>
      Has graduated from high school;
    <LI>
      Is married, or having been married is divorced; or
    <LI>
      Is pregnant.
  </OL>
  <P>
  In addition, any legally authorized medical, dental, or mental health service
  may be rendered to a minor without the consent of a parent or legal guardian
  when, in the physician's judgment, an attempt to secure consent would delay
  treatment, thereby increasing risk to the minor. A minor may also give effective
  consent for any legally authorized medical or mental health service to determine
  the presence of, or to treat, pregnancy, venereal disease, drug dependency,
  alcohol toxicity or any reportable disease. See also, "Abortion."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>Will a physician incur liability for accepting the consent of a
minor?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A physician who has relied in good faith upon the representations of any
  person that he or she is a minor whose consent alone is sufficient for treatment
  will not be liable for improper consent. However, this does not waive any
  right or cause of action any minor or other person may have arising out of
  any treatment or procedure administered.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="CME">CONTINUING MEDICAL EDUCATION ("CME")</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>What are the CME requirements in Alabama?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Physicians licensed in Alabama must receive at least 12 Category I CME hours
  annually in order to receive an annual registration certificate. Category
  I CME programs are sponsored by:
  <OL>
    <LI>
      Organizations accredited by the Council on Medical Education of the Medical
      Association of the State of Alabama;
    <LI>
      Organizations accredited by the Accreditation Council for Continuing Medical
      Education;
    <LI>
      Organizations accredited by the American Osteopathic Association to conduct
      continuing medical education for osteopathic physicians;
    <LI>
      Organizations accredited by the American Academy of Family Physicians; or
    <LI>
      Organizations accredited by the American College of Obstetrics and Gynecology.
  </OL>
  <P>
  Every physician subject to the CME requirements must maintain records of
  attendance or certificates of completion demonstrating compliance. Each physician
  must certify annually that he or she has met the annual CME requirements
  on a form provided on the annual license registration certificate application.
  In addition, physicians who maintain their personal residence outside of
  Alabama, but who maintain a significant practice within Alabama, must comply
  with Alabama's CME requirements. See also, "Medical Licensure."
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What are the CME requirements for initial licensure?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Physicians receiving their initial license to practice medicine in Alabama
  after June 30th are exempt from the CME requirements for the calendar year
  in which they receive their initial license. Also, physicians who reinstate
  their license to practice medicine after June 30th are exempt from the CME
  requirements for the calendar year in which their license is reinstated.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What are the CME requirements for retired physicians?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Retired physicians who no longer practice medicine but who desire to maintain
  a current license may request a waiver from the CME requirements by writing
  to the Alabama State Board of Medical Examiners. If, however, a retired physician
  re-enters the practice of medicine, in any form, he or she must notify the
  State Board of Medical Examiners within 15 days that he or she is no longer
  retired and that physician must comply with the CME requirements.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="CTR">CONTRACTING ISSUES</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>What is a valid contract?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A valid contract is one which is legally enforceable. If a contract is legally
  enforceable, a non-breaching party may sue the breaching party to have the
  contract enforced. A court will enforce valid contracts either by requiring
  the breaching party to pay money damages or by requiring "specific performance."
  Specific performance requires that the breaching party perform the terms
  of the contract.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What is generally required to form a valid contract in Alabama?</I></B>
<P>
The traditional requirements include:
<OL>
  <LI>
    <B>Agreement</B> - An agreement is made when there is an offer and acceptance
    of terms. An offer is only valid if a reasonable person would believe that
    an offer has been made. An acceptance can be either express or implied.
  <LI>
    <B>Consideration</B> - Consideration for a contract is defined as an act,
    a forbearance, or the creation, modification, or destruction of a legal relation,
    or a return act, bargained for and given in exchange.
  <LI>
    <B>Two or more contracting parties</B> - Two or more parties are necessary
    to create a valid contract.
  <LI>
    <B>Legal objects</B> - The object and purpose of a contract must be legal.
    Courts will not enforce a contract or parts of a contract which are contrary
    to law.
  <LI>
    <B>Capacity</B> - All contracting parties must be competent and be 18 years
    of age or older.
</OL>
<P>
<B><I>What is a non-competition clause?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A non-competition clause is a contractual provision in which one contracting
  party agrees not to compete with the other contracting party for a specified
  duration of time in a specified geographic area. These provisions are often
  found in employment contracts or contracts involving the sale of a business.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>Are non-competition clauses enforceable against physicians?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  No. Alabama law prohibits non-competition clauses which seek to restrict
  the professional practice of a physician.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="CSUB">CONTROLLED SUBSTANCES REGISTRATION</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>What are the general requirements for dispensing controlled
substances?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Physicians who prescribe controlled substances must register with the Alabama
  Board of Medical Examiners, and be issued an Alabama Controlled Substance
  Registration Certificate. This Certificate must be renewed annually. In addition,
  physicians registered to dispense controlled substances must keep records
  and maintain drug inventories which comply with federal laws, as well as
  rules issued by the State Board of Medical Examiners, the State Board of
  Health, and the State Board of Pharmacy.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What constitutes grounds for suspension or revocation of a physician's
Controlled Substances Registration Certificate?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A physician's Controlled Substances Registration Certificate may be suspended
  or revoked for the following reasons:
  <OL>
    <LI>
      Furnishing false or fraudulent material information in the controlled substance
      application;
    <LI>
      Conviction of a crime under any state or federal law relating to any controlled
      substance;
    <LI>
      Suspension or revocation of a physician's federal registration certificate
      to manufacture, distribute or dispense controlled substances;
    <LI>
      Violating the rules governing the practice of pharmacy and the operation
      of pharmacies; or
    <LI>
      Excessively dispensing controlled substances to patients.
  </OL>
  <P>
  Excessively dispensing controlled substances has been interpreted to mean
  that the controlled substances were dispensed for no legitimate medical purpose,
  or that the amount of controlled substances dispensed by the physician was
  not reasonably related to the proper medical management of the patient's
  illness or condition. It is important to note that drug addiction is not
  considered an illness or condition which justifies continued dispensing of
  controlled substances, except in dosages which are gradually decreased for
  the purpose of curing addiction.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What rules apply to the prescribing of Schedule II controlled
substances?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  The prescribing of Schedule II amphetamine and amphetamine-like anorectic
  drugs is strictly regulated under Alabama law. The proper use of Schedule
  II controlled substances is limited to the following illnesses:
  <OL>
    <LI>
      Narcolepsy;
    <LI>
      Hyperkinesis;
    <LI>
      Brain dysfunction of sufficiently specific diagnosis or etiology which clearly
      indicates the need for these substances;
    <LI>
      Epilepsy;
    <LI>
      Differential psychiatric evaluation of clinically significant depression;
      provided however, that such treatment shall not exceed a period of 30 days
      unless the patient is referred to a licensed physician specializing in the
      treatment of depression; or
    <LI>
      Clinically significant depression shown to be refractory to other therapeutic
      modalities; provided however, that such treatment shall not exceed a period
      of 30 days unless the patient is referred to a licensed physician specializing
      in the treatment of depression; or
    <LI>
      For the clinical investigation of the effects of such drugs or compounds,
      in which case an investigative protocol must be submitted to and approved
      by the State Board of Medical Examiners before the investigation begins.
  </OL>
  <P>
  Physicians prescribing Schedule II amphetamine or amphetamine-like drugs
  must also maintain specific records to be made available to the State Board
  of Medical Examiners upon request. The records must include the diagnosis
  and reason for prescribing the controlled substance, the name of the drug,
  dose, strength, quantity of drug, and the date prescribed or distributed.
  <P>
  No Schedule II controlled substance may be dispensed without the written
  prescription of a physician, except when a physician dispenses the controlled
  substance directly to the ultimate user. In addition, prescriptions may not
  be refilled more than six months after the prescription date, or more than
  five times without the physician renewing the prescription.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What occurs upon the suspension or revocation of a physician's Controlled
Substances Registration Certificate?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  If a physician's Controlled Substances Registration Certificate is suspended
  or revoked, all controlled substances in the physician's possession at the
  time of suspension or revocation will be placed under seal. Furthermore,
  no disposition may be made of substances under seal until the time for taking
  an appeal has lapsed or until all appeals have been concluded, unless a court
  orders the sale of perishable substances and the deposit of the proceeds
  of the sale with the court. When a revocation order becomes final, all controlled
  substances are forfeited to the State, and the Drug Enforcement Administration
  is promptly notified of all orders suspending or revoking a physician's
  Controlled Substances Registration Certificate.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>May the State Board of Medical Examiners suspend a physician's Controlled
Substances Registration Certificate without prior notice?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Yes. The State Board of Medical Examiners may suspend a physician's Controlled
  Substances Registration Certificate if the Board finds that there is an imminent
  danger to the public health or safety warranting immediate suspension. The
  Board may suspend a physician's Controlled Substances Registration Certificate
  while simultaneously instituting revocation proceedings. This suspension
  can continue until the revocation proceedings are completed, including any
  judicial review of such proceedings, unless the Board withdraws the suspension.
  What fines may be imposed upon a physician for violating the Controlled
  Substances Statute?
  <P>
  The State Board of Medical Examiners, acting as the certifying board, may
  assess administrative fines of up to $1,500 for each violation of any of
  the provisions of the Controlled Substances Statute or any other controlled
  substances rule or regulation promulgated by the State Board of Medical
  Examiners.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="DEA">DEATH CERTIFICATES</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>When must a death certificate be filed?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A death certificate must be filed with the local registrar of the district
  in which the death occurs within 5 days after occurrence is known or, if
  the place of death is not known, then with the local registrar of the district
  in which the body is found or death is pronounced. In addition, funeral directors
  have special obligations under Alabama law for filing death certificates.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>When must a fetal death certificate be filed?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A certificate of every fetal death must be filed with the local registrar
  of the district in which the fetal death occurs within 3 days after the
  occurrence is known. However, if the fetus has not advanced beyond the twentieth
  week of gestation, a death certificate is not required. The attending physician
  or midwife must sign the death certificate and give his or her address and
  date of signature, together with all available medical information. In case
  of plural fetal deaths, a separate certificate must be made for each child.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="DEP">DEPOSITIONS</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>What is a deposition?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  A deposition is a series of questions which can be answered orally under
  oath or by providing documents which are relevant to the requested information.
  Attorneys use depositions to prepare for trial. Anyone within the court's
  jurisdiction who may have information relevant to the issues at trial may
  be deposed.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What happens when you are asked to give a deposition?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  If you are deposed it is important to be aware that the statements you make
  are under oath, just as if you were testifying in a court of law. Therefore,
  it is necessary to answer all questions truthfully. If you do not understand
  a question, do not attempt to answer, and simply state that you would like
  the question repeated. It is also important to keep in mind that you may
  later be asked to testify at trial. Since your deposition will be under oath,
  any subsequent trial testimony which conflicts with your deposition testimony
  can be detrimental to your credibility. Your attendance at a deposition can
  be compelled by subpoena.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="DRI">DRIVERS LICENSE ADVISORY BOARD</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>What is the Drivers License Advisory Board?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  The Department of Public Safety created a Drivers License Advisory Board
  for advising the director of the Department on medical issues relevant to
  licensing drivers. The Board consists of nine physician members appointed
  by the director and nominated by the Medical Association of the State of
  Alabama.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>Is there immunity associated with making a report to the Drivers License
Advisory Board?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Yes. Neither the Board members nor any physician licensed to practice in
  Alabama will incur liability for providing reports, records, examinations,
  opinions or recommendations to the Board. In addition, any other person acting
  in good faith and without malice will have immunity from civil liability
  for making a report to the director of the Department of Public Safety.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
  <H3>
    <A NAME="EMP">EMPLOYEE/INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR</A>
  </H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<B><I>What is the difference between an employee and an independent
contractor?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  An employee performs services on behalf of his or her employer and the employer
  has the right to control and direct the employee in the details by which
  the employee performs services. In contrast, an independent contractor is
  not subject to the same degree of control by the employer and often works
  in a specialty area.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B><I>What are the tax consequences of improperly characterizing an individual
as either an employee or independent contractor?</I></B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  Should the Internal Revenue Service ("IRS") determine that a relationship
  is one of employer/employee rather than independent contractor, the employer
  is liable for withholding and FICA taxes, as well as subject to penalties.
  Should the IRS determine that a relationship is one of independent contractor
  rather than employer/employee, the independent contractor may have failed
  to pay self-employment taxes. Generally, the IRS uses the following criteria
  in order to determine that an individual is an employee instead of an independent
  contractor:
  <OL>
    <LI>
      Works full time for a single entity;
    <LI>
      Is required to follow specific hours of work;
    <LI>
      Is assisted or supervised by individuals employed by the entity;
    <LI>
      Is engaged in a continuing relationship rather than for a specified time
      or a specific job;
    <LI>
      Must personally provide the services to be rendered;
    <LI>
      Provides services that are part of or integrated in the entity's business;
    <LI>
      Is trained by or at the direction of the entity;
    <LI>
      Must comply with the entity's instructions concerning the job;
    <LI>
      Provides the services on the entity's premises;
    <LI>
      Performs the work in a sequence set by the entity;
    <LI>
      Receives payment for services rendered in regular amounts at set intervals;
    <LI>
      Is required to submit regular reports to the entity;
    <LI>
      Relies on the entity to furnish tools and materials;
    <LI>
      Services can be terminated by the entity;
    <LI>
      May terminate his or her own services at will without incurring liability;
    <LI>
      Does not generally offer services to the public;
    <LI>
      Performs services only to the entity involved;
    <LI>
      Does not have a major investment in the facilities used in performing the
      services;
    <LI>
      Will not make a profit or suffer a loss in connection with his or her services;
      or
    <LI>
      Will receive payment for business and traveling expenses.
  </OL>
  <P>
  Given the aggressive stance by the IRS with regard to payroll taxes, these
  criteria merit consideration when evaluating physician employment or independent
  contractor agreements.
</BLOCKQUOTE><CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER>
</BODY></HTML>
