<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/GRYPARCH.GIF">
<CENTER><H3><A NAME="FEE">FEES AND FEE SPLITTING</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the general rule regarding physician's fees?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Physicians are entitled to reasonable compensation for their services.  Compensation is unreasonable if a physician is not appropriately licensed to practice or if a physician receives fees on the assurance that a manifestly incurable disease can be cured.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May a physician charge different fees for the same service?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Physicians may charge different fees to different patients, but must be careful to honor any contractual relationships in a managed care context.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May a physician split his or her fees received for professional services with a referring party?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A physician should not divide fees or agree to split fees received for professional services with any person for bringing or referring a patient.  See also, <A HREF="LEGMEDA.HTM#AKS">Anti-Kickback Statute.</A></BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="FOR">FORCE, USE OF</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>When is a physician authorized to use force?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A physician, or a person acting under his or her direction, may use reasonable physical force to administer treatment if:

<OL>
   <LI>The treatment is administered with the consent of the patient or, if the patient is a minor or an incompetent person, with the consent of his parent, guardian or other person responsible for his or her care and supervision; or
   <LI>The treatment is administered in an emergency and a physician reasonably believes that no one competent to consent can be consulted and that a reasonable person wishing to safeguard the welfare of the patient would consent.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="GOO">GOOD SAMARITAN LAW</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the good samaritan law?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>When a physician renders first aid or emergency care to an injured person at the scene of an accident gratuitously and in good faith, he or she will not be liable for any civil damages as a result of his or her acts or omissions.  Furthermore, a physician rendering care will not be liable for any civil damages as a result of any act or failure to act to provide or arrange for further medical care or treatment for the injured person.<P>
When a physician gratuitously advises medical personnel at the scene of an emergency based upon information received by voice or biotelemetry equipment, and such actions are ordered by the physician to sustain life or reduce disability, the physician will not be liable for such actions when consistent with established medical procedures.</BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPH.HTM">Appendix H</A>, Alabama Good Samaritan Statute).

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="HIV">HIV TESTING</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What are the general requirements for HIV testing?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Before an HIV test is performed, a health care provider or testing facility should obtain voluntary, informed consent to administer the test.  A general consent form should be signed which specifies the testing for HIV infection by antibody tests or other means.<P>
When written consent for HIV testing has not been obtained, consent is implied when an individual presents himself or herself to a physician for diagnostic treatment or other medical services and the physician determines that a test for HIV infection is necessary for any of the following reasons:

<OL>
   <LI>The individual's medical care may be modified by the presence or absence of HIV infection; or
   <LI>The HIV status of the individual is necessary in order to protect health care personnel from HIV infection.</OL>

Prior to the 1993 decision in <U>Hill v. Evans</U>, the doctrine of implied consent was also available for individuals who, based upon reasonable medical judgment, were at high risk for HIV infection.  This exception to the general requirement of written consent for HIV testing was struck down as unconstitutional because the exception did not protect either the individual or health care worker.</BLOCKQUOTE>
 
<B><I>What is a physician's duty upon diagnosis of HIV infection?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Either a physician ordering the HIV test, his or her designee, a physician designated by the applicant, or the Alabama Department of Public Health must notify an individual of a positive HIV test result. The notification must include:

<OL>
   <LI>Face-to-face post-test counseling on the meaning of the test results, the possible need for additional testing, and the need to eliminate behavior which may spread the virus to others;
   <LI>Information as to the availability of appropriate health care services, including mental health care, and appropriate social and support services; and
   <LI>An explanation of the benefits of locating, testing and counseling any individual to whom the infected person may have exposed to the HIV virus and a full description of the services of the Department of Public Health in locating and counseling all such individuals.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPA.HTM#C">Appendix C</A>, Sample Authorization Form for HIV Test Result Disclosure).


<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="IMP">IMPAIRED PHYSICIANS</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the Impaired Physicians Committee?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Impaired Physicians Committee is a committee of physicians licensed to practice in Alabama and selected by the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners.  The function of the Committee is to evaluate physicians who may be impaired by a physical or mental illness, or by excessive use of drugs or alcohol.<P>
If the Board of Medical Examiners has reasonable cause to believe that a physician is impaired, that person may be evaluated by the Impaired Physicians Committee.<P>
Any report made to the Alabama Impaired Physicians Committee constitutes a report to the Board of Medical Examiners for the purposes of any mandatory reporting of physician impairment required under Alabama law.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Does the Impaired Physicians Committee notify the Board of Medical Examiners of its evaluation?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Impaired Physicians Committee will notify the Board of Medical Examiners of any physician who is unable to practice medicine with reasonable skill and safety to patients, if the physician fails to or refuses to participate in programs of treatment or rehabilitation recommended by the Committee.</BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPH.HTM#I">Appendix I</A>, Alabama Impaired Physicians Committee Statute).

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="JUR">JURY DUTY</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>May a physician be excused from jury duty?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The law does not exempt physicians from jury duty.  However, a judge may exercise broad discretion to excuse a physician from jury duty upon a showing of extreme inconvenience, undue hardship, or public necessity.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="MLIC">MEDICAL LICENSURE</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What are the general requirements for a certificate of qualification to practice medicine in Alabama?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>All applicants must graduate from one of the following institutions:

<OL>
   <LI>A college of medicine accredited by the Liaison Committee on Medical Education of the American Medical Association;
   <LI>A college of osteopathy accredited by the American Osteopathic Association;
   <LI>A college of medicine not accredited but which is approved by the Board of Medical Examiners if the applicant received a diploma after February 9, 1988; or
   <LI>A college of medicine not accredited but whose graduates are eligible for certification by the Education Council for Foreign Medical Graduates, if the applicant received a diploma on or before February 9, 1988.</OL>

If a diploma is based upon training received at a hospital which is not located within the same country as the medical school, or where the director of the training is not directly responsible to the administration of the medical school, the applicant must have the director send a letter to the Board outlining the dates of training, the exact type of training completed and an evaluation of the applicant's performance.<P>

If the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners determines that there exists substantial, credible evidence that a college of medicine or osteopathy located outside of the United States has issued a diploma to an individual who has not attended the residency program, then the applicant holding a diploma from such college must submit the following documentation:

<OL>
   <LI>Documentation of actual attendance at all portions of the residency program; and
   <LI>Documentation of actual attendance and participation in clinical rotations at a hospital affiliated with the college of medicine or osteopathy and offered as a part of the overall program of medical education.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the post-graduate requirements?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>All applicants must have completed one year of post-graduate or residency training in any of the following programs:

<OL>
   <LI>A program listed in the directory of approved residency training programs published by the American Medical Association;
   <LI>A program accredited by the American Osteopathic Association; or
   <LI>A program accredited by the Accreditation Committee of Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons of Canada.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the examination requirements?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>All applicants must achieve a passing score on one of the following examinations:

<OL>
   <LI>The United States Medical Licensing Examination;
   <LI>The Federation Licensing Examination;
   <LI>The National Board of Medical Examiners Examination;
   <LI>The National Board of Osteopathic Physicians and Surgeons Examinations;
   <LI>The Licensing Medical Council of Canada Examination; or
   <LI>Any other examination or combination of examinations currently approved or which may later be approved by the Board of Medical Examiners.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the requirements for foreign medical graduates?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>All applicants who graduate from a college of medicine not accredited by the Liaison Committee of Medical Education or the American Osteopathic Association must: (1) achieve certification given by the Education Council for Foreign Medical Graduates; or (2) achieve a Fifth Pathway Certification and pass the examination administered by the Education Council For Foreign Medical Graduates.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Are there additional requirements for certain applicants?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  All applicants who have not passed a written, state licensing examination, the examination given by the National Board of Medical Examiners, the United States Medical Licensing Examination, the National Board of Osteopathic Physicians and Surgeons Examination, the examination given by the Licensing Medical Council of Canada, the Special Purpose Examination, or the Federation Licensing Examination within ten (10) years immediately preceding the date of their application must either:

<OL>
   <LI>Achieve a minimum score of 75 on the Special Purpose Examination; or
   <LI>Be certified by or achieve a passing score on a recertification examination given by one of the specialty boards approved by the American Board of Medical Specialties or one of the specialty boards approved by the American Osteopathic Association within ten (10) years immediately preceding the date of the application.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Is there an interview requirement?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Alabama Board of Medical Examiners may, in its discretion, require that an applicant attend a personal interview with the Credentials Committee of the Board or a representative of the Board in the following circumstances:

<OL>
   <LI>When the applicant's answer to any question on the application is incomplete or requires additional explanation;
   <LI>When the Board is in receipt of any information concerning the applicant that would require additional information or explanation;
   <LI>When it appears that the applicant may have committed an act constituting grounds for denial of a license.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What is the fee for filing an application?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>All applicants must submit an application fee in the amount of $175.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What is the Board of Medical Examiners' policy regarding applicants who have been treated for chemical dependency, substance abuse or mental illness?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Board of Medical Examiners has a policy of referring physicians with a history of treatment for chemical dependency and substance abuse to the Alabama Physicians Recovery Network ("PRN") for evaluation and a recommendation back to the Board of Medical Examiners.<P>
Referral to the PRN will not be delayed pending receipt of other elements of the application such as verification of medical school and residency qualifications, license verification in other states and test results.<P>
Upon receipt of a referral for evaluation and recommendation from the Board of Medical Examiners, the Medical Director of the PRN will evaluate and examine the information available and will determine what, if any, further information and/or evaluations are required in order for the PRN to make a recommendation to the Board of Medical Examiners on the applicant.  The Medical Director is authorized to communicate directly with the applicant to secure any additional information which may be required by the PRN to complete the evaluation.  In the event the Medical Director is unable to obtain the necessary information or the applicant fails or refuses to comply with requests for information and/or evaluation, the Medical Director will notify the Board of Medical Examiners who will in turn notify the applicant in writing that his or her application will not be considered unless and until a recommendation is received from the PRN.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What constitutes grounds for denial of a certificate of qualification?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Board of Medical Examiners may deny an application on any of the following grounds:

<OL>
   <LI>Failure of the applicant to achieve a passing score on any required examination;
   <LI>Failure of the applicant to complete the application form or to provide additional information requested by the Board;
   <LI>A finding that the applicant has submitted or caused to be submitted false, misleading, or untruthful information to the Board;
   <LI>Failure to appear before the Board or a committee of the Board if formally requested to appear; or
   <LI>A finding by the Board that the applicant has committed any of the acts or offenses constituting grounds for license suspension or revocation.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What acts or offenses constitute sufficient grounds for the suspension or revocation of a physician's license?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Alabama Medical Licensure Commission is authorized to suspend or revoke the medical license of any physician who has been found guilty of any of the following acts or offenses:

<OL>
   <LI>Fraud in applying for or procuring a license to practice medicine or osteopathy in Alabama; or
   <LI>Immoral, unprofessional or dishonorable conduct.
   <LI>Practicing medicine or osteopathy in such a manner as to endanger the health of patients;
   <LI>Conviction of a felony;
   <LI>Conviction of any crime or offense which reflects the inability of the physician to practice medicine or osteopathy with due regard for the health or safety of his patients;
   <LI>Conviction for any violation of a federal or state law relating to controlled substances;
   <LI>Use of any untruthful or deceptive or improbable statements concerning a physician's qualifications or the effects or results of his or her proposed treatment;
   <LI>Distribution of controlled substances to any person or patient for reasons other than a legitimate medical purpose;
   <LI>Gross malpractice or repeated malpractice in the practice of medicine or osteopathy;
   <LI>Division of fees or agreement to split fees received for professional services with any person for referring a patient;
   <LI>Performing unnecessary diagnostic tests or medical or surgical services;
   <LI>Charging grossly excessive fees;
   <LI>Aiding or abetting the practice of medicine by any person not licensed to practice medicine in the State of Alabama;
   <LI>Conviction of fraud in filing Medicare, Medicaid, or third party payor claims;
   <LI>Any disciplinary action taken by another state against a licensee to practice medicine or osteopathy;
   <LI>Refusal to appear before the Board of Medical Examiners after having been formally requested to do so;
   <LI>Making any fraudulent or untrue statement to the Medical Licensure Commission or to the Board of Medical Examiners;
   <LI>The removal of staff privileges of a licensee by a hospital in any state when such action is related to medical incompetence, moral turpitude, drug or alcohol abuse; or
   <LI>Being unable to practice medicine or osteopathy with reasonable skill and safety to patients by reason of illness, inebriation, excessive use of drugs, narcotics, alcohol, chemicals or any other substance, or as a result of any mental or physical condition.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What is unprofessional conduct?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Prescribing or otherwise distributing Schedule II stimulant drugs to any person other than for the treatment of narcolepsy hyperkinesis, epilepsy, clinically significant depression, or brain dysfunction of a specific etiology which clearly indicates the need for such substances.  Additional examples of unprofessional conduct are contained in the regulations of the Medical Licensure Commission.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May a physician be fined for violating the Medical Licensure Commission regulations?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  The Medical Licensure Commission may assess an administrative fine of $2500 for each violation of Medical Licensure Commission rules or regulations.  The Medical Licensure Commission may also issue public or private reprimands, public or private censures, letters of admonition, letters of advisement, and may impose involuntary restrictions upon a physician's license to practice medicine.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the penalties for submitting a fraudulent application?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Submitting a false or fraudulent application for a medical license constitutes a Class C felony.  A physician is deemed to have submitted a false or fraudulent application for a medical license if he or she:

<OL>
   <LI>Submits or causes some other person to submit any materially false, fraudulent or deceptive statement in any document connected with the application;
   <LI>Makes or causes another person to make any false, fraudulent or deceptive statement to the employees, agents or members of the Medical Licensure Commission or Board of Medical Examiners connected with the application;
   <LI>Attempts to give assistance to another or attempts to use the assistance of another in answering questions or solving problems contained in the licensing examination;
   <LI>Attempts to use unauthorized notes, symbols or other items for assistance in answering questions or solving problems contained in the licensing examination;
   <LI>Attempts to use an unauthorized copy of the licensing examination obtained by himself or herself or another person in preparing for the licensing examination; or
   <LI>Attempts to make or obtain an unauthorized copy of the examination or questions of the examination, or retains a copy of the examination or a question of the examination.</BLOCKQUOTE></OL>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="MMAL">MEDICAL MALPRACTICE</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the degree of care owed to a patient?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, in performing medical services a physician's duty is to exercise the reasonable care, diligence and skill that physicians in the same general neighborhood, and in the same general line of practice, ordinarily have and would exercise in a similar case.  In regard to a hospital providing services to a patient, the hospital must use that degree of care, skill and diligence used by hospitals in the community.  However, neither physicians, surgeons, nor hospitals are considered to be insurers of successful treatment or service.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>For insurance companies, what are the medical malpractice reporting requirements?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Insurance companies selling malpractice insurance to physicians, hospitals or other health care providers in Alabama are required to report to the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners any final judgment or settlement resulting from a claim for damages for personal injuries caused by negligence.  The report must be made within 30 days after a judgment in court or agreement to settle the claim, and the report must contain the name of the physician, hospital or health care provider who is the insurance policy holder, the name of the claimant, a summary of the allegations made in the lawsuit, the injuries incurred by the claimant and the terms of the judgment or settlement.<P>
The report, along with any and all information, interviews, reports, statements, memorandum, or other documents produced by the Board of Medical Examiners as a result of any investigation of the subject matter of the report are privileged and confidential.  This confidentiality, however, does not apply to records made in the regular course of business of a physician, hospital or other health care provider.  Furthermore, information, documents or records which are otherwise available from their original source will not become immune from discovery simply because they are presented to or are considered by the Board of Medical Examiners.  <I>See also,</I> <A HREF="LEGMEDNP.HTM#PEE">Peer Review</A>.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>For physicians, what are the medical malpractice reporting requirements?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>During the first 30 days of each year, a physician is required to report any final judgment or settlement to the Board of Medical Examiners which was rendered against him or her during the preceding year as the result of a claim of negligence or performing professional services without consent.  The Board of Medical Examiners keeps a record of all reports and makes an annual review of any physician who acquires two or more final judgments or settlements which exceed a total of $100,000, or four or more final judgments or settlements of any amount during the preceding three year period.  This review is undertaken by the Board of Medical Examiners to determine whether disciplinary action should be taken against the physician.  The Board of Medical Examiners also reviews each settlement to determine if there was an error, omission or negligence by the physician.  If the Board determines there was no error, omission or negligence, the settlement is not considered for the purposes of disciplinary action.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="MWA">MEDICAL WASTES</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What are medical wastes?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>There are seven categories of medical wastes:

<OL>
   <LI><U>Animal Waste</U>:  carcasses and body parts of animals exposed to human infectious agents as a result of the animals being used for the production and/or testing of biologicals and pharmaceuticals or in research.
   <LI><U>Blood and Body Fluids</U>:  all human blood and blood components (i.e., serum and plasma) as well as tissue, semen, vaginal secretions, cerebrospinal fluid, synovial fluid and amniotic fluid.  This category does not include feces, nasal secretions, sputum, sweat, tears, urine or emesis unless they contain visible blood.
   <LI><U>Microbiological Waste</U>:  discarded cultures and stocks of human infectious agents and associated microbiologicals, as well as discarded live and attenuated vaccines, and those animal vaccines which are potentially infectious to humans.
   <LI><U>Pathological Wastes</U>:  all discarded human tissues, organs and body parts which are removed during surgery, obstetrical procedures, autopsy, laboratory, embalming or other medical procedures.
   <LI><U>Renal Dialysis Waste</U>:  all liquid waste from renal dialysis contaminated with peritoneal fluid or with human blood visible to the human eye.  Solid renal dialysis waste is also included if it is saturated with blood or body fluids.
   <LI><U>Sharps</U>:  any used or unused discarded article that may cause punctures or cuts and which has been or is intended for use in animal or human medical care or research.  Examples include hypodermic needles, IV tubing with needles attached, scalpel blades and syringes (with or without needle attached).  In addition, glassware, blood vials, pipettes, and similar items are included if they are contaminated with blood or body fluids.
   <LI><U>Surgical Waste</U>:  all materials discarded from surgical procedures which are contaminated with human blood, blood components, or body fluids.  Examples include, disposable gowns, dressings, sponges, lavage tubes, drainage sets, underpads, and surgical gloves.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>


<B><I>What is the proper method of disposing of medical wastes?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Every generator of medical waste must prepare, maintain and update as necessary a written plan to ensure proper management of medical waste.  The plan should address all of the following factors which are applicable to the generator:
<OL>
   <LI>The type of medical waste generated;
   <LI>Proper separation, packaging and labeling procedures for untreated medical wastes intended for off-site transportation;
   <LI>Treatment methods to be utilized on-site;
   <LI>The transporter of any untreated medical waste transported off-site, including the name, address and telephone number of a responsible person;
   <LI>Storage facilities utilized both on-site and off-site;
   <LI>All treatment-processing facilities utilized;
   <LI>All disposal facilities utilized;
   <LI>The frequency with which medical waste is removed off-site from medical waste generator's facility; and
   <LI>Training of employees.</OL>

In addition, each generator of medical waste must notify the Alabama Department of Environmental Management of the following information:

<OL>
   <LI>The name and mailing address of the generator;
   <LI>The name and telephone number of the responsible person; and
   <LI>The street address, including nearest city, of the generator's off-site facility.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER>
