<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/GRYPARCH.GIF">
<CENTER><H3><A NAME="NDAT">NATIONAL PRACTITIONER DATA BANK ("DATA BANK")</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the Data Bank?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Data Bank is a federally established information source which collects and releases to eligible parties the following information as it relates to the professional competence and conduct of physicians, dentists, and, in some cases, other licensed health care practitioners:

<OL>
   <LI>Medical malpractice payments;
   <LI>Adverse licensure actions taken by state licensure boards;
   <LI>Adverse actions on clinical privileges taken by hospitals and other health care entities; and
   <LI>Adverse actions on professional society membership.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What entities are covered under the Data Bank's reporting and inquiry requirements?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE><U>Reporting</U>: Medical malpractice insurers, state licensing boards (medical and dental), hospitals and other health care entities, and professional societies have mandatory reporting requirements regarding physicians and dentists.<BR>
<U>Inquiry</U>: Hospitals must query the Data Bank in certain situations, while state licensing boards, other health care entities and professional societies are granted discretion with regard to making an inquiry.  Medical malpractice insurers are not allowed to request information from the Data Bank.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What types of malpractice payments must be reported?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Each person or entity (including medical malpractice insurers) that makes a payment under an insurance policy, self-insurance, or otherwise on behalf of a physician in settlement of or in satisfaction of a judgment against a physician must report that information to the Data Bank.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What types of actions must be reported by state medical boards?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>State medical boards must report certain disciplinary action to the Data Bank taken against the license of a physician or dentist based on professional competence or conduct.  Examples include revocation, suspension, censure, reprimand, probation or surrender.  Reportable actions, however, must be based on reasons relating to professional competence or professional conduct which affects or could adversely affect the health or welfare of a patient.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What types of actions must be reported by a hospital?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Hospitals must report certain adverse actions taken against the clinical privileges of a physician that fall within one of the following categories:

<OL>
   <LI>A professional review action based on a physician's professional competence or professional conduct that adversely affects his or her clinical privileges for a period of more than 30 days;
   <LI>Acceptance of the surrender or restriction of clinical privileges while a physician is under investigation; or
   <LI>Acceptance of the surrender or restriction of clinical privileges in return for the hospital not conducting an investigation relating to possible professional incompetence or improper professional conduct.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>When must a hospital request information from the Data Bank?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Hospitals must request information from the Data Bank under the follow circumstances:

<OL>
   <LI>At the time a physician applies for a position on its medical staff, or for clinical privileges at the hospital; and
   <LI>Every 2 years for each physician who is on the hospital's medical staff or has clinical privileges at the hospital.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What types of actions must be reported by professional societies?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Professional societies must report professional review activity which adversely affects the membership of a physician.  Reportable actions must be based on reasons relating to professional competence or professional conduct which could adversely affect the health or welfare of a patient.  Adverse membership actions involving censures, reprimands or admonishments should not be reported.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May a plaintiff's attorney request information from the Data Bank?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A plaintiff's attorney or a plaintiff who represents himself or herself can obtain information from the Data Bank if a medical malpractice action has been filed by the plaintiff against a hospital and the specific physician on whom the information is requested is named in the suit.  Obtaining Data Bank information on a particular physician is permitted only after evidence is submitted which demonstrates that the hospital failed to make a mandatory query from the Data Bank regarding the physician named in the plaintiff's suit.  Information obtained from the Data Bank on the physician can only be used against the hospital and not the physician.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Can a physician challenge a Data Bank report?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  A physician can request Data Bank review of a report when a physician believes the information in the report is inaccurate.  There is a sixty (60) day time frame in which to dispute the accuracy of a report, which begins to run from the process date shown on the Practitioner Notification Document.  It is also suggested that a physician attempt to negotiate with the reporting entity (both before and after submission of the report) to address any concerns.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>If a report is made to the Data Bank, does a physician have a means of "explaining" the report?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  The Data Bank will accept a 600 word rebuttal statement from a physician to explain his or her side of the story.  A rebuttal statement can be filed regardless of whether a physician disputes a report.</BLOCKQUOTE>


<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="NOT">NOTIFIABLE DISEASES</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>Does a physician have a duty to report certain diseases?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  A physician is required to report the occurrence of cases or suspected cases of notifiable diseases to the Alabama State Board of Health.  These diseases are deemed "notifiable" due to their epidemic potential.  The report must contain certain information as set forth by the Alabama State Board of Health.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Is there immunity and confidentiality associated with reporting notifiable diseases?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  A physician making a report of a notifiable disease is immune from any civil or criminal liability.  All medical reports are confidential and are not subject to inspection, subpoena, or admission into evidence in any court, except proceedings brought to compel the examination, testing, commitment, or quarantine of an infected person.</BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><I>What are the penalties for failure to make a report?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>If a physician has knowledge of a notifiable disease and refuses or willfully fails to make a full and prompt report of such disease to the State Board of Health, he or she can be found guilty of a misdemeanor, and may be fined not less than $100 nor more than $500.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the requirements for reporting active tuberculosis cases and cases of sexually transmitted disease?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A physician who diagnoses or treats a case of active tuberculosis or sexually transmitted disease, any administrator of a hospital, dispensary, correctional facility or other institution in which there is a case of active tuberculosis or sexually transmitted disease, any person in charge of any laboratory performing a positive test for active or suspected active tuberculosis or sexually transmitted disease, and any pharmacist dispensing anti-tuberculosis medication must report this information to the state health officer, the county health officer, or their designee.  These reports must include, at a minimum, the name of the patient and the name and address of the physician.  These reports are confidential and are not subject to public inspection, subpoena, or admission into evidence in any court except proceedings brought to compel the examination, treatment, commitment or quarantine of an infected person.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the requirements for testing and reporting syphilis for pregnant women?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Any attending physician who treats a pregnant woman must test for syphilis during the first trimester of pregnancy, the third trimester of pregnancy, and during delivery.  All positive or reactive tests must be reported as a notifiable disease.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Are physician's required to instruct persons on the prevention and cure of sexually transmitted diseases?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  Physicians have a duty to instruct patients treated for a sexually transmitted disease of the methods to prevent the spread of the disease and the necessary treatment.  If a patient afflicted with a sexually transmitted disease knowingly transmits, assumes the risk of transmitting, or does any act which will probably or likely transmit such disease to another person, the patient can be found guilty of a Class C misdemeanor.</BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><I>Are medical records relating to sexually transmitted diseases confidential?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  All information, reports and medical records concerning persons infected with sexually transmitted diseases are confidential and are not subject to public inspection or admission into evidence in any court, except proceedings to compel examination, treatment, commitment or quarantine of an infected person.  However, individual medical records may be released upon the written consent of the patient.  Anyone violating the confidentiality of these medical records can be found guilty of a Class C misdemeanor.</BLOCKQUOTE> 

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPA.HTM#B">Appendix B</A>, Alabama Notifiable Diseases/Conditions).

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="ORG">ORGAN DONATION</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>Who may be an organ donor?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Any individual of sound mind and 18 years of age or older may donate all or any part of his or her body.  The following persons (in order of priority) may authorize donation of a decedent's body:

<OL>
   <LI>The spouse;</LI>
   <LI>An adult son or daughter;</LI>
   <LI>Either parent;</LI>
   <LI>An adult brother or sister;</LI>
   <LI>A guardian of the deceased at the time of his death; or</LI>
   <LI>Any other person authorized or under obligation to dispose of the body</OL>

If the donee (those persons listed above) has actual notice of contrary indications by the decedent or that a member of a prior class is opposed to the donation, the donation may not be accepted.  The persons authorized to make the donation may do so after or immediately prior to death, and donation of a body authorizes any examination necessary to assure medical acceptability of the gift for the purposes intended.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>How may a person become an organ donor?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A person may execute a will providing for the donation, and the donation will become effective upon the death of the donor.  A person may also become an organ donor by carrying an organ donation card on his or her person, which has been signed by the donor in the presence of two witnesses, who must also sign the document in the donor's presence.<P>
When a patient who is not an organ donor dies in a hospital, the hospital administrator, or a designated representative, is required to request consent to the donation of the deceased patient's organs.  The request and its disposition must be noted in the patient's medical record.  Exceptions to the request requirement include circumstances where, based upon medical criteria, such request would not yield an anatomical gift which would be suitable for use, and where, based upon the attending physician's special knowledge of the decedent and/or the circumstances surrounding the death of the patient, the attending physician determines that a request should not be made for an anatomical gift.  Such determination by the attending physician must be noted in the patient's medical record.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>How can a person revoke his organ donor status?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A person may revoke his status as an organ donor by executing a signed statement or orally revoking the gift of organ donation in the presence of two persons or the attending physician.</BLOCKQUOTE>


<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="PAR">PARTNERSHIPS AND PROFESSIONAL CORPORATIONS</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What are partnerships?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A partnership is an entity distinct from its owners wherein two or more "persons" carry on a business as co-owners for profit.  A "person" can include individuals, partnerships, corporations and other associations.  A partnership can own property in its own name, and the owners are called general partners or partners.  Absent an agreement to the contrary, all partners have equal rights in the conduct of the partnership business and to participate in its management.  All partners have authority to bind the business, and a partnership is bound by the acts of its partners who are apparently carrying on the partnership business in the usual manner.<P>
In a general partnership, all partners are jointly and severally liable for the debts, obligations and liabilities of the business, to the extent the business is unable to pay.  In addition, partners have contribution rights against each other and against the partnership if a partner acts properly.  Partners also owe each other a fiduciary duty to act in good faith and deal fairly with other partners, and absent an agreement to the contrary, partners share the profits of the business equally.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What is a limited liability company?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Limited Liability Companies ("LLCs") are a comparatively new corporate structure in Alabama.  The LLC is an unincorporated organization that limits the liability of its owners to their investment in the entity.  In essence, LLCs combine the tax treatment of partnerships with the limited liability characteristics of corporations.  Unlike the limited partnership, there is no need for a general partner who has unlimited liability exposure.  Each of the members in an LLC enjoy limited liability, and unlike limited partnerships, each member can actively engage in the management of the entity.<P>
LLCs must be established and operated in strict compliance with the requirements in the Alabama authorizing statute.  Members in an LLC cannot freely transfer their interests in the same manner as shareholders or holders of limited partnership interests.  Instead, the members must withdraw from the LLC, and receive fair value from the LLC for their interest.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are professional corporations?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The original purpose behind professional corporation statutes was to provide tax benefits for individual professionals; however, tax reform has eliminated many of these benefits.  Professionals may still choose to pursue professional corporation status because it generally limits liability for actions of certain professional and non-professional employees and can provide normal corporate protection against other general liabilities.<P>
Every physician professional corporation should file incorporation documents and an annual report with the Alabama State Board of Medical Examiners.<P>
Physicians may also utilize the standard C-corporation structure.  The principle advantage of the standard C-corporation structure is that it limits the liability of all investors to their initial investment.  Although there are necessary formalities that must be followed in order to establish and operate a corporation, these formalities are not difficult.  In particular, the articles of incorporation must be filed with the Secretary of State.  The corporation must pay franchise taxes, and it must also follow corporate governance requirements to insure that the activities of the corporation are valid.<P>
The principal disadvantage of C-corporations is double taxation.  Profits of the entity are taxed once at the corporate level, and again after they are distributed to shareholders.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="PAY">PAYMENT OF CLAIMS</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>How many days does a health plan have to pay a physician?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>All persons, health maintenance organizations, health insurers, preferred provider organizations and any employer sponsored health benefit company providing health coverage, directly or indirectly, has 25 working days after receipt of a proper claim to reimburse a health care provider.  After this time period, interest at the rate of 1.5 percent per month is assessed against the payor.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What if a claim is disputed by a health plan or insurer?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>If a claim is disputed, the 25 working day rule will not apply as long as the company does the following:

<OL>
   <LI>Notifies the provider within 2 weeks of the receipt of the claim that the claim is in dispute and specifies which items are in dispute; and
   <LI>Pays any undisputed portion of the claim within 30 days of receipt of the claim and makes a timely, good faith effort to resolve the dispute.</OL>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Does a physician have to belong to a specific health plan in order to receive reimbursement from that plan?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>As of the drafting of this book, this question is unsettled.  Under the Any-Willing-Provider law passed by the Alabama Legislature in April of 1994, a health plan beneficiary could assign reimbursement for health services directly to a provider even though the provider was not a member of the patient's particular health plan. This allowed an out-of-plan provider to treat and receive payment for care provided to an enrollee of a particular health plan, such as a Health Maintenance Organization.  The validity of Alabama's Any-Willing-Provider law, however, was challenged in Federal District Court and held to be in conflict with federal law.  In addition, the court held that the law did not apply to Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Alabama because Blue Cross is not bound by insurance industry regulations.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="PEE">PEER REVIEW</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is peer review?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Peer review is a generic term to describe a variety of processes where physicians evaluate the quality of medical care rendered by other physicians.  For instance, credentialing is a form of peer review activity which involves the screening of a physician's application for medical staff privileges with a health care provider, and includes follow-up investigations of a physician's qualifications.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What is the Health Care Quality Improvement Act ("HCQIA")?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>HCQIA is a federal statute passed by Congress in 1986 in response to rising medical malpractice concerns, and the ability of incompetent physicians to cross state lines without detection.  Congress sought to improve the quality of health care by encouraging good faith peer review activity and by creating a nationwide system for reporting peer review findings.  See also, "National Practitioner Data Bank."<P>
To foster peer review, HCQIA provides qualifying health care providers and peer review bodies with certain immunities from anti-trust and other liability for damages that might arise from lawsuits brought by physicians who become subject to adverse peer review actions.</BLOCKQUOTE> 

<B><I>Under what circumstances is a physician-member of a peer review panel immune from liability?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Physicians who serve on a peer review committee (or a committee of similar purpose) and who review any aspect of professional care will generally not be held liable for damages as a result of any action taken or recommendation made as a member of the peer review committee if the action was taken without malice and in a reasonable belief that such action was warranted by the facts.<P>
HCQIA extends immunity from certain liability to actions by "professional review bodies," which are defined as health care entities (hospitals, health maintenance organizations, group medical practices and professional societies) and the governing body or any committee of a health care entity.  In order to qualify for immunity, the review body must take action against a physician based on his competence or professional conduct.  The action must be taken in the reasonable belief that: (1) it is in furtherance of quality health care after a reasonable effort to obtain the facts; (2) after adequate notice and hearing procedures; and (3) with reasonable belief that the action was warranted.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Does Alabama have any peer review statutes?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  There are three Alabama statutes that govern physician peer review activity.</BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPH.HTM#L">Appendix L</A>, Alabama Peer Review Statutes).

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="PDIS">PHYSICIAN DISCIPLINE - MANDATORY REPORTING</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>Do physicians have a duty to report certain physician conduct?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  Physicians are required to report information on other physicians licensed to practice medicine in Alabama whom they believe may be guilty of one of the acts specified as grounds for discipline.  In addition, the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners may investigate any evidence which appears to show that a physician licensed to practice medicine in Alabama is or may be guilty of any of the acts, offenses, or conditions set out as grounds for discipline.<P>
Any person who in good faith makes a report to the Board of Medical Examiners or to the Alabama Medical Licensure Commission will not be liable to any person for any statement or opinion made in such report.  <I>See also,</I> <A HREF="LEGMEDFM.HTM#MLIC">Medical Licensure</A>.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="PEXP">PHYSICIAN EXPERT WITNESSES</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is an expert witness?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>An expert witness may give opinion testimony based upon his or her own knowledge of the facts.  An expert's opinion may also be based upon facts in evidence that are assumed in a hypothetical question posed to the expert.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May a physician expert witness charge for his or her services?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, expert witnesses may be reasonably compensated for time spent assisting a party in litigation.  The amount of compensation may be proportionate to the experience of the individual.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>May a physician expert witness be asked at trial or during deposition how much time he/she spends testifying for plaintiffs and defendants, and how much is earned from such endeavors?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, the total number of times a physician has previously testified as an expert and the amount of compensation received for such testimony may be revealed during questioning.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Is a physician expert witness required to permit attorneys and other legal representatives to be present during an independent medical examination?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, yes.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="PHO">PHYSICIAN HOSPITAL ORGANIZATIONS (PHOs)</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is a PHO?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A PHO is a joint venture between physicians and a hospital to control the delivery and cost of health care services.  Generally, a PHO is a managed care organization comprised of a hospital and all or part of its medical staff which markets both inpatient and outpatient services to purchasers of health care services.  Physician and hospital members typically share responsibility for capitalizing and operating the PHO.<P>
Although the revenue from managed care contracts may pass through a PHO, PHOs are generally not structurally integrated.  That is, physician and hospital members continue to operate separately.  In addition, the physician members typically retain responsibility for treatment decisions, while hospital members manage finances and administer payment systems.  Many PHOs enter into fully capitated contracts and establish internal risk sharing mechanisms designed to foster efficient utilization of health care services.<P>
Some PHOs may employ physicians to serve as consultants or medical directors or to perform utilization review.  PHOs may also perform other administrative services (e.g., operation of billing and information systems) or offer "practice enhancements" (e.g., loans, income guarantees, malpractice insurance premium subsidies, and equipment leases).</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the benefits of a PHO?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>From the point of view of a purchaser of health care services, a PHO can "package" hospital and physician services under a variety of pricing mechanisms.  However, this service is not unique and is accomplished by health maintenance organizations and other managed care organizations.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What issues affect the formation of a PHO?</I></B>

<OL>
   <LI>PHO Control:  From the physicians' side, it is important that a PHO is controlled equally by the hospital and the physicians.  Both parties should have equal control in establishing clinical and service guidelines, as well as establishing the fee structure to be utilized by the PHO.
   <LI>Fraud and Abuse Concerns:  If a PHO is not capitalized equally by the hospital and the physicians, but rather the hospital contributes more than 50% of the costs associated with the PHO, the arrangement could be viewed as a violation of the anti-kickback statute.  Any contribution by the hospital which exceeds 50% could be perceived as a method of providing remuneration to the physicians in return for the referral of Medicare and/or Medicaid patients to the hospital.
   <LI>Stark II Concerns:  A physician's investment and/or compensation arrangement with a PHO may implicate the Stark II prohibitions.  Stark II prohibits referrals by a physician to an entity in which the physician (or a family member of the physician) has a financial relationship for certain services known as "designated health services".
   <LI>Antitrust Concerns:  As with any managed care organization, the development of a PHO which intends to integrate physicians to establish practice patterns and fee schedules raises antitrust concerns.  The primary issues involve price fixing, market allocation, group boycotts and an issue commonly known as the "essential facilities" doctrine.  The last two issues may arise in a situation where a PHO is comprised of less than all the members of the medical staff, thereby excluding some physicians.  If the excluded physicians need the hospital to provide services (i.e., the hospital is an "essential facility"), antitrust problems may develop.  However, antitrust risk depends on the relevant geographic market for the physician services in question and the market power of the hospital and/or the PHO.
   <LI>Development of a PHO is a complicated and serious undertaking.  A physician or physician group involved in PHO formation should seek legal representation from an attorney who does not represent the hospital's concerns.</OL>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="PPR">PHYSICIAN/PATIENT RELATIONSHIP</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>How is the physician/patient relationship formed?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, the physician/patient relationship is formed when a physician agrees to treat a patient.  Since the relationship is consensual, a physician may choose not to treat a patient.  However, a physician's right to refuse to accept a patient should not be based solely on a patient's age, sex or race.  Obviously, some exceptions exist.  For instance, a gynecologist is not obligated to accept a male patient.  Federal courts have also prohibited physicians from refusing to accept a patient who is HIV-positive solely because he or she carries the HIV virus. <I>See also</I>, <A HREF="LEGMEDA.HTM#ADA">Americans With Disabilities Act</A>.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>How is the physician/patient relationship terminated?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Once established, a physician is not free to unilaterally terminate the physician/patient relationship at will.  To do so might constitute abandonment, which means the physician would be liable for any injury resulting from his or her termination of the relationship.  Generally, proper termination of the physician/patient relationship fits into one of three categories:

<OL>
   <LI>The patient has no need of further treatment;
   <LI>The patient voluntarily terminates the relationship or initiates termination; or
   <LI>The physician terminates the relationship while providing the patient with a reasonable opportunity to find alternative care.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPA.HTM#C3">Appendix C</A>, Sample Patient Dismissal Letter).

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="PLEG">PRESCRIBING LEGEND DRUGS</A></H3></CENTER>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"Legend drugs" means all drugs bearing the warning "caution, federal law prohibits dispensing without prescription" or words to the same effect.  Legend drugs must be stored in the prescription department or the prescription department storage room of each pharmacy.  Furthermore, legend drugs may be dispensed only on the prescription of a licensed practitioner authorized to prescribe such drugs.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<CENTER><H3><A NAME="PRE">PRESCRIPTIONS</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the procedure governing the substitution of generic drugs?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, only a licensed physician may substitute generic drugs for a different drug or brand of drug.  In addition, written prescription forms must have two separate signature lines so a physician can indicate his or her decision.  Under one signature line, the words "dispense as written" must be printed, while under the other signature line, the words "product selection permitted" must be printed.  This allows the physician to communicate instructions to the pharmacist as to whether the physician authorizes generic drug substitution.  However, a licensed pharmacist is permitted to select a less expensive drug for the brand name drug prescribed if the less expensive drug is pharmaceutically or therapeutically equivalent to the drug ordered by the physician.  The pharmacist must record on the prescription form the name and manufacturer or distributor of any drug selected and dispensed in lieu of the drug prescribed.<P>
When a physician calls a prescription in over the telephone, he or she should instruct the pharmacist as to whether generic drug substitution is permissible.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER>
