<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/GRYPARCH.GIF">
<CENTER><H3><A NAME="RAB">RABIES REPORTING</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>When is a physician required to report suspected cases of rabies?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A physician having knowledge that a person has been bitten by an animal and has required inoculation against rabies must promptly notify the county health officer or rabies inspector.  Upon receiving this information, the rabies inspector or county health officer must place the animal in quarantine with a duly licensed veterinarian for observation.  The veterinarian under whose care the animal has been committed for quarantine must report the results of his or her observation to the attending physician of the person bitten.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="RAD">RADIATION CONTROL</A></H3></CENTER>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Alabama State Board of Health is designated as the state radiation control agency and given responsibility and authority to license or register any individual, organization or equipment which utilizes ionizing radiation.  The Board of Health develops and conducts programs for evaluation of hazards associated with the use of ionizing radiation.  The agency also maintains a file of registrants possessing X-ray machines or other machines and devices producing ionizing radiation.<P>
The statute providing for state radiation control does not limit the kind or amount of radiation that may be intentionally applied to a person for diagnostic or therapeutic purposes by or under the direction of a licensed physician or other practitioner of the healing arts.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="REP">REPORTING THE LOSS OF HOSPITAL PRIVILEGES</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What types of disciplinary actions must be reported?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Any disciplinary action taken by a hospital against a physician relating to professional ethics, medical incompetence, moral turpitude, or drug or alcohol abuse must be reported to the Alabama Board of Medical Examiners.  Disciplinary action includes termination, reduction or resignation of hospital privileges for any of the above listed reasons.  The report must be in writing and made within 60 days of the date of the disciplinary action.  Reports of disciplinary action by hospitals are privileged from discovery and the individual making the report is immune from liability.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Do professional societies have to report disciplinary action taken against a physician?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  Professional societies comprised primarily of physicians, must report any disciplinary action taken against a member if the action taken is related to professional ethics, medical incompetence, moral turpitude, or drug or alcohol abuse.  This report must also be in writing and made within 60 days of the disciplinary action.  Reports of disciplinary action by professional societies are privileged from discovery and the individual making the report is immune from liability.  <I>See also</I>, <A HREF="LEGMEDNP.HTM#NDAT">Data Bank</A>.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="STK">STARK II</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is Stark II?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Stark II is a federal statute which became effective January 1, 1995, and which prohibits a physician from making a referral to an entity for the furnishing of "designated health services" paid by Medicare or Medicaid if the physician (or an immediate family member) has a financial relationship with the entity.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What is a "Referral"?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A "referral" is defined as "the request by a physician for [an] item or service, including the request by a physician for a consultation with another physician and any test or procedure ordered by, or to be performed by (or under the supervision of) that other physician."  The "request or establishment of a plan of care by a physician which includes the provision of the designated health service" also constitutes a referral.  There are exceptions, however, for certain tests ordered by pathologists, radiologists, and radiation oncologists.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>How does one determine if a referral under Stark II is prohibited?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, there is a two-step approach to determine if a referral is prohibited by Stark II.  First, Stark II only applies for a referral to an entity for the furnishing of a "designated health service" paid for by Medicare or Medicaid.  There are currently eleven "designated health services": 

<OL>
   <LI>Clinical laboratory services;
   <LI>Physical therapy services;
   <LI>Occupational therapy services;
   <LI>Radiology services, including magnetic resonance imaging, computerized axial tomography scans, and ultrasound services;
   <LI>Radiation therapy services and supplies;
   <LI>Durable medical equipment and supplies;
   <LI>Parenteral and enteral nutrients, equipment, and supplies;
   <LI>Prosthetics, orthotics, and prosthetic devices and supplies;
   <LI>Home health services;
   <LI>Outpatient prescriptive drugs; and
   <LI>Inpatient and outpatient hospital services</OL>

Second, if a referral involves a "designated health service" paid for by Medicare or Medicaid, the second step requires a determination of whether the referring physician has a "financial relationship" with the entity to which the referral is to be made.  A "financial relationship" includes:

<OL>
   <LI>Any ownership or investment interest in the entity; and/or
   <LI>Any compensation arrangement with the entity.</OL>
 
(Note that a "financial relationship" with the entity can involve the physician or his or her immediate family member).<P>
If both steps are satisfied (the referral of a "designated health service" paid for by Medicare or Medicaid and a financial relationship with the entity to which the referral is made) Stark II would prohibit the referral unless a Stark II exception is satisfied.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>If a referral is prohibited by Stark II, are there any exceptions?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  There are three categories of exceptions to Stark II.  The first category relates to both ownership and investment interests, as well as compensation arrangements.  The second category relates to ownership and investment interests only, while the third category relates to compensation arrangements only.<P>
It is important to remember that Stark II is an "exceptions" act.  This means that a covered referral is prohibited unless an exception can be completely satisfied.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the exceptions to both ownership and investment interests, and compensation arrangements?</I></B><P>

There are three exceptions to both ownership and investment interests and compensation arrangements.

<OL>
   <LI><U>Personal services</U> - A referral is permissible if the referring physician personally furnishes the designated health services.<P>
   <LI><U>In-office ancillary services</U> - Referrals for services other than durable medical equipment (excluding infusion pumps) and parenteral and enteral nutrients, equipment and supplies are permissible if the services are furnished:
   <UL>
   <LI>Personally by the referring physician;
   <LI>Personally by the physician who is a member of the same group practice as the referring physician; or
   <LI>Personally by individuals who are directly supervised by the physician or by another physician in the group practice; and
   <LI>In a building in which the referring physician (or another physician who is a member of the same group practice) furnishes physicians' services unrelated to the furnishing of designated health services; or
   <LI>In the case of a referring physician who is a member of a group practice, in another building which is used by the group practice for the;
   <UL>
   <LI>Provision of some or all of the group's clinical laboratory services; or
   <LI>For the centralized provision of the group's designated health services (other than clinical laboratory services);</UL>
   <LI>That are billed by:
   <UL>
   <LI>The physician performing or supervising the services;
   <LI>By a group practice of which such physician is a member under a billing number assigned to the group practice; or
   <LI>By an entity that is wholly owned by such physician or such group practice;</UL>
   <LI>The ownership and investment interest in such services must meet such other requirements as the Secretary of Health and Human Services may impose by regulation as needed to protect against program or patient abuse.</UL>
   <LI><U>Prepaid plans</U> - Stark II does not prohibit referrals for designated health services under certain statutorily defined prepaid plans including federally qualified health maintenance organizations.
</OL>
 
<B><I>What is a "group practice"?</I></B><P>

A group practice is defined as:

<OL>
   <LI>Two or more physicians;<P>
   <LI>Legally organized as a partnership, professional corporation, foundation, not-for-profit corporation, faculty practice plan, or similar association;
   <UL>
   <LI>In which each physician who is a member of the group provides substantially the full range of services which the physician routinely provides, including medical care, consultation, diagnosis, or treatment, through the joint use of shared office space, facilities, equipment and personnel;
   <LI>For which substantially all the services of the physicians who are members of the group are provided through the group and are billed under a billing number assigned to the group and amounts so received are treated as receipts of the group;
   <LI>In which the overhead expenses and income from the practice are distributed in accordance with methods previously determined;
   <LI>In which no physician who is a member of the group directly or indirectly receives compensation based on the volume or value of referrals by the physician;
   <LI>In which the members of the group personally conduct no less than 75% of the physician-patient encounters of the group practice; and
   <LI>which meet such other standards as imposed by regulation.</UL>
</OL>

<B><I>Can a physician in a group practice ever receive a productivity bonus?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  A physician in a group practice may be paid a share of overall profits of the group, or a productivity bonus based on services personally performed or services incident to such personally performed services, so long as the share or bonus is not determined in any manner which is directly related to the volume or value of referrals by such physician.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What are the exceptions to ownership and investment interests?</I></B><P>

There are four exceptions to ownership and investment interests.

<OL>
   <LI><U>Publicly traded securities and mutual funds</U><P>
   Ownership of shares, bonds, debentures, notes or other instruments in a company which had, at the end of its most recent fiscal year, or an average during the three previous fiscal years, total assets exceeding $75,000,000.<P>
   <LI><U>Hospitals in Puerto Rico</U><P>
   Designated health services provided by a hospital in Puerto Rico.<P>
   <LI><U>Rural provider</U><P>
   Designated health services furnished in a rural area by an entity, if substantially all of the designated health services furnished by the entity are furnished to patients living in the rural area.<P>
   <LI><U>Hospital ownership</U><P>
   Designated health services provided by a hospital if:
<UL>
   <LI>the referring physician is authorized to perform services at the hospital; and
   <LI>the ownership or investment interest is in the hospital itself and not merely a subdivision of the hospital.</UL>
</OL>

<B><I>What are the exceptions to compensation arrangements?</I></B><P>

There are eight exceptions relating to compensation arrangements.<P>

I.) <U>Rental of office space and rental of equipment</U>
<UL><LI>Rental of office space is not viewed as an impermissible compensation arrangement under Stark II if the following requirements are met:
   <OL>
   <LI>the lease is set out in writing, signed by the parties, and specifies the premises covered by the lease;
   <LI>the space rented or leased does not exceed that which is reasonable and necessary for the legitimate business purposes of the lease and the premises are used exclusively by the lessee, except that the lessee may make payments for the use of space consisting of common areas if such payments do not exceed the lessee's pro rata share of expenses for such space based upon the ratio of the space used exclusively by the lessee to the total amount of the space (other than common areas) occupied by all persons using such common areas;
   <LI>the lease provides for a term of rental for at least one year;
   <LI>the rental charges over the term of the lease are:
<UL><LI>set in advance;
   <LI>consistent with fair market value; and
   <LI>is not determined in a manner that takes into account the volume or value of any referrals or other business generated between the parties;</UL>
   <LI>the lease would be commercially reasonable even if no referrals were made between the parties; and
   <LI>the lease meets such other requirements as may be imposed by regulation as needed to protect against program or patient abuse.
</OL>
   <LI>Rental of equipment is not viewed as an impermissible compensation arrangement under Stark II if the following requirements are met:
<OL><LI>the lease is set out in writing, signed by the parties, and specifies the equipment covered by the lease;
   <LI>the equipment rented or leased does not exceed that which is reasonable and necessary for the legitimate business purposes of the lease and is used exclusively by the lessee;
   <LI>the lease provides for a term of at least one year;
   <LI>the rental charges over the term of the lease:
<UL><LI>are set in advance;
   <LI>are consistent with fair market value; and
   <LI>are not determined in a manner that takes into account the volume or value of any referrals or other business generated between the parties;</UL>
   <LI>the lease would be commercially reasonable even if no referrals were made between the parties; and
   <LI>the lease meets such other requirements as may be imposed by regulation as needed to protect against program or patient abuse.</OL></UL>
II.) <U>Employment relationships</U>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Any amount paid by an employer to a physician (or an immediate family member) who has a bona fide employment relationship with the employer for the provision of services if:
<OL><LI>the employment if for identifiable services;
   <LI>the amount of compensation is:
<UL><LI>consistent with the fair market value of the services; and
   <LI>not determined in a manner that takes into account (directly or indirectly) the volume or value of any referrals by the referring physician;</UL>
   <LI>the salary is provided pursuant to an agreement which would be commercially reasonable even if no referrals were made to the employer; and
   <LI>the employment meets such other requirements as may be imposed by regulation as needed to protect against program or patient abuse.</OL>
The employment relationship exception does not prohibit the payment of a productivity bonus to the employed physician based on services personally performed by the physician.</BLOCKQUOTE>
III.) <U>Personal service arrangements</U>
<BLOCKQUOTE>In general, remuneration from an entity under a personal service arrangement is permissible if:
<OL><LI>the arrangement is set out in writing, signed by the parties and specifies the services covered by the arrangement;
   <LI>the arrangement covers all the services to be provided by the physician (or an immediate family member of such physician) to the entity;
   <LI>the services contracted for do not exceed those that are reasonable and necessary for the legitimate business purposes of the arrangement;
   <LI>the term of the arrangement is for at least one year;
   <LI>the compensation to be paid over the term of the arrangement is:
<UL><LI>set in advance;
   <LI>does not exceed fair market value; and
   <LI>except in the case of a physician incentive plan, it is not determined in a manner that takes into account the volume or value of any referrals or other business generated between the parties; and</UL>
   <LI>the services to be performed under the arrangement do not violate any state or federal law; and
   <LI>the arrangement meets such other requirements as may be imposed by regulation as needed to protect against program or patient abuse.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>
IV.) <U>Remuneration unrelated to the provision of designated health services</U>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Remuneration which is provided by a hospital to a physician is permissible if the remuneration does not relate to the provision of a designated health service.</BLOCKQUOTE>
V.) <U>Physician recruitment</U>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Remuneration paid by a hospital to a physician to induce the physician to relocate to the hospital's service area or to be a member of the hospital's medical staff is permissible if:
<OL><LI>the physician is not required to refer patients to the hospital;
   <LI>the amount of remuneration is not directly or indirectly based on the volume or value of any referrals by the physician; and
   <LI>the arrangement meets other requirements imposed by the Secretary to protect against program or patient abuse.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>
VI.) <U>Isolated transactions</U>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Isolated transactions, such as a one-time sale of property or practice, is permissible if:
<OL><LI>the bona-fide employment relationship requirements regarding the amount of remuneration and fair market value are met; and
   <LI>the transaction meets other requirements imposed by the Secretary to protect against program or patient abuse.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>
VII.) <U>Certain group practice arrangements with a hospital</U>
<BLOCKQUOTE>An arrangement between a hospital and a group practice under which designated health services are provided by the group but billed by the hospital is permissible if:
<OL><LI>with respect to services provided to hospital in-patients, the arrangement is pursuant to the provision of an in-patient hospital service under federal law;
   <LI>the arrangement began before December 19, 1989, and has continued in effect without interruption since such date;
   <LI>with respect to the designated health services covered under the arrangement, substantially all of such services furnished to patients of the hospital are furnished by the group under the arrangement;
   <LI>the arrangement is pursuant to an agreement that is set out in writing and that specifies the services to be provided by the parties and the compensation for services provided under the agreement;
   <LI>the compensation paid over the term of the agreement is:
<UL><LI>consistent with the fair market value of the services; and
   <LI>the compensation per unit of services is fixed in advance and is not determined in a manner that takes into account the volume or value of any referrals or other business generated between the parties;</UL>
   <LI>the compensation is provided pursuant to an agreement which would be commercially reasonable even if no referrals were made to the entity; and
   <LI>the arrangement between the parties meets such other requirements as may be imposed by regulation as needed to protect against program or patient abuse.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>
VIII.) <U>Payments by a physician for items and services</U>
<BLOCKQUOTE>Payments made by a physician are permissible if the payment is:
<OL><LI>to a laboratory in exchange for the provision of clinical laboratory services; or
   <LI>to an entity as compensation for other items or services if furnished at fair market value.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</OL>


<B><I><A NAME="SKPEN">Are there any reporting requirements under Stark II?</A></I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  Under the statute, each entity which provides designated health services for which payment may be made by Medicare and/or Medicaid is required to report the following information concerning the entity's financial relationship to the Secretary of the Health Care Financing Administration, including:

<OL>
   <LI>The designated health service provided; and
   <LI>The names and physician identification numbers of all physicians with a financial relationship with the entity, or whose immediate family members have a financial relationship.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>


<B><I>What are the penalties for violation of Stark II?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>There are several possible penalties for violation of Stark II, including:

<OL>
   <LI>Denial of payment by Medicare or Medicaid for designated health services provided in violation of Stark II;
   <LI>Any person who collects money for a service in violation of Stark II must refund the payment;
   <LI>A civil money penalty of up to $15,000 and exclusion from the Medicare and Medicaid programs for each service billed may be imposed on any person that submits a bill who knows or should know that such bill violates Stark II;
   <LI>Any physician or entity that enters into an arrangement or scheme which the physician or entity knows or should know has the principal purpose of making a referral in violation of Stark II (i.e., circumvention scheme) is subject to a civil money penalty of $100,000 for each scheme and may be excluded from participation in the Medicare and Medicaid programs; and
   <LI>Any person who is required to report information but fails to do so, is subject to a civil money penalty of not more than $10,000 for each day for which reporting is required to have been made.</OL></BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPM.HTM">Appendix M</A>, Stark II Statute).

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="SLIM">STATUTE OF LIMITATIONS FOR MEDICAL MALPRACTICE</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is the statute of limitations for medical malpractice in Alabama?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Malpractice actions must be brought within two years after the incident giving rise to the claim of medical malpractice.  However, if the cause of action is not discovered and could not reasonably have been discovered within two years of the incident causing the claim, the action may be brought within six months from the date of discovery or the date of discovery of facts which would reasonably lead to discovery of the claim, but all actions must be brought within four years after the incident.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Is the statute of limitations for medical malpractice different for minors?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  In the case of a minor under four years of age, the minor has until his or her eighth birthday to bring suit.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="SUB">SUBPOENAS</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What is a subpoena?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A subpoena is a piece of paper generally issued by the clerk's office of any state or federal court requiring a person or entity to attend and give testimony at a certain time or place.  A subpoena can be used to compel testimony in a court of law or for a deposition.<P>
A subpoena can also require a person to produce certain books, papers or documents and is called a subpoena duces tecum.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What does a subpoena look like?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A subpoena is nothing more than a piece of paper issued by the clerk of court which states the name of the court, the title of the action and the action required to be taken.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>How is a subpoena served?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A subpoena may be served by a sheriff, his deputy, or by another person who is not a party to the suit and is over the age of 18.  Service of a subpoena may be served upon a person either personally or by leaving a copy at his or her house with a person of suitable age.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Can a non-party receive a subpoena?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  A subpoena can be served on a non-party to a suit if that person has relevant information or documents.</BLOCKQUOTE>  

<B><I>Can subpoenas be issued for administrative proceedings?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Can a physician refuse to produce documents based on a claim of privilege?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Generally, a plaintiff who sues and places documents such as medical records in issue has been held to waive confidentiality.  However, before a physician produces any medical records, he or she should first request and receive a signed release from the patient.  Without a signed release by the patient, release of the patient's medical records can present some risk to the physician, and the physician should consult an attorney.  In addition, it is important to remember that psychiatric patient records, and records regarding drug and alcohol treatment are afforded greater protection from disclosure.  <I>See also</I>, <A HREF="LEGMEDBE.HTM#CONF">Confidentiality of Medical Information.</A></BLOCKQUOTE>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="TER">TERMINATION OF LIFE SUPPORT</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>What are the legal standards and procedures for determination of death?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Under Alabama law, a person is considered medically and legally dead if, in the opinion of a medical doctor licensed in Alabama, based on usual and customary standards of medical practice, there is no spontaneous respiratory or cardiac function and there is no expectation of recovery of spontaneous respiratory or cardiac function.  When respiratory and cardiac function are maintained by artificial means, a person is considered medically and legally dead if there is total and irreversible cessation of brain function determined by objective neurological testing.<P>
A physician is not prohibited from using other procedures for determining death if such procedures are based on usual and customary standards of medical practice.  Death may be pronounced in this circumstance before artificial means of maintaining respiratory and cardiac function are terminated.  However, under these circumstances death must be confirmed independently by another medical doctor licensed in Alabama.  Physicians are granted immunity from criminal or civil liability if they comply with the Alabama standards and procedures for determination of death.<P>
When organ transplantation is contemplated, there must be independent confirmation of the death by another physician.  Furthermore, neither the physician making the determination of death nor the physician making the independent confirmation may participate in the removal or transplantation of the organ or body part.</BLOCKQUOTE>

(See <A HREF="LEGMDAPA.HTM#N">Appendix N</A>, Termination of Life Support).

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=400><P>
<H3><A NAME="VIT">VITAL STATISTICS</A></H3></CENTER>

<B><I>Who receives reports of vital statistics?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The Alabama State Board of Health has established an Office of Vital Statistics which is run by the State Registrar.  In addition, the State Board of Health can designate vital records registration districts on a county basis.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>What events must be reported to the Alabama State Board of Health, Office of Vital Statistics?</I></B>

<OL>
   <LI>Live births within 5 days of birth;
   <LI>Assumption of custody of an infant of unknown parentage within 5 days after occurrence;
   <LI>Fetal deaths within 5 days after occurrence if the fetus has advanced to, or beyond, the twentieth week of gestation;
   <LI>Induced termination of pregnancy within 10 days after the last day of the month; and
   <LI>Deaths within 5 days of occurrence.</OL>

<B><I>What is the procedure for completing and filing a birth certificate with the Office of Vital Statistics?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>If a birth occurs in an institution (a hospital or facility which provides inpatient or outpatient medical, surgical or diagnostic care or treatment) or in route thereto:

<OL>
   <LI>The person in charge of the institution must complete the certificate, secure the signatures and file the certificate with the appropriate fee obtained from the mother or father as established by the Office of Vital Statistics; and
   <LI>The physician or other person in attendance at the birth must provide medical information and certify the birth within 72 hours.</OL>

If a birth occurs outside an institution, the certificate shall be prepared and filed by one of the following in the indicated order of priority:

<OL>
   <LI>The physician in attendance at the birth or who sees the child within 3 days after birth;
   <LI>Any other person in attendance at or immediately after the birth; or
   <LI>The father, the mother, or in their absence, the person in charge of the premises where the birth occurred.</OL>

For any of the above situations, if the mother was married at the time of either conception or birth, or between conception and birth, the name of the husband shall be entered on the certificate as the father of the child.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Who prepares and files a report when a fetal death or induced termination of pregnancy occurs?</I></B>

<OL>
   <LI>When the event occurs in an institution, the person in charge, or his or her designee; or
   <LI>When the event occurs outside an institution, the physician in attendance.</OL>

<B><I>Are reports of induced termination of pregnancy kept confidential?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  These reports are maintained in strict confidence by the Office of Vital Statistics and are not available for public inspection, or subject to discovery in a civil action except under certain circumstances.  Reports of induced termination of pregnancy should not contain the name or address of the patient, nor any other identifying information.<P>
The Office of Vital Statistics will publish data on induced terminations of pregnancy, but will not release the names of physicians or other individuals involved.  The number of procedures performed by any particular institution or physician will only be released at the request of the State Board of Health pursuant to a civil or criminal action related to licensure, the need for licensure of health facilities or during legal action for failure to report.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>When a death occurs, what is a physician's reporting requirements?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>The physician in charge of the care of the patient for the illness or condition that resulted in death must complete and sign the medical certification and transmit the certificate within 48 hours after receiving the certificate.  If the physician cannot determine the cause of death within 48 hours after receipt of the certificate, the physician should indicate the cause of death as "Pending" and should sign the certificate.  Once the cause of death is known, the physician should forward the cause of death to the State Registrar.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Can a physician obtain information submitted to the Office of Vital Statistics?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>A physician acting on behalf and for the benefit of the person to whom the information relates can obtain a copy of the person's record.</BLOCKQUOTE>

<B><I>Are there penalties for failing to report or properly report an event?</I></B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Yes.  Any person who does any of the following shall be guilty of a felony:

<OL>
   <LI>Willfully and knowingly submits false information with the intent to deceive without authority;
   <LI>Makes, counterfeits, alters or amends any certificate;
   <LI>Willfully and knowingly obtains or possesses a certificate which is:
<OL><LI>counterfeit, altered or amended;
   <LI>false in whole or in part;
   <LI>related to the birth of another person; or</OL>
   <LI>Without lawful authority, possesses any certificate known to be stolen or unlawfully obtained.</OL>

Any person who willfully and knowingly fails or refuses to provide required information is guilty of a misdemeanor.</BLOCKQUOTE>
