<CENTER><H2><A NAME="C">APPENDIX C</A></H2>

<H3>SAMPLE LEGAL FORMS</H3></CENTER><HR>

<CENTER><B>Sample Authorization Form For HIV Test Result Disclosure</B></CENTER><P>

I ________________________, authorize __________________________, M.D. to release my HIV test results to ____________________________________________________.  This authorization shall remain in effect until ____________________.<P>

I release and hold harmless _____________________________, M.D., and the medical practice, their members and employers, for all liability, including for negligence that may arise from complying with this authorization.<P>

The use of this authorization is limited to the following:<P>
________________________________________________________________________<BR>
________________________________________________________________________<BR>
________________________________________________________________________<BR>
_______________________<P>

Signature:_________________________<P>                                                      


Relationship to Patient:______________<P>                                        

Date:_____________________________<P>                                                           
<HR>
<CENTER><B><A NAME="C2">Sample Authorization For Release Of Medical Information And Records</A></B></CENTER><P>

I, ____________________, authorize ____________________, M.D. to furnish medical information and records concerning ________________________ to  ______________________________.<P>

I release and hold harmless ____________________, M.D., and the medical practice, their members and employers, for all liability, including for negligence, that may arise from complying with this authorization.<P>

I understand that the medical record maintained by ____________________, M.D., may contain medical and administrative information from other health care providers.  I also understand that ____________________, M.D., is authorized by Alabama law to charge me for duplication costs incurred in connection with copying my medical records.<P>

This authorization shall remain in effect until ____________________.<P>

Signature:__________________________<P>                                              

Relationship to Patient:_______________<P>                                

Date:______________________________<P>                                                   
<HR>
<CENTER><B><A NAME="C3">Sample Patient Dismissal Letter</A></B></CENTER><P>


Dear ____________________:<P>

I find it necessary to inform you that, effective ____________________, I will no longer be available to render professional medical services to you.<P>

As you are aware, your condition requires medical attention.  Hence, I suggest you place yourself under the care of another physician immediately.<P>

I will treat you until the effective date stated in the first paragraph above.  This should give you enough time to choose another physician.<P>

I would be happy to provide you or the subsequent physician copies of your medical records upon request.  If you are having difficulty locating a subsequent treating physician, please let me know and I will suggest ways of finding another physician.<P>
Signature:____________________________<P>      

Date:________________________________<P>   
<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER><HR>
<CENTER><H2>APPENDIX N</H2>

<H3><A NAME="N">TERMINATION OF LIFE SUPPORT</A></H3></CENTER>

<B> 22-31-1.     Standards and procedures for determination of death generally.</B>

<OL>
   <LI>A person is considered medically and legally dead if, in the opinion of a medical doctor licensed in Alabama, based on usual and customary standards of medical practice, in the community, there is no spontaneous respiratory or cardiac function and there is no expectation of recovery of spontaneous respiratory or cardiac function.<P>
   <LI>In the case when respiratory and cardiac function are maintained by artificial means, a person is considered medically and legally dead if, in the opinion of a medical doctor licensed in Alabama, based on usual and customary standards of medical practice in the community for the determination by objective neurological testing of total and irreversible cessation of brain function, there is total and irreversible cessation of brain function.  Death may be pronounced in this circumstance before artificial means of maintaining respiratory and cardiac function are terminated.  In the case described in this subsection, there shall be independent confirmation of the death by another medical doctor licensed in Alabama.  (Acts 1979, No. 79-165, p.276,  1.)
</OL>

<B> 22-31-2.     Use of other methods.</B><P>

Nothing in this chapter shall prohibit a physician from using other procedures based on usual and customary standards of medical practice for determining death as the exclusive basis for pronouncing a person dead.  (Acts 1979, No. 79-165, p.276,  2.)<P>

<B> 22-31-3.     Procedure where part of body to be used for transplantation.</B>

<OL>
   <LI>When a part of a donor is proposed to be used for transplantation pursuant to article 3 of chapter 19 of this title and the death of the donor is determined as set forth in section 22-31-1, there shall be an independent confirmation of the death by another medical doctor licensed in Alabama.<P>
Neither the physician making the determination of death nor the physician making the independent confirmation shall participate in the procedures for removing or transplanting a part.<P>
   <LI>When a part of a donor is proposed to be used for transplantation pursuant to article 3 of chapter 19 of this title and the death of the donor is determined as set forth in section 22-31-1, complete patient medical records shall be kept, maintained and preserved.  (Acts 1979, No. 79-165, p.276,  3, 4.)
</OL>

<B> 22-31-4.     Liability for acts.</B><P>

A person who acts in accordance with the terms of this chapter is not liable for damages in any civil action or subject to prosecution in any criminal proceeding for his act.  (Acts 1979, No. 79-165, p. 276,  5.)<P>

<CENTER><H6>Return to the Legal Guide <A HREF="LEGMED.HTM#TOC">Table of Contents</A></H6></CENTER>
