<HEAD>

  <META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">

  <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 3.03z">

  <TITLE>WORKERS' COMP REGULATIONS ADOPTED</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY background="../pics/PARCH.GIF">

<P>

<CENTER>

  <U><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">WORKERS' COMP</FONT></B></U>

</CENTER>

<P ALIGN=Center>

<U><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">REGULATIONS ADOPTED<BR>

</FONT></B></U>

<CENTER>

  <P ALIGN=Left>

  <BR>

  <FONT SIZE=3>The Alabama Department of Industrial Relations, in conjunction

  with the Workers' Compensation Medical Services Board, has given final approval

  to utilization management and bill screening regulations applicable to workers'

  compensation claims state wide. These regulations, which became effective

  September 12, 1996, establish procedures for the conduct of utilization review

  and bill screening by insurers, claims administrators, third party payers

  and employers who undertake utilization review and/or bill screening of claims

  for medical services in workers compensation cases. The regulations govern

  many aspects of claims adjudication including submission of claims by physicians

  and other providers, timely payment of undisputed medical claims,

  pre-certification requirements and procedures, second surgical opinions,

  and the qualifications of personnel engaged in clinical review. </FONT>

</CENTER>

<P ALIGN=Left>

<FONT SIZE=3>Undisputed claims for medical services must be paid to the provider

within twenty-five working days of receipt of a claim in the approved form.

The payer may request additional documentation which can delay the beginning

of the twenty-five working day limit. If there is a dispute regarding the

legitimacy of the claim for medical services, the employer or his agent must

notify the provider within two weeks that the claim is in dispute, specify

which items of service are in dispute and pay any undisputed portion of the

claim.</FONT>

<P ALIGN=Left>

<FONT SIZE=3>Utilization review can take place at three levels, first level

clinical review (nurse review), second level clinical review (medical director

or physician consultant), and third level clinical review (peer clinical

review). At the request of an attending physician or other ordering provider,

a non-certification or denial of payment for medical services made at the

second level clinical review must be referred for peer clinical review. Third

level clinical reviewers must be either in active practice (standard appeal)

or licensed to practice (expedited appeal) and be board certified in the

same or similar specialty as the ordering physician whose medical services

are being non-certify or denied. Standard appeals must be decided within

thirty days and provision is made for expedited appeals in emergency situations.

In every case the ordering physician is entitled to receive upon request

an explanation of the clinical basis for the denial.</FONT>

<P ALIGN=Left>

<FONT SIZE=3>Physicians desiring to obtain a copy of the utilization management

and bill screening regulations for workers' compensation claims should contact

the Workers' Compensation Division of the Alabama Department of Industrial

Relations at 334-343-3868.<BR>

</FONT><P> 

<CENTER><H4>Back to <A HREF="LEG.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">Legal Update.</A></H4></CENTER>
