<HEAD><TITLE>Getting Involved in the AMA</TITLE>
<LINK REV="MADE" HREF="../index.html"></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../pics/PARCH.GIF">
<H1><CENTER>GETTING INVOLVED IN YOUR AMA</CENTER></H1><P>

<I><B>Making a difference.  Strengthening the medical profession.  Ensuring health system reform that benefits your patients.  Creating a brighter future for you and your colleagues. </B></I> These are only some of the reasons one might consider a leadership role in organized medicine.  The American Medical Association is <B>your organization</B>, and by getting involved you can help shape its future, as well as the future of the medical profession in general.<P>

The AMA Young Physicians Section (AMA-YPS) was formed in 1986.  Among its goals are to facilitate the development of young physician leaders within the Association.  It does this through a variety of means, including:
<UL>
<LI>offering leadership development seminars at its Annual and Interim Meetings;
<LI>facilitating the "mainstreaming" of young physicians by encouraging qualified candidates to run for AMA councils and  committees, as well as leadership positions in state, county, and specialty societies;
<LI>nominating and/or endorsing qualified candidates aspiring to leadership positions; and
<LI>working toward a position for a young physician on the AMA Board of Trustees.
</UL>
This manual was conceived by the AMA-YPS Governing Council to help further the Section's goals.  It briefly describes the leadership positions available within the AMA to physician members of all ages.  It also outlines the considerations one needs to make, and the steps one needs to take, when aspiring to office.<P>

What are <B>not</B> covered in this booklet are positions on the AMA-YPS Governing Council or AMA-YPS Assembly Convention Committees; information on these openings is available by contacting the AMA Department of Young Physician Services.  Also not included is information on how to represent your state medical society or national medical specialty society as a delegate or alternate delegate to the AMA House of Delegates, since qualifications and election processes are determined by the individual state or specialty society.<P>

The Governing Council hopes that this publication will be helpful to young physicians aspiring to AMA office.  Furthermore, the Governing Council members are willing to work directly with any young physician interested in seeking a leadership position.  Also, the council can provide advice on strategies specific to the position being sought. Let us hear from you!<P><P>
<B>Original Editor: Janice J. Robertson</B><P><HR>
<H4><CENTER><B><I><A NAME="TOC">TABLE OF CONTENTS</A></I></B></CENTER></H4><P>
