<H3><I><CENTER><A NAME="GCS">GENERAL CAMPAIGN STRATEGIES</A></CENTER></I></H3>
        
The Department of Young Physician Services and the Governing Council have developed this fact sheet to aid those representatives who are interested in running for office but may not know where to begin.  The Governing Council would be most interested in talking with any young physician who is interested in seeking an AMA office, and can advise as to the strategy most specific to the position being sought.
<UL>
   <LI><B>Talk to the AMA-YPS Governing Council. </B> The Council is willing to advise you as to the specific steps you need to take, and advise you on a strategy most appropriate to the office being sought.<P>
   <LI><B>Contact your state and specialty societies and tell them of your decision to run for a national office.  Obtain their support and/or endorsement for your candidacy. </B> Even if the society is unable or unwilling to provide funding, it may have experience in running other campaigns.  This experience can be lent to your candidacy.<P>
   <LI><B>Evaluate yourself </B>and your strengths and weaknesses. Evaluate not only from your point of view, but also that of the prospective voter.  Play strongly to your perceived strengths.  Don't proactively defend your perceived weaknesses, but be able to respond to any questions regarding them.<P>
   <LI><B>Get as well known as possible prior to declaring your candidacy. </B> Volunteer to monitor a House reference committee for the AMA-YPS; volunteer to testify on AMA-YPS policy if needed; volunteer to staff the YPS Central Booth--this makes you visible to those attending the House of Delegates meeting.  Invite your friends and colleagues to stop by to visit and pick up literature.<P>
   <LI><B>Network at every opportunity. </B> Introduce yourself to other young physicians.  Collect business cards.  Attend your state or specialty caucuses and regional get-togethers.  Actively participate in special caucuses or strategy sessions, i.e., women in medicine, managed care, group practice physicians, hospital medical staff.  Attend section council meetings.  Go to your state delegation breakfasts and lunches.  Contact your delegation head to get a schedule of group social functions and outings, and participate in as many as possible.  Attend all social functions and receptions.<P>
   <LI><B>Identify a small group of supportive physicians</B> who are willing to campaign on your behalf.  Brief them on your perception of the key issues you have identified and how you stand on them.  Ask them to call other friends who may be supportive of your candidacy to start the network going.<P>
   <LI><B>Update your CV and prepare a statement of interest. </B> For the AMA Board and councils, prepare your statement for inclusion in the official election manual.<P>
   <LI><B>During the House or Delegates</B> meeting, ask your colleagues to introduce you to their colleagues.  Attend every delegation caucus you can to become recognized.  Prepare brief remarks and be prepared to answer questions.<P>
   <LI><B>Prepare your speech well in advance</B> and practice giving it prior to the meeting.  Adequate preparation will allow you to give a speech that effectively communicates your personality as well as your stances on the issues.  You might also wish to take advantage of any speaker training seminars offered by the AMA, your state medical society, or your community.  At the Annual Meeting, each Board candidate has an opportunity to address the AMA-YPS and other sections.<P>
   <LI><B>There is no substitute for personal one-on-one contact. </B> Let potential voters know the plans you have made to make time available in your practice to devote the duties of your office.  Do not pressure them for commitment to vote for you if they hesitate; rather, make a note and return to them later on in the meeting to see if they have changed their minds or have any other questions.  If it is clear they are supporting an opponent, thank them for their time and move on.<P>
   <LI><B>Sign up for the AMPAC Campaign School. </B> This week-long school, while focused on campaigns for political office outside of medicine, gives insights and training that can make the difference between a victory celebration and a narrow defeat.  At a minimum, you'll have a new understanding and awareness of how campaign goals and decisions are made.
   <LI><B>Talk to everyone; don't ignore anyone. </B> Every contact you make and every voter you gain can translate into more support and more votes.  Everyone is a potential voter, and the one voter you ignore could cost you more than just that one vote.<P>
</UL>
<B>Running for office is a valuable experience, win or lose. </B> The experience gained from any campaign, no matter how all, will come in handy in the years to come.  Have fun and try hard to win, but remember that the race itself is valuable.  No matter what the results of the election are, physicians are all working for the same cause and will continue to work together for many years to come.<P><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER><HR>

<H3><I><CENTER><A NAME="TCC">ELECTION GUIDELINES FOR TRUSTEE AND COUNCIL CANDIDATES</A></CENTER></I></H3>
  
The following guidelines were recommended by the Convention Committee on Rules and Credentials in 1992 and were subsequently adopted by the House of Delegates.
<UL>
   <LI><B>There should be no formal campaign activities during the Interim Meeting.</B>  This would not preclude distribution of a declaration of candidacy on the last day of the Annual Meeting or one announcement of candidacy by a mailing prior to the Interim Meeting. This rule would prohibit campaign parties and the distribution of campaign literature and gifts at the Interim Meeting.<P>
   <LI><B>On Thursday of the Annual Meeting, an announcement of a candidate that has been produced by the candidate can be distributed to the House of Delegates.</B><P>
   <LI><B>There will be only one big party at the Annual Meeting financed by a coalition or a state or special delegation irrespective of the number of candidates from that society or coalition.</B> This would limit a candidate to only one big party at the Annual Meeting whether financed by a coalition or a state or specialty delegation. This would also limit a state or specialty society or coalition to one big party irrespective of the number of candidates from that society or coalition.<P>
   <LI><B>Displays of campaign posters, signs and literature in public areas of the hotel in which Annual Meetings are held are prohibited.</B>  Displays of such materials detract from the dignity of the position being sought and are unsightly.  Campaign posters may be displayed at the campaign parties and campaign literature may be distributed in the non-official business folder for members of the House of Delegates.<P>
   <LI><B>A reduction in the volume of the telephone calls from candidates, literature and letters by or on behalf of candidates should be encouraged.</B> The Election Manual was initiated as a mechanism to reduce the number of telephone calls and mailings members of the House of Delegates receive from or on behalf of candidates. The Election Manual provides an equal opportunity for each candidate to present the material he or she considers important to bring before the members of the House of Delegates and should relieve the need for the additional expenditures incurred in making non-scheduled telephone calls and duplicative mailings.<P>
   <LI><B>Campaign gifts can be distributed at only the Annual Meeting in the non-official business folder and at one campaign party.</B>  Gifts should not be mailed to delegates and alternate delegates in advance of the meeting.<P>
</UL>
<P><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER><HR>
<CENTER><H3><I><A NAME="BOT">AMA BOARD OF TRUSTEES</A></I></H3></CENTER><P>

The AMA Board of Trustees is elected by the AMA House of Delegates.  The Board has ultimate responsibility for setting Association priorities, and for making decisions regarding how to allocate the Association's financial resources.  Also among its responsibilities are interpreting and implementing policies established by the House, issuing reports on issues referred to it by the House, and reviewing reports prepared by AMA councils.<P>

AMA officers/trustees represent the Association before governmental agencies and national and international health-related organizations, as well as at policy forums, public information meetings, and media relations events.  They also appear before various Federation audiences (state, county, and specialty societies), alliances, civic groups, medical schools, group practices, and business organizations.  Trustees also testify on legislative and regulatory issues before congressional committees and federal agencies.<P>

With regard to organization of the Board itself, the AMA Bylaws simply require that "immediately following the conclusion of the annual convention, the Board shall organize by electing a chair, a vice chair, a secretary-treasurer, and committees necessary for its functions." The Bylaws also call for the election of an executive committee of at least three members.  Beyond that, the Bylaws are silent on the internal organization of the Board and the process by which the Board determines its operating rules and procedures.  The presumption is that such consideration is best determined by the Board itself in response to needs and circumstances at a particular time.<P>

<H4><I>Membership</I></H4>

<UL>
   <LI>The AMA-BOT consists of <B>seventeen</B> members, including designated positions for a resident physician, and a medical student.  The Speaker and Vice Speaker serve as <I>ex officio</I>, nonvoting members.<P>
   <LI>Trustees are elected "at large" rather than as representatives of specific groups (except for the resident and student trustees).  With the exception of the student trustee, all trustees are elected by the House of Delegates.<P>
   <LI>Members of the Board of Trustees must resign all other positions held by them in the Association upon their election to the Board.  No person, while on the Board, shall be a delegate or an alternate delegate to the House of Delegates (the Speaker and Vice Speaker retain their positions as delegates).
</UL>
<H4><I>Term/Tenure of Non-Resident/Non-Student Trustees</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Term of three years; maximum tenure of three full terms.
</UL>
<H4><I>Time Commitment</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>The AMA-BOT meets a minimum of four times a year.<P>
   <LI>If a Trustee misses six consecutive Board meetings, this will be reported to the House and the office will be considered vacant.<P>
   <LI>The time commitment away from home may range from 35 to 150 days, with the average time anticipated for a newly elected officer at approximately 50 days per year.<P>
   <LI>Board positions include honoraria and per them compensation, expense reimbursement, and AMA-paid premiums for term life insurance.  The underlying principle in setting Board compensation levels is to reimburse officers and trustees for time spent on AMA business with the general result of neither profit nor loss to them.
</UL>
<H4><I>Qualifications</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>All Trustees must have been an Active AMA member for at least two years immediately prior to election.<P>
   <LI>Commitment to service.<P>
   <LI>Time available to discharge the duties of office.<P>
</UL>
Young physicians who are devoting large amounts of time to practice development must reflect seriously on whether they have enough time available to fulfill the duties of a prospective elected position.  Family and collegial support is also essential, as the duties of the various offices often occur on weekends or during time normally spent at home or in the office.<P>
<H4><I>Elections</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Each candidate for the Board of Trustees must be nominated by a member of the House of Delegates.<P>
   <LI>Trustee elections are held at the Annual Meeting.<P>
   <LI>An election manual is produced prior to the Annual Meeting, which contains information on all candidates for the Board of Trustees.  Candidates and their sponsoring societies prepare text and submit copy for publication.  It also is suggested that information concerning sponsoring and endorsing societies be included.  Also suggested for inclusion is information from the candidate as to relevant biographical information, and, if desired, a personal statement.<P>
   <LI>Two-minute nominating speeches for trustees are presented during the Sunday opening session of the AMA House of Delegates Annual Meeting.  Also, Trustees may avail themselves of opportunities to address the various Sections during the Annual Meeting.
</UL><P><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER><HR>
<CENTER><H3><I><A NAME="COUN">AMA COUNCILS</A></I></H3></CENTER>
There are seven AMA councils whose functions are specified by AMA Bylaws.  Each is comprised of member physicians, plus designated seats for resident physician and medical student representatives.  The AMA-YPS has chosen not to seek a "slotted" seat for AMA councils, believing that such a slot would be detrimental rather than helpful to young physician interests.  Rather, the AMA-YPS advocates "mainstreaming" of young physicians at this level of leadership.<P>

The AMA prepares and distributes annually a demographic analysis of the councils, with a comparison to the physician population overall and the AMA physician membership.  State and specialty societies (in nominating or sponsoring candidates); the House of Delegates (in electing council members); and the Board of Trustees, the Speakers and the President (in appointing or nominating physicians for service on AMA councils or in other leadership positions), are urged to consider the need to enhance and promote diversity.  This includes not only the representation of women, young physicians, international medical graduates, and minorities, but also the areas of substantive expertise needed on
the councils.<P>

<H4><I>General Information</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>All council members are reimbursed in accordance with AMA policy for expenses incurred in conjunction with their attendance at council meetings.<P>
   <LI>Each council selects its own chair and vice-chair and may adopt such rules and regulations as it deems necessary and appropriate, subject to approval by the Board.
</UL>
<H4><I>The Councils</I></H4>
More specific details regarding each of the following councils are discussed on the following pages:
<UL>
   <LI>Council on Constitution and Bylaws
   <LI>Council on Ethical and Judicial Affairs
   <LI>Council on Legislation
   <LI>Council on Long Range Planning and Development
   <LI>Council on Medical Education
   <LI>Council on Medical Service
   <LI>Council on Scientific Affairs
</UL><P>
Where a young physician has been appointed or elected to a council, that information has been indicated, since a young physician may be able to provide other young physicians with special insights into the position's demands and help identify strategies in terms of successful campaigns.  If more information about a specific council is needed, the AMA Department of Young Physician Services can give you the name of the council secretary, who can provide you with names and addresses of all council members, meeting dates, and copies of council reports.<P>
<P><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
<H3><A NAME="CCB">Council on Constitution and Bylaws (CC&B)</A></H3>
The functions of CC&B are to serve as a fact-finding and advisory committee on matters pertaining to the Constitution and Bylaws. The Council recommends such changes in the Constitution and Bylaws as it deems appropriate for action by the House of Delegates.<P>
<H4><I>General Information</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>The Council consists of <B>eight</B> members, including a resident and a student.  In addition, the Speaker and Vice Speaker of the House of Delegates serve as ex officio members without the right to vote.<P>
   <LI>The Board of Trustees nominates eligible members for each vacancy; further nominations may be made from the floor of the House.<P>
   <LI>The AMA-YPS Governing Council can endorse the nomination of a young physician campaigning for election to this Council.  <B>To have a nomination endorsed by the Governing Council, a candidate must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency).</B>  AMA-YPS Assembly members may actively campaign for a young physician candidate.<P>
   <LI>Members are elected by the House of Delegates at the Annual Meeting.<P>
   <LI>Term of three years; no more than two terms.<P>
   <LI>Four meetings per year:
   <UL>
   <LI>March/April: 1 1/2 day meeting (Saturday, Sunday)
   <LI>June: the Friday before the Annual Meeting
   <LI>September/October: I 1/2 day meeting (Saturday, Sunday)
   <LI>December: the Friday before the Interim Meeting.
   </UL>
   <LI>All meetings held in Chicago with the exception of the meeting preceding the Interim Meeting.<P>
</UL>
<H4><I>General Qualifications</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind;<P>
   <LI>Involvement with the Council while a medical student or a resident physician may be helpful but is not a requisite for Governing Council support.
</UL><P><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
<H3><A NAME="CEJ">Council on Ethical and Judicial Affairs (CEJA)</A></H3>

CEJA has original jurisdiction in all questions involving the Principals of Medical Ethics of the AMA and the constitution, bylaws and rules of the Association.  Its functions are: (1) to interpret the Principles of Medical Ethics; (2) to interpret the Constitution, Bylaws, and rules of the Association; (3) to investigate general ethical conditions and all matters pertaining to the relations of physicians to one another or to the public, and to make recommendations; (4) to receive appeals filed by applicants who allege that they, because of color, creed, race, religion, ethnic origin, national origin, or sex, have been unfairly denied membership in a state or specialty society; (5) to request that the President appoint investigating juries to which CEJA can refer complaints or evidences of unethical conduct which in its judgment are of greater than local concern; and (6) to approve applications and nominate candidates for affiliate AMA membership.  Additionally, the Council resolves all questions involving membership and conflicts between two or more state associations or their members.  The Council reports to the House of Delegates through the AMA Board of Trustees.<P>
<UL>
   <LI>Members are elected at the Annual Meeting by the House of Delegates on nomination by the President.  State medical associations, national medical specialty societies, special AMA sections, other organizations represented in the HOD, and Trustees may submit the names and qualifications of candidates for the President's consideration.<P>
   <LI>The AMA-YPS Governing Council may endorse the candidacy of a young physician nominated by a state medical society or national medical specialty society.  <B>To have a nomination endorsed by the Governing Council, a candidate must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency).</B><P>
   <LI>The Council consists of nine members, including a resident and a student.<P>
   <LI>Members must resign all other positions held by them in the AMA on their election to the Council.  No CEJA member can be a delegate or alternate to the AMA-HOD, a general officer, or serve on any council, committee or section governing council.<P>
   <LI>Term of seven years (for those other than the student/resident); one term only.<P>
   <LI>Six meetings per year (every two months), all 1 1/2 days each, usually Saturday/Sunday, except for:
<UL><LI>June: Friday/Saturday before the Annual Meeting
   <LI>December: Friday/Saturday before the Interim Meeting.</UL>
</UL>
<H4><I>General Qualifications</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind;<P>
   <LI>Involvement with the Council while a medical student or a resident physician may be helpful but is not a requisite for Governing Council support.<P><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
</UL>
<H3><A NAME="COL">Council on Legislation (COL)</A></H3>
COL's functions are as follows: (1) to review proposed federal legislation and recommend appropriate action in accordance with AMA policy; (2) recommend changes in existing policy when necessary to accomplish effective legislative goals; (3) to serve as a reference council through which all legislative issues are channeled prior to final consideration by the Board; (4) to maintain constant surveillance over the legislation scene and to anticipate future legislative needs; (5) to recommend to the Board new federal legislation and legislation to modify existing laws of interest to the Association; (6) to monitor the development and issuance of federal regulations; and (7) to develop models for state legislation.  It reports to the House of Delegates through the Board of Trustees.<P>
<UL>
   <LI>The Council consists of <B>twelve</B> voting members, including a resident and a student.  It also includes, as observers, representatives of the American Medical Association Alliance and American Medical Political Action Committee.<P>
   <LI>Members are appointed by the Board of Trustees from among the nominations made by state medical associations, national medical specialty societies, and special AMA sections.<P>
   <LI>The AMA-YPS Governing Council also may submit the names of qualified young physician candidates.  The Council also may consider supporting the candidacy of a young physician nominated by a state medical society or a national medical specialty society.  <B>To have a nomination endorsed by the Governing Council, a candidate must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency).</B>  In the case of an official AMA-YPS nomination, the Governing Council may also apply other criteria.<P>
   <LI>One year terms (beginning on July 1 of each year); no more than six terms.<P>
   <LI>At least five weekend meetings are held a year, including meetings held in conjunction with the AMA Annual and Interim Meetings.<P>
</UL>
<H4><I>General Qualifications</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty legislative activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind;<P>
   <LI>Involvement with the Council while a medical student or a resident physician may be helpful but is not a requisite for Governing Council support;<P>
   <LI>Interest/activity in legislative arena.<P>
</UL><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
<H3><A NAME="CLR">Council on Long Range Planning and Development (CLRPD)</A></H3>

CLRPD makes recommendations regarding the AMA's long-range objectives; projects the resources, programs and organizational structure needed to ensure that the Association reaches its long range objectives; serves as a focal point for the Association's planning activities; and studies anticipated changes in the environment in which medicine and the Association must function.  The Council reports to the House of Delegates through the Board of Trustees.<P>
<UL><LI>The Council consists of <B>ten</B> members:
<UL>
   <LI>five members are appointed by the Speaker of the House of Delegates:
   <UL><LI>two must be appointed from the membership of the House of Delegates;
   <LI>two must be appointed from the membership of the House of Delegates OR from the AMA membership at large; and
   <LI>one must be a resident;</UL>
   <LI>four members are appointed by the Board, and may be members of the AMA House of Delegates OR from the AMA membership at large; and
   <LI>one member must be a medical student, who is appointed by the Governing Council of the Medical Student Section with the concurrence of the AMA Board of Trustees.</UL>
<LI>The AMA-YPS Governing Council can nominate qualified young physician candidates to this Council; the Governing Council also is willing to consider supporting the candidacy of a young physician nominated by a state medical society or national medical specialty society.  <B>To have a nomination endorsed by the Governing Council, a candidate must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency).</B>  In the case of an official AMA-YPS nomination, the Governing Council may also apply other criteria.<P>
   <LI>Term of three years; no more than two terms.<P>
   <LI>The CLRPD meets five times per year, including meetings on the Friday preceding the AMA Annual and Interim Meetings.  The other three meetings typically are 1 1/2 day meetings on Saturday/Sunday.  Travel and meeting preparation require another three to six days annually.
</UL>
<H4><I>General Qualifications</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind;<P>
   <LI>Knowledge of AMA policy and policy development process;<P>
   <LI>Background in planning, socioeconomics and statistics is helpful;<P>
   <LI>Involvement with the Council while a medical student or a resident physician may be helpful but is not a requisite for Governing Council support.<P><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT>
</UL>
<H3><A NAME="CME">Council on Medical Education (CME)</A></H3>
The functions of CME are to: (1) study and evaluate all aspects of medical education to ensure an adequate continuing supply of well qualified physicians to meet the medical needs of the public; (2) study and evaluate education needs in the allied health professionals and services to insure the provision of an adequate continuing supply of well-qualified allied health personnel; (3) review and recommend policies for medical and allied health education; (4) consider and recommend means by which the AMA can continue to provide information, leadership and direction to the existing inter-organizational bodies dealing with medical and allied health education; and (5) consider and recommend means and methods whereby physicians and allied health personnel may be assisted in maintaining their professional competence and the development of means and criteria for recognition of such achievement.  The Council also serves as the parent council for committees dealing with more specific areas of medical education.  The Council reports to the House of Delegates through the Board of Trustees.<P>
<UL>
   <LI>The Council consists of <B>twelve</B> members, including a resident and a student. Also, one member also must be a private practitioner who is not a salaried faculty member of a medical school.<P>
   <LI>The Board of Trustees nominates eligible members for each vacancy; further nominations may be made from the floor of the House.  Members are elected by the House of Delegates at the Annual Meeting.<P>
   <LI>The AMA-YPS Governing Council can endorse the nomination of a young physician campaigning for election to this Council.  <B>To have a nomination endorsed by the Governing Council, a candidate must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency).</B>  AMA-YPS Assembly members may actively campaign for a young physician candidate.<P>
   <LI>Term of three years; no more than two terms.<P>
   <LI>Four meetings per year.
</UL>
<H4><I>General Qualifications</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind;<P>
   <LI>Attributes are:
   <UL><LI>a broad knowledge of undergraduate, graduate and continuing medical education;
   <LI>national recognition as an authority on medical education;
   <LI>experience as a medical educator;
   <LI>knowledge of the AMA as an organization representing the medical profession.</UL>
   <LI>Involvement with the Council while a medical student or a resident physician may be helpful but is not a requisite for Governing Council support.</UL><P><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
<H3><A NAME="CMS">Council on Medical Service (CMS)</A></H3>
The functions of CMS are to: (1) study and evaluate the social and economic aspects of medical care and suggest means for the timely development of services in a changing socioeconomic environment; (2) investigate social and economic factors influencing the practice of medicine; (3) confer with state associations, component societies and national medical specialty societies regarding changing conditions and anticipated proposals that would affect medical care; and (4) assist medical service committees established by medical societies. It reports to the House of Delegates through the AMA Board of Trustees.
<UL>
   <LI>The Council consists of <B>twelve</B> members, including a resident and a student.<P>
   <LI>The Board of Trustees nominates eligible members for each Council vacancy; further nominations may be made from the floor of the House.  Members are elected by the House of Delegates at the Annual Meeting, except for the student member who is appointed by the Medical Student Section with the concurrence of the Board.<P>
   <LI>The AMA-YPS Governing Council can endorse the nomination of a young physician campaigning for election to this Council.  <B>To have a nomination endorsed by the Governing Council, a candidate must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency).</B>  AMA-YPS Assembly members may actively campaign for a young physician candidate.<P>
   <LI>Term of three years; no more than two terms.<P>
   <LI>Five to six meetings per year, including meetings in conjunction with the AMA Annual and Interim AMA-HOD Meetings.
</UL>
<H4><I>General Qualifications</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind;<P>
   <LI>Involvement with the Council while a medical student or a resident physician may be helpful but is not a requisite for Governing Council support.<P>
</UL><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
<H3><A NAME="CSA">Council on Scientific Affairs (CSA)</A></H3>

CSA advises AMA on aspects of biomedical research and helps formulate policy on scientific issues.  Its responsibilities are to: (1) advise on promising developments in medicine and biomedical research that warrant public attention; (2) advise on professional and public information activities that might be undertaken by the AMA; (3) prepare policy positions on scientific issues; (4) advise on policy positions on aspects of government support, involvement or control of biomedical research; (5) advise on opportunities to cooperate with national medical specialty societies, voluntary health agencies, other professional organizations and government agencies; (6) evaluate the benefits that might be derived from joint development of domestic and international programs on scientific affairs; and (7) propose activities that the AMA might undertake, either individually or jointly with medical societies.  It reports to the House of Delegates through the Board of Trustees.<P>
<UL>
   <LI>The Council consists of <B>twelve</B> members, including a resident and a medical student.<P>
   <LI>The Board of Trustees nominates eligible members for each vacancy; further nominations may be made from the floor of the House.  Members are elected by the House of Delegates at the Annual Meeting.<P>
   <LI>The AMA-YPS Governing Council can endorse the nomination of a young physician campaigning for election to this Council.  <B>To have a nomination endorsed by the Governing Council, a candidate must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency). </B>  AMA-YPS Assembly members may actively campaign for a young physician candidate.<P>
   <LI>Term of three years; no more than two terms.<P>
   <LI>Generally six meetings per year:<UL>
   <LI>June, December: 1/2 day meetings held in conjunction with the AMA Annual and Interim Meetings;
   <LI>January, March, July, September: 2-3 days each, including 1-2 weekend days.</UL>
</UL>
<H4><I>General Qualifications</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind;<P>
   <LI>Involvement with the Council while a medical student or a resident physician may be helpful but is not a requisite for Governing Council support.<P><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
</UL><HR>

<CENTER><H3><I><A NAME="PAC">AMPAC BOARD OF DIRECTORS</A></I></H3></CENTER>

The purposes of the American Medical Political Action Committee are to provide: (1) campaign support for candidates who are "friends of medicine" to the U.S. Congress; and (2) physicians and their spouses with information and training on political trends and techniques of involvement.  Its goal is to educate and motivate so they can aid the candidate of their choice and have their views heard in the legislative decision-making process.
<H4><I>General Information</I></H4>
<UL>
   <LI>AMPAC activities are directed by a <B>ten</B> member Board, which includes a seat for a physician spouse.<P>
   <LI>The AMA Board of Trustees appoints AMPAC Board members from nominations submitted by state, county, and specialty societies, and AMA sections.<P>
   <LI>The AMA-YPS Governing Council can nominate qualified young physician candidates to the AMPAC Board; the Governing Council also is willing to consider supporting the candidacy of a young physician nominated by a state medical society or national medical specialty society.  <B>To have a nomination endorsed by the Governing Council, a candidate must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency). </B> In the case of an official AMA-YPS nomination, the Governing Council may also apply other criteria.<P>
   <LI>Appointments are made annually in October, and take effect in December.  The AMPAC Board then elects its officers annually in December.<P>
   <LI>Each term is a one-year term, with a maximum tenure of 10 years.<P>
   <LI>The AMPAC Board meets four times a year, including meetings in conjunction with the Annual and Interim Meetings.<P>
   <LI>Expenses are reimbursed in accordance with AMA policy.<P>
</UL>
In selecting AMPAC Board members, the Board of Trustees uses the following objective criteria:
<UL>
   <LI>State--A geographic balance is desirable.<P>
   <LI>Age/Practice Status--Effort should be made to assure that newly appointed members to the AMPAC Board will continue in active practice throughout the period of time they expect to serve on the Board.<P>
   <LI>Party Affiliation--A near equal representation between Republicans and Democrats is desirable.<P>
   <LI>PAC Experience--Previous leadership at the state PAC level will enable appointees to more quickly integrate in AMPAC activities.  Special attention should be given to the performance of individual state PACs.<P>
   <LI>AMA Experience--Service as a delegate or alternate delegate in the AMA House of Delegates is an important qualification, but nominees who do not serve in that capacity should not be eliminated from consideration.<P>
   <LI>Organized Medicine Experience--Previous leadership roles at the state, county and national medical specialty level are desirable.<P>
   <LI>Campaign Experience--Greater efforts should be made to identify individuals who have had hands-on experience in political campaigns and grassroots activism.<P>
   <LI>Knowledge of AMA Policies--AMPAC Board members travel extensively throughout the Federation and are viewed as representatives of the AMA as well as of AMPAC.<P>
   <LI>Community Leadership Experience--A background in community involvement demonstrates an appreciation and greater understanding of volunteer activity.<P>
</UL><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER><P><HR>

<CENTER><H3><I><A NAME="ADV">AMA ADVISORY COMMITTEES</A></I></H3></CENTER>

At present, there are several advisory committees to the AMA Board of Trustees for which the AMA Young Physicians Section Governing Council can submit the names of qualified candidates.  The Board of Trustees appoints the members of each committee from among the names submitted by state and county medical societies, specialty societies, and AMA sections.  The Governing Council also is willing to consider seconding the nominations of qualified young physician candidates nominated by their county, state, or specialty society.<P>

In June 1994, all advisory committees were established for a period of two years. At the conclusion of that time a report will be rendered and the committee disbanded.  There is no provision in the rule for renewal of the advisory committee's charter, although it is logical to assume that this will occur if there is solid reason to believe that its work is not complete.  The Board selects the officers of each advisory committee.<P>

Each committee reimburses expenses in accordance with AMA policy.<P>

The <B><A NAME="ADV">Advisory Committee on Group Practice Physicians</A></B> was originally established for the two-year period from January 1990 through December 1991.  The committee charter has been extended twice, and may be further extended for two-year periods by the Board of Trustees.  Its purpose is to provide advice to the AMA Board of Trustees and Association staff on both policy matters and program activities that bear directly on physicians practicing in medical groups.
<UL>
   <LI><B>Thirteen</B> voting members (broadly representative of the physician group practice community, respected physicians within that community, with an appropriate mix as to the type, location and size of their respective group practices):<P>
   <UL><LI>Two seats are designated seats for the delegate and alternate delegate to the AMA House from the American Group Practice Association;
   <LI>One seat is slotted for the Medical Group Management Association Observer seat in the AMA House;
   <LI>One seat is for a non-MD administrator;
   <LI>In addition, the Executive Vice President of AGPA and the Executive Director of the MGMA serve as <I>ex officio</I> nonvoting members.<P></UL>
   <LI>Two-year term.<P>
   <LI>The committee generally meets twice a year; meetings are held in conjunction with the AMA Annual and Interim Meetings.
</UL>
To be considered for nomination by the AMA-YPS Governing Council to the committee, OR to have AMA-YPS support for your nomination by your state, county, or specialty society, one:
<UL>
   <LI>Must be an AMA member, and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 OR in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency);<P>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Must practice in a group setting; and<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind.
</UL><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
The <B><A NAME="IMG">Advisory Committee on International Medical Graduates</A></B> was created in 1989 to enhance the image and address the concerns of international medical graduates.  It is a direct communications link between IMGS, their ethnic medical associations and the AMA.
<UL>
   <LI>The Committee has <B>ten</B> members, including a resident physician.<P>
   <LI>Two meetings per year, except that up to two others may be authorized if necessary.  Meetings are held in conjunction with the AMA Annual and Interim Meetings.<P>
   <LI>Two-year term.
</UL>
To be considered for nomination by the AMA-YPS Governing Council to the committee (there is no young physician position), OR to have AMA-YPS support for your nomination by your state, county, or specialty society, one:
<UL>
   <LI>Must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 OR in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency);<P>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind; and<P>
   <LI>Must be a graduate of a non-United States or Canadian medical school.
</UL><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
The <B><A NAME="IMG">Advisory Committee on Minority Physicians</A></B> was initially formed in 1992.  The committee is responsible for analyzing pertinent data, trends, policy and ongoing activities on minority health care, minority physician and student manpower, and minority representation in the AMA.  Minority has been defined by the AMA Board of Trustees as African American, Hispanic Latino American, and Native American.
<UL>
   <LI>The Committee has <B>eleven</B> members, including a young physician, a resident, and a student.<P>
   <LI>At least three members must be AMA delegates or alternate delegates.<P>
   <LI>Two meetings per year, except that up to two others may be authorized if necessary.  Meetings are held in conjunction with the AMA Annual and Interim Meetings.<P>
   <LI>Two-year term.
</UL>
To be considered for nomination by the AMA-YPS Governing Council to the young physician position or an at-large position, OR to have AMA-YPS support for your nomination by your state, county, or specialty society, one:
<UL>
   <LI>Must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 OR in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency);<P>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities;<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind; and<P>
   <LI>Must be a member of one of the following minority groups:  African American, Hispanic American, or Native American.
</UL><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P>
The <B><A NAME="WPI">Advisory Panel on Women Physician Issues</A></B> was initially formed in 1979.  The committee's purpose is to identify and analyze ongoing and emerging issues of direct concern to women physicians, women medical students, and women patients; to recommend policies, develop programs, and provide advice and counsel to the AMA Board of Trustees, councils and staff on matters of importance to women in medicine; and to promote the greater involvement of women in the membership and leadership organized medicine.
<UL>
   <LI>The Committee is composed of <B>ten</B> members, including a young physician, a resident and a student, at least four members must be AMA delegates or alternate delegates.<P>
   <LI>Two-year term.<P>
   <LI>The committee meets at least twice a year in conjunction with the Annual and Interim Meetings of the AMA-HOD.  Other meetings may be held at times and locations approved by the Board.
</UL>
To be considered for nomination by the AMA-YPS Governing Council to the young physician position or an at-large position, OR to have AMA-YPS support for your nomination by your state, county, or specialty society, one:
<UL>
   <LI>Must be a woman physician, an AMA member, and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 OR in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency);<P>
   <LI>Should be active in state/specialty activities; and<P>
   <LI>Should have committee experience of some kind.
</UL><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER><P><HR>

<CENTER><H3><I><A NAME="RRC">RESIDENCY REVIEW COMMITTEES</A></I></H3></CENTER>
The AMA-YPS Governing Council nominates young physician candidates who are interested in being nominated to a residency review committee (RRC).  RRCs propose requirements for revising residency program accreditation standards and determines whether individual programs comply with the requirements. Membership on each RRC consists of an equal number of representatives appointed by the American Medical Association, the appropriate medical specialty board, and for most, the designated national medical specialty society.  The Council on Medical Education reviews all nominations and ranks the candidates; the Board of Trustees, however, actually makes the selection.<P>

Committee size is variable, ranging from as few as six representatives to a maximum of twelve members.  Also, several committees have "slotted" resident physician positions.  AMA appointments are for a two-year period, with the maximum tenure being six years.<P>

The time commitment also varies from RRC to RRC, from at few as two days per year to as many as 15 days annually.  Beyond the time commitment involved in attending meetings, considerable time is needed to prepare for the meetings.<P>

The following RRCs exist: Allergy and Immunology, Anesthesiology, Colon and Rectal Surgery, Dermatology, Diagnostic Radiology, Emergency Medicine, Family Practice, Internal Medicine,  Medical Genetics, Neurology, Nuclear Medicine, Obstetrics and Gynecology, Ophthalmology, Orthopedic Surgery, Otolaryngology, Pathology, Pediatrics, Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation, Plastic Surgery, Preventive Medicine, Psychiatry, Radiation Oncology, Surgery, Thoracic Surgery, and Urology.<P>

Specific information on any RRC is available by contacting the AMA Group on Medical Education.<P>

To be nominated by the AMA-YPS Governing Council, one:
<UL>
   <LI>Must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency).<P>
   <LI>Must have two letters of recommendation.  A letter from a specialty society is preferable, not mandatory.<P>
   <LI>Must be residency trained in the discipline in question.<P>
   <LI>Must be board certified in the discipline in question.<P>
   <LI>Should be active in organized medicine.<P>
   <LI>Should have committee activity of some kind.<P>
   <LI>Should have an academic appointment, and current or recent experience in the conduct of an accredited residency training program is preferable.
</UL>
The Governing Council will determine the number of nominees for any position.  The Governing Council also will consider supporting the nomination of any young physician sponsored by his/her state or specialty society.<P><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P><HR>

<CENTER><H3><I><A NAME="CAC">CME ADVISORY COMMITTEES</A></I></H3></CENTER>

There are two committees which report to the Council on Medical Education for which the AMA  YPS Governing Council nominates qualified candidates.  They are described below:<P>

<B><I>Continuing Medical Education Advisory Committee</I></B>--This committee supervises the quality of the AMA's continuing medical education offerings and is directly involved in maintaining the Association's ability to accredit continuing medical education programs.  CMEAC also handles various issues regarding continuing medical education, and other issues as assigned by the Council on Medical Education.
<UL>
   <LI>Eight members, at least one of whom must be a practicing physician
   <LI>The Committee meets 3-4 times a year
   <LI>Expenses are reimbursed in accordance with AMA policy
   <LI>One year appointments
</UL>
<B><I>Graduate Medical Education Advisory Committee</I></B>--This committee reviews and recommends the acceptance, rejection, or modification of proposed changes in the standards for accreditation of residency training programs.  Further, the committee identifies, studies, and documents problems and formulates recommendations toward their solutions.
<UL>
   <LI>Eight members, at least one of whom must be a practicing physician
   <LI>The Committee meets 3-4 times a year
   <LI>Expenses are reimbursed in accordance with AMA policy
   <LI>One year appointments
</UL>
To be nominated by the AMA-YPS Governing Council for either advisory committee, one:
<UL>
   <LI>Must be an AMA member and qualify for the YPS (under age 40 or any age if in the first five years of practice following completion of a residency).<P>
   <LI>Should be active in organized medicine.<P>
   <LI>Should have a background and/or strong interest in either continuing medical education or graduate medical education, depending upon the committee position being sought.<P>
   <LI>Should have committee activity of some kind.<P>
</UL><FONT SIZE=2><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER></FONT><P><HR>
<CENTER><H3><I><A NAME="OLO">OTHER LEADERSHIP OPPORTUNITIES</A></I></H3></CENTER>

As the introduction noted, this publication does not cover positions on the AMA-YPS Governing Council or AMA-YPS Assembly Convention Committees; information on these openings is available by contacting the AMA Department of Young Physician Services. Also not included is information on how to represent your state medical society or national medical specialty society as a delegate or alternate delegate to the AMA House of Delegates, since qualifications and election processes are determined by the individual state or specialty society.  If you need assistance in reaching your state or specialty society, contact the AMA Department of Young Physician Services.<P>

If, however, you are now involved in the AMA-YPS Assembly but are not interested in the various high-profile leadership positions discussed earlier in this publication, there are several other opportunities you may wish to consider once you leave the AMA-YPS.<P>

<H4><B><I>Hospital Medical Staff Section</I></B></H4>

The AMA-HMSS is similar to the AMA-YPS in that it is a special section created to meet the needs of an defined population.  The HMOs' purpose is to provide a forum for hospital medical staffs to meet nationally to discuss common issues and concerns and to increase the awareness of and to communicate the issues that are affecting physicians a members of hospital medical staffs.  Through its twice-yearly meetings convened just prior to the AMA-HOD, the AMA-HMSS provides a means to address the concerns facing physicians who have hospital privileges and to propose solutions.<P>

Physicians have the opportunity to represent their hospital medical staffs at these meetings.  Each representative must be elected by the medical staff, and must be an AMA member who is an active voting member of the medical staff with clinical privileges at the hospital.<P>

The Section's activities are directed by a seven-member governing council, plus the immediate past chair, who serves as an <I>ex-officio</I>, voting member.  Specific information about other officer positions is available from the AMA Department of Hospital Medical Staff Services.<P>

<H4><B><I><A NAME="SMS">Section on Medical Schools</A></I></B></H4>

The purpose of the Medical Schools Section is to provide a direct means for approved medical schools to participate in AMA activities.  The Section's membership consists of (1) the chief administrative officer (i.e., dean) of each approved medical school, or a member of the staff of the chief administrative officer designated by the chief administrative officer; (2) two members of the staff of the chief administrative officer or the faculty of each approved medical school, selected by the chief administrative officer of the medical school; and (3) a member of the faculty of each approved medical school selected by the physician members of the faculty.  All Section members must be members of the AMA.  The Section's meeting is convened the day prior to the AMA Annual and Interim Meetings.<P>

The Section's activities are directed by a eight-member governing council. Specific information about the officer positions is available from the AMA Department of Medical School Services.<P><CENTER>Return to the <A HREF="#TOC">Table of Contents</A> or to the <A HREF="YPS.HTM" TARGET="_parent" NAME="ClickMe">YPS Main Page</A></CENTER><P>
<HR>
