<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B15-144</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA083-000589-B014-177</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://ns.medac.comnet.mt:80/webactiv/features.htm 194.223.143.33 19970216022813 text/html 8396
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 16 Feb 1997 02:31:22 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
Last-Modified: Fri, 09 Aug 1996 05:46:12 GMT
Content-Length: 8196
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Web Active Featured Site</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY Background="beige1.jpg">


<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><B>WEB ACTIVE FEATURED SITE
<HR noshade><P>
Traditional - pre Internet phase
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
The story of this Web site has two starting points,
in late 80s. First, a classical relational database application
and not so common full-text database. Second, a hypertext paradigm
that emerged as a more promising knowledge-based system vis-&agrave;-vis
expert systems that were slowly losing its momentum and a popularity
gained in mid 80s. The objective of our system was an information
system and knowledge-based tool for International Law and Diplomacy.


<P>
We started developing our system in 1992 guided by
the idea of combining these two premises through an <B>integration
of relational database and hypertext features</B>. At that time, on
the side of hypertext we were experimenting using tools such as
Knowledge Pro, HyperWriter and <I>Neil Larson's</I> MaxThink. Given the
limits of technology of the time, we developed in 1994 the relational
database for international legal documents legally binding to
Malta. It was a DOS-based xBase application aimed to meet the
needs of a specialist in International Law. Texts of international legal documents provided by the Malta's Ministry of Foreign Affairs were scanned an re-typed depending on the quality of documents. In this process special scanning procedures and techniques were introduced.

<P>
Eventually, in 1995 we developed Windows-based system, in which
relational database and hypertext had been integrated. Guided by the ideas
of <I><A HREF="../zine/select/gumboot1.htm">Vannevar Bush</A>, Ted Nelson</I> and other pioneers of a hypertext
paradigm, we have been trying to promote the idea of creating
cognitive network of hypertext links for the international law
and diplomacy.

<P>
The system with hybrid features resists theoretical
classification, but as sometimes praxis precedes the theory our
endeavour was attracting attention and recognition, and now the system
is in use in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Malta, with a
growing number of countries, institutions and individuals expressing
the interest in it.


<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>Internet phase - World Wide Web
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
We have started developing our Web-site by converting
our experience, knowledge and expertise acquired in years of work
in the field, and when IT infrastructure is concerned, in LAN
environment and LAN-based applications. 

<P>
For the Web-site we have used different techniques.
First we tried to implement our system of integrated relational
database and hypertext. We had the following requirements:
<P>

<UL>
<table border=0>
<tr><td valign=baseline><img src="abluedot.gif" hspace=10>
</td><td valign=baseline>to avoid the manual conversion of more than 2,000 
documents we have in the database. All of the existing 
HTML-tools were not useful for this task;<BR></td></tr>
<tr><td valign=baseline><img src="abluedot.gif" hspace=10 width=14 height=14>
</td><td valign=baseline>to have automatic management of the hypertext-links 
among these 2,000 documents; even if we manage to 
create such a huge number of HTML-documents it 
would give us almost impossible task of the 
maintenance of this structure given the hypertext links 
among the documents;<BR></td></tr>
<tr><td valign=baseline><img src="abluedot.gif" align=middle hspace=10 width=14 height=14>
</td><td valign=baseline>to integrate LAN-based application with 
Internet-system in order to have creation of 
hypertext-links integrated in teaching and research 
processes at the Academy. In other words, our 
objective is to have our students writing their thesis, 
research papers and other documents through making 
hypertext-links. Function of professors and mentors 
should be to judge the quality of these links. It is a 
challenging and difficult task for which we now have 
full technical capabilities.<BR> </td></tr>
</table>
</UL>


<P>
Starting from these requirements we have developed
our <A HREF="http://www.medac.comnet.mt:81/doilm/grdoilm.html">
Hypertext Information System "Diplomacy and International
Affairs"</A>. It is the functional backbone of our Web-site with
more than 40 MB of various international legal documents. Proprietary
Web server on port 81, which operates in synergy with a general
purpose Web server MS Internet Information Server (IIS), enables
on-the-fly generating Web pages of bibliographical references
and full-texts of treaties, resolutions, statements and other
documents reposited in a database. Moreover, search results are,
also, generated as Web pages with a list of retrieved documents
linked to their source in a database.

<P>
Once we have achieved proper management of documents
we have decided to explore visual potentials of Web. For this
purpose we have created traditional Web-site.

<P>
Graphical design of the home page is inspired by
an ancient Greek vase in the shape of <I>kantharos</I>, since
we are on the Mediterranean, and the other Mediterranean symbols
and content can be found on different pages. In order to make,
otherwise dry textual material more appealing, various graphical
and sophisticated Web publishing techniques are applied. The most
lively and interesting part of this part of the Web site is our
<A HREF="../zine/warn1.htm">MADS ZinE</A> - E(lectronic maga)zine. MADS ZinE serves as a non-conventional
forum for various topics and a medium where we can experiment
with new presentation and Web publishing techniques like:

<UL>
<img src="areddot1.gif" hspace=10>frames;<BR>

<img src="areddot1.gif" hspace=10>CGI (Common Gateway Interface);<BR>

<img src="areddot1.gif" hspace=10>Java programming language;<BR>

<img src="areddot1.gif" hspace=10>various plug-ins.
</UL>



<P>
Also, of interest for a visitor - professional is
<A HREF="../wshop/wshop0.htm">Workshops and Conferences</A> chapter (cluster of Web pages), where
the list of all meetings organised by the Academy and often with
a full text of contributions can be found. The same holds true
for the Academy's publications (those out of print), some of them
being result of these international meetings.


<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>Further developments
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
Our plans for the future include:

<UL>
<table border=0>
<tr><td valign=baseline>
<img src="aolivdot.gif" hspace=10></td><td>integration of our address - Who is Who database,
with the help of new emerging tools like MS dbWeb or
 <A HREF="http://www.corel.com">Corel WEB.DATA</A>;<BR></td>

<tr><td valign=baseline><img src="aolivdot.gif" hspace=10></td>
<td>indexing the Web site;<BR></td>

<tr><td valign=baseline>
<img src="aolivdot.gif" hspace=10></td>
<td>applying Adobe's Acrobat .PDF format for Web
publishing of a material that was originally developed with desktop
publishing or word processing packages, whose complicated page
layout cannot be satisfactorily convert to Web pages;<BR></td>

<tr><td valign=baseline>
<img src="aolivdot.gif" hspace=10></td>
<td>more active interaction with scholars and professionals
through various forms of feedback like listservs, guest books,
etc.;<BR></td> 

<tr><td valign=baseline>
<img src="aolivdot.gif" hspace=10></td>
<td>investigation of <A HREF="http://epsilon.cs.unc.edu/~stotts/MMM/">
Multi-Head/Multi-Tail (MHMT)</A>
Web hypertext concept project run at the University of North Carolina
at Chapel Hill, that achieved prominent place in the last two
International WWW conferences.<BR></td>
</table>
</UL>
<HR>

<table border=0>
<tr><td valign=top>
<A HREF="../default.htm"><IMG SRC="ahome1-s.gif"> Home</A>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies, University of Malta, Msida, MSD 06, MALTA;&nbsp;
Telephone: +356 483090 or +356 32902817; &nbsp;Fax: +356 483091 or +356 336450;&nbsp;
E-mail: <A HREF=mailto:academy@medac.comnet.mt>academy@medac.comnet.mt</A>
</B></FONT>
</td></table>

</BODY>

