<TITLE>Presentation</TITLE>
<HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="spiral-b.jpg">

<B><H2>PRESENTATION</H2>
<P>
The Mediterranean region is the cradle of ancient and modern diplomacy.
One finds diplomacy making its first steps in the East Mediterranean
region during the Antiquity, and in Northern Italy during the
Middle Age. Later, it sharpened its skills in handling relations
between the Christian countries of Western and Southern Europe
and the World of Islam. Battles for supremacy over the Mediterranean
Sea alternated with intensive diplomatic activity in the European,
Ottoman and North African capitals. But, colonisation of Northern
Africa and the increasing domination of the Mediterranean by extra-regional
powers profoundly altered relationships within the region. Once
the hub of diplomatic action, the Mediterranean became the object
of global rivalry.
<P>
The end of the Cold War profoundly changed the international landscape
and generated new demands for regional and cross-cultural diplomacy.
The growing awareness of environmental maritime problems increased
the need to find cooperative solutions to the Mediterranean as
a whole. A multitude of diplomatic efforts reflect this development.
They include the Mediterranean Action Plan, projects for a Conference
on Security and Cooperation in the Mediterranean and the creation
of a Council of the Mediterranean. Furthermore, the countries
around the Mediterranean are compelled to address jointly for
the first time arms control and regional security questions, partly
related to the Balkan conflict, and partly to the Middle East
Peace Process.
<P>

<img src="maltamed.jpg" align=left hspace=10></a>
Malta is situated in the very centre of the Mediterranean Sea
and has experienced throughout its long history the effects of
migrations, conquests and regional struggles. With a language
based on Arabic and traditions deeply anchored in European Christian
values, Malta can converse with both cultures and has an understanding
for both. Malta is also the source of initiatives for an active
pan-Mediterranean diplomacy. Its geographical location and cross-cultural
past makes Malta the ideal location for training diplomats from
the entire Mediterranean region.
<P>
<HR SIZE="4">
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<BR>
<img src="ginevra2.jpg" align=right hspace=10></a>
The Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies was established
in 1990 as a joint undertaking between the University of Malta
and Geneva's <A HREF="http://heiwww.unige.ch/">Graduate Institute of
International Studies</A>, Switzerland.
The latter has been active for many years in the field of training
diplomats, running its own training programmes, specializing in
multilateral diplomacy and international security. The Graduate
Institute has also been instrumental in setting up <A HREF="sister/dsp0.htm">
<B>diplomatic training institutes</B></A> in the Caribbean
(Institute of International Relations in Trinidad) and in Africa
(International Relations Institute of Cameroon, Institute of Diplomacy and
International Studies in Nairobi, Kenya). The Mediterranean Academy of
Diplomatic Studies, thus, joined a group of closely inter-related regional
institutions. All of these institutions have received financial
support from the Swiss Government. For resource allocation and
academic coordination it relies on the Graduate Institute of International
Studies.
<P>
<HR SIZE="4">
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<BR>
<a href="diag4.gif">
<img src="diag4-s.gif" align=left hspace=10></a>
In the case of the Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies,
a bilateral agreement between the Governments of Malta and Switzerland
outlines the Academy's basic objectives and the contributions
each side is committed to make (<I>Please, click on the icon for the larger
diagram</I>). Both Governments have undertaken
to seek involvement of other Mediterranean countries and international
organizations in the Academy so as to make it a truly regional
and international venture. As a result of such efforts, the Government
of Tunisia is joining the Academy under an agreement with the
Government of Malta. Italy sponsors a chair of Mediterranean Diplomacy
and Relations, whereas the United Nations Environment Programme
(UNEP) finances a chair of Environmental Diplomacy. The Academy
also maintains useful contacts with the Commonwealth Secretariat
which sponsored a visiting professor lecture series.
<P>
</B>
<HR SIZE="4">
</BODY>
