</HEAD>
<TITLE>Fields of Study and Course Offerings</TITLE>
<HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="spiral.jpg">

<B><H2>FIELDS OF STUDY AND COURSE OFFERINGS</H2>
<P>
The Academy subscribes to a pluridisciplinary approach of Diplomatic
Studies. There are five fields of study, in each of which there
is at least one course offered per semester. A certain number
of courses fitting into the Academy's curriculum will be taught
at the University of Malta. The course offerings are subject to
change.
<P>
IR International Relations
<P>
Fall Semester
<P>
<VAR>IR 1a - Theories of International Relations</VAR>
<P>
This course begins by analyzing the basic approaches to current
International Relations Theory. It will look at what schools of
thought can best explain conflict and cooperation in today's international
system. The course will then examine the concepts of power politics,
foreign policy making, international cooperation and some elements
of international political economy.
<P>
Form: lecture and discussion; one written test.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. students and for those M.A. students
who have no previous academic background in this field.
<P>
Spring Semester
<P>
IR 2a - <U>Selected Topics in International</U>
<P>
<U>Relations after the End of the Cold War</U>
<P>
 This course will examine current issues of International Politics.
It will consist of case studies on topics dealing with the challenges
of the United Nations, regional cooperative arrangements, minorities
and human rights, peacekeeping and conflict resolution.
<P>
Form: seminar-course; one oral presentation with written outline.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. students and for those M.A. students
who have chosen International Relations as one of their fields
of study.
<P>
IH International History
<P>
Fall Semester
<P>
IH 1a - <U>International History of the 19th and 20th </U>
<P>
<U>Centuries</U>
<P>
This course considers the principal events, actors and developments
that have characterized the history of International Relations
since 1815, with special emphasis on important negotiations and
their outcomes. Themes discussed include the order of Vienna;
nationalism and imperialism; the causes and consequences of the
two World Wars; the East-West confrontation; decolonisation and
North-South relations; and the process of European integration.
<P>
Form: lecture and discussion; one written test.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. students and for those M.A. students
who have no previous academic background in this field.
<P>
Spring Semester
<P>
IH 2a - <U>Highlights of Mediterranean History</U>
<P>
Conducted in seminar style, this course discusses selected historical
developments in the Mediterranean region within the framework
of the main themes that have defined the Mediterranean in international
relations since antiquity, with special emphasis on the 19th and
20th centuries.
<P>
Form: seminar-course; one oral presentation with written outline.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. students and for those M.A. students
who have chosen International History as one of their fields of
study.
<P>
IL International Law
<P>
Fall Semester
<P>
IL 1a - <U>International Law</U>
<P>
 This course introduces the students to the General Principles
in International Law and International Environmental Law. Topics
include nature and sources of IL, relationship between Municipal
Law and IL, subjects of IL and State Responsibility, Global Environmental
Conventions and Institutions.
<P>
Form: lecture and discussion; one written test.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. and those M.A. students who have no
previous academic background in this field.
<P>
Spring Semester
<P>
IL 2a - <U>Mediterranean Environmental Policy and Law</U>
<P>
 This course examines the Mediterranean environmental protection
activities under legal and policy-oriented perspectives. First,
it explains the Mediterranean Action Plan. Second, national action
plans and policies will be discussed. Finally, the MedPlan will
be used as a case study for illustrating problems and prospects
of multilateral environmental cooperation.
<P>
Form: lecture and discussion; one assignment.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. and those M.A. students who will write
their thesis in this field.
<P>
IE International Economics
<P>
Fall Semester
<P>
IE 1 - <U>International Economics</U>
<P>
This course will be devoted to the economic analysis of international
trade: Theory and Policy. In the theory part the topics are: the
Theory of comparative advantage, the gains from trade and the
patterns of trade. In the Policy part, the analysis will be directed
to the protectionist policies and the advantage of freer international
trade.
<P>
Form: lecture and discussion; one written test.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. students and for those M.A. students
who have no previous academic background in this field.
<P>
Spring Semester
<P>
IE 2 - <U>International Economics</U>
<P>
This course will be directed towards the analysis of the financial
and monetary aspects of international trade. The internatioanl
monetary analysis focuses on the balance of payments, the adjustment
process, the exchange rate regimes and the international monetary
system. Finally students will be introduced to economic integration
and the key institutions in international trade.
<P>
Form: lecture and discussion; one assignment.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. students and for those M.A. students
who have no previous academic background in this field.
<P>
DIP Diplomacy (Reserved for M.Dip. students)
<P>
Fall Semester
<P>
DIP 1 - <U>Diplomacy</U>
<P>
 This course combines traditional and modern approaches to diplomacy.
The traditional approach examines actors of diplomacy, functions
of missions, rules and process of diplomacy, immunities and privileges.
The modern approach to diplomacy considers new tendencies in diplomacy
caused by development of science and technology, especially information
technology. Practice-related presentations will be provided by
current and former diplomats and policy makers.
<P>
Form: lecture and discussion; one written test, computer assisted
learning.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip students.
<P>
Spring Semester
<P>
DIP 2 - <U>Practical Aspects of Diplomacy</U>
<P>
 This course consists of simulation of international negotiation
and crisis management. It also addresses practical aspects of
bilateral and multilateral relations, social skills and protocol
use of information technology in conducting diplomatic activities
(network access to remote databases and information systems, etc.).
<P>
Form: simulations supervised by experienced diplomats and institutions
specialized in negotiation exercise, computer assisted learning.
<P>
Compulsory for all M.Dip. students.
<P>
</B>
<HR>
