</HEAD>
<TITLE>Special Programmes and Activities</TITLE>
<HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="spiral.jpg">

<B><H2>SPECIAL PROGRAMMES AND ACTIVITIES</H2>
<P>
In addition to the regular coursework, the Academy offers a number
of special programmes and activities, the purpose of which are
to improve the analytical skills of the students.
<P>
Research Methods and Writing
<P>
This course intends to improve skills in researching, organising
and writing a scientific essay. Emphasis will be placed on the
use of sources and data, including computerised data and computer
networks. This exercise is compulsory for M.A. and M.Dip. students.
<P>
Current Events
<P>
This seminar's objective is to train the participants to analyse
and discuss current events. Participants will be asked to follow
key developments in international affairs and give short oral
and written presentations. This seminar is mandatory for M.Dip.
students and open to interested M.A. students.
<P>
Selected Topics of Mediterranean Relations
<P>
This seminar is an interdisciplinary approach to selected topics
of importance to the Mediterranean region. It will examine the
various sources that threaten stability of the Mediterranean and
will look at efforts to create common parameters of cooperation
in the region. This seminar is mandatory for all students.
<P>
Introduction to the International Environmental Law and Diplomacy
<P>
This course develops a set of concepts and theoretical perspectives
to understand trends in the politics of global environmental problems.
These concepts and perspectives center on questions of historical
development of the environmental issues, international cooperation
and institutions, major global conventions and state liability.
The intention of the course is to build analytical tools that
diplomats or policy-makers can use in a wide variety of situations
involving transboundary environmental issues and to be conversant
with contemporary trends in the politics of such issues. The course
will use negotiations of the Montreal Protocol on Protection of
the Ozone Layer as a case study. This course is compulsory for
all M.Dip. and those M.A. students who will write their thesis
in this field.
<P>
Computer applications
<P>
All students not conversant with PCs will have to attend initiation
classes during the first month of studies. These will be followed
by classes dealing with computer networks, databases and desktop
publishing. M.Dip. students will have to attend an additional
series of classes on computer applications in diplomacy.
<P>
Language Courses
<P>
Language and Public Speaking classes are compulsory for M.Dip
students and constitute a full examinable subject, a failure in
which precludes the award of the degree. All non-Maltese M.Dip
students will be tested in written and oral English skills at
the beginning of the academic programme. Students who are holders
of a degree or equivalent qualifications in English may take Public
Speaking and Higher Level Directed Studies in English. The latter
have the opportunity to take French classes, depending on the
number of students.
<P>
Guest Lectures
<P>
Each year the Academy invites academics, policy makers and foreign
policy experts of Malta and abroad to give a lecture or a series
of lectures to the participants of the Academy. Special lecture
series with guest lecturers are scheduled on topics such as:
<P>
The Euro-Mediterranean Partnership, the OSCE and its Mediterranean
dimension, arms control regimes, conflict management, and North-South
relations.
<P>
</B>
<HR>
