<HEAD>

<TITLE>Following decades of rapid technological development, information technology (IT) enters a new phase of growing applications in most areas of human life. The decreasing cost and increasing performance of hardware, as well as the power and easy use of soft
</TITLE>

<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">
<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="student1">
<META NAME="DOCCOMM" CONTENT="r     ">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><B>WORKSHOP ON</B> 
<P>
<B>USE OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY IN INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS</B>
<HR>

<P>
20th November - 1st December 1995</CENTER><HR>

<P>
Organised by:
<P>
<B>Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies</B> 
<P>
<B>Commonwealth Network of IT for Development (COMNET-IT)</B>

<P>
in collaboration with
<P>
<B>Multilateral Affairs Directorate, Ministry of Foreign Affairs
of Malta</B> 
<P>
<B>The Management and Training Services Division, Commonwealth
Secretariat</B>
<P>
<B>Welcome to the Web-site developed during the Workshop on Use
of Information Technology in International Relations. The initial
version of this Web-site is developed by participants.</B>
<P>
<A HREF="#generalinfo">INTRODUCTION AND GENERAL INFORMATION </A>
<P>
<A HREF="programm.htm">PROGRAMME OF THE WORKSHOP </A>
<P>
<A HREF="partic.htm">LIST OF PARTICIPANTS</A> 
<P>
<A HREF="document.htm">DOCUMENTS</A> <HR>

<P>
<B><A NAME="generalinfo">Workshop on the Use of Information Technology
in International Relations</A></B> 
<P>
<A href="photo1.gif"><IMG src="photo1-s.gif" align=left hspace=3></A>
A Workshop for senior or middle management of Ministries of Foreign
Affairs and International Relations Departments, who are or will
be engaged in the planning and/or management of Information Systems
for International Relations.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR>

<P>
<B>Venue</B> 
<P>
Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies, University of Malta
<HR>

<P>
<B>Course Objective</B><HR>

<P>
Developing countries, especially those with limited financial
and human resources, find it difficult to meaningfully participate
in today's intensive multilateral and bilateral diplomatic activities
which increasingly tackles issues that have great impact on national
interests and policies. Moreover, maintaining diplomatic network
is a big financial and organizational burden for most of the developing
states. The development of Information Technology makes diplomatic
activities less costly but more efficient.
<P>
<B>This Workshop is aimed at introducing use of Information Technology
in International Relations to small, developing and other states
with limited resources</B>. The Workshop will be a significant
contribution to the overall strengthening of the capacity of the
countries concerned in both conducting their external relations
and participating in a meaningful manner in subregional, regional
and worldwide diplomatic activities. Participants will acquire
both theoretical and practical knowledge on the use of Information
Technology in International Relations.
<P>
<B>Training Approach</B><HR>

<P>
The teaching method will be based on traditional and computer-based
approach. and will include lectures, seminars and computer simulation.
The Internet-module of the Workshop will be covered through conceptual
introduction as well as through practical activities such as:
on-line presentations, developing of home-pages, etc. Participants
will be introduced to the experience of other countries in their
efforts towards the computerisation of diplomatic activities.
Special attention will be paid to Malta's experience in the use
of Information Technology in international relations.
<P>
MEDITERRANEAN ACADEMY OF DIPLOMATIC STUDIES
<P>
The Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies was established
in 1990 as a joint undertaking between the University of Malta
and the Graduate Institute of International Studies of Geneva,
Switzerland. The Academy is an autonomous institution with its
own statute, established within the framework of the University
of Malta. It offers diplomats and officials from the Mediterranean
region a degree programme that leads to a Master in Diplomacy,
which is an internationally recognized university degree.
<P>
The Academy established in 1992 a Unit for Computer Applications
in Diplomacy. Its objective is to provide diplomats with conceptual
and technical skills for working in today's rapidly changing international
environment, that is increasingly influenced by information technology.
The Unit also assists Foreign Ministries in their computerisation
efforts.
<P>
The Unit have had the following major projects in last 3 years:
<OL>
<LI>Workshop on Computer Applications in Diplomacy (sponsored
by UN and Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Malta) 24-28 January
1994;
<LI>Database of International Legal Documents with texts of all
international legal agreements legally binding to Malta (June
1994);
<LI>Course in &quot;IT and Diplomacy&quot; for the students at
the Academy;
<LI>&quot;Internet Corner&quot; Project with main task to familiarize
students and staff members with new forms of communication through
Internet;
<LI>Computer-based Package for Learning Diplomacy
</OL>

<P>
THE COMMONWEALTH NETWORK OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY FOR DEVELOPMENT
<P>
The Commonwealth Network of Information Technology for Development
(COMNET-IT) is a Network Organisation aimed at fostering the building
and enhancing of networks of institutions (and networks of people)through
the mediation of computer networks. Its aims to promote informed
dialogue and communication between institutions to encourage and
empower individuals within them to become active participants
in the development process. It also acts to facilitate the sharing
of information about development related issues, existing skills
and expertise, and available products and services. COMNET-IT
uses a variety of means, including training, information databases
and various forms of human-computer communications, to enhance
linkages between sources and users of information and knowledge.
<P>
The Management Systems Unit, the Malta Government's Agent for
Reform, has been mandated with managing the International Secretariat
of this new Commonwealth Foundation.
<P>
THE MANAGEMENT AND TRAINING SERVICES DIVISION OF THE COMMONWEALTH
SECRETARIAT
<P>
The Management and Training Services Division (MTSD) of the Commonwealth
Secretariat came into existence in July 1993 when the Management
Development and the Fellowships and Training Programmes were amalgamated
as a result of reorganisation of the Secretariat. The MTSD has
a mandate to provide a lead role in Commonwealth activities in
the following areas:
<P>
Administration and managerial reform
<P>
Human resource development through skills enhancement
<P>
Supporting development of information and new technologies
<P>
Human resource development for post-apartheid South Africa.
<P>
The MTSD targets its training to the specific skills needs of
senior and mid-level officials, managers and technologists through
specalised group training programmes, work attachments or study
visits in multifarious sectors including management and administration,
entrepreneurship and business development, science and advanced
technologies and the environment, to name a few. Each year, some
4.000 persons, most of them middle-level managers, officials,
technologists or technicians, pursue courses both in the former
sector of training (certificate, diploma and masters degree courses)
and in the non-formal sector of training (workshops and seminars,
training attachments and study visits as well as academic exchanges)
on training awards for training in over 300 institutions. The
majority of the training programmes in the formal sector and supply-oriented,
being generally offered by relevant institutions for individual
and group awards, whilst nearly all those in the non-formal sector
category are demand-oriented.
<P>
MTSD's funding resources for assistance to member countries come
from the Commonwealth Fund for Technical Co-operation (CFTC),
which is the Commonwealth's sole multilateral agency for development.
The CFTC is a unique mechanism for development co-operation, set
apart from traditional aid agencies by being a system of mutual
assistance.
<P>
CFTC's resources, expertise and training facilities as well as
money, are contributed by both developed and developing countries,
the latter playing a dual role as donors and recipients. MTSD
continues to consolidate technical co-operation in areas where
some developing member countries have experience, expertise and
facilities to share with others who may not have the requisite
capabilities and facilities.
<P>
THE REPUBLIC OF MALTA
<P>
Malta is and archipelago situated almost exactly in the centre
of the Mediterranean Sea between Southern Europe and Northern
Africa. It is located 50 miles south of Sicily, 180 miles for
the nearest point on the African coast, 1,100 East of Gibraltar
and 1,050 miles West of Port Aid. The total area of the archipelago
is 122 square miles of which Malta, the largest island, occupies
95 square miles and Gozo, a sister island lying a few miles to
the Northwest, occupies 26 square miles.
<P>
Malta has a typically Mediterranean climate enjoying dry, warm
Summers and mild Winters.
<P>
The estimated population on the Maltese islands is 365,000. Nearly
all Maltese are bilingual, with Maltese and English being the
official languages of the country.
<P>
Malta is a parliamentary democracy with a President as the Constitutional
Head of State.
<P>
A member of the Commonwealth and the United Nations, in 1990 Malta
applied to join the European Union. 
</BODY>

