<HEAD>

<TITLE>DIPLOMACY@INFORMATION</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY text="#ffffff" link="#00ff00" vlink="#00ffff" background="bback2.jpg">

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5 color="ffff00">DIPLOMACY@INFORMATION.TECHNOLOGY</FONT></B>
<HR size=4 noshade>

<P>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>Networking Project<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></I>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The Networking Project &quot;Diplomacy@Information.Technology&quot;
is a joint initiative of the Diplomatic Studies Programme of the
Graduate Institute of International Studies in Geneva and the
Commonwealth Network of IT for Development. The major objective
of the Project is to promote the use of Information technology
(IT) in diplomacy and international relations. Special emphasise
is laid on capacity building in the field of IT and diplomacy
for countries with limited financial and human resources for diplomatic
activities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The Networking Project is organised through the regional
centers of excellence in information technology and diplomacy
at the following institutes and academies associated with the
Diplomatic Studies Programme:<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>The Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies
- Malta.</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>The Institute of Diplomacy and International
Relations (IDIS) - Nairobi.</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>The Institute of International Relations (IIR)
- Trinidad and Tobago.</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>The Institute of International Relations of Cameroon
(IRIC) - Yaounde.</FONT> <BR>
<BR>

</UL>

<P>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Regional Centers of Excellence have the following
objectives:<BR>
</FONT></B>
<UL>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>To familiarize decision-makers and diplomats
with the potential applications and implications of Information
Technology in international relations.</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>To support and perform educational activities
which increase the popular understanding of the opportunities,
challenges and dangers posed by developments in Information technology
and telecommunications.</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>To support the creation of national and regional
political, legal and economic structure that will encourage the
use of Information Technologies for development.</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>To provide training and capacity building in
Information Technology for diplomats and students of international
relations and diplomacy.</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>To initiate the process of the computerization
of Ministries of Foreign Affairs;</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>To participate in the creation of regional IT-infrastructure
for the exchange of information about the regional political,
economic and social issues.</FONT>
<LI><FONT SIZE=2>To promote and conduct academic research on the
following issues: the development of IT and foreign policy of
developing countries, the participation of developing countries
in the Global Information Infrastructure, the importance of the
transfer of information technology and the protection of intellectual
property for the foreign policy of developing countries, etc.</FONT>

</UL>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The coordination and conceptualisation of the Networking
Project is done by the Coordinating Unit established by the Diplomatic
Studies Programme and Commonwealth Network of IT for Development.
The Coordinating Unit is at the Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic
Studies, Malta.<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="description.htm" >Full Description of the Project</A>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>For more information contact:<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Coordinating Unit: Networking Project &quot;Diplomacy@IT&quot;</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>University of Malta</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Msida, Malta</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>phone: +356-483090; fax:+356-483091</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>e-mail: netproject@medac.comnet.mt; http://www.medac.comnet.mt/netproject/
<BR>
</FONT>
</BODY>

