<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">COURSE ON INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY
AND DIPLOMACY</FONT></B>
<HR>

<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Arial">INTRODUCTION<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Following decades of rapid technological
development, information technology (IT) enters into a new phase
of growing applications in most areas of human life. The lower
cost and increasing performance of hardware, as well as the power
and easy use of software, have all come together in a way that
will fundamentally alter the way most people live and work. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">Diplomacy like many other human activities
is profoundly transformed. Moreover, since the key ingredients
of diplomacy - <B>information</B> and <B>interaction </B>- are
nowadays highly automated through digitalization and networking,
the changes in diplomacy is even more substantial. The development
of IT will compel diplomats:<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI>to work in <I>the new social, political and economic environment
</I>characterized by the changes in the concept of sovereignty,
the emergence of the global economy and global information infrastructure;
<LI>to deal with <I>new topics</I> such as protection of intellectual
property on a multilateral and bilateral level, and 
<LI>to use <I>the new tools </I>made available by information
technology, such as automation of office activities, global networking,
etc.. <BR>
<BR>

</UL>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The Course is based on the comprehensive
and interdisciplinary approach to information technology and diplomacy.
Beside providing training in the use of the computer as a working
tool, the Course focuses also on various issues raised through
the use of information technology. Thus the main objective of
the Course is to provide participants with proper conceptual and
methodological skills for working in the new international environment
which is shaped, to a large extent, by information technology.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Arial">The Course is divided into the following
three areas:<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="Newenvir.htm" ><B>New political, social and economic environment for diplomatic activities;</B></A>
<LI><A HREF="NEWTOPIC.htm" ><B>New topics on diplomatic agendas;</B></A>
<LI><A HREF="Newtools.htm" ><B>New tools for diplomats</B></A>.
<BR>

</UL>

</BODY>

</HTML>
