<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The OSCE after the 1996 Lisbon Summit</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5>The OSCE after the 1996 Lisbon Summit</FONT></B>
<HR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Lecture by Dr. Martin Dahinden, </FONT></B><FONT SIZE=1>Deputy
Head of OSCE Co-ordination Staff, Federal Department of Foreign
Affairs, Bern<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies, University of Malta
- 9 December 1996<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
The topic of my lecture is &quot;The Organisation for Security
and Co-operation in Europe after the 1996 Lisbon Summit&quot;.
There is probably no better place to have such a lecture than
Malta. Malta has from the beginning, of the previously called
Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe, played an active
and important role within the so-called Helsinki process. At the
same time, Malta has been a door-opener for security co-operation
beyond the Euro-atlantic area, adding to it the Mediterranean
dimension and drawing our attention to the fact that security
in Europe cannot be separate from security of the adjacent areas.
As new kinds of risks and challenges to security in Europe emerge,
we should learn to follow Malta's example and embark in our thinking
and in our deeds beyond the familiar limits.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>The Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe<BR>
</B>
<P>
The Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe (CSCE) was
created in the early 1970s as a multilateral forum for dialogue
and negotiation in the area stretching form Vancouver to Vladiwostok.
In 1975 the Heads of State or Government of the participating
States signed the Helsinki Final Act. At that time the threat
of large scale military confrontation in Europe still existed
and the two blocks represented fundamentaly differing approaches
on ideological, political, economic and human rights issues.<BR>

<P>
The Helsinki Final Act established basic principles for behaviour
among the participating States and of governments towards their
citizens. The Final Act is not a Treaty but a politically binding
agreement like all the subsequent CSCE and OSCE documents. The
CSCE States decided for regular follow-up meetings to review the
implementation of the commitments undertaken, to set new standards
and norms, to expand co-operation and to maintain political dialogue.
The further work was divided into three main parts, the so called
baskets, i.e.<BR>

<OL>
<LI>questions relating to security in Europe,
<LI>Co-operation in the field of economics, science and technology,
and the environment, and
<LI>Co-operation in humanitarian fields. 
</OL>

<P>

<P>
The CSCE was just one element in a very complex and comprehensive
process that led to a peaceful change in Europe. One of CSCE's
specific contribution was to provide a political platform and
strong moral support for the protagonists of democratic change
in Eastern Europe.<BR>

<P>
After signing the Helsinki Final Act, the Heads of States and
Governments of the CSCE states did not met again until the very
end of the Cold War. In 1990 they came together again in Paris
to formally recognise the end of the division of Europe. At that
occasion all CSCE countries committed themselves to the values
of democracy, rule of law, human rights and market economy. The
challenge ahead was no longer the struggle for common values,
but to meet the challenges presented by the post-Cold War period.
<BR>

<P>
The 1990 &quot;Charter of Paris for a New Europe&quot; marked
in fact the turning point in the history of the CSCE. The CSCE
started to change smoothly from a forum for dialogue and negotiation
to a more active operational structure. The first permanent institutions
emerged: the Conflict Prevention Centre in Vienna, the Office
for Free Elections (now known as the Office for Democratic Institutions
and Human Rights) and the Secretariat. The Paris Charter created
also bodies for political consultation and decision-making, starting
with regular summit meetings. In 1994 the name was changed from
Conference to Organisation.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>NATO-Enlargement and European Security Architecture <BR>
</B>
<P>
One week ago, the Heads of State and Government of the 54 OSCE
participating States met again for a Summit Meeting. This Summit
Meeting was dominated by one topic: the forthcoming NATO enlargement.
The differing opinions of the leading statesmen of Europe and
North America were put forth very clearly.<BR>

<P>
In his address, Russian Prime Minister Chernomyrdin energetically
took a stand against the extension of the NATO military infrastructure
in the direction of Russian territory. He conjured up the danger
of creating new dividing lines in Europe. &quot;We are convinced&quot;,
Mr. Chernomyrdin said, &quot;there are still time and reasons
to think once again what the NATO enlargement is conductive to.
If our common goal is a united and peaceful Europe, then how can
we achieve it through the enlargement of military alliances?&quot;.
<BR>

<P>
US Vice President Al Gore took the floor shortly after Prime Minister
Chernomyrdin. He too expressed himself in no uncertain terms.
NATO, he said, is and remains a defensive alliance of like-minded
democratic states. It is a threat to no one, and is a contribution
to the creation of stability. &quot;At the same time as NATO enlargement
proceeds,&quot;, said Vice President Gore, &quot;NATO wants in
parallel to build a strong co-operative relationship with Russia
and other states&quot;.<BR>

<P>
While Russia supports a reinforcement of the OSCE as an umbrella
for European security co-operation, it was clear that they favour
the creation of a special relationship directly between Russia
and NATO outside of the OSCE.<BR>

<P>
Other Heads of State and Government also spoke their minds. French
President Chirac, took a differing view from other leaders of
NATO members and supported like Russia a Charter for European
Security. Leaders of the Baltic and the Visegrad countries emphasised
their willingness to becoming NATO member in near future. Little
by little, a clear and exact reflection of the security concerns
and the security policy objectives of the 54 States in the OSCE
region emerged. The lively debate showed that the OSCE still continues
to be an animated forum for discussion of security issues in the
Euro-atlantic area.<BR>

<P>
The Summit Meeting made it very clear that in the hard core of
security questions, the OSCE will not play a decisive role. The
decision as to whether and how NATO will be enlarged will not
take place within the OSCE. The OSCE cannot supply any substantive
security guarantees. Unlike the United Nations, the OSCE is even
not entitled to resort to any coercive measures. Its decisions
are based on the consensus of all the participating States, and
while executing its decisions the OSCE depends on the co-operation
with the participating states.<BR>

<P>
How can the OSCE contribute under these conditions to security
in Europe?<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>Principles of Behaviour among the Participating States<BR>
</B>
<P>
It is most likely that the OSCE's role will be a supplementary
one very much like the role OSCE played in the days of the Cold
War, when the CSCE established basic principles for behaviour
among States. In Lisbon, the Heads of State or Government were
fully aware of this function OSCE can play also in a strategic
environment that has dramatically changed. Together they made
a profession of allegiance to principles for the co-operation
of the States and of security organisations with each other.<BR>

<P>
Many of these principles now enshrined in the Lisbon Summit Declaration
have not been agreed on the first time. However, in the current
political context, they have taken on a particular significance.
I will now cite a few of those principles: <BR>

<P>
The right of each and every State to choose its own security arrangements,
including treaties of alliance, is reaffirmed.<BR>

<P>
No State may strengthen its security at the expense of other States.
<BR>

<P>
No State or group of States have any superior responsibility for
maintaining peace and stability in the OSCE region.<BR>

<P>
No State or group of States shall regard any part of the OSCE
region as its sphere of influence.<BR>

<P>
Presence of foreign troops on the territory of a participating
State must be in conformity with international law, the freely
expressed consent of the host State, or a relevant decision of
the United Nations Security Council.<BR>

<P>
All of the spheres of security have to be transparent. Security
arrangements - and thereby enlargements of military alliances
- should be of public nature, predictable, and open.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>Interlocking and Mutually Reinforcing Institutions <BR>
</B>
<P>
The principles and commitments just mentioned are important as
norms of behaviour when security organisations in Europe evolve
and security arrangements change. Their real utility is to be
found in the fact that they make the behaviour of the States and
of the organisations more calculable in a difficult phase of international
relations.<BR>

<P>
At the same time, I should emphasised that they are not designed
to prevent the further development and enlargement of security
organisations in Europe. Neither do they define the modalities
for co-operation between the OSCE and other security organisations
such as NATO or WEU. Nor do they define the specific role of each
of those organisations in the future. There is a common understanding
that there should be a non-hierarchic co-operation among interlocking
and mutually reinforcing institutions. But what this exactly means
is still subject for a debate.<BR>

<P>
In the meantime, the peace process for Bosnia and Herzegovina
has provided an important model for this kind of co-operation
and co-ordination among different organisations. Just to recall
some main specifics: The peace process is based on an Agreement
between the parties directly involved. A group of countries -
the contact Group under strong US-leadership - was decisive for
the conclusion and eventually for the implementation of the Dayton
Peace Agreement. The different international organisations had
specific tasks within the peace process according to the particular
contributions they could make. NATO, EU, OSCE, ICRC, UNHCR, World
Bank, Council of Europe and many other organisations carried out
important tasks. However, there is no international organisation
acting as lead agency for the overall peace process.<BR>

<P>
I am convinced that the experience to be drawn from the Dayton
peace process will have a major impact on future forms of co-operation
among security organisations in Europe. It will undoubtedly also
have a major impact on the specific role each organisation will
have in the future.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>New risks and challenges<BR>
</B>
<P>
Unfortunately, NATO enlargement and the co-operation between the
different security organisations almost monopolised the public
attention during the 1996 Lisbon Summit.<BR>

<P>
During the last two years, the OSCE participating States have
in a broad discussion identified and evaluated the risks and challenges
to security in the OSCE area. Despite the important work undertaken
this topic has not enjoyed as much attention as it merits.<BR>

<P>
The risks stemming from military capabilities have been drastically
reduced since the end of the Cold War. This was indeed a result
of disarmament and the confidence and security building measures
in Europe. Where military risks still are important - like the
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction - international co-operation
has been developed and improved.<BR>

<P>
In parallel new risks are becoming important such as ethnic tensions,
aggressive nationalism, violations of the rights of persons belonging
to national minorities, difficulties of economic transition, terrorism,
organised crime, drug and arms trafficking, uncontrolled migration
and environmental damage. <BR>

<P>
Most of those risks affect individual citizens in Europe and North
America more directly than the question of NATO enlargement or
discussions on future European security structures. <BR>

<P>
OSCE's capability to contribute to solving those problems will
be decisive for OSCE's future role and for its continued public
support. This does not mean that the OSCE should develop capabilities
to cope with all sorts of risks and challenges identified. The
OSCE should continue to build on its strength and to more closely
co-operate with other institutions.<BR>

<P>
What could be the specific contributions of OSCE in an international
division of labour with other security organisations. In my view,
the OSCE should concentrate its efforts in three areas:<BR>

<P>
Firstly, OSCE should remain a comprehensive forum for dialogue.
Secondly it should continue its work in the area of arms control,
and thirdly, OSCE should strengthen its role in early warning,
conflict prevention and crisis management. <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>Comprehensive Forum for Dialogue<BR>
</B>
<P>
As I already underlined, the discussion on NATO enlargement at
the Summit Meeting in Lisbon has demonstrated that the OSCE continues
to be an animated forum for discussion of security issues.<BR>

<P>
The Heads of State and Government decided in Lisbon that the OSCE
should actively continue the dialogue on European security which
started two years ago. This dialogue is ambitiously named the
&#132;Discussion on a Common and Comprehensive Security Model
for Europe for the Twenty-first Century&quot;. Among many other
issues, a Platform for Co-operative Security defining the modalities
of co-operation between security organisations is also part of
this dialogue. In the same way, the elaboration of a Charter for
European Security is to be taken into consideration. Unlike the
documents of the OSCE to date, such a Charter would in the view
of France and Russia also contain legally binding elements.<BR>

<P>
The future security dialogue will include a review of the observance
of OSCE principles and the implementation of commitments. In parallel
the dialogue among the 54 OSCE participating states will also
include enhancing instruments of joint co-operative action in
the event of non-compliance with the OSCE commitments by a participating
State. You would surely agree with me that steps for better implementation
of commitments is of greater importance than the further refinement
of existing commitments.<BR>

<P>
The role of the OSCE as a forum for dialogue in which all States
can give a voice to the all the problems concerning their security
cannot be overestimated. This is particularly important for smaller
States like Malta or Switzerland, states which are not members
of any military alliances. They can make themselves heard in the
OSCE on equal terms with other States.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>Arms Control and Disarmament<BR>
</B>
<P>
The OSCE can point to an unique history of success right in the
domain of arms control. Beginning with the time of the Cold War,
the then CSCE has been contributing to an unparalleled transparency
in Europe by means of information exchange, inspections and other
measures. These measures have created confidence among the States
and have decisively diminished the risk of armed conflict and
of misunderstanding or miscalculation of military activities which
could give rise to apprehension, particularly in a situation where
the participating States lack clear and timely information. <BR>

<P>
Even so progress has been made, the OSCE faces still important
challenges in the field of arms control and disarmament. These
tasks concern not only instruments for the whole OSCE area, but
also the development of specific instruments in a regional context.
The already concluded and the yet to come negotiations based on
the Dayton Peace Agreement are examples for this second tier of
arms control tasks.<BR>

<P>
The OSCE participating States have now agreed upon a framework
and an agenda to continue their work after Lisbon and to develop
further instruments of arms control.<BR>

<P>
Of particular significance for security in Europe is the Treaty
on Conventional Armed Forces in Europe (CFE) to which members
of NATO as well as countries of the former Warsaw Pact are parties.
The CFE Treaty is a corner-stone of military co-operation for
all of the OSCE States. This very complex Treaty sets upper limits
for heavy weapons systems and establishes decisive measures for
verification and control. Since the early 1990s, the CFE Treaty
has led to a reduction of conventional armament unparalleled in
history. Till now, approximately 57,000 pieces of major weapons
systems (tanks, artillery pieces, armoured combat vehicles, combat
aircraft and attack helicopters) have been reduced. However, the
Treaty is based on the now obsolete bloc-to-bloc approach. Today's
task is to conserve the achievements of the CFE undiminished,
simultaneously adapting it to the new realities and opening it
up to other States. In the end, all of the States in the OSCE
region will draw profit from an improvement of the CFE Treaty.
This is why in Lisbon all the Heads of States or Government welcomed
the decision of the CFE States Parties to adapt the Treaty. <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>Early Warning, Conflict Prevention and Crisis Management<BR>
</B>
<P>
The third pillar of the OSCE's future role should be a central
role in early warning, conflict prevention, crisis management,
and in post-conflict rehabilitation.<BR>

<P>
It is evident and in keeping with the comprehensive character
of the OSCE that these efforts should not be limited to the political
and military domains, but must also encompass human rights, the
rule of law, the economic dimension, and the environment. Only
in this way will medium and long term success be assured in reducing
tensions and in putting an end to conflicts even before they arise.
<BR>

<P>
The OSCE has been doing this since the early nineties. Pioneer
work in the fields of conflict prevention and crisis resolution.
The OSCE set up a set of early-warning instruments so that political
measures could be applied before tensions broke out into open
conflict.<BR>

<P>
The High Commissioner on National Minorities, a post currently
held by the former Dutch foreign minister Max van der Stoel, functions
as an instrument to identify and promote the early resolution
of ethnic tensions that might endanger peace, stability, or relations
between OSCE participating States. The HCNM operates independently
from all parties involved in tensions. He is empowered to conduct
on-site missions and to engage in preventive diplomacy at an early
stage of tension. He may issue an &quot;early warning report&quot;
to the OSCE, formally calling attention to the seriousness of
the situation. In geographic terms the High Commissioners activities
are very broad. During the year of the Swiss OSCE Chairmanship,
the HKNM was active in Croatia, Estonia, the Former Yugoslav Republic
of Macedonia, Hungary (situation of the Slovak minority), Kazakstan,
Kyrgystan, Latvia, Romania, Slovakia and in the Ukraine.<BR>

<P>
Silent diplomacy is the main working tool of the High Commissioner.
Due to his reputation and the quality of his work, he has access
to the highest political levels. In carrying out his tasks he
works closely together with the Council of Europe and with the
OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights in Warsaw.
<BR>

<P>
The foremost of the many OSCE instruments in the field of conflict
prevention is without any doubt the OSCE Missions. OSCE Missions
are geared to making a long-term contribution to conflict resolution
and to operate under the means of preventive diplomacy. They will
in the future continue to be the most efficient instrument for
conflict prevention.<BR>

<P>
The work of the OSCE Missions was vested with top priority during
the 1996 Swiss OSCE Chairmanship, and it will undoubtedly retain
its priority character in the coming years. <BR>

<P>
At the beginning of the Lisbon Summit the Swiss Minister of Foreign
Affairs, Mr. Flavio Cotti, made a statement on the political situation
in the OSCE region and on the state of the affairs in the OSCE.
It was to a large extent a report on the work done by OSCE Missions.
<BR>

<P>
Tangible progress has been registered in Ukraine: a status of
autonomy for the Crimea has been anchored in the new Constitution.
Progress can also be seen in Moldova, where a political solution
to the conflict in Trans-Dniestria seems possible in the near
future. Improvements were obtained in the South Ossetian conflict
in Georgia, where the OSCE Mission was able to institute a dialogue
on the highest level so that the perspectives for a solution to
the conflict look better at present. The achievements of the OSCE
Mission in Latvia concerning the situation of the local Russia-speaking
population, have also been recognised.<BR>

<P>
In other areas of tension or conflict, there is hardly any progress
to be noted, and the major part of the work lies ahead. In Nagorno-Karabakh,
the two year cease-fire is maintained, but there is a lack of
readiness by the Parties to the conflict to accept a compromise
and to work on a political solution. The OSCE has built up a very
elaborate structure in order to resolve this conflict. However,
without the will of those concerned, the question arises as to
how long the OSCE should continue keeping its elaborate structures
in place.<BR>

<P>
Particularly dramatic is the situation in Tajikistan, a country
on the geographic border of the OSCE area, whose fate is closely
tied to the uncertain developments in Afghanistan, and which is
given only little attention by the western media. It will be one
of the most difficult endeavours for OSCE to ban the risk of a
large scale open conflict and to promote political dialogue between
the parties. This work has to be done together with the United
Nations.<BR>

<P>
Far better known in the public is the role of the OSCE in Chechnya.
It was an unquestionable success that the OSCE was the only Organisation
which was able to remain present with a political mission in an
internal conflict to one of the most powerful participating States.
In doing so, it not only ensured an international presence, informing
the community of States on the developments; it also went to great
efforts to establish dialogue between the Parties or to keep this
dialogue running in the critical phases. This activity has by
no means been concluded. Chechnya is a good example of the fact
that the weaknesses of the OSCE are at the same time its strong
points. With means of coercion or intervention at its disposal,
Russia would hardly ever have agreed to the deployment of an OSCE
Assistance Group in Chechnya. Only the consensus- and dialogue-oriented
methods of the OSCE made it possible to obtain Russia's agreement.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>Bosnia and Herzegovina<BR>
</B>
<P>
The OSCE was neither able to prevent nor to resolve the conflict
in Bosnia. However, it was entrusted with key tasks in the implementation
of the Dayton Peace Agreement. <BR>

<P>
The supervision of the preparation and of the conduct of the elections
by the OSCE was a decisive step in the peace process. The elections
set up legitimate authorities in Bosnia and Herzegovina. However
the conduct of the municipal elections entailing vast potential
for conflict still lies ahead. The support and the supervision
of the Bosnian municipal elections will be one of the chief tasks
of the OSCE next year.<BR>

<P>
Arms control negotiations between the Bosnian Parties and those
in Ex-Yugoslavia were concluded in 1996 under the auspices of
the OSCE. They aim at creating a military equilibrium and confidence
in the military domain. The correct implementation of this task
will place strong demands on the OSCE in the coming years as well.
At present, negotiations are also taking place on far-reaching
disarmament negotiations to stabilise the entire Region.<BR>

<P>
Bosnia was the greatest operational challenge in the history of
the OSCE. In record time, a Mission was set up comprising around
250 experts and 350 local employees in 25 field offices and 5
regional centres. This task could only be carried out due to the
readiness of the OSCE States to make available a considerable
amount of both personnel and financing within a very short time.
As an organisation, the OSCE itself disposes of only an extremely
modest infrastructure. Now it is important that the OSCE assesses
the experience it has gained in Bosnia, and puts it to appropriate
use.<BR>

<P>
Needless to say, it will also be necessary for the OSCE to reinforce
itself institutionally, and above all to increase its ability
to react swiftly to situations of crisis. However, it should thereby
not relinquish the big advantages it has enjoyed till now. As
I see it, these advantages lie primarily in the OSCE's great flexibility,
and in the readiness of the participating States to become directly
engaged within the context of the OSCE, making available both
the personnel and the funds necessary.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>Enhanced Co-operation on Security Issues <BR>
</B>
<P>
To response to tensions and crisis situations is one thing, to
achieve long term stability throughout the OSCE area is quite
another.<BR>

<P>
OSCE has since the early 1990ies developed instruments for better
implementing OSCE commitments. Of particular importance is the
work of the Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights
in the area of election Monitoring, assistance in democratic institution
building and in the promotion of human and political rights.<BR>

<P>
In 1992 a programme of co-ordinated support for recently admitted
participating States was launched for States that have been admitted
to the CSCE in the wake of the disintegration of former Yugoslavia
and the Soviet Union. The programme was designed to make available
to those States diplomatic, academic, legal and administrative
expertise and advice on CSCE matters. In the future, particular
emphasis will be put on the better integration of the Central
Asian States in the OSCE.<BR>

<P>
In Lisbon, the OSCE participating States decided to reinforce
their co-operation in a number of areas in which the OSCE has
particular experience, and which are crucial for long-term security
in Europe.<BR>

<P>
One of the points of emphasis is the promotion of good-neighbourly
relations and of cross-border co-operation. In essence, this is
a form of long-term conflict prevention within a regional context.
Many neighbouring OSCE countries have unresolved problems with
one another. To a modest degree, the OSCE has already promoted
regional co-operation up to now, for instance, by means of regional
round tables or by the creation of confidence-and security-building
measures, within or outside the Stability Pact for Europe. This
is an activity that OSCE now intends to deepen and expand.<BR>

<P>
In the OSCE region today, there are practically no conflicts which
do not originate in one way or another from problems in the relation
between minority and majority segments of the population, or from
problems between different ethnic groups. The war in former Yugoslavia
and the conflicts in the Caucasus region are powerful examples
of this. The OSCE has already established significant commitments
for the States vis-&agrave;-vis persons belonging to national
minorities. It is important that these standards be implemented
properly and that the many outrightly bitter or latent minority
issues in the OSCE area be politically resolved. Switzerland has
made special efforts to ensure that this topic will also be a
part of the reinforced security co-operation among the OSCE States.
The opposition or even harsh reluctance of many States to improving
the situation of minorities and to draw support in this undertaking
by means of international co-operation, was in fact very evident
at the Lisbon Summit. It will require hard work in order to achieve
progress in this domain in the near future. <BR>

<P>
Opposition to fostering deeper co-operation between the OSCE and
the Mediterranean States was also unfortunately quite strong.
This resistance has various causes. The Mediterranean area is
not of the same crucial importance for all of the OSCE participating
States, and therefore many States have no desire in a special
status for co-operation in the Mediterranean partners. The USA
is very sceptical since it has no interest in having core issues
of the Middle East Peace Process become objects of consultation
within the OSCE. However, it is my opinion that Europe and the
entire Mediterranean cannot be separated from one another with
respect to security issues. In end effect, it is thanks to the
unrelentless efforts of Malta that co-operation with the Mediterranean
Partner States was included into the areas of intensified security
co-operation. An important achievement is the decision by the
OSCE States to extend, upon request, experience in the area of
arms control to partner States in the adjacent Mediterranean area.
<BR>

<P>
During its term as Chair-country, Switzerland made particular
efforts to strengthen the efficiency of the work of the OSCE and
to achieve a better division of labour between OSCE and other
international organisations in particular with the United Nations
and with the Council of Europe. In preparing the Summit Meeting
Switzerland was strongly in favour of a package to strengthen
the operational capabilities of the OSCE. Unfortunately there
was not enough support for such an undertaking at the present
time, and the Lisbon achievements in this regard are less than
modest. The OSCE will at least start to elaborate a mandate for
a co-ordinator on OSCE economic and environmental activities.
The idea was strongly supported by the US, Russia and other Eastern
European States and in the same time opposed by the EU. The state
of freedom of media and the treatment of journalists have worsened
during the past few years. In response, the OSCE will elaborate
a mandate for an OSCE Representative on Freedom of the Media.
The Representative's working methods would be similar to those
of the High Commissioner on National Minorities. The idea for
a Media Representative was of German origin and supported by many
other delegations.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>A European Security Process<BR>
</B>
<P>
In closing, permit me to come back to the very beginning of my
lecture and to make a personal remark.<BR>

<P>
I do not believe that in the future Europe will see a firmly-established
security order such as it was after the 1815 Vienna Congress or
following the two World Wars. The future security order will not
be a fixed, long-term oriented structure, but rather more of a
process - a European security process. It is only through continual
adaptation, through constant change, that we can jointly find
answers to the ever more complex security risks and challenges
of the post-Cold War period.<BR>

<P>
Many actors - states, organisations, non-governmental organisations,
and even the media and business enterprises - all make in their
own way various contributions to security in Europe. The role
that I see for the OSCE in this interplay, I have just outlined
to you.<BR>

<P>
The establishment of a hierarchy or of an exact specification
of the role of each and every individual organisation appears
to be neither realistic nor desirable. On the other hand, it is
all the more important that principles and procedures for efficient
further co-operation be developed. <BR>

<P>
In Lisbon, from where Vasco da Gama's voyages to unknown worlds
set sail, the States of the OSCE set out principles and guide-lines
for a steady course along the unknown path which lies ahead of
us.<BR>

<P>
Thank you for your attention. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
