<HEAD>

<TITLE>ADDRESS BY BRITISH HIGH COMMISSIONER OF MALTA</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Trebuchet MS,Arial">
ADDRESS BY BRITISH HIGH COMMISSIONER OF MALTA
<BR>
TO ACADEMY OF DIPLOMATIC STUDIES: 4 DECEMBER 1996<P>
BRITISH FOREIGN POLICY</FONT>
</B></CENTER>

<TT>
<P>
<B><U>Opening Remarks</U></B><BR>

<P>
A Diplomat, like other people, has to adapt to a profoundly changing
world. The revolution in communications and technology means that
today I am never more than minutes away from those in London who
give me instructions and place on me a growing load of requirements.
I confess to some regrets that this is so. I even have a touch
of envy for the
<P>
American Ambassador in Paris at the beginning of the nineteenth
century. Thomas Jefferson is recorded to have written &quot;We
have not heard anything from our Ambassador to France for three
years. If we do not hear from him this year, let us write him
a letter.&quot;
<P>
Times have changed. A constant flow of telegrams crosses my desk
and that of every other British diplomat every day. The opportunity
to act without instructions has all but disappeared. Again I am
tempted to view with nostalgia the comment of the nineteenth century
British Foreign Secretary, Lord Palmerston that
<P>
&quot;The only use of a plenipotentiary is to disobey his instructions.
A messenger would do if it is necessary to follow them strictly.&quot;
<P>
But if we are too close to home by fax and E-mail to be able to
act without instructions we are also close enough to influence
them. I rather like the description of diplomacy by a slightly
later Foreign secretary, Lord Salisbury. He commented that a diplomat's
skills involved
<P>
&quot;a judicious suggestion here, an opportune civility there,
a wise concession at one moment and a far sighted persistence
at another; tact, immovable calmness and patience that no folly,
no provocation, no blunder can shake.&quot;
<P>
This is not to say that British diplomacy always lives up to this
but I will conclude this introduction to my remarks today by thanking
the Director of the Academy for the civility of his invitation
to be with you this morning.
<P>
<B><U>Introduction</U></B>
<P>
British Foreign policy today is directed to ensuring that the
United Kingdom and the Dependent Territories for which we are
responsible are secure and prosperous and that British nationals
can live, trade and travel safely overseas in a decent and stable
world. 8.6 million British nations live abroad and we are responsible
for 16 Dependent Territories in the Atlantic, Pacific, Indian
Ocean and Caribbean including one territory in the Mediterranean,
Gibraltar.<BR>

<P>
British well being depends on interests that still stretch around
the world. Proportionately we invest, trade and travel abroad
more than any other country. Pursuing our overseas interests is
an increasingly complex business. The markets for goods, services
and information are mare and more global. Countries are increasingly
interdependent and achieving our goals is easier if we can build
alliances and partnerships whose aims overlap ours. The united
Kingdom belongs to 80 international organisations. We need multilateral
diplomacy to achieve effective action on crime, drugs, terrorism,
the environment and arms control all of which issues have a direct
consequence for British nationals.<BR>

<P>
Our position in the world remains a strong one. our economy is
the sixth largest in the world. With only I% of the world's population,
we account for 5% of world trade. 35% of the frontline staff in
British diplomatic posts around the world are devoted to trade
promotion, more than are occupied in any other task.
<P>
No other country combines a seat on the UN Security Council with
membership of NATO, the EU, the G7 and the Commonwealth. It is
worth picking out some recent examples of our activities to illustrate
their global spread. We can claim a substantial share of the credit
for the progress towards peace in former Yugoslavia. In Hong Kong
we have reached agreement with China on the handover of responsibilities.
In the southern hemisphere we have obtained Argentina's co-operation
for a Falklands oil exploration licensing round without compromising
our position on sovereignty.<BR>

<P>
We communicate from London with an audience of 140 million through
the BBC World Service. Through another organisation, the British
Council, we promote British education, culture, science and technology.
our Know How Fund has been playing a successful part in helping
the political and economic reform of Eastern Europe and the countries
of the former Soviet Union. More widely the British overseas Assistance
programme has been praised by the OECD amongst others for its
business-like approach.
<P>
<B><U>Britain and the EU</U></B>
<P>
Britain's commitment to the EU is one of the major pillars of
our Foreign Policy. Many of you may be interested in our attitude
to the European Union mainly in the context of Malta's own evolving
linkages with the Union. I shall not be addressing the question
of what Malta's relationship with Europe should be. That is for
the Maltese to determine. Not for a British diplomat. But we have
assured the Government of Malta that we are supportive of their
intention to have a close and developing relationship with the
European Union. We also will be continuing to work for close bilateral
relations with Malta.
<P>
May I firmly dispose of the misleading view that the British are
reluctant Europeans. We are too conscious of our position on the
western edge of the European continent to believe that the affairs
of the rest of Europe, just across the channel, are not our business.
We have seen the European Community, now the Union, as one of
the mast important means whereby the countries of Western Europe
have become reconciled, our most important national interest is,
like other countries, in our territorial security; the maintenance
of peace and stability, not only in the countries of the present
European Union, but in the whole of Europe and its immediately
adjacent areas. This includes the Mediterranean region.<BR>

<P>
Our own national interests go beyond this. We in Britain live
by international commerce. We export a third of what we produce:
more than Germany and France; more even than Japan and the United
States. Britain is more heavily involved in outward investment
than any other country except the United States, only the United
States attracts more foreign inward investment, over 40% of all
investment in Europe from the United States and Japan comes to
the United Kingdom. Britain is the world's leading centre for
international banking and foreign exchange. It is the most important
centre for aviation and marine insurance. Through the services
we provide we help others to improve their own economic performance.
We also help ourselves. Insular isolation was never an option
for us. As President Kennedy put it more than three decades ago
- No nation can build its destiny alone.<BR>

<P>
It follows that we were never interested in a Europe that was
going to be inward looking and exclusive. Before entering the
community we wanted to know what sort of Europe we were joining.
But from the standpoint of British national interest we could
not afford to stay outside a European community which was becoming
the most important trading block in the world. The Single Market
was not quite made in Britain - but very nearly. It was launched
by a British commissioner. It was completed under a UK Presidency.
It was based on British ideas about how to bring prosperity to
the people of Europe. It now accounts for 371 million consumers
and over 40% of world trade. We needed to be a part of the decision
making process within that market. Associate status or a Norwegian
style, free-trading relationship was not the answer for the United
Kingdom. Such a relationship would have given us market access
but it would have excluded us from the decision making process.
We would have had to accept standards and technical norms imposed
by the Union for the most important part of our exports without
having any say on what standards were adopted. We needed to be
able to influence how the community developed.<BR>

<P>
Having joined the community, we have no doubts about the benefits:
benefits of membership of the single market, benefits of working
together with other nations of the Union in a Common Foreign and
Security Policy and in co-operating in Justice and Home Affairs.
But we have always had a clear view about what type of Union we
wanted to belong to. Most importantly we have always seen the
nation state as the basic building block of the international
system. The state remains the object of most people's primary
allegiance. International relations are about dealings between
states. The reality is that there is no demand or wish on the
part of the people of Europe to surrender their national identities
to a super state. The United Kingdom believes that the European
Union, if it is to carry the support of its peoples with it, has
to be a partnership of nations rather like de Gaulle's concept
of a &quot;Europe des Patries&quot;.<BR>

<P>
<B><U>CFSP</U></B>
<P>
In the field of the European Union's Common Foreign and Security
Policy Britain has strongly supported the co-ordination of national
policies and believes that this could go further. We have co-operated
in the agreement of common positions which have enabled the Community
to speak out with a united voice on many world problems - a process
in which incidentally candidate members for membership have been
encouraged to associate themselves. But we believe that this process
needs to be one in which the members of the Union participate
as individual nations. We aim to proceed through common analysis
to common policy and common action but we do not see the Common
Foreign and Security Policy of the EU replacing national foreign
policies. Our experience is that if there is no collective will
within the European Union to act, it is unwise to try to force
through action for instance by artificial voting procedures. And
we value the different perspectives that different countries bring
to discussion of issues: in our case a special awareness of the
importance of transatlantic relations; in the case of the southern
members of the Union wider Mediterranean insights.
<P>
<B><U>EU/Mediterranean Perspectives</U></B>
<P>
Europe needs firm action and firm decisions. It should not be
just a talking shop. I have already mentioned Britain's belief
that Europe's interests must extend to areas adjacent to Europe.
For that reason we welcomed the opening of the EU/Mediterranean
dialogue in Barcelona last October. In Barcelona we made a specific
proposal which received general support. We believe that economic
development has a major contribution to make to the stability
of the region. In our view a priority for the EU should be to
try to encourage and facilitate the flow of private investment
from Britain to the Mediterranean. Our Barcelona proposal involved
two British initiatives:<BR>

<P>
- a study to be jointly financed by the European Commission and
the United Kingdom into constraints on inward investments in the
Mediterranean
<P>
- an investment conference to be held in London on 6 and 7 March
1997.
<P>
A study by professional consultants is well underway. They are
producing material on individual Mediterranean markets either
a Business Guide or an Investors Guide for the developing markets
of the region. The main outputs of the former are Jordan, Egypt,
Tunisia and Morocco. Business guides will be produced on Algeria,
Syria, Lebanon and the Palestine Authority. Malta along with Cyprus,
Israel and Turkey is expected to produce its own Business Guide
for the conference.
<P>
What we are proposing, which has the blessings of the European
commission and others, is much more specifically targetted than
exercises such as the Amman summit. We are not seeking to look
at the whole economic future of the region. We are looking at
the specific question of what it is that has deterred investment
in North Africa and the Middle East. Why has it received such
a tiny fraction of the vast investment that is going on around
the world? How can both the countries concerned change their own
international economic policies to attract investment. How can
the businessmen, the financial institutions and others in Western
Europe be made aware of the scope for investment in those states?
<BR>

<P>
Our initiative is of course not the whole of the answer for the
problems of the region. We support for example the work being
done on a stability charter. First of all this is a political
declaration. secondly, it will provide for easier and more regular
contacts on issues that night cause tension between European and
Middle Eastern countries. Throughout the world preventive diplomacy
is going to be given a greater priority than it has had in the
past. A stability charter will be relevant in making easier and
more productive the kind of diplomatic links that can identify
potential sources of tension. A precedent is the stability pact
for the Central and Eastern European countries and their relationship
with Western Europe. That has been seen as a helpful innovation.
We are supporting a similar innovation in South-Eastern Europe
and we have floated the idea of such a process in the Middle East.
<P>
An important element in the region's security and stability is
continuing progress with the Middle East Peace Process. We watched
with great concern the recent developments that led to tragic
bloodshed on the West Bank and Gaza strip, and caused the peace
process to falter. It is essential that the parties should regain
the momentum that has been lost. We have been active in the United
Nations, in the EU, and in bilateral contacts at the highest level
with leaders in the region: we have urged that confidence in the
process be restored by the fulfilment of commitments under existing
agreements.<BR>

<P>
The UK's commitment to peace in the region is also shown by our
continued financial contribution to the Palestinians (some 87
million pounds from 1994 to 1997). The EU is the largest aid donor
to the region.
<P>
<B><U>Britain and NATO</U></B>
<P>
A second pillar of our Foreign Policy is our membership of NATO.
The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation came into existence 50
years ago. It has proved to be one of the most durable military
alliances in history, and the most successful.
<P>
It has enhanced the security of all its members because its objectives
are simple and credible. The Washington Treaty declared that an
armed attack upon the territory of any member state would be regarded
as an attack on all. To wage war on one is to declare war on all.
NATO added to other pressures on the Soviet system and economy,
played a significant role in its collapse and hundreds of millions
of Europeans emerged from the shadows to democracy. NATO had not
had to fire a shot. The challenges today are different as we have
seen in the Gulf and Bosnia.
<P>
We believe NATO has a continuing vital role in responding to threats
to peace. Rapid deployment can be the key to containment: to checking
adventurism before it escalates into all-out conflict. It is therefore
also a highly cost-effective deterrent. NATO is developing a Combined
Joint Task Force Headquarters to plan for such missions. Britain
is working on similar lines. We have established a Joint Rapid
Deployment Force and a Permanent Joint Headquarters to give us
the means of effective rapid response to a threat to our interests.
<BR>

<P>
There is a risk that, despite our best efforts, stockpiles of
weapons of mass destruction will grow and spread. Over a dozen
countries have either a capability to deploy chemical or biological
weapons, or development programmes at an advance stage. A few
of then are already capable of producing chemical or biological
warheads for ballistic missiles.<BR>

<P>
The likelihood of conflict is if anything increasing. We have
seen how the end of superpower tension has emboldened others to
push their territorial and ideological ambitions. We have seen
overt aggression and the covert export of terrorism. Nor do we
believe can we relax our vigilance in the nuclear field. Like
others we are concerned about reports that further counties may
be seeking to develop nuclear weapons.<BR>

<P>
The United Kingdom believes that our planning must take account
of potential crisis points across the world. The last assessment
I read had 53 entries.
<P>
Past differences between European countries and America over Bosnia
were not healthy. Europe was criticised for not dealing effectively
with the crisis. It is evident that Bosnia was too much for Europe
alone. We have always put a premium on close relations with the
United States. The transatlantic relationship is another pillar
of our policies. The United Kingdom believes that the proper European
attitude to America should be to reinforce United States' involvement
by building the European identity within NATO, and developing
the ability of European nations to contribute more to the Alliance.
<BR>

<P>
We recognise that Russia is also fundamental to equilibrium in
Europe. NATO and Russia must build a real strategic partnership,
founded on substance. We believe we need to build a new security
architecture with Russia. No-one can describe exactly what the
building will look like when finished. And for the moment Russians,
even Russian Defence Ministers, have many other things on their
mind.
<P>
Each journey begins with a step and we believe that there are
steps that we should take now. The Russian co-operation with IFOR
in Bosnia has required us to establish liaison arrangements through
an exchange of officers. The United Kingdom believes those can
be made permanent and indeed broadened.
<P>
The fact that we can talk of such a new relationship with Russia
emphasises how different the world has become.
<P>
<B><U>The Commonwealth</U></B>
<P>
A fourth pillar of our Foreign Policy is the Commonwealth which
encompasses a quarter of mankind.
<P>
We are 53 different nations. We have 53 different sets of experiences
to share, and a wealth of history to guide us. Our membership
is not limited to a particular geographical region. We take a
genuinely global perspective. We are committed to far-reaching
principles, and are involved in the consideration of practical
responses to the new challenges of today.<BR>

<P>
As one example the Commonwealth's Private Investment Initiative
was launched during President Mandela's historic visit to Britain
in July.
<P>
The Initiative's first regional fund, in Africa, has already approved
projects in Zambia and Zimbabwe.
<P>
Trade and investment is the theme which Prime Minister Major has
proposed for next year's Commonwealth Heads of Government meeting
in Edinburgh. We do not forget in our efforts to promote increased
trade that investment can be slow to reach the poorest countries.
In 1994, only three per cent of total private flows of the developing
world went to Africa. There are many countries where development
assistance will have a vital role for some time helping to create
the conditions in which they too can benefit from economic successes
elsewhere. The Commonwealth's technical assistance programmes
are an example of well-targeted aid helping to meet this aim.
They have Britain's strong support.<BR>

<P>
Britain has also been at the forefront of efforts to ease the
debt burden weighing on the most heavily-indebted countries. The
British Chancellor of the Exchequer, was Pleased at last month's
meeting of Commonwealth Finance Ministers to secure support for
his ideas on debt relief ideas first advanced at earlier Commonwealth
meetings in Valletta and in Trinidad and Tobago. This Commonwealth
endorsement helped secure agreement the following week at the
IMF and World Bank in Washington.
<P>
<B><U>The United Nations</U></B>
<P>
The United Nations has done good work for five decades. The United
Kingdom has been at its heart from the start. From the drafting
of the Charter, as first host in London of this Assembly and of
the Security Council, we have been the UN's staunch supporter.
<P>
From the first stirrings of environmental concern in the 1960s;
to the fight against AIDS since the 1980s; through to management
innovation and financial reform in the 1990s; Britain has been
a driving force for the UN's changing agenda. In 1947 we were
a party to the first case to come before the International Court
of Justice. This year a British judge became the Court's first
ever woman member.
<P>
Even before the end of the Cold War our forces have served the
UK cause for decades. For 30 years the UN operation in Cyprus
has depended on British troops and logistics. In the last five
years British forces have served in Kuwait and Cambodia, Rwanda
and Angola, Georgia and Bosnia. Today Britain commits more troops
to UK peacekeeping than any other member state with 10,250 out
of a total of 69,000.
<P>
We believe we need a strong and effective United Nations.
<P>
Britain and France has sketched out a model, to use the skills
of diplomats, soldiers, academics and others to defuse tension
and promote dialogue. The presence of aid workers, human rights
monitors, or UN envoys can help contain a brewing crisis. We strongly
support the OAU'S efforts to work with the UN in preventive diplomacy
and conflict resolution.
<P>
<B><U>Peacebuilding</U></B>
<P>
Our second proposal is for a new approach to peacebuilding. To
provide lasting security requires more than diplomacy and military
force. To build real peace we must bridge the gap between our
humanitarian aid and long-term development work.
<P>
We suggest two elements are key to a new approach.
<P>
First, we must adopt a <B>longer-term perspective</B> in tackling immediate
crises. Even when a ceasefire is holding, or elections have taken
place, if the framework of society is shaky, a continued international
presence can offer stability until a government can cope.
<P>
Second, we think we need <B>far better co-ordination</B> in what we do.
If funds are to be gathered and used quickly and effectively,
donors themselves must make a greater effort to meet their promises
of help. Before operations begin, as planning gets underway, 
the International Financial Institutions must be involved from
the start, as they were in Cambodia. All the actors in the UN
system must be working together, military and political, humanitarian
and development, crossing the traditional boundaries between rival
baronies. Such a Coalition of interest could plug the gap we see
too often now, until the major reconstruction programmes can begin.
<P>
Our proposal is to build on these principles in <B>UN Programmes
for Stabilisation and Transition</B>.
<P>
Britain supports enlargement of the Security Council; to broaden
its base without reducing its effectiveness. Permanent membership
is the key issue. Permanent members of the Security Council must
be both willing and able to make a significant contribution through
the UN to international security. That is what the Security Council
is about. This is what it must remain if it is to be effective.
Germany and Japan are playing an increasing part across the range
of UN business, and are among the top three financial contributors.
It is right that they should benefit from an expansion of the
permanent membership, with the wider rights that entails, but
also with the wider responsibilities. To contribute to security
and peacekeeping. Broad geographical balance in an enlarged Council
also need to be maintained.<BR>

<P>
But the UN system will never work if we do not fund it properly.
The UN is on the verge of financial collapse. It is owed over
3.7 billion dollars in unpaid contributions. Troop contributors
are owed nearly I billion dollars. Last year 39 countries failed
to pay at all. The UK favours tightening of penalties for non-payment,
including the charging of regular budget deficits from the peacekeeping
budget. Perhaps an appropriate policy could best be entitled no
representation with taxation!<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Britain and Africa</B></U>
<P>
An example of the United Kingdom's approach to regional problems
is the UK African peacekeeping initiative, launched in September
1994. This is playing a leading role by helping Africans to respond
to regional crises. In January 1995 Zimbabwe joined the UK in
organising a workshop for senior officers from 17 African countries
to examine peacekeeping practices and principles. We have since
hosted two African peacekeeping map exercises, most recently in
March this year. The Zimbabwe staff College has became the first
regional centre of excellence for UN peacekeeping training, and
we assisted its development and the first peacekeeping course
there last November. We are working on a comparable centre of
excellence in Ghana.<BR>

<P>
Besides helping with training, we offer practical assistance to
African armies for peacekeeping tasks. short term training teams
from the UK helped train the Zimbabweans for deployment to Angola,
and the Ghanaians in January 1996 before their deployment in Liberia.
The Anglo-French Peacekeeping Glossary, done by the Ghana Armed
Forces staff College was another way in which we brought support
efforts together. We are sponsoring two African military officers
on secondment to the UN secretariat, which will help increase
African experience of the UN and give the UN a source of African
expertise.
<P>
Africa is at the heart of British assistance for overseas development.
Last year we spent some 400 million pounds on direct support for
Africa. Some of it was for emergency relief. But our main objectives
in Africa as elsewhere are to help reduce poverty and increase
growth.
<P>
<U><B>Conclusion</B></U>
<P>
I was told long ago that a diplomat hovers between banality and
indiscretion. People want to be told things that he should not
reveal and are impatient if he is discreet. I regret that much
of what I have said will not be new to you but I have tried to
put it into context.
</TT>
</BODY>

</HTML>

</DOC>
