</TD><TD WIDTH=295></TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<B>Basic readings<BR>
<BR>
</B>AKEHURST, chapter 10<BR>
BROWNLIE, chapter 25, sections 8-10<BR>
BUERGENTHAL, chapter 5, sections IV, V<BR>
GREEN, chapter 25<BR>
LEVI, chapter 17<BR>
SHEARER, chapter 14, sections 7, 8<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=2>Definition and typology<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=2>In the broadest sense, a treaty is an
agreement between two or more subjects of international law, which
is governed by that law. The Vienna Conventions on the law of
treaties (1975) and on the law of treaties between states and
international organizations and between international organizations
(1986) moreover require that such agreements must be put down
in writing. The name given to a particular agreement (charter,
covenant, convention, treaty, agreement, protocol, exchange of
notes, etc.) does not affect its legal status. A written treaty
normally consists of an introductive part (title, designation
of parties, preamble), a substantive part and final clauses (consent
to be bound, entry into force, termination, possibly renewal,
authentic languages etc.).<BR>
<BR>
A distinction is made between bilateral treaties concluded between
two parties only and multilateral treaties concluded between three
or more parties. Bilateral treaties are written in two original
copies and exchanged, multilateral treaties in a single original
copy which is given to a depository. A bilateral treaty may permit
accession by other parties, and thus become a multilateral treaty
after the first accession.<BR>
<BR>
Another distinction is made between contractual treaties, which
deal with a transaction, and law-making treaties, which lay down
objective rules applicable to all parties. Among the latter the
conventions codifying and developing rules of international law
are the best known.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="conclusion"><B><FONT SIZE=2>The conclusion of treaties
<BR>
</FONT></B></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>To conclude a treaty, it is normally necessary to
negotiate its content. For bilateral treaties this is done by
duly empowered representatives of the parties in face-to-face
discussions or even over the telephone, by fax or using electronic
facilities. Multilateral treaties are negotiated within the framework
of a conference or of a collective organ of an international organization.
Once the text is agreed on, it has to be authenticated to prevent
any further unilateral modifications. Bilateral treaties are authenticated
by initialing each page. Multilateral treaties are approved by
the deliberative organ in a resolution to which their text is
appended, and which is in turn signed by the person chairing the
meeting, thus providing the necessary authentication.<BR>
<BR>
Consent to be bound may already be expressed by signing a treaty.
Mostly however signature merely means an undertaking to initiate
internal procedures for obtaining consent to be bound, which will
then be expressed by ratification or approval. Ratification is
done through a formal instrument signed by the head of State.
The instrument of approval is signed by a lesser authority such
as the head or a member of the government. In the case of bilateral
treaties, their text is incorporated into the instrument expressing
consent to be bound and these are exchanged. In the case of multilateral
treaties the instrument is simply a statement of consent to be
bound and is handed over to the depository. Where a treaty provides
for the possibility of accession, an instrument of accession,
similar to one of ratification or approval of the multilateral
treaty, is handed over to the depository.<BR>
<BR>
A bilateral treaty may take the form of an exchange of notes in
which each party already expresses consent to be bound. A normal
treaty may provide that consent to be bound be expressed through
the notification that internal procedures with regard to the conclusion
and bringing into force of treaties have been complied with.<BR>
<BR>
At the internal level of States, consent to be bound may be subject
to previous approval of the treaty by parliament or even popular
vote.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="entry"><B><FONT SIZE=2>Entry into force<BR>
</FONT></B></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>This is governed by the final provisions of the treaty,
which for this reason, become effective as soon as the text is
authenticated.<BR>
<BR>
Bilateral treaties become effective as a result of signature or
of the exchange of instruments expressing consent to be bound,
or after the lapse of a stated time after such signature or exchange.
Provisional implementation pending the final expression of consent
to be bound may be provided for.<BR>
<BR>
In the case of multilateral treaties a distinction must be made
between entry into force of the treaty as such and its entry into
force with regard to a given party. The treaty itself will become
effective after a stipulated number of parties have expressed
consent to be bound. With regard to these parties, the treaty
becomes effective at the same time. For each party expressing
consent to be bound after the treaty itself has entered into force,
it becomes effective as a result of this expression of consent
to be bound. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="validity"><B><FONT SIZE=2>Validity<BR>
</FONT></B></A><BR>
<FONT SIZE=2>The validity of a bilateral treaty or of consent
to be bound by a multilateral treaty may be challenged in the
following situations:<BR>
<BR>
1. The person expressing consent to be bound lacked the necessary
powers to do this, or the provisions of municipal law regarding
the expression of such consent have not been observed or only
incompletely implemented. Invalidity may be claimed in such cases
provided the other party or parties had no grounds to believe
in good faith that consent to be bound was properly expressed.
<BR>
2. Consent to be bound has been expressed as the result of an
error which was essential for such consent to be given.<BR>
3. Consent to be bound was obtained as a result of deliberate
misleading of the party concerned (fraud).<BR>
4. Consent to be bound was obtained by using violence against
the representative of the party in question or against the party
itself.<BR>
5. The treaty as a whole or parts of it are incompatible with
provisions of <I>jus cogens</I> existing at the time of its conclusion
or which have emerged afterwards.<BR>
<BR>
The validity of consent to be bound is not affected by a change
of government in which the one that authorised it is replaced
legally or illegally by another. This is so because the treaty
binds the State as such and not any given organ of it.<BR>
<BR>
Invalidity of consent to be bound normally deploys its effects
only from the moment it was established (<I>ex nunc</I>) and does
not cancel effects the treaty may have already deployed. The Vienna
Convention of 1975 however provides for the possibility that consent
to be bound has been invalid from the outset (<I>ex tunc</I>)
and that any effects already deployed must be voided retroactively.
This may be difficult if the treaty has been implemented for a
certain length of time and legal situations have been created
in good faith as a result.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="amendment"><B>Amendment and revision<BR>
</B></A><BR>
Parties to a treaty in force may agree to modify some of its provisions
without wishing to affect its continued validity as a whole. The
possibility and procedure of amending a treaty are normally laid
down in its final clauses. For a bilateral treaty, both sides
must agree to an amendment. In the case of multilateral treaties,
it may be possible to approve amendments by majority, which then
become binding on all parties after having been ratified by a
requisite number of them. It may also be that amendments only
bind those who accepted them and that parties which rejected them
remain bound by the treaty in its original form among themselves
as well as with regard to those which accepted the amendment.
<BR>
<BR>
Parties may wish to completely overhaul a treaty. In the case
of multilateral treaties, this may be provided for in the treaty
itself, e.g. article 109 of the UN Charter. Revised treaties normally
can only bind parties which have accepted the revision, and thus
there may be situations were some States remain bound among themselves
and with regard to others by an earlier version whereas others
are already bound in their mutual relations by the revised version.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
Second session<BR>
<BR>
<B>TREATIES II: RESERVATIONS, EFFECTS, SPECIAL CLAUSES,    INTERPRETATION,
TERMINATION, SUCCESSION<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Basic readings<BR>
<BR>
</B>AKEHURST, chapter 10<BR>
BROWNLIE, chapter 25, sections 8-10<BR>
BUERGENTHAL, chapter 5, sections IV, V<BR>
GREEN, chapter 25<BR>
LEVI, chapter 17<BR>
SHEARER, chapter 14, sections 7, 8<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="reservations"><B>Reservations<BR>
</B></A><BR>
During the conclusion of a multilateral treaty some States may
express reservations regarding specific provisions or their interpretation,
while still wanting to ratify the treaty as such. States who would
like to accede to an already existing treaty may find themselves
in a similar situation. Provided no provision of the treaty nor
indeed its very nature exclude this, such States may, when depositing
their instrument of ratification or accession, make a statement
that they will not consider themselves bound by a specific provision,
or will only accept to be bound if a certain interpretation is
given to it.<BR>
<BR>
Normally a reservation should only be applicable with regard to
parties which have consented to it. However the Vienna Convention
of 1975 has codified a different approach which at the time was
already well established: The reservation is notified to all parties.
Those which do not react are considered to have accepted it. Those
which object must indicate whether this only concerns the reservation
itself or whether they object also to the treaty becoming effective
between them and the State who made the reservation.<BR>
<BR>
This practice gives rise to several regimes regarding the implementation
of the treaty: (1) among parties who have not made a reservation
the treaty applies in full; (2) between the party that made a
reservation and those which failed to object to it, the treaty
applies as modified by the reservation; (3) between the party
who made a reservation and the parties which only objected to
the reservation as such, the treaty applies minus the provision
affected by the reservation; (4) between the party who made a
reservation and those which as a result objected to that party
being admitted to the treaty, the latter does not apply at all.
In this last case however, the State which made a reservation
is still counted as a party to the treaty as long as at least
one other party did not object to its admission.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="effects"><B>Effects<BR>
</B></A><BR>
Once a treaty is in force between them, parties are expected to
implement its provisions in good faith. The same good faith is
sometimes invoked for not implementing a provision when this has
become impossible or very difficult due to a fundamental change
of the circumstances that prevailed at the time of the conclusion
of the treaty (<I>clausula rebus sic stantibus</I>). This &quot;clause&quot;
is sometimes invoked with regard to the treaty as a whole. International
practice, including that of tribunals, is very reticent to accept
this type of reasoning.<BR>
<BR>
According to a basic principle of international law, a treaty
can only deploy its effects among parties to it. It may not grant
rights or impose obligations to third parties. The law of treaties
as codified by the Vienna Convention of 1975 admits some exceptions
to this rule:<BR>
<BR>
- If rights are granted to a third party and the latter accepts
them or simply makes use of them, it acquires a title to such
rights.<BR>
- If duties are imposed on a third party and the latter formally
accepts them, it enters an obligation to abide by them.<BR>
<BR>
A special problem arises if a State concludes treaties with different
partners whose contents are incompatible. Normally this means
that the State in question will have to choose which treaty provision
it wants to implement and to accept the consequences of not abiding
by the other. In the case of regional integration systems, parties
tend to undertake the duty of re-negotiating existing treaties
which are not compatible with that system. Pending this, they
are permitted to continue implementing the earlier treaties. On
the other hand they are not allowed to conclude new treaties that
would not be compatible with the integration regime.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="special"><B>Special clauses<BR>
</B></A><BR>
The Most Favoured Nation Clause, in its traditional guise, is
found in bilateral treaties. The parties agree to give each other
the benefit of more favourable regimes that they might in future
grant to another State. Contrary to affirmations made in the past,
the compulsory granting of such a regime is not subject to the
other party offering countervailing concessions.<BR>
<BR>
The General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) has introduced
the most favoured nation clause at the multilateral level. Any
party consenting a more favourable regime to either another party
or a third State must grant the same advantages to all other parties
to the GATT. Thanks to this system, the worldwide level of customs
duties has been reduced significantly within a few decades.<BR>
<BR>
A General System of Preferences (GSP) has been introduced by GATT
with regard to developing countries. Rich countries granting a
special advantage to one developing country have to extend it
to all others, while not having to do the same with regard to
other rich countries. Developing countries benefitting from GSP
are not obliged to grant reciprocal facilities to the country
offering it to them, nor to other members of GATT. A similar regime
has been incorporated into the Lom&eacute; Conventions between
members of the European Union and ACP countries for the benefit
of the latter. Developing countries outside the ACP group are
not allowed to benefit from this regime.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="interpretation"><B>Interpretation<BR>
</B></A><BR>
It is not always possible to draft treaty clauses in such a way
as to make them perfectly clear. Moreover, treaty provisions are
often the result of a compromise which in fact hides a disagreement
between parties. Thus their meaning is deliberately obscure. All
this means that interpretation is more often required than not.
<BR>
<BR>
International practice, as codified by the Vienna Convention of
1975, places the treaty text at the centre of any interpretation
efforts. As long as the text allows for a clear implementation
which does not lead to unreasonable or absurd results, there is
no need to look for a different meaning through interpretation.
If the text lacks clarity, assistance has first to be sought from
the context provided by the remainder of the provision, by the
treaty itself or by the subject-matter it deals with. If the context
fails to clarify the matter, the views of the parties at the time
of conclusion of the treaty may be elicited from preparatory work
(<I>travaux pr&eacute;paratoires</I>) such as minutes of deliberations
or statements made by representatives of the parties.<BR>
<BR>
Treaties in force for a long time tend to acquire a life of their
own, so that historical interpretation based on the view of the
parties at the time of conclusion may not be helpful. Such intentions
can change over the years, so that acceptable solutions may be
better reached by considering the objectives of the treaty itself
according to a teleological investigation.<BR>
<BR>
Treaties may present gaps (lacunae) which a judge may have to
fill in order to deal with a case submitted to him. The most frequent
method used in such situations is analogy, which may be provided
by other parts of the treaty or by other international instruments
dealing with the same issue. If analogy fails, the teleological
approach may have to be used again, in particular if the treaty
to be interpreted is the constitution of an international organization.
The International Court of Justice has repeatedly stated that
such an organization must have the means to fulfil its purpose
and for this must have the necessary competences, even if its
constitution does not mention them.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="suspension"><B>Suspension and termination<BR>
</B></A><BR>
The suspension of a bilateral treaty or of treaty relations under
a multilateral treaty may result from an agreement among the parties
or from independent circumstances. The latter are most often the
interruption of diplomatic relations or an armed conflict between
the parties. A conflict which includes many countries may even
lead to the suspension of regional treaties as a whole. Whenever
the causes for a suspension have disappeared, treaty relations
may be resumed by agreement among the parties.<BR>
<BR>
The termination of a treaty is normally regulated by its final
clauses. Where this is not the case, parties may be unable to
agree on the possibility or the conditions of termination. In
such situations, a party may wish to unilaterally terminate a
bilateral treaty or to withdraw from a multilateral treaty even
in the absence of a provision to this effect. The other party
or parties may accept such a unilateral termination or withdrawal.
If they do not, the question arises as to whether the termination
or withdrawal is nevertheless effective.<BR>
<BR>
A party sometimes invokes a cause of invalidity in order to obtain
unilateral termination of a treaty relationship. However it will
normally be stopped from doing so because it has implemented the
treaty for some time without objecting to it. This is why the
concept of fundamental change of circumstances is often used.
If such a change renders the implementation of certain obligations
totally or nearly impossible, it may be taken into account. Otherwise,
international practice is reticent to apply the concept of fundamental
change.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="succession"><B>Succession to treaties<BR>
</B></A><BR>
The general issue of succession of States will be dealt with during
the sixth session. For the moment, only its aspects related to
treaties are being considered. Succession may occur as a result
of the fusion of two States, of secession of a new State from
an existing one or of disintegration in the course of which the
original State disappears. In this last case there is normally
no succession as regards treaties. In the case of fusion the States
concerned will have to decide which of the former regimes of bilateral
treaties they would prefer to retain. The other contracting parties
may however invoke a fundamental change of circumstances in order
to avoid extension to the new State of treaties applied formerly
to one of the participants in the fusion. <BR>
<BR>
Succession following secession has been the main subject of discussion
of lawyers. It applies in all cases of decolonization and more
recently also to the disintegration of the Soviet Union, as the
international community has accepted to consider the Russian Federation
as its legal continuation, thus treating the access to independence
of other former Soviet republics as instances of secession.<BR>
<BR>
With regard to succession to bilateral treaties in the case of
secession, relations between the seceding State and the other
party have to be considered on one hand, relations between the
other party and the surviving State from which secession occurred
on the other. The latter mostly remain unchanged, except where
the other party is able to show that the secession has produced
a fundamental change of circumstances. As for relations between
successor States and the other parties to bilateral treaties,
two regimes have been applied:<BR>
<BR>
1. Under the regime of the &quot;clean slate&quot;, the successor
States consider all treaties which were concluded on their behalf
or extended to their territory by the predecessor State as terminated.
However, they continue to be applied for a transitional period,
during which the new State considers whether to retain some of
them. This approach is known as the &quot;Nyerere doctrine&quot;.
<BR>
<BR>
2. The second regime on the contrary assumes the continued validity
of all treaties concluded by the predecessor State, but gives
the successor State a delay during which it may ask the other
parties to re-negotiate them. This approach was followed by a
number of francophone countries.<BR>
<BR>
For their part, the other contracting parties may refuse the continued
applicability of a bilateral treaty with a successor State on
the grounds of fundamental change of circumstances.<BR>
<BR>
As regards multilateral treaties, the general practice, which
was codified by the Vienna Convention on Succession of States
With Respect to Treaties of 1978, is as follows: A successor State
desirous to remain to be bound by a multilateral treaty extended
to its territory by the predecessor State must notify to the depository
a statement to this effect, failing which it will be considered
to have withdrawn. This system does not apply to constitutions
of international organizations, because the new State must formally
request and be granted admission.<BR>
<BR>
International organizations may also succeed each other as parties
to treaties. This was the position taken by the International
Court of Justice as regards succession between the League of Nations
and the United Nations in relation to international Mandates.
<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
