<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Editorial, MEDAC News, No.4, Aug 96</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#aCbEc8">

<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=10 BORDER=0>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=146 VALIGN=TOP BGCOLOR="#9e162e" vspace=8>
<IMG SRC="mednews2.gif" WIDTH=90 HEIGHT=45 BORDER=0 ALIGN=BOTTOM><BR><FONT SIZE=2 COLOR="#FFFFFF"><B>No.4 Aug 96</B></FONT><BR><P>
<BR><P>


<IMG SRC="rfalk1.jpg" WIDTH=138 HEIGHT=147 BORDER=0><BR><FONT SIZE=2 COLOR="#FFFFFF"><B>Professor Richard Falk</B></FONT><BR></TD>

<TD VALIGN=TOP BGCOLOR="#aCbEc8">

<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#FFFFFF"><B>Editorial</FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>The Likud Victory Versus Democratic Peace</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
Even before the startling  Likud victory in the Israeli presidential
elections at the end of May, respected Palestinian voices, most
notably that of Edward Said, had signaled that the peace process
was in deep trouble, at least as far as the Palestinians were
concerned.  In this regard, there has been an ambiguity embedded
in the phrase &quot;peace process&quot; as relating to both inter-governmental
negotiations  between Israel and its Arab neighbors and the negotiations
with the Palestinians that have been the core conflict ever since
the establishment of Israel almost fifty years ago.  With the
Likud in power, what has been achieved on the inter-governmental
level is likely to be sustained, although the extension of the
process to Syria and Lebanon is now highly unlikely to take place.
 But with the Palestinians the prospects of deterioration are
strong and frightening, for having raised expectations of peace
and statehood, the impact of deliberately expanding settlements
and downgrading Palestinian hopes for the future, is likely to
generate an inflammatory, mass, violent backlash.
<P>
The wider, regional impacts of the Likud control of the Israeli
policy process are difficult to discern at this stage, depending
on the shape of the coalition that governs in Tel Aviv, on the
degree of unity that is achieved on the Arab side, on the extent
to which the United States Government is prepared to lean heavily
on the Israeli leadership, and the degree to which European and
Mediterranean political forces exert their influence.  But, above
all, one thing is clear: the reality of constitutional democracy
as expressed through free elections in Israel has endangered peace
and security in the region.  In this regard, the recent Israeli
elections remind us ominously of the Algerian elections of a few
years ago that would have put the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS)
in power had it not been for the controversial intervention of
the military, an intervention that itself generated a descent
into large-scale bloody civil strife.  In the Israeli case unlike,
of course, the Algerian example, there is every likelihood that
the electoral outcome will be fully respected no matter how benighted
its effects on the well-being of Israelis, Palestinians, Arabs,
Europeans, and others.
<P>
In both these instances, there is something deeply troubling about
the political illusions of the current age.  In Algeria, the secular
world community that has been preaching the universal virtues
of political democracy and free elections, stands by in silent
approval while the Algerian military repudiates an election and
puts the winners in jail.  In Israel, a secular state linked geopolitically
to the United States, a democratic election produces results that
jeopardize the whole regional prospect, possibly quite drastically,
and the Western governments meekly congratulate the winners and
try to pretend that nothing much has changed.  Both positions
are suspect, but what is more to the point, cast severe doubt
on the naive claims of proponents of &quot;democratic peace.&quot;
<P>
What do these proponents claim? In simplest terms, despite some
variations, the central claim is that constitutional democracies
with strong private market sectors do not fight each other, and
are generally moderate in their foreign policy outlook.  In extravagant
language, Francis Fukuyama suggested that maybe &quot;the end
of history&quot; was at hand because the victors in the cold war
were committed to the steady expansion of the zone of democratic
peace, and that this would bring into being a world based on peace,
prosperity, and respect for the rule of law.  In fact, other developments
have ensued.  Religious politics has revived in a series of national
settings, including that of Israel, with attitudes rather hostile
to secular constitutionalism.  In the Asian/Pacific region, anti-democratic
regimes that rely on an activist state in relation to economic
policy are showing signs of success and stability.  And, then,
in a series of free elections the wrong side seems to be winning,
or at least gaining in strength, as in the elections recently
held in Turkey and India.
<P>
What shall we make of this series of developments? It remains
the case, to paraphrase Churchill, that democracy generally is
the least deficient political option given what else is available.
 But it is also evident that democracy is unlikely to prevail
everywhere, and even where it does, the results in certain settings
can spell doom for the peoples involved.  I would also want to
argue that democracy is not enough, especially for countries that
are linked to the destiny of a region or of the world.  If a political
culture is deformed, drawn to violence and domination, then the
mandate of the citizenry is more likely than not to be tilted
in the direction of like-minded leadership.  Indeed, this seems
to be what has occurred in Israel, despite the brave face that
is being put at the moment.  Above all, what is suggested, is
the importance for students of politics and diplomacy of depicting
the relationship between political culture and the governmental
system in particular countries.  Such a depiction might have made
us more sensitive to the virtues of respecting democratic results
in Algeria, and of avoiding their full impact in Israel, or possibly,
and more modestly, having a better sense of what to expect in
both instances.
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B>Professor Richard FALK</B><BR>
<I>Princeton University,</I><BR>
<I>Distinguished Visiting Professor</I><BR>
<I>Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies</I><BR>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>


</BODY>
</HTML>
