<P>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">1. <A NAME="introduction">INTRODUCTION</A></FONT></B>
<HR>

<P>
Lecture titles with question marks are supposed to draw an audience.
I admit, however, that this question, which is neither rhetorical
nor straightforward enough to clarify its meaning, may confuse
potential listeners more than it might attract them. Aha! some
will say, this is a reference to age-old quarrels in the Balkans.
No! others will retort, the reference is to recent days of peace
and poverty rather than the ongoing situation of war and poverty.
<P>
Of course, what prompts the title and the theme of this lecture
is the present war, with its incalculable destruction and wanton
death. This is a tragedy of staggering proportions, such as was
not supposed to occur in Europe after 1945. The reference is also
to the seismic changes which have occurred in the Balkans, as
in the rest of formerly Communist Europe since 1989. It is the
general upheaval throughout this area which poses the question
of whether the Balkans are going forward into an uncertain future,
or into a familiar past.
<P>
The answer I propose may be justifiably criticized as belonging
to the messy category of what the French call a <I>r&eacute;ponse
de normand</I>. In some ways, yes, the Balkans will continue to
face the maladies that have plagued them for so long. In other
ways, no, Balkan problems are, at this very moment, being redefined
by ongoing events. More specifically, I propose to look at three
long-standing Balkan quandaries <FONT SIZE=2>-</FONT>political
dispersion, foreign domination, economic development<FONT SIZE=2>-
</FONT>in the light of secular historical trends and against the
backdrop of present events. <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">2. <A NAME="dispersion">DISPERSION</A></FONT></B>
<HR>

<P>
Over the last three centuries one can discern an unmistakable
tendency towards political dispersion or fragmentation in the
Balkans. To put it in its simplest terms, political units in the
Balkans, contrary to patterns in more familiar parts of Europe,
have been becoming ever smaller. This tendency, I submit, is likely
to continue.
<P>
Whereas in the late seventeenth century virtually all the Balkans
were still under Ottoman rule, in the eighteenth century the area
came to be shared between the Habsburg and the Ottoman empires.
The pattern of large, regional empire was only gradually punctured
in the nineteenth century. It is easy to forget that there was
still a Turkish garrison in Belgrade in the 1860s. Serbia and
Romania acquired full sovereignty only in 1878 and Bulgaria was
not a fully independent state until 1908. In the twentieth century,
this pattern of fragmentation accelerated twice. First, in the
aftermath of World War I with the dismantlement of the Austro-Hungarian
empire. Second, in 1991/2 with the collapse of Yugoslavia. This
successor state, made up of the fragments of earlier empires,
itself collapsed into newer and smaller fragments.
<P>
Is there a logic to this process of fragmentation? There is indeed.
It lies in the drive to satisfy national aspirations. Every people
in the Balkans seeks its state. Even those peoples not recognized
until recently as distinct peoples, such as the Bosnian Muslims,
the Macedonians and the Moldovans partake in this drive. In fact,
they throw themselves into it all the more vigorously, as if to
make up for lost time, for the youth of their cause, and for the
fragility of their newly acquired identity.
<P>
Let us note that the logic of nation-state creation 'is a borrowed
logic. It is derived directly from West European experience but
it works in opposite ways in the Balkans. West European nationalism
drew political fragments together; it enlarged markets, strengthened
units of defense and expanded cultural entities. Its strong, perhaps
unfortunate, assimilationist force homogenized large territories.
In the Balkans, however, nationalism turned out to be a centrifugal
rather than a centripetal force. It did not create territorial
homogeneity. Rather, it reinforced resistance to assimilation
and made heterogeneity newly problematic.
<P>
<A NAME="fragmentation">How have recent events affected the long-standing
Balkan tendency towards political dispersion or fragmentation?
Quite clearly, they have given it further powerful impetus. The
disintegration of Yugoslavia and the wars of the Yugoslav Succession
are the most obvious manifestation of this tendency. </A>
<P>
Moldova's decision to strike out on its own, difficult path rather
than seek unification with Romania provides less dramatic confirmation.
Even events immediately outside the area, notably the break-up
of the Soviet Union and the split of Czechoslovakia, have sharpened
the Balkan inclination towards fragmentation. 
<P>
<FONT COLOR=#0000FF>At the same time, the opposite processes in
Western Europe, particularly the unification of Germany and the
slow but steady construction of the European Union, have underscored
the extent to which the logic of history appears to operate in
a counter-direction in the Balkans from that which it assumes
in the West.</FONT>
<P>
Even more fundamentally, recent events have legitimized the reality
of fragmentation as never before. They have enshrined the notion
of secession as a no-fault, no-cost process. <A NAME="federalism"><FONT COLOR=#0000FF>They
have de-legitimized federalism as a way of overcoming the dilemmas
of national construction in the area</FONT>. They have created
the illusion that one can attain homogeneous political units at
home while enjoying participation in such heterogeneous distant
units as the European Union. Nor has this process of fragmentation
played itself out. The question now is whether the fragments are
themselves to become states. </A><BR>

<P>
In concrete terms, we are looking not only at the emergence of
a Serb Republic of Bosnia but also at the prospect of, say, an
independent Kosovo and a sovereign Sanjak; perhaps somewhere down
the line, an Istrian state and a Rhodop Republic of Bulgarian
Turks. Let me hasten to acknowledge that these are not all imminent
possibilities; some are presently quite hypothetical. Today, however,
they can no longer be pushed off a future historical agenda.
<P>
<A NAME="small"><FONT COLOR=#0000FF>Let me also add that fragmentation
need not be an evil. Small may indeed be beautiful. It will only
be beautiful, however, if these small political units cooperate
with each other, at the very least on the economic level and,
it is to be hoped, on the political level as well. Yet, the wounds
of fragmentation are so deep that such cooperation is unlikely.
Even more significantly, these small states will only be beautiful
in their own eyes if they are ethnically and religiously homogeneous.
Unfortunately, they have demonstrated that they are prepared to
take radical measures to attain this homogeneity. For this reason
alone they are unlikely to be a truly pretty sight.</FONT></A>
<BR>

<H3><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">3. <A NAME="domination">DOMINATION</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=4>
</FONT></H3>

<HR>

<P>
The Balkans are an area historically dominated by great, outside
empires. The nature of such domination, from the Roman-Byzantine
era through the brief Soviet period, has varied over time but
the fact of domination has remained constant. I would add that
it is most short-sighted to discount the perspectives of future
domination.
<P>
Although the extended hegemony of the Eastern Roman or Byzantine
empire has left its traces, it is the longest recent domination,
variously characterized as Muslim, Ottoman, or Turkish, which
has defined the area, even giving it its name. It has bequeathed
its legacy in politics as in everyday life; Balkan communities
continue to be constituted in the social-religious categories
inherited from the Ottomans. Muslims throughout the Balkans continue
to be identified with this now extinct empire.
<P>
In its last stages the dominant Ottoman empire was itself dominated
by others, making the Balkans a sort of sub-satellite or the dependency
of a dependent empire. As such, the Balkans were also an apple
of discord among several would-be hegemons. None of these rival
and succeeding empires - Habsburg, German, or Soviet -exercised
hegemony over the whole area or for very long. Even Stalin failed
to gain control of Greece and he soon lost Yugoslavia, whereas
his successors were unable to keep even little Albania in tow.
<P>
How have recent events affected this pattern of domination? The
most serious recent claimant for hegemonic status, the Soviet
Union, has disappeared. Its successor, the Russian Federation,
does not even border on the Balkans, a situation unknown since
the late seventeenth century. Moreover, the end of bipolarity
in the international system has made it possible to ease the pressure
on the Balkans as an area of potential super-power confrontation.
Finally, the coordination of great power foreign policies through
the United Nations and of Western policies through NATO has reduced
the potential for diplomatic miscalculation, such as occurred
in 1914 and cost the world so dearly. 
<P>
The pattern of domination in the Balkans is lighter today than
it has been in the past. Ironically, this is not only cause for
relief but also for concern. The great powers, to their own stupefaction,
have come to realize that their diminished capacity for influencing
the course of events in the Balkans also means that they cannot
exert benign influence. In other words, if it is more difficult
for them to make things worse in the Balkans, it has become even
more difficult to make them better. Indeed, in a spectacular historical
turnabout, it is now the Balkans peoples who are humiliating the
great powers and international organizations, much as these powers
and the Concert of Europe humiliated the Balkan peoples in the
past.
<P>
Still, this situation is unusual and, I would maintain, unlikely
to endure. The only historical era where the Balkans enjoyed relative
independence, the years from 1918 to 1940 - in many ways not a
very happy time - proved of short duration. The present period
too is something of an anomaly. Future outside domination may
well be less obtrusive than that of the past. Once peace has come,
it is likely to be exerted largely through economic channels.
Political domination will be geared to denying the Balkans to
rival powers, rather than imposing one's own will on the area.
In other words, future domination will be more discrete, more
subtle, perhaps more enlightened than that of the past. It is
improbable, however, that the Balkans will be left to chart their
own path on their own terms.
<P>
Indeed, even today we have unmistakable evidence that the stakes
in the Balkans are rising and few international actors can resist
the temptation to put their chips on the table. By fostering or
frustrating agreement in ex-Yugoslavia (as in Moldova), Russia
can demonstrate that it is still a great power. The new, united
Germany seeks to show in this area that it is already or again
a great power, prepared to assume international responsibilities
commensurate with its status but independent of its past. It is
in the Balkans too that France must prove itself if it is to have
any hopes of still being considered a great power. Here too, the
United States would persuade the world (and itself) that it possesses
that elusive quality called &quot;leadership&quot;. And it is
in the Balkans that the new or non-conventional actors of international
politics are cutting their teeth: The European Union would attest
that it is not only a manager of agricultural surplus and a standardizer
of technical norms but that it is also a diplomatic power. NATO
would demonstrate that it has successfully outlived its original
raison d'&ecirc;tre. The United Nations would show that it can
compete with the great powers as an independent world actor.
<P>
No, the international politics of the post-Cold War world are
unlikely to bypass the Balkans, any more than did the politics
of the past.<BR>

<H3><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">4. <A NAME="development">DEVELOPMENT</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=4>
</FONT></H3>

<HR>

<P>
Many observers would consider the fundamental problem of the Balkans
to be chronic, acute under-development. Indeed, the term &quot;Balkans&quot;
is even sometimes used as almost a synonym for economic backwardness.
<P>
The identification of Balkiness and backwardness is, in some ways,
unfair. Slovenia has recently enjoyed a level of development comparable
to parts of neighbouring Italy or Austria. <A NAME="metro"><FONT COLOR=#0000FF>The
first city in Europe to have electricity was (then Hungarian,
now Romanian) Timisoara. The metro of Budapest preceded that of
Paris.</FONT> Still, it is a fact that developed areas constituted
oases in the Balkans. Disparities were enormous, often on a North/South
axis. </A>
<P>
For instance, the per capita income in socialist Yugoslavia reached
Austrian standards in the North but fell to Nigerian standards
in the South. Development under communism, quantitatively impressive,
turned out to be largely misdirected. Chronic and secular under-development
has been, historically, blamed on the Turks. The insurmountable
character of the ravages wrought by the Turks in conquering the
area and their indifference to progress constitute one of the
few unifying beliefs throughout the area. In fact, however, recent
scholarship points to other reasons for the area's underdevelopment.
<A NAME="backward"><FONT COLOR=#0000FF>The transfer of the point
of gravity of the world economy towards the Atlantic in the sixteenth
century, for example, condemned the Balkans to becoming an economic
backwater, even independently of Turkish depredations. In many
respects, the Balkans merely shared the fate of the rest of Eastern
Europe and much of Central Europe, frustrated in its development
by social and geographic factors as much as by technical ones.</FONT></A>
<P>
Even more striking is the fact that the gap between the Eastern
part of Europe and the advanced West has continued to grow throughout
our century. A recent calculation estimated that per capita income
in Eastern Europe as a whole in 1910 represented less than half
of Western European levels. This percentage has been failing steadily
and has now reached a historic low, of one quarter of Western
levels. In other words, Eastern Europe, including the Balkans,
is not only under-developed and has been under-developed for centuries,
but it is becoming ever more so.
<P>
What now have recent changes done to solve the problem of backwardness?
By changes I mean not only the political upheavals of 1989 and
those that followed in ex-Yugoslavia. I am also referring to such
disparate phenomena as the disruption of trading patterns and
the introduction of privatization and marketization.
<P>
Some of these changes are, at least potentially, positive. would
suggest, however, that the obstacles to development have attained
even greater prominence and they throw their shadow on whatever
economic potential exists. The Balkans, like the rest of Eastern
Europe, are obliged to re-industrialize. In other words, they
must undergo a second time the process of what Marx called primitive
accumulation. This process will be even more painful than the
first because it must overcome the latter's dysfunction in terms
of general economic disequilibria, pollution and social costs.
Moreover, contrary to the cases of Germany and Japan after World
War 11, the old industrial plant in Eastern Europe is still standing,
with its attendant interests and the consequent impossibility
of starting truly afresh.
<P>
By all indications, post-communist countries will have to proceed
in their task of transformation without any substantial outside
help. Investment capital never flowed easily in this direction
and it will not do so now. There will be no new Marshall Plan,
not only because the advanced economies are themselves undergoing
a slump but, above all, because there is no compelling reason
for the West to help. Fear of communism was the real motor of
Marshall aid; this has now disappeared and nothing comparable
has replaced it.
<P>
Not only will the Balkans not receive significant capital inflows
but they have already and will continue to suffer a debilitating
outflow of human capital. The brain drain is particularly acute
in countries at war, like the successor states of Yugoslavia,
but it affects all other countries in the area. It is often the
most promising elements, whether in terms of education or spirit
of enterprise, that are lost. The training of alternative, new
cadres is a slow process. The &quot;nomenclature capitalists,&quot;
or former party functionaries who have come to the fore in the
process of transformation provide few guarantees of fundamental
economic reform and no guarantees of a justly organized society.
<P>
One need not be a Marxist to argue that economic development constitutes
the core of the Balkan dilemma and to wager that if this problem
is overcome, other problems would be surmounted as well. One is
tempted to go further to say that if prosperity reigns, then the
dispersion of political units would become irrelevant and the
will to cooperation would grow. If these countries attain an advanced
economic standing, they could resist foreign domination and would
be respected and welcomed as equal partners by outside powers.
Such a view is, however, simplistic. One cannot have development
without countering political dispersion and the Balkans cannot
develop while they remain a dominated object of international
politics. In short, the Balkans are caught in the vicious web
of familiar contradictions from which they have been unable to
escape.
<H3><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Arial">5. <A NAME="conclusion">CONCLUSION</A></FONT><FONT SIZE=4>
</FONT></H3>

<HR>

<P>
What can one say in summary? It is most improbable that the ongoing
crisis in Yugoslavia, whatever its outcome, will solve any of
the area's ills. Certainly, the present course of events is doing
nothing to resolve the chronic problems of political dispersion
or fragmentation, outside domination and chronic under-development.
In this sense, the Balkans may well be the same again, alas! At
the same time, one may perhaps be pardoned for expressing a glimmer
of hope. <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<A NAME="optimism">Today, it is clearer than ever before that
the Balkans could evolve further in a self-destructive direction,
completely antithetical to their own interests. The very intensity
of the ongoing crisis underscores the urgency of the problems
of the area just as the discrepancy between processes there and
those in the rest of Europe, including even the other ex-Communist
countries, highlights the specificity of the Balkans. The ravages
of war and the shock of regime transformation might well jolt
at least some people in this area into self-critical reflection.
</A><BR>

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Perhaps, just perhaps, visionary individuals and
key social groups will then tackle Balkan problems head on, in
the realization that their real tasks and interests lie in finding
modes of political cooperation, forms of regional integrity, and
programmes of economic development. But, of course, this is a
very optimistic prospect. <IMG SRC="balk2.jpg" WIDTH=283 HEIGHT=198 BORDER=1 ALIGN=ABSMIDDLE></FONT></B>

<HR>

<P>
<TABLE border=0>
<TR><TD valign=top><A HREF="../../default.htm"><IMG SRC="../../ahome1-s.gif"> Home</A>
</TD><TD valign=top><B><FONT SIZE=2>(C) Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies, University of Malta, Msida, MSD 06, MALTA;&nbsp; Telephone: +356 483090 or +356 32902817; &nbsp;Fax: +356 483091 or +356 336450;&nbsp; E-mail: <A HREF=mailto:academy@diplomacy.edu><B>academy@diplomacy.edu</B></A><B> </B></FONT></B>
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

