<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Has the Cold War Ended?</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER><P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Trebuchet MS,Arial">Has the Cold War Ended?</FONT></B><BR> 
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Trebuchet MS,Arial"><B>By Prof. Fred Tanner, Director of the Academy</B></FONT>
<P></CENTER>

<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=10 CELLPADDING=0 BORDER=0>
<TR VALIGN=TOP>
<TD WIDTH=144><IMG SRC="infir21.jpg" WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=177><BR>
<IMG SRC="censu11.jpg" WIDTH=144 HEIGHT=99>
<FONT SIZE=2><TT><B>After the lecture, Prof. Tanner (right) in a debate with two former Maltese minsters, R. Naudi (middle) and C. Tabone (left)</B></TT></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=75%>
<P>
When President Bush and Chairman Gorbachov met in Malta in December
1989, not only the Mediterranean Sea was tempestuous, turbulent
and out of control was also the once so disciplined Socialist
Bloc extending from East Berlin to Vladivostok and from Estonia
to Turkmenistan. Democratic, ecclesiastic and nationalist movements,
fueled by economic and ideological bankruptcy of the Socialist
system had cornered the nomenclature in Moscow.
<P>
The Kremlin tried to deal with the decline of the Soviet empire
through reform and retrenchment. But Stalinist hard-liners were
waiting in the wings for undoing <I>Perestroika</I> at home and
abroad. This dramatic development was the stage upon which the
Bush-Gorbachov meeting took place here in Malta.
<P>
The Malta Summit was not a meeting between equals, but rather
between a self-asserted United States and a vulnerable but militarily
still dangerous Soviet Union. Sergei Tarasenk later recalled that
at Malta, the Foreign Minister Shevardnadze and President Gorbachov
felt that the Soviet Union was in a free fall, that their superpower
status would go up in smoke unless it was reaffirmed by the Americans.
<P>
President Bush agreed to come to the rescue of charming Gorbachov
and his reformist policies. He flew to Malta to personally support
the difficult process of <I>Perestroika</I>. The Malta meeting
meant the beginning of a cooperative relationship between the
superpowers to bail-out a reformist and moderate Soviet Union.
But, as we know, it turned out to be a loosing battle against
the insurgent forces of democracy and self-determination. All
the concerted efforts finally failed as the pandora box had been
opened up during the 1989 break down of the Berlin Wall.
<P>
Over the 6 years following the Malta Summit, a myriad of historic
events has been taking place. Moscow acquiesced to the regime
change of countries under its orbis in East Central Europe. It
allowed the reunification of Germany to take place and discouraged
militant reactionary forces in Eastern Germany to oppose the unification
by force. The Red Army started to withdraw from the Eastern European
region and in 1991 the Soviet Union slowly disintegrated and President
Gorbachov resigned as the last ruler of the Soviet Empire on Christmas
Day of the same year.
<P>
The post-Cold War world was rapidly tested by the Iraqi invasion
of Kuwait. The large-scale military response of the West under
U.S. leadership was tacitly accepted by the Soviet Union. Since
then, the world has been exposed increasingly to regional problems
and tragedies ranging from Somalia, Rwanda and Burundi to the
Balkans, but also some silver linings of hope and peace appeared
on the horizons in the Middle East, Central America, Southern
Africa and Cambodia.
<P>
Now and here, we are confronted with the intriguing question of
whether the Cold War is really over? This question is particularly
intriguing today, because of the political come-back of the Communists
in Russia, Poland and other countries of the former Socialist
bloc.
<P>
I propose to explore the question of the end of the Cold War by
first briefly looking at what the Cold War has been about. This
will allow us to then contrast this with today's international
situation. On the ground of this comparison we can then tackle
the arguments supporting and contradicting the thesis that the
Cold War is really over.
<P>
The Cold War has been marked by superpower bipolarity, that, in
turn was fostered by three defining features: clashing ideologies,
geopolitical rivalry, and the fear of a nuclear war. Thus, the
Cold War was a war of ideas and a war over control of territory.
The common fear of nuclear catastrophe, on the other hand, has
been portrayed by many scholars as the reason for the <I>Cold
Peace</I> under which both powers had an interest in preserving
the status quo despite the official rollback rhetoric. But, the
Cold Peace or Cold War was fought many times over in hot and bloody
wars in Korea, Vietnam, Afghanistan and numerous other places
of the developing world.
<P>
The relations among the superpowers have been guided by a number
of unwritten rules such as:
<OL>
<LI>Preserve nuclear weapons as a last resort;
<LI>preserve the nuclear weapons as a reserved domain of the superpowers;
<LI>respect the spheres of influence of the other superpower;
<LI>avoid direct military confrontation.
</OL>
<P>
Given these characteristics of the Cold War, we may that the Cold
War is over by now. One of the superpowers, the Soviet Union has
disintegrated. This has led to the disappearance of the bipolar
system and its rules of conduct. Furthermore, the ideological
clash has come to an end: Communism/Marxism lost its role as an
viable alternative to the liberal economy model.
<P>
We can test the argument of the end of the Cold War with the somber
assumption that President Yeltzin's government may be replaced
tomorrow by a regime that is excessively nationalistic and hostile
towards the West. This probably would lead to a new kind of Cold
War politics, but not necessarily to the return of a Cold War
international system. Neither the economic power base, nor an
ideological superstructure are currently available for Russia
to resume a sustained global policy of confrontation with the
United States.
<P>
There are other and unfortunately quite negative indicators that
the Cold War has come to an end. I refer here to the emergence
of the dark forces of nationalism and ethnic fanatism that were
suppressed under the Cold War regime. These subterranean forces
have been at work for a while, but it needed an earthquake to
find out where the fault lines are. In our case, the earthquake
has violently erupted in Yugoslavia, the Caucasus, the Black Sea
area and other regions of the former Soviet Union.
<P>
The outbreak of ethnic and religious tensions and civil wars can
be taken as indicators for the victory of liberalism over the
heavy-handed centralized authoritarianism of Moscow. It is a bitter
triumph, however, that has made some observers nostalgic of the
Cold War period. Let us not hope that the end of the Cold War
could be the beginning of something worse.
<P>
This observation may be appropriate for now briefly looking at
arguments supporting the thesis that the Cold War has not ended.
Under such a thesis, the decline of Russia would be reversible,
it may just be a temporary contraction of a broader cyclical development.
If geopolitical position is a central variable, then the Cold
War may not be over, but we are just in a period of extensive
d&eacute;tente. If the Cold War was caused by the rise of Soviet
military power, then these conditions still persist today, as
Russia controls hundreds of strategic missiles and thousands or
strategic nuclear warheads.
<P>
The START II nuclear arms agreement, a major part of which was
agreed upon during the Bush-Gorbachov meeting in Malta, has not
been ratified. There are today slim chances that this important
agreement would enter force before the June 1996 presidential
elections in Russia. It is also in trouble on the American side,
as it has been held hostage by Senator Jesse Helms for the budget
battle with the White House.
<P>
Other signs of the continuation of Cold War is the Russian claim
to invalidate the Conventional Forces in Europe Agreement (CFE),
that has been worked on during the Malta Summit. Russia argues
that the CFE is a relict of the Cold War, as it restricts Russian
military build-up in the Caucasus and Black Sea area, regions
that have become the hot spots with Chechnia, Abkhazia and other
conflicts within or adjacent to Russian territory.
<P>
Another view of why the Cold War may not be over is delivered
by Prof. Andre Liebich of the Graduate Institute of International
Studies in Geneva, a sister institution of our Academy. According
to Prof. Liebich, the decline of the Soviet Union and its dissolution
can be understood as the liberation of Russia from its imperial
overstretch. Andre Liebich portrayed it as the Russian bear shaking
off the un-necessary burden of non-Russian republics, that have
been heavily subsidized by Moscow, and not the other way around.
In this line of argument, the retreat of Russia to its ethnic
base may be an invigorating experience, that --in due time-- may
give Russia back the status of a superpower.
<P>
After looking at some arguments about whether the Cold War has
really finished, we should now turn to the question of where we
are today in relation to the Cold War period.
<P>
If the Cold War is over, shouldn't we be able to fall back to
the conditions that existed before the outbreak of the Cold War?
<P>
This may be possible only in an abstract approach, where we assume
that the Cold War has been freezing the evolution of time. Distinguished
historian John Gaddis eloquently rejects this argument: &quot;Alike
time itself, history flows in one direction only; a return to
prior conditions is as improbable as it would be for an arrow
to reverse its course in mid-flight.&quot;
<P>
In an Eurocentric view, the conditions have changed irreversibly
over the last 50 years. First, the European Union is today a political
and economic reality that is very difficult to undo. The integration
of European states has led to the disappearance of the Franco-German
rivalry that has dominated European politics for centuries. Second,
during the Cold War a new thinking has emerged and has found today
near-universal support. The idea of free-market economics and
liberal democracy. The Paris Charter of 1990 codified the prevalence
of these principles in a historic meeting that brought together
all participants to the Cold War as well as all neutral and non-aligned
states.
<P>
The liberal democracy thought, that had established itself in
Western Europe after the end of World War II has been operationalized
during the Cold War through the Council of Europe and its Human
Rights Convention as well as the Social Charter. Non-governmental
organizations such as the European Cultural Foundation have been
working throughout the Cold War to promote the noble ideas of
cultural, human and value-based cooperation.
<P>
A spin off of the liberal democracy movement has been the emergence
of the concept of <I>democratic peace</I>. The <I>democratic peace</I>
idea finds its origins in Kantian and Jeffersonian thinking. The
guiding idea is that liberal democracies do not fight each other
regardless of the military capability they possess. In the post-Cold
War period the democratic peace idea began to slowly permeated
into practical policy considerations: The committed support for
developing countries in their efforts to move to some kind of
democratic system may increase the chances for lasting peace <I>more</I>
than hard core security pacts and arms control agreements that
exclude value-based cooperation
<P>
A third condition emerging during the Cold War has been the trend
toward globalization. Globalization is not a result of the Cold
War, but it has somewhat discreetly been developing over the last
decades. Globalization, which appears to be an irreversible historical
process, means that international interactions are increasingly
of a global nature and that they increasingly escape the control
of the state. Mass communication, global economic interdependence,
and permeable boundaries start to have profound impact upon the
international community, states and societies.
<P>
Professor Richard Falk from Princeton University, who is this
year a Distinguished Visiting Professor at our Academy, has been
instrumental in spelling out and conceptualizing the positive
and negative effects of globalism on peace, social justice, human
rights and democracy.
<P>
Global governance finds, in some ways, its way back to the period
before the Cold War. The founding of the United Nations in 1945
have considered the United Nations to be the universal guardian
of collective security. We know that during the Cold War the bipolar
structures prevented the UN from assuming this role. During the
great transformations in the late 1980s and early 1990s the hope
re-emerged that the UN finally will be able to take up this original
role. The UN-sanctioned crushing of Iraq during the Gulf War and
the ambitious UN involvement in Cambodia appeared as precursors
of a brave new world based on the effective implementation of
global common security. But, unfortunately, the euphoria about
global governance under the UN umbrella quickly faded with the
sobering experiences in Yugoslavia, Rwanda, Somalia and the Caucasus.
<P>
To conclude, I would like to argue that we find ourselves today
in a situation that neither resembles the Cold War nor the pre-Cold
War period. The years following the Malta summit have made it
clear, that early hopes for a stable post-Cold War order based
on principles of collective security and liberal democracy were
premature. We will have to get used to live in a world that appears
now more complex than ever before. The break-up of global East-West
patterns has allowed many regional rivals to finally their genuine
differences. Peace is slowly expanding its realm into the Middle
East, South Africa and now hopefully also into the Balkans. At
the same time, the sustained expansion of the zone of peace is
threatened by nationalist revival, the growth of communal violence
and notorious economic underdevelopment.
<P>
We have overcome the Cold War, we know now that the history has
not come to an end. Liberal democracy and human rights have not
yet won their battles
<P>
The break-up of global East-West patterns has allowed many regional
rivals to finally settle their genuine differences. Peace is slowly
expanding its realm into the Middle East, South Africa and now
hopefully also into the Balkans. At the same time, the sustained
expansion of the zone of peace is threatened by extremism, intolerance
and notorious economic underdevelopment.
<P>
Liberal democracy and human rights have not yet won their battle.
The Cold War may be over, but the non-arrival of the predicted
end of history will oblige organisations such as the European
Cultural Foundation to pursue their mission with renewed vigour.

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
 
</BODY>

</HTML>


