<HEAD>
<TITLE> Graduation Speech </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<Body Background="Ring5.GIF">


<H1><CENTER>
Graduation Speech </H1>
<TT><I><B>
By Professor Fred Tanner, Director of the Academy
</I></TT></B>
</CENTER>


<BODY>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
Dear graduates,


<P>

<img src="Ftanner2.jpg" align=right hspace=10>This graduation represents the formal ending of your studies here in
Malta. Your work, performance and commitments toward academic 
excellence is being awarded by the conferment of the Master Degree 
in Diplomatic studies. The end of your studies, should however, by no 
means imply the end of your relationship with our Academy and with 
Malta. 

<P>
We hope that your acquired skills and knowledge will always remind
you that you have a generous alma mater present here in Malta.
The end of your studies should be the beginning of new relationship
among all of us, a relationship guided by our common efforts to
contribute on our own level and wherever we will be to the cause
of peace, democracy and the rule of law. 

<P>
It is no accident that I mention these values, and you know very
well why. It is the Barcelona Declaration of last November that
succeeded for the first time in the history to unite the Mediterranean
States, North and South, East and West, to subscribe to common
values in the area of security, economic relations and human rights.
The Mediterranean has brought to fruition on a regional and cross-cultural
level what is still being pursuit at universal scale. I refer
here to the trilogy of the United Nations with its Agenda for
Peace, the Agenda for Development and the Agenda for Democracy
and Human Rights; the latter may or may not see the light of the
day. 

<P>
But, we know that the Euro-Med parameter is not yet complete.
Libya is missing as are the Balkan states. Furthermore, the effective
implementation of the principles will represent one of the major
challenges of Mediterranean diplomacy over the coming years. There
is a good chance that you personally will be involved in this
important mission, unless you will be posted in remote places
such as New Dheli, and even then, I am confident, you will do
your best to convince everybody of the virtues and merits of the
Barcelona Process.

<P>
It is no secret that Malta has been at the forefront of the Barcelona
process from the very beginning and you have been able to witness
this through a number of presentation of eminent guest speakers
from Malta and abroad. This is primarily due to the dynamic and
persistent policy engineered by the Hon. Professor Guido de Marco,
Deputy Prime Minister and Minster of Foreign Affairs. He noted
even before the Barcelona Conference that &quot;the Mediterranean
basin emerged from the Cold War very poorly equipped to deal with
its regional problems, both in terms of accepted practices, and
even more in terms of institutions, promoting the process of regional
consultation and cooperation.&quot;. 

<P>
The Maltese project for a Stability Pact in the Mediterranean,
that was presented at Barcelona and formally tabled last April
at a follow-up meeting has precisely for objective to codify,
refine and operationalise the principles and norms adopted by
the Euro-Med community.   I am proud to announce that the Academy
will make its own contribution to the Barcelona process by convening
this fall Mediterranean and EU desk officers and diplomats from
all  27 Euro-Med partners in the framework of an information and
training session.  We hope that this will just be the beginning
of a long-term involvement of the Academy in the Euro-Med legacy.

<P>
But, we know that the Euro-Med partnership can only succeed if
the external conditions are right. Some conditions have greatly
improved during the time that you have spent here in Malta. The
bloody conflict in Bosnia has been peacefully conquered by robust
NATO peacekeeping under the Dayton Peace settlement. Durable peace
is, however, far from achieved.  But anything we have today is
better than what we had one year ago. We are all winners if infamous
leaders such as Karadzic may turn out to be losers in the endgame
of the Yugoslav conflict. 

<P>
But the silver lining on the horizon of one side of the Mediterranean
is overshadowed by gathering dark clouds in others. In the Middle
East, the forces unfriendly to the peace process have prevailed
in the Israeli elections. The resulting Arab common front has
never been as strong ever since its breakdown almost 20 years
ago when Egypt concluded separate peace with Israel.  The pendulum
for peace or war can swing either way. In these critical moments,
skillful and persuasive diplomacy and reason only can make a difference
to the cheap and easy appeals to intolerance and confrontation.

<P>
In the final analysis, the outcome of conflicts in the Middle
East, the Balkans and the future performance of the security partnership
of Barcelona will depend on the hard and committed work by the
next generation. You graduates are this next generation. You will
be directly involved in the policy-making of tomorrow. According
to Professor Richard Falk of Princeton University, who has been
enriching our academic life this year at the Academy as a distinguished
visiting professor, the effects of globalisation and post-modernism
will help to reduce the cultural and sub-regional differences.
But globalisation alone may not be enough to overcome sub-regional
and cultural cleavages. What is needed is the build-up of a common
identity and a we-feeling. 

<P>
I hope that your experiences at the Academy have helped to foster
this we-feeling. It is clear that a we-feeling does not come easy
after growing up in a we-they world. In this sense, the cyberspace
gateway, the databanks, and other instant electronic information
made available by the Academy's Unit for Computer Application
can play an important role of identity shaping, even after you
have returned back to your home countries. 

<P>
Let me also mention another unifying factor. This is, despite
of all its deficiencies, the University Residence. Over the last
9 months, this place has succeeded to unite students and diplomats
from all four corners of the Mediterranean in their confusion
and deference towards green-turned-yellow buses, that drive recklessly
fast and still show up late for class. 

<P>
But the residence also has become the site of shared pleasure
of various Mediterranean cuisine, common sports events and of
course the first MEDAC Tennis open with its brilliant finalists.
Hopefully this event will be the first of a glorious tradition
yet to come. 

<P>
I think this is the moment to come to an end and to say a few
words of thanks. First, we all agree that the move to the Academy's
new premises has broadened both its physical space and its realm
for future contributions. I would like to thank the University
of Malta  for providing this premises and all the other services
necessary assuring the proper functioning of our institution.

<P>
Second, thanks go to all the governments and organisations that
have contributed to the Academy, including the Malta government,
Switzerland, Italy, but also the Commonwealth and the Commission
of the European Union. 

<P>
Third, I would like to acknowledge the commitment and work of
all colleagues and staff that have helped to make this year a
success. We have to say good-bye to two colleagues, Professor
Hilal Elver and Dr. Jacob Kettola, for both of whom we wish a
successful continuation of their careers in distant countries.

<P>
Lastly, thanks and congratulations go to the graduates.  We wish
you luck on your future journey in international diplomacy and
hope that it will be accompanied by excellence, persistence and
a human-oriented vision. 
</BODY>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</HTML>
