<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>The Diplomatic Studies Programmes</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY Bgcolor="faebd7">

<h1><b>THE DIPLOMATIC STUDIES PROGRAMMES</b></h1>
<hr>

<h2>Introduction</h2>

<a href="sister.jpg">
<img src="sister-s.jpg"></a><P>


The Diplomatic Studies Programmes (DSP) are a joint venture of the following institutions:

<ul>
<li><a href="http://heiwww.unige.ch/">The Graduate Institute of International Studies in Geneva (IUHEI);</a>
<li><a href="iirt.htm">The Institute of International Relations of the University of  the West Indies, Trinidad (IIRT);</a>
<li><a href="iric.htm">The International Relations Institute of Cameroon of the University of Yaounde II (RIC);</a>
<li><a href="idis.htm">The Institute of Diplomacy and International Studies of the University of Nairobi, Kenya (IDIS</a>);
<li>The Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies of the University of Malta (MEDAC).
</ul>

<hr>
<h2>Profile of the Diplomatic Studies Programme</h2>

The IUHEI was actively involved in the establishment of the other four institutions, as a result of which all share a  multidisciplinary approach and a similar teaching philosophy. All five institutions are linked to a university and, while having close relations with the foreign ministry of the country in which they are established, are not attached to it. Even with regard to the university with which they are linked, they enjoy full autonomy except in academic matters.<p>
<p>
The aim of all Diplomatic Studies Programmes is to enhance the capacity of diplomatic establishments of countries with limited resources, especially small and poor third world countries. To this effect, a variety of training programmes with a regional scope are offered at different levels to all persons used regularly in a diplomatic capacity by the governments who present their candidature. The expressions "diplomatic" and "diplomat" are thus understood in this context in a broad sense. In the last few years, efforts have been made to also cater for the specific needs of the diplomacies of countries in transition seeking their full integration into a pluralistic and market-oriented international system. This new task falls mainly upon the IUHEI in Geneva and the Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies in Malta.<p>
<p>
<hr>
<h2>New Developments</h2><p>

<h3>The Use of Information Technology</h3><p>

This technology has the potential of making possible for  the first time an active participation in international  relations of even the smallest actors. As catering for such actors is one of the main objectives of the institutions associated under the Diplomatic Studies Programmes, efforts are under way to provide them with the capacity of computerising foreign ministries and providing the latter with the necessary databases and applications software.<p>

The Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies has done pioneering work in this field. It set up a Unit for Computer Applications in Diplomacy in 1992, which designed a model for the computerisation of foreign ministries for the UN Meeting on the Strengthening of Foreign Ministries in Transition held in Malta in June 1993. Following up on this, it organised in January 1994 a Workshop on Computer Applications in Diplomacy for representatives of such
foreign ministries in transition, and is currently engaged in the computerisation of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Malta. For this Ministry, a database on International Legal Instruments was established, covering more than 2000 such instruments and equipped with custom-made user software.<p>

Over the next two years, the institutions in Trinidad,  Yaound and Malta should be brought to the same level of capacity, so that they may make vailable their services for the computerisation of foreign ministries in their  region. All institutions, including the IUHEI in Geneva,  will be linked in a network using such communication facilities as the Internet. Each institution will have to set up its own Unit for IT Applications.


<h3>New forms of training</h3><p>

Once the institutions are properly computerised and able to operate as a network, it will be possible to use distance teaching as a major element of their programmes. As a  result, specialised academic staff will be shared by all and research work and supervision of theses will be possible through electronic contacts.<p>

It will also become possible for diplomats who cannot leave their countries to attend training programmes abroad, to participate in such programme over the electronic media, once proper facilites exist at the ministry for which they work. This will be of special importance for very small island states in the Caribbean, around Africa and in the Indian Ocean, and in the Pacific. Thus, it is hoped that the existing network of institutions working together  within the framework of the Diplomatic Studies Programmes  might in future be extended to the Pacific and to South-East Asia.<p>

The institutions would also be well equipped to cater for  such specialised training programmes as TRAINFORTRADE of UNCTAD, by acting as regional coordinators of programmes  and "trainers of trainers".


</BODY>
</HTML>
