<BODY>

<H2><B>PREFACE</B></H2>

<P>
Fred TANNER and James A. SCHEAR<HR>

<P>
The Mediterranean has long been a venue for tensions and conflicts.
Located on the crossroads between Europe, the Middle East and
Africa, the various subregions of the Mediterranean have been
prone not only to pressures created by Cold-War era confrontations
but also to the disruptive effects of unresolved local disputes,
most notably between Israel and her Arab neighbors. Though the
ebbing of the East-West conflict has greatly improved Mediterranean
security, regional disputes still abound and a wide array of non-military
issues - such as cross-border migrations, natural resource management,
and maritime policing issues - pose challenges that require urgent
attention. Fortunately, in recent years, the region has experienced
an upsurge of diplomatic activity aimed at promoting measures
of stability, cooperation and conflict resolution.
<P>
The factors underlying this search for greater cooperation are
diverse. More and more states, it would appear, have reached the
judgment that the security hazards they face cannot be solved
unilaterally or through military means alone. The penalties of
non-cooperation also are becoming more apparent. As technology
spreads, the hazards of uncontrolled weapons proliferation grow
ever more acute, requiring collective solutions. In the economic
sphere, development at the national level is increasingly dependent
upon inter-state cooperation and integration into the global economy.
The difficult question, clearly, is how to best forge cooperation
in matters of security while also preserving vital interests,
national independence and cultural identity.
<P>
One of the most hopeful developments in recent years has been
the advent of direct dialogue between Israel, the Palestinians,
and Arab states on the terms of a comprehensive peace settlement.
This dialogue, which has survived continuing violence and occasional
set-backs, has opened up a new pathway for multilateral discussions
on arms control and regional security - the so-called ACRS process.
In tandem with progress on the political side, these deliberations
could in time lead to the adoption of region-wide arms limitation
and confidence-building measures (CBMs) involving Israel and the
Arab states, including the Maghreb countries. Correspondingly,
there is growing interest in global disarmament regimes, such
as the treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT)
and the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC). Participation in these
regimes has far-reaching implications for states in terms of treaty
implementation, verification and safeguarding activity.
<P>
Thus, it would appear that practical steps toward arms control
and confidence-building will provide an important part of any
larger framework for regional security in the Mediterranean. Clearly,
such measures should not be viewed as a panacea for all types
of regional insecurities, and they must be carefully adjusted
to the pace of efforts aimed at settling the political and social
dimensions of ongoing conflicts. Yet, the very process of working
together on security problems may help to generate a sense of
common purpose among states and peoples and thereby improve the
climate in which constructive political change becomes possible.
<P>
The Mediterranean, in sum, is a promising arena for new forms
of multilateral security cooperation. With the decline of the
Cold-War era tensions, such collaborative activity is becoming
more possible; but the full potential of new cooperative ventures
remains to be fully explored, and the persistence of security
challenges at the regional level suggests that no one can take
future cooperation for granted.
<P>
To examine current security trends and the prospects for multilateral
cooperation in this difficult area, the Mediterranean Academy
of Diplomatic Studies and the Henry L. Stimson Center sponsored
a two-day conference on &quot;Arms Control, Confidence-Building
and Security Cooperation in the Mediterranean, North Africa and
the Middle East,&quot; on 24-26 June 1994, in Malta. We were very
fortunate that over thirty high level participants from governments,
international organizations and the academic community were able
to attend the meeting. A number of these individuals made presentations
at the conference and their papers are included in this volume.
<P>
The participants addressed the following categories of topics:
<UL>
<LI>Security trends in the Mediterranean;
<LI>Global and regional dimensions of arms control and disarmament;
<LI>Confidence-building measures in regional security; and
<LI>Multilateral cooperation in the maritime domaine and in key-non
military areas.
</UL>

<P>
The order of papers published in this volume has been arranged
according to these categories.
<P>
In closing, we wish to offer our sincere thanks to a number of
organizations that supported the conference and this publication.
They include the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Malta, the Foundation
for International Studies, University of Malta, the American Center,
the Association des Etudes Internationales, Tunisia, and the Directorate
of Development Cooperation and Humanitarian Aid of the Swiss Ministry
of Foreign Affairs. On the Stimson Center side, support for the
conference was provided by the Carnegie Corporation of New York,
the W. Alton Jones Foundation, the Rockfeller Foundation and the
Rockfeller Brothers Fund. 
</BODY>

