<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word ">

<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="student1">

<META NAME="DOCCOMM" CONTENT="">

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word ">
<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">
<META NAME="CREATIM" CONTENT="1995:9:20:5:41:">

<META NAME="VERSION" CONTENT="1">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>OPENING ADDRESS </H2>

<P>
<B>Professor Guido DE MARCO</B>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and
<P>
Minister of Foreign Affairs, Malta<HR>

<P>
Mr. Chairman, Excellencies, Ladies and Gentlemen
<P>
The end of the Cold War left the Mediterranean region facing a
multitude of problems and challenges, ranging from economic and
social disparities to pollution of the environment, arms proliferation
and conflicts, and the escalation of nationalism and extremism
in all its manifestations. Insecurity and instability are the
net result of this situation.
<P>
On the southern shores of the Mediterranean, the area stretching
from North Africa to the Middle East, the consequence of economic
problems and population explosion contribute to exacerbate an
already difficult socio-political situation. In part, this is
the result of the disequilibrium between the levels of development
on the northern and southern shores.
<P>
Socio-economic tensions coupled with unstable political systems
and the specificity of the historical and cultural condition of
access to modernity affect the domestic situation in many countries
and form a fertile ground for the development of religious extremism.
In particular, the growing influence of Islamic fundamentalism
in some countries lying on and around the southern shores of the
Mediterranean is perceived as a destabilizing factor and as a
potential threat to regional security. In addition to that, the
continued armed forces build-up in the area continues at alarming
levels.
<P>
These and other issues are affecting, directly or indirectly,
all countries in the Mediterranean region and even beyond. By
now, the need to meet the challenges posed in the area through
the concentrated efforts of all interested parties has been recognized,
as past and recent attempts at generating a dialogue on issues
of common concerns clearly demonstrate. The dramatic changes that
took place in the international political and
<P>
security environment in the aftermath of the Cold War and the
recent positive developments occurring in the Middle East are
adding momentum to the last spate of initiatives concerned with
security, stability and cooperation in the region.
<P>
It is in this context that Malta welcomes the convening of this
international workshop on ''Arms Control, Confidence-Building
and Security Cooperation in the Mediterranean, North Africa and
the Middle East'', co-organised by the Henry L. Stimson Centre,
USA, and the Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies at the
University of Malta.
<P>
This meeting convenes at the right time. The Middle East Peace
Process has entered a dynamic phase while European states start
realising that with the end of the Cold War, events in the Middle
East, North Africa and the Mediterranean are of direct significance
to their security.
<P>
A peace process is made up by a bilateral and multilateral track.
Both are addressing in one way or another questions of security
cooperation, confidence-building and arms control.
<P>
The multilateral talks on Arms Control and Regional Security have
seen considerable progress over the last few months, due of course
to the breakthrough in bilateral negotiations between Israel and
the Palestinians as well as Israel and Jordan.
<P>
They deal with a very wide scope ranging from confidence-building
measures to the control of conventional armament and weapons of
mass destruction, including a Nuclear Weapon Free Zone for the
Middle East. However, this important agenda on regional security
cooperation is influenced by the global arms control process,
which is currently in a crucial stage:
<P>
The Chemical Weapon Convention, which has already more than 160
signatories may enter into force by January 1995. This agreement
represents an important step for security in the Middle East,
North Africa
<P>
and the Mediterranean. We should not forget that chemical weapons
have been used extensively during the first Gulf War.
<P>
The Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty will expire next year if
not extended. The debate about an extension of the NPT has already
begun. The NPT plays an important role in the Middle East Peace
Process, as it is considered by some states as a primary instrument
to arrive at a Nuclear Weapon Free Zone in the region.
<P>
Other important items of the global arms control agenda include
negotiations for a Comprehensive Test Ban and a convention banning
further production of nuclear weapons-grade material.
<P>
Western security institutions such as NATO and the WEU have begun
to pay more attention to the Mediterranean region. Conflicts affecting
the Southern flank in the Balkans and the Caucasus have redirected
the attention of the Alliance from a purely East-West perspective.
Arrangements of soft security cooperation in the context of Partnership
for Peace extend today over parts of the Balkan and into Central
Asia.
<P>
Co-operative efforts to reduce the risk of armed conflict in the
region have to pursue a comprehensive approach. Regional and sub-regional
arms races can only be successfully addressed in a co-operative
fashion only.
<P>
Furthermore, confidence-building measures cannot take place in
a vacuum; they must be part of a comprehensive process. In times
when non-military risks have climbed the agenda of national security
policies, CBMs must be accompanied by co-operative measures in
the political, economic and environmental fields.
<P>
The experience gained by the Conference on Security and Cooperation
in Europe (CSCE) may be useful for regional security cooperation,
as it can serve as a model. Indeed, achievements of confidence-building
regimes at the end of the Cold War period in Europe have inspired
efforts in many other parts of the world.
<P>
However, we should not succumb to the belief that we can simply
transfer the CSCE to other regions. In Europe, for instance, confidence-building
had as its primary objective to stabilise the East-West relations,
whereas in the Middle East the building of confidence should make
the peaceful change in the region more palatable to all parties.
<P>
It is with this scenario in mind that we have to examine the concept
of Confidence Building Measures in the Mediterranean.
<P>
In the first place we have to acknowledge that the arms escalation
in the region is ever present; an escalation which goes beyond
the conventional weaponry.
<P>
Many of the countries on the southern flank own tactical ballistic
missiles. Chemical and bacteriological weapons if further developed,
can achieve strategic objectives in the region as to endanger
its stability. The proliferation of arms of mass destruction will
certainly affect the security situation in the region. But it
will be a mistake to evaluate the security situation in the Mediterranean
on strictly military terms. The socio-economic situation in the
Mediterranean is the main source of anxiety. Unemployment is in
the vertical. In less than thirty years the population in the
North Africa and the Middle East has grown by 118% as compared
to the 8% forecast for Europe. In North Africa and in the Middle
East the population will grow from 250 million to almost half
a billion.
<P>
It is relevant today that albeit with some delay, the linkage
between security in Europe and security in the Mediterranean has
been fully realised.
<P>
The NATO Summit of January 1994 declared that ''We reiterate our
conviction that security in Europe is greatly affected by security
in the Mediterranean. We strongly welcome the agreements recently
concluded in the Middle East Peace Process which offer a historic
opportunity for a peaceful and lasting settlement in the area.
This much awaited breakthrough has had a positive impact on the
overall situations in the Mediterranean, thus opening the way
to consider measures to promote
<P>
dialogue, understanding and confidence building between the countries
in the region. We direct the Council in the permanent session
to continue to review the overall situation, and we encourage
all effort conducive to strengthening regional stability.''
<P>
At this very moment the Corfu Summit is discussing the Mediterranean.
As president Klepsch said three hours ago ''The Greek Presidency's
proposal for a new common Mediterranean policy is a further positive
element in the efforts to achieve stability and peace. The European
Parliament supports this proposal for the creation of a Mediterranean
forum embracing all the member states of the Union and the Mediterranean
countries''.
<P>
Malta can look with satisfaction at seeing how high the Mediterranean
stands in the international agenda. For it was Malta which brought
about the realisation of the Mediterranean Basket in the Helsinki
Summit I.
<P>
We have also proposed and Helsinki Summit II made it its own that
the CSCE becomes the regional arrangement for peace-keeping in
the region in terms of Chapter VIII of the Charter of the United
Nations. A link was created between security in the CSCE region
with the global concept of security in terms of the United Nations
Charter.
<P>
Malta has sponsored the CSCM proposal and to my knowledge has
been the only country in the region to pass a resolution to that
effect by a unanimous vote of the House of Representatives.
<P>
Malta's proposal for a Council of the Mediterranean is receiving
a wide support. In a report by Spanish Parliamentarian Senior
R. de Rato in the Sub-Committee on the Southern Region to the
North Atlantic Assembly, a detailed analysis of Malta's proposal
of the Mediterranean was made. The rapporteur stated that ''realisation
of a CSCM is of course not for tomorrow; a number of NATO nations
themselves are not interested for reasons of feasibility or of
interest with the Middle East peace process or because of concerns
that Naval Arms Control measure would hamper operational flexibility.
Therefore our deliberations should take into account
<P>
other options. One variation has been put forward by Malta, by
way of a Council of the Mediterranean whereby through non rigid
arrangements one can have a setting for the development of a common
understanding''.
<P>
We know that a Gyminck is to take place in Alexandria early July
to discuss informally the Mediterranean region; a Gymnick which
is going to be attended by a limited number of countries.
<P>
We always have reservations when limitations are applied, unless
these limitations are governed by criteria of selection which
are politically sound as well as objective. They have to be clear,
transparent and logical; otherwise as I had occasion to state
when addressing last week the Western European Union Parliamentary
Assembly, the sense of exclusion may generate suspicions and create
negative reflexes.
<P>
Your presence here this evening is a confirmation of the Mediterranean
dimension in the international agenda. A dimension which requires
understanding and development of a dialogue.
<P>
If a result of this dialogue and of the confidence building measures
aligned thereto prove positive, we will succeed in getting the
countries of the region to discuss their common concerns, their
common interest and their common heritage, and we will have succeeded
in getting together the countries of the Mediterranean to discuss
their common future for the first time in history. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
