<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word ">

<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">

<TITLE>SECURITY TRENDS IN THE MEDITERRANEAN:</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="student1">

<META NAME="DOCCOMM" CONTENT="">

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word ">
<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">
<META NAME="CREATIM" CONTENT="1995:9:20:5:47:">

<META NAME="VERSION" CONTENT="1">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>SECURITY TRENDS IN THE MEDITERRANEAN</H2>

<H3>A Perspective from North Africa</H3>

<P>
<B>Ambassador Ahmed OUNAIS</B>
<P>
Director General of Political Affairs
<P>
Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Tunisia<HR>

<P>
I was invited to present to you a North African perspective on
Security Trends in the Mediterranean. These are my personal views
and comments.
<P>
The long process that culminated in the signing of the Helsinki
Act on August lst, 1975, started with the stabilisation of the
European Region, which means the admission of all by all, within
identified and respected borders, and with mutual differences
in political systems and regimes.
<P>
What has made possible such a process of negotiations in the fields
of Security, Cooperation and Human Rights is:
<P>
1. The stability of the political map and the general commitment
not to alter it by means of violence or war; and
<P>
2. The balance of power, the shared belief that any attempt against
any party will be countered by efficient means. This <U>guarantee
</U>extends to all parties: members of the two blocs as well as
the non-aligned and neutral countries.
<P>
The structure of balanced power enables the groups of countries
to enter a deal as large as the Helsinki Act and its subsequent
confidence building measures in so many fields. Of course, stability
does not mean a freeze. Actually, the political map as it was
has changed, but a change which came from within - a change proprio
motu. Indeed, the seeds of Helsinki were tremendously portent.
<P>
The teachings of the process, as we perceived them, were designed
to build confidence on the basis of stable and secured entities.
Stable, because they enjoy mutual and global recognition and secure,
because they rely on the shared belief that aggression is actually
suicidal.
<P>
The picture in the Mediterranean today is different from the continental
Europe of the late 1960s. The unsettled conflicts in the Middle-East,
Cyprus, ex-Yugoslavia and Western Sahara are proof of the shifting
political map of the region. The stability and the structure of
security are yet to be assured: though all current conflicts are
subject to an active process of negotiations, many Mediterranean
parties feel uncertain about their full acceptance in the regional
process while mistrust continues to reign.
<P>
Besides these internal factors, the international realities, as
they appear, do not help in confidence building: the partial and
hazardous strategies, either hesitant and seemingly paralyzed
or opportunistic and discriminatory, bear a large responsibility
in the extent of instability, antagonism and allergic relationship
among some Mediterranean countries.
<P>
Disputes and claims of diverse nature - ethnic, religious - constitute
a source of concern in many places. Furthermore, the military
factor is still dominant in the current process of settlement
of these issues.
<P>
We will consider the security trends in the Mediterranean under
three headings:
<H4><B>1. The International Aspects</B></H4>

<P>
The conflicts in the Mediterranean do not originate in the East-West
confrontation; they go back to the earlier imperial or colonial
era.
<P>
The Cold War had its impact over them - fueling, delaying, freezing
- but, by nature, they take root in the chain of events of the
old world. Therefore, sequels of the past are still to be found
in today's political arena.
<P>
The challenge of the past is not insurmountable. With due respect
to the rights and claims of all nations, we can use the present
political and legal culture to address the longlasting litigations
and crises: liberty, equality, reciprocity, legality, universal
values and principles, as well as a feeling of responsibility
and dignity.
<P>
The main features of the present picture, as we perceive them,
are as follows:
<P>
a) The Colonial Dimension
<P>
Surprisingly, the Mediterranean still suffers from colonial rule
as witnessed on its west flank in Ceuta and Mellilla and on its
east flank in the territories occupied by Israel. The colonial
phenomenon is indeed redundant; the ultimate solution in these
colonial spots could not be different from other historic precedents.
Nevertheless, these are sequels of anachronistic strategies, which
heavily affect political relations among Mediterranean countries.
<P>
We, in North Africa, have experienced colonial rule under which
intruders expel the natives and occupy their land and home, as
part of the strategy devised by the rulers. The new settlers enjoy
military, economic and technical facilities which help them radically
transform the environment, including the human relationship and
political set-up: very soon the colonisers get so arrogant as
to claim political rights and national sovereignty over the land.
<P>
Though legally null and void <I>ab initio</I>, this process has
repeated itself to the point of blindness. The North African countries
do not compromise on this issue, one of the bitterest pieces of
our modem history in the Maghreb.
<P>
b) Military Occupation
<P>
Needless to say, military occupation is a sore truth of the region.
Are confidence building measures conceivable together with military
occupation, all among the same parties? It is rather squaring
the circle: We question the rationale of such policy and believe
that a pledge for normalisation implies actual ending of military
occupation. Confidence Building is the next step after normalisation.
<P>
The Mediterranean will certainly take a qualitative step forward
when the phenomenon of military occupation ceases to exist, as
well as when the military regimes themselves cease to exist. That
will be the threshold of an all encompassing normalisation, the
prerequisite to a Mediterranean policy of cooperation and the
building of a common concept of security.
<P>
c) Arms Control and Regional Security
<P>
The present regional status is based on assymetry and double standard.
The Mediterranean countries are not equal parties to the international
instruments governing disarmament, non-proliferation and control
regimes.
<P>
The unequal status with regard to arms of mass destruction, nuclear
technology and systems of delivery will thus hinder promoting
confidence and regional security. Initiatives on coordination
and control of conventional arm transfer into the region cannot
ignore that status, as well as the status of net importer countries
and those which are partial producers.
<P>
It is part of the confidence building policy to weigh the actual
military status of the concerned parties and pledge equal international
guarantees for all.
<P>
d) International Legality
<P>
The building of regional cooperation is not a way of escape from
common law. International legality is basic and binding to all.
The search for regional understanding and cooperation could only
take stock of basic &quot;clear&quot; relationships with regard
to international legality and, additionally, develop more advanced
facilities and free concessions. In no way could it justify some
parties avoiding their obligations or legitimise attempts to force
other parties to renounce their rights in accordance with international
conventions and essential UN resolutions. It is not a substitute
to international legality.
<P>
In the process of building mutual understanding and regional system
of cooperation, admission of international legality helps generate
reliability and better predictability, leading to an atmosphere
of relaxation and improved openness and receptivity. Deliberate
rejection of international legality can only generate suspicion
and justify counter-strategies and defensive attitudes. Unequal
parties could only become true and genuine partners through their
common respect of international legality.
<P>
e) Respect of Nations
<P>
The Mediterranean, cradle of old civilizations, has given birth
to many nations which fought their way to existence and lived
their time of grandeur: whatever the fate and the present size
of these nations, they have resisted the trials of time and put
forward their indestructible will and right to live as nations.
Based on ethnic or religious or cultural values, these nations
claim a specific identity and intractable rights to land, culture
and free exercise of sovereignty.
<P>
Since the first World War, the Mediterranean order failed in its
many attempts based on exclusion or dominance. The decolonisation,
the regional wars, the disintegration of Yugoslavia are living
proof that dominance, exclusion or imposed federal &quot;aggregation&quot;
are not durable: the restoration of these old &quot;nucleus&quot;
Nations is irresistible.
<P>
The order of the day ought to be the shaping of a new Mediterranean
order, based on non-domination and on the respect of Nations with
their differences.
<P>
f) The External Factor
<P>
War, antagonism, extremism, have long been the lot of the Mediterranean
peoples. Though rooted in the very local realities and passions,
these events have been heavily &quot;fueled&quot; by actors from
abroad: providers of weapon and logistics, clients and semi-allies,
accomplices by way of disinformation. The external powers have
constantly played their roles in the current affairs of the unstable
and coveted Mediterranean.
<P>
Let us not forget that fifty two years ago (November 1942), the
Allied forces landed in North Africa as a stronghold in order
to free Europe. It was two years before the landing in Normandy;
and that in the wake of the de-colonisation period, the navies
of the two super-powers were permanently operating in the Mediterranean.
The area was constantly used in the interest of Europe and other
powers.
<P>
The end of the Cold War and the consequences of the second Gulf
War have brought a qualitative change in the role of the outside
actors: the basic structure of interests has remained unchanged,
but with field objectives adapted to the new geometry of forces.
While processes of negotiations are being developed in all the
hot spots around the Mediterranean, important observations are
worth mentioning:
<P>
i) Enforcement of international legality is poor, erratic and
seemingly paralysed;
<P>
ii) A major role is assumed by the UN in all crises but one;
<P>
iii) Against the policy of curbing the arms race in the region,
as declared after the Gulf War and supported by new agreed instruments
for
<P>
transparency and control regimes, huge amounts of advanced conventional
arms are transferred to the region.
<P>
iv) The United States, being the co-sponsor of the Peace Process
in the Middle-East, is the strategic ally of one party to the
negotiations, Israel, providing it with strategic armament and
assistance, regular financial aid and sharing with it high military
technology;
<P>
v) In the same token, regimes of sanctions (either bilateral or
international) extend to other negotiators: Syria, Lebanon and
Jordan as well as to selected countries of the second row: Libya
and Iraq, not to speak of Sudan and Iran.
<P>
The contrast is quite clear: the &quot;fair and free negotiations&quot;
are developing amid heavy and open pressure applied on the Arab
and Islamic side of the table by the biggest world actor on the
stage.
<H4>2. The National Aspects</H4>

<P>
We realize the weight of international factors on the current
Security trends. The dilemma is heavier with the concurrence of
difficulties within the concerned nations.
<P>
Two main groups are going through difficult times: the Slav and
the Semitic groups of nations are yet to find their balance and
harmony among themselves. Horizontal conflicts among the Slavs
(particularly Yugoslavs in the south) as well as among the sons
of Abraham, Arabs and Jews, are rather well known features, North
and South of the Mediterranean.
<P>
Furthermore, conflictual relations are periodically cropping up
within the Jewish community as well as the Arab community. Indeed,
they are not making it any easier.
<P>
We will just consider the level of these differences in connection
with the regional Mediterranean perspective: their impact on respective
domestic policy is not of relevance to us.
<P>
a) Normalisation
<P>
As physicians and psychiatrists know, normalcy is the rule but
hardly the reality of life. More than is the case with individuals,
nations favor identifying themselves with heroic achievements,
legends and myths; they may even claim divine privileges over
the rest of mankind. Legitimate feeling of exaltation, when it
is the reward of real sacrifice and successful action of self
defense, could easily turn into abnormal doctrines and transpolitical
strategies.
<P>
A chain of historic events has built up series of national standards
of that kind. No matter if it does not affect the political culture,
in harmony with the spirit of the time. But it matters very much
if other nations fall victim of such abnormalcy.
<P>
I will not go any further into this; I will just conclude that
<U>normalcy</U> is the gateway to <U>normalisation</U>. When nations
use self-exaltation and set their standards so as to hurt the
rights and dignity of other nations, they ought to stand first,
as normal people, align themselves as just human beings, no less
but indeed no more, and admit normalcy as a common rule.
<P>
Once they normalise and align themselves with the common standard
of international legality and assume principles of reciprocity
and equal treatment, they will deserve normalisation with other
civilized nations and will be admitted as equal among equals.
So did the white community in South Africa: they deserve our respect.
<P>
b) Fundamentalism
<P>
Fundamentalism is a serious threat to many countries all over
the Mediterranean. As an expression of religious absolutism, it
is inconsistent with a strategy of pluralism, tolerance and universal
values, which are the basic premises of regional cooperation among
nations of different faith and culture.
<P>
Religious extremism has expanded from Israel to Iran and thereafter
to other neighbours among Islamic and Christian societies all
along the South and North Mediterranean, all the way up to Morocco
and Yugoslavia. It has been fueled by several factors:
<P>
- Failure to resolve the Arab-Israeli conflict and particularly
the Palestinian question, whose resolution is undoubtedly one
of the major keys to peace and security in the region. It fuels
the forces of extremism that want to substitute the appeal of
religion and martyrdom to international law and regular diplomacy,
<P>
- The West's perceived opportunism, as it first used the Jihad
in Afghanistan then turned hostile to the Muslim people in their
struggle for freedom and dignity;
<P>
- The danger of Serbian expansion, aiming at the destruction of
the Muslim population in Bosnia.
<P>
These various sources are compounded by the widespread frustration
over economic stagnation which further fuels the ongoing historical
struggle between the forces of democratisation and the forces
of conservatism and extremism.
<P>
These movements use violence in their effort to punish individuals
or take over a country and replace its secular government with
a theocratic regime poised to fight the basic values of democracy
and individual liberties, identified with evil.
<P>
The disturbances in Algeria by the Fundamentalists and the actual
threat over its regime constitute a challenge to the stability
and the security of all neighbouring countries including southern
Europe.
<H4><B>3. Regional and sub-regional momentum</B></H4>

<P>
The current processes of negotiations have their own logic and
momentum. In the Middle-East, Cyprus and ex-Yugoslavia, they ultimately
aim at defining the national expression of minorities. The Eastern
basin of the Mediterranean will enter an era of stability and
common security when the political map is fixed and legitimised
through mutual and total recognition.
<P>
The picture in the Western basin is different. Though totally
committed to the objectives at stake in the Eastern flank, the
Western basin countries already enjoy a status of relative stability
and supra-national organisation. The five Maghreb countries (Members
of the Union of Arab Maghreb created in 1989) and the four latin
European countries (members of the European Union) and Malta have
set up in October 1990 a process of multilateral cooperation known
as 5 + 5. This sub-regional system of cooperation answers the
common specific concerns and priorities of the member countries,
which are of economic and social nature.
<P>
The serious imbalance in these fields between the two groups has
a security dimension. The Forum 5 + 5 is designed to initiate
a global approach to these diverse issues and to develop a broad
and permanent dialogue on cooperation and security in the sub-region.
Such a process has different scope and political dynamics, compared
with the current processes in the Eastern basin. The issues at
stake are of a different nature.
<P>
The challenges in both sub-regions are equally surmountable, but
with separate logic and momentum. What is comforting is that all
contribute to a new genesis of understanding and broad integration.
Subordination of these processes would hinder the momentum of
the global dynamics.
<P>
With the European experience in mind, we may illustrate the current
Mediterranean trend with the following scale:
<P>
From To
<P>
1. Political negation Political being
<P>
2. Legal recognition Stability
<P>
3. Co-existence Cooperation
<P>
4. Multilateral cooperation Supra-national organisation
<P>
= regional security (Common institutions with
<P>
regional mandate)
<P>
While the Eastern basin countries are in between &quot;political
being and legal recognition&quot;, the Western basin countries
are between &quot;multilateral cooperation and supra-national
organisation&quot;.
<P>
The current phase in the Middle East, which is of diplomatic nature,
is a mixed approach in between &quot;multilateral negotiation
and conditional recognition&quot;.
<P>
One may ask whether, considering the particular &quot;Mediterranean
structure&quot;, a larger forum of the size of CSCM would operate
as a catalyst and help overcome the last resistance in the current
negotiations. I would favour a positive but cautious approach.
<P>
Substantive progress should be acknowledged: the reciprocal recognition
by Israel and the PLO has helped lift important obstacles in the
process of normalcy and normalisation, and it cleared some deliberate
confusion over basic concepts which have long obstructed the dialogue
between the parties, (such as terrorism, collective and individual
rights, national and citizen status). Together with this substantive
step, other issues of ethical and legal dimension are to be cleared:
mainly the colonial dimension, the military occupation, and the
respect of international legality. A clear stand
<P>
on these issues is of strategic importance, for the Mediterranean
as well as the world.
<P>
We would therefore recommend more meetings on informal basis,
rather than a formal CSCM-Conference, in order to first help build
a strong consensus on issues of human and ethical dimension, extending
to all the conflicts still pending in the Mediterranean arena.
<H4><B>4. Conclusion</B></H4>

<P>
More than any other region, the Mediterranean must meet the challenge
of setting up a regional order so as to conciliate equal rights
with unequal might among all riparian Nations. For the first time
in history, the Mediterranean is trying to find its way towards
one comprehensive system, including all nations big and small,
based on non-domination, and common principles rather than exclusive
factors. The concept is not coexistence as was the European order
before the Helsinki Act, which was based on balance of terror,
but a system based on three premises:
<P>
- acceptance of equal rights for all nations;
<P>
- acceptance of free cooperation;
<P>
- acceptance of differences in power, faith and ethnicity.
<P>
It will be indeed an unprecedented Mediterranean order. 
</BODY>

