<H2>CSBMs : The Ugly Duckling Remains a Duck -but a Pretty Good
One </H2>

<P>
<B>Ambassador Lynn HANSEN</B>
<P>
Former Head of U.S. Delegation to CFE-Talks
<P>
Political Advisor, HQ U.S. Air Force Europe<HR>

<P>
In 1981, while the Madrid CSCE follow-up Meeting was in full swing
attempting to agree on the mandate for the Stockholm Conference,
a German foreign affairs institute hosted a conference on confidence
building measures. In some respects it was like this one. It was
attended by a large number of academics, diplomats, and security
experts from all parts of the world. A fair amount of skepticism
was in evidence. Many security pundits found it difficult to conceive
of confidence-building measures as creating greater security and
stability. The title for this paper takes its inspiration from
the then head of the London based International Institute for
Strategic Studies (IISS), Christopher Bertram. Taking his cue
from the fairy tale by the famous Dane, Hans Christian Andersen,
Bertram said during the Germans conference that CBMs were ugly
ducklings that would never turn into swans.
<P>
After approximately eight years of implementation experience,
I would personally agree with Bertram that CBMs have not, figuratively
that is, turned into the beautiful swan of Hans Christian Andersen's
fairly tale. Nonetheless, the ugly duckling has shown itself to
be a pretty good duck, not things of absolute beauty, CBMs are
now universally recognized as practical tools which do, in fact,
build confidence and security.
<H4><B>1. Basic Precepts - A Subjective View</B></H4>

<P>
The theory of confidence-building is far less convincing than
the practice. For two glorious years I occupied a chair in political
science at the United States Air Force Academy in Colorado. The
brilliant and well-trained young officers who taught in that department
intimidated me with their knowledge and enthusiasm. However, I
was perplexed by the importance they placed on academic theories
of political science and international relations. Many times I
had cause to stop and reflect as to whether theory had played
any role whatsoever in my own experience as a policy-maker in
government. I suppose it did, but I was far more interested in
practice.
<P>
Speaking very frankly to you, even when I was a negotiator I often
wondered about whether the theoretical arguments we were making
concerning the potential for CSBMs to eliminate surprise attack
were really true or whether the thrust of the argument was mainly
political. Surprise attack, my military background told me, is
a highly complex subject which is not resolved by slogans on quick
answers. And, I reasoned, if a nation really wants to launch a
surprise attack, CBMs are unlikely to pose an unsurmountable obstacle.
Yet, the practice of implementing CBMs can contribute to improving
relationships that help eliminate the reasons for surprise attack.
<P>
So I am convinced that confidence building measures do have an
important, even critical, role to play among states that desire
political change in their relationships where military capabilities
impact on those relationships.
<P>
I began working in the field of confidence-building measures while
still an active member of the Armed Forces of the United States.
I had served twice as a liaison officer to the Group of Soviet
Forces in East Germany. My duties involved observing to the maximum
possible extent the activities of those forces. In their attempts
to limit my observations, the Russians twice shot at me. It should
not therefore be surprising that I considered the Soviet Union
as my personal enemy, in addition to be the political adversary
and potential enemy of the United States.
<P>
It was difficult for me to accept the very idea of confidence-building.
I had no interest in having confidence in the USSR or the Soviet
Armed Forces. The intellectual examinations of the subject made
sense, but I viewed them with the suspicion that military men
often have for intellectuals and diplomats. The key issue, as
I saw it, was security. I attempted to capture this thought in
an article I wrote in 1983, following is a quote from that article
:
<P>
<I>Many who have attempted to address the conceptual question
of confidence-building have begun with the psychological dimension
of what constitutes trust. This is, however, approaching the problem
backwards. International confidence is, and always will be, directly
related to the condition of one's own security.</I> 
<P>
For a time, I launched a small and distinctly unsuccessful campaign
to change the name of confidence-building measures. I felt that
many languages did not convey the nuanced difference of meaning
that exists in English between &quot;confidence&quot; and &quot;trust&quot;,
consequently, the idea was often conveyed that we were building
&quot;trust&quot;. As a relatively hard-boiled military man, I
did not want to &quot;trust&quot; anyone. My view was that one
should have confidence in one's own security, not in the intentions
of a potentially hostile power. The change in name from CBM to
CSBM (confidence-and security-building measures) at the Madrid
CSCE following up meeting helped some, even though the name change
arose from different considerations and had little practical effect
in the design of measures.
<H4><B>2. A Process</B></H4>

<P>
As you may have noted, confidence and security-building is a process,
not a single event or a single measure. It is more important to
begin the process than it is to get everything perfect in the
first step. It would be neither possible nor wise to simply lift
the CSBM provisions of Vienna Document 1992 and apply them casually
to other regions. Indeed the European process has been step-by-step
beginning with the extremely modest Helsinki confidence-building
measures of the 1975 CSCE Final Act and proceeding to the watershed
Stockholm Document, and the two Vienna documents.
<P>
Of course, it would also be serious folly not to reap the benefits
of the European process. The beginning in other regions should
not, therefore, be the 1975 Helsinki Final Act, but appropriately
modified versions of measures that have been successful in the
European environment.
<P>
Specific criteria, however, should be developed and employed.
In preparing for the Stockholm negotiations, the West insisted
that future measures had to be 1) military significant, 2) [politically]
binding, 3) verifiable, and 4) applied to an agreed area, which
in this case was the whole of Europe.
<P>
There is no need to discuss these principles further. It is only
important here to note that eventual measures should be built
on a well-defined concept with specific principles. A quote from
a United Nations study on CBMs may be helpful in this context.
<P>
<I>...neither declarations of intent or a repetition of generally
recognized principles nor mere promises for a certain behavior
in the future, e.g., in cases of armed conflict, satisfy the exigencies
of removing perceptions of threat and suspicion...Confidence-building
measures must therefore be such that they translate universally
recognized principles, such as the renunciation of the use of
threat of use of force in accordance with the UN Charter, into
reality by the application of concrete, specific, and verifiable
measures.</I> 
<H4><B>3. Openness</B></H4>

<P>
States traditionally seek to guarantee their security by building
up their armed forces in order to be able to effectively respond
to a perceived threat. Consequently, one of the chief objectives
of confidence-building measures is for states with potentially
or actual conflicting philosophies to cooperatively assure each
other that their security is not threatened by offensive action.
Since most states would evaluate capability rather than intention,
this is not as easy as many would suppose.
<P>
Because the first use of force initiating a conflict would involve
the use of conventional armed forces, a critical step in confidence-building
is the provision of reasonable and accurate information pertaining
to those forces and their activities. The objective is to communicate
that military activities, both in a general and in a specific
sense, are not precursors to pre-emptive attack.
<P>
Many intellectuals argued that confidence-building ought to include
information and obligation regarding nuclear and other non-conventional
weapons. However an insistence on such inclusion would have condemned
the effort in Europe to failure from the beginning. This is because
nuclear weapons, in particular, were considered as weapons of
last resort which served a deterrent function and would not be
used in the initiation of hostilities.
<P>
With the hindsight of experience, European states are now convinced
of the importance of openness and transparency in the confidence-and-security-building
process. Excessive secrecy in military affairs has been recognizedas
one of the greatest impediments realizing the political objectives
set forth in the 1975 Helsinki CSCE Final Act. However, this has
not alwaysbeen the case. Soviet Foreign Minister Gromyko, at the
beginning of the Stockholm Conference in January 1984 was scathing
in his criticism of confidence-and security-building measures
which promoted openness and transparency. He compared them with
an illicit peak through a fence aimed at gaining intelligence
and therefore unilateral advantage. There were also many in the
West who were decidedly uncomfortable with the idea of providing
a potential adversary with detailed information on their armed
forces. This was particularly true of the military.
<P>
Near the end of the Stockholm Conference, when it became clear
that there would be agreement on-site inspection, three or four
military representatives stated that their defense establishments
were displeased at the thought of foreign inspectors looking at
their defense arrangements. In each case, the response was to
remind that the political decision had already been taken and
the Western negotiators were going to support that decision. The
armed forces in virtually every participating state are now among
the most enthusiastic supporters of the confidence-building process
and the inspection provisions that have been agreed in both CSBM
agreements and arms reduction treaties.
<H4><B>4. Information Exchange</B></H4>

<P>
Many will argue a host of reasons why they cannot agree to an
exchange of information at early in the confidence-building process.
If these arguments carry enough political weight, it may be difficult
to agree on a complete and total exchange of military information
disaggregated to the level of regiment/brigade, and independent
battalion.The attempt should then be made to agree at some lesser
level of dissaggregation. Irrespective of the level of disaggregation
in the information, it is critical that the process gets underway
and that the commitment is made to include information exchange
as part of confidence-and security-building. Later, when the process
deepens and confidence in the process itself increases, lower
levels of disaggregation will be both advisable and possible.
<P>
Contrary to what Mr. Gromyko said at the initiation of the Stockholm
Conference, an open and honest exchange of information according
to unambiguous provisions does not bestow an exploitable unilateral
advantage on any state. To those seeking genuine and lasting stability
based on mutual understanding, the advantage is at least a bilaterally
shared advantage, and in most cases even multilateral.
<P>
No state has a complete understanding of another state's intelligence
capabilities and analysis. But every state understands that every
other state has an intelligence apparatus that has reached certain
conclusions about the capabilities of other states. Often, these
conclusions are based on <I>worst case</I> analyses based on either
faulty information or political purpose, and sometimes both. The
objective is to create a situation where one state can say of
another that its understanding of the military situation in that
state corresponds to reality. In such a situation, an honest and
objective exchange of information can deprive contemptible leaders
of credible worst case analysis. Of course, this sword can cut
both ways and each state must evaluate for itself where its national
security interests are best served. Nonetheless, the experience
in Europe is unequivocal: openness and transparency are key to
establishing credible and long term cooperative relationships
among states that had previously been potential adversaries.
<H4><B>5. Pre-Notification of Military Activities</B></H4>

<P>
The Helsinki Final Act, in its <I>Document on confidence-building
measures and certain aspects</I> <I>of security and disarmament
</I>provides clear explanation and rationale in its preamble for
the pre-notification of certain military activities.
<P>
<I>Recognizing the need to contribute to reducing the dangers
of armed conflict and of misunderstanding or miscalculation of
military activities which could give rise to apprehension, particularly
in a situation where the participating States lack clear andtimely
information about the nature of such activities.</I>
<P>
The military dimension of prenotification, i.e., dealing with
the question of misunderstanding or miscalculation of military
activities, was followed in the Final Act by the conviction that
prenotification also has a political function.
<P>
<I>Convinced of the political importance of prior notification
of major military manoeuvres for the promotion of mutual understanding
and the strengthening of confidence, stability, and security.
</I>
<P>
Every army must exercise in order to be a competent fighting force
able to fulfill its military objectives and strategy. Large armies
must conduct large scale military activities such as manoeuvres
and movements. Because of the possibility that offensive action
could be launched as a surprise attack out of an exercise posture,
some states believed that prenotification measures should focus
on large-scale activities. If one were to focus exclusively on
the military dimension of confidence-building, such a position
has some merit. But in the European process, one wanted to deal
also with the political function of confidence- building. Indeed,
when the Helsinki measures were agreed in 1975 both East and West
already possessed national technical means sufficient to insure
knowledge about major military maneuvers as they unfolded. So
the purely military aspect of early CBMs took a backseat to the
political function, i.e., the political act of providing information.
<P>
In the Stockholm negotiation of CBMs, the West began by suggesting
that the numerical threshold for pre-notification of military
activities should be at about 6,000 soldiers. This represented,
in gross terms, a regiment or brigade level exercise. After additional
analysis showed that such a low notification threshold would result
in an extremely high number of notifications, the West lowered
its demands to that of a division-level exercise. For Europe,
this level represented a significant military exercise, even though
most recognized that a division-level exercise was hardly a threat
to European security; but in pursuing the political objective,
it was judged to be about right. Thus, in 1986 it was possible
to agree on a threshold for notification which became operable
whenever 13,000 troops, or 300 tanks were organized into a divisional
structure or at least two
<P>
brigades/regiments. When it was subsequently recognized that the
size of military activities in Europe had decreased, the numerical
trigger for notification was also lowered. Again, not because
of the military aspect or the fear of surprise attack, but because
the political function of confidence-building through pre-notification
was deemed sufficiently important to make the change.
<H4><B>6. Matters of Concern: Amphibious, Airborne, Transfers,
Concentrations</B> </H4>

<P>
Whenever possible, it is important to notify those activities
that cause another state concern. Because of their location on
the Baltic Sea, the Scandinavian countries were eager to include
amphibious activities in a CSBMs regime. Other states were concerned
about airborne activities, especially parachute landings. These
interests were accommodated with a minimum degree of difficulty.
On the other hand, it was not possible to meet the former Soviet
Union's demands that independent air and naval activities be included
in the regime. The reasons it was not possible were complicated
but can be summarized by noting the West's perception that the
real reason for the inclusion of such naval and air activities
was to make nuclear elements (normally dealt with in a bilateral
setting) part of a multilateral negotiation dealing with conventional
arms. Nonetheless, naval and air activities which form part of
otherwise notifiable activities were included.
<P>
A good example of the West's willingness to meet the concerns
of other states related to the question of transfers and movements.
For a long time it appeared that there could be no agreement on
this issue. The United States, in particular, was unwilling to
compromise in any way its ability to transfer troops in or into
Europe on their way to a crisis in the Middle East or elsewhere.
Member states of the Warsaw Pact regarded the large transfer of
American forces to Europe each fall to participate in the
<P>
REFORGER exercise as cause for concern and reasoned that a movement
or transfer of such magnitude should be pre-notified as part of
a confidence- and security-building regime. The U.S., for its
part, did notobject to the concept of notification, but did not
know how to agree to the East's proposition without degrading
the ability to move quickly and in force to other regions.
<P>
About a month before the negotiation was concluded, each side
understood the limits of the other's position. The U.S. understood
that it could notify troops moving to Europe for the purpose of
participating in the annual REFORGER exercises as long as such
notification covered only exercise troops and did not impose a
prenotification requirement in the rapid movement of other troops
through Europe for development in another region. Thus, the idea
began to take shape that whenever troops were to move within Europe
or to move into Europe from outside the zone, notification would
be given provided such troops were to be concentrated for the
purpose of participating in notifiable activities. The text of
the measure illustrates how both sides' interests were preserved.
<P>
<I>The engagement of formations of land forces of the participating
states in a transfer from outside the zone of application for
CSBMs to arrival points in the zone, or from inside the zone of
application for CSBMs to point of concentration in the zone, to
participate in a notifiable exercise activity or to be concentrated.
</I>
<P>
Similarly, the West was reluctant to use such terms as ''manoeuvers&quot;
or &quot;movements&quot; because of the difference in military
cultures and the specific meanings of such terms. The &quot;out-of-garrison&quot;
concept was devised to cover all contingencies where military
forces left their garrison to conduct any kind of military activity.
The East was categorical in its rejection of the term &quot;out-of-garrison&quot;
and it does not appear in the text. Nonetheless, the concept is
preserved through appropriate operational language.
<H4><B>7. Visual Monitoring</B></H4>

<P>
One of the fundamental advantages of the Stockholm Document over
the Helsinki Final Act is the obligatory nature of the requirement
to invite observers and to receive on-site inspections. Because
these requirements are non-discretionary, there is no question
about the obligation. Failure to comply has a different connotation
than failure to implement a voluntary measure. While the concept
of volunteerism is in itself theoretically appealing, it can be
exploited as a reason not to do something in practice. By and
large, then, voluntary measures should be avoided.
<P>
Recalling Soviet Foreign Minister Gromyko's critical comments
about openness and transparency made at the opening of the Stockholm
Conference, it is noteworthy that in the first year of implementation
of the Stockholm CSBMs agreement the Soviet Union conducted more
on site inspections than any other state . Sixteen of the 23 members
of the two military alliances which had earlier regarded each
other with mutual suspicion were involved in inspections in 1987,
the first year of implementation. Within 15 months of the end
of the CSBM's negotiation, on-site inspections had become a part
of the regular political and military-security landscape in Europe;
they were no longer regarded as either unusual or as a manifestation
of mistrust and suspicion. In addition to on-site inspections,
47 military activities were also pre-notified, many of which were
at the level of 17,000 troops which required the invitation of
observers.
<P>
From 1987 to 1991 the number of notifiable military activities
in Europe reduced significantly as shown in figure 1. This decline
in the number of notifiable activities resulted in a decline in
the number of observations conducted.
<P>
<I>Figure 1</I><HR>

<PRE>
          1987    1988    1989    1990   1991    TOTAL    
NATO        17      13      11      10     5       56     
WTO         25      22      17      7      4       75     
NNA         5       3       3       4      1       16     
TOTAL       47      38      31      21     10      147    
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
Of course, Europe was undergoing colossal political changes during
this period. Within the confidence- and security-building process,
an information exchange measure was agreed and the emphasis shifted
from observation of notified military activities and on-site inspection
to the evaluation of the information provided in accordance with
the new measures. CSBMs activity in 1992 was illustrative of the
change in focus: only three on-site inspections were conducted
and just four observations of prenotified military activities
were carried out. On the other hand, 24 different states conducted
visits to military facilities for the purpose of evaluating the
CSBM regime's new information exchange visit. These 24 states
included three of the successor states to the former Soviet Union
: Russia, Belarus, and Ukraine. Finland, Sweden, Austria, and
Switzerland who had previously opted not to become involved in
on-site inspections were by now actively involved in evaluation
visits.
<P>
The point to be made here is that when the number of observations
and on-site inspections declined, states agreed on other measures
which preserved the confidence-building purpose of exposing military
forces on their own territory to visual scrutiny by other states
in the region.
<P>
In 1990, as the process continued, states were also able to agree
to provide information on plans for the deployment of major weapon
and equipment systems as well as to give each other information
on their military budgets. A new measure on visits to air bases
was also agreed as was a mechanism for dealing with unusual military
activity and for cooperating with respect to hazard incidents
of a military nature. It was also agreed that Annual
<P>
Implementation Meetings would be held in which the implementation
of agreed CSBMs would be examined as well as possible improvements.
<H4><B>8. Open Skies</B></H4>

<P>
It is almost universally recognized that verification of international
agreements is the responsibility of national governments that
are parties to the agreements. This would rule out the use of
an open skies platform for verification purpose. An Open skies
regime is thus considered to service the confidence-building function
rather than as an act of verification. This is a recognized principle
in the European environment.
<P>
This has special significance for the Middle East where the perception
is strong that Israel benefits from satellite technology for surveillance
purposes while Arab states do not. An open skies regime for the
Middle East would have to be a shared as a cooperative effort
in which the participants agree on the platform to be used, the
sensor suite, and the modalities of flying an open skies mission.
One would expect representatives from both the observing and the
observed state to be on board the open skies aircraft with the
observing state directing the flight path according to predetermined
rules and modalities. The nationality of the platform in such
case is almost irrelevant. It could be leased, part of a pool,
or provided by one or the other party.
<P>
Certainly, an open skies regime as a confidence-building measure
could provide very positive assurance that one state is not preparing
aggressive action against another. Some may argue that a determined
aggressor could hide intentions from periodic open sky flights.
However, an attack which had any chance of success could require
substantial preparations which would be extremely hard to hide
from open skies sensors.
<H4><B>9. Applicability and Adaptability</B></H4>

<P>
There is no hiding the fact that the Middle East is not Europe
in either geographical or political terms. Whereas decades of
diplomatic discourse preceded the Stockholm and Vienna agreements
on CSBMs, there was little or no such dialogue between Israel
and its neighbors until recently. The process is still largely
in its formative stages and much remains to be decided on a political
level that is critical to the achievement of agreements in the
military-security sphere.
<P>
Where possible and in the interest of rapid progress, one should
profit from the European experience in considering what CSBMs
might play a stabilizing role in the Middle East. In many cases,
approaches may need to be adapted to a particular set of conditions
that may be unique. In others, the approach may of necessity be
incremental -- doing as much as possible now and improving upon
it later. These are, of course, issues to be decided by participants
themselves.
<P>
In particular, two of the European measures could play a vital
role. The first is the idea of a communications network. There
is already considerable understanding on this point and little
more needs to be said here. The second, however, is a larger challenge.
It is the question of establishing something like the CSCE Conflict
Prevention Center (CPC) in Vienna.
<P>
The first thing participating states would need to decide is precisely
what role a CPC could and should play in the Middle East. In other
words, the basic concept and objectives of the center need to
be developed long before the center comes into being. Then, provisions
must be made to provide the center with the requisite authority
to perform the function and objectives set for it. This, of course,
includes fiscal support. Another issue to be resolved is whether
the CPC is a place or a function. In theory, a function could
be conducted in several different ways. But the center as a place
calls for centralization of function. To perform its overall mission
well, the center would need access to all available information,
data, intelligence,
<P>
and communications. Some sort of investigative power should also
be vested in a center.
<P>
In its early stages, it might well be that a Middle Eastern CPC
would require an active, perhaps even directive, role by the sponsors
of the Middle Eastern Peace Process. This &quot;outside-the-region&quot;
participation would promote a more comprehensive view of activities
in the region that are relevant to peace, stability, and security
while at the same time muting criticism of partisanship.
<H4><B>10. Finally, the Psychological Dimension</B></H4>

<P>
The Soviet military negotiator, a major general, and I regarded
each other with considerable mutual suspicion at the beginning
of the Stockholm CSBM negotiations. Each was convinced that whatever
the other might suggest would be harmful to our own cause. Because
I have been a negotiator in the Madrid CSCE follow-up meeting,
my Soviet counterpart had been well-briefed on what he might expect
from me. It was clear in the early part of the negotiation that
he didn't wish to conduct his business with me personally. At
least a year went by before there was any direct communication
on a bilateral basis.
<P>
After it became clear to both of us that both sides were prepared
to work toward a possible agreement the climate between us became
less chilly. We still stood on the opposite sides of many issues.
As noted earlier, a Soviet objective was to include naval operations
in the negotiation. My instructions were clear, independent naval
activities would not find a place in the final agreement. One
day we were invited to the Czechoslovakian embassy for lunch.
As was often the case, we were seated in close proximity to each
other. Suddenly, he looked up from his plate at me and said, ''you
know, if you had proposed the inclusion of independent naval activities,
we would have said no.'' To an extent that broke the ice. We then
begun to meet bilaterally, just the two of us.
<P>
All in all, we must have spent something over a hundred hours
discussing military operations in their relevance to each of our
positions. It was largely a conversation between two military
men and I was never sure he was convinced that I really had retired
and was now an ambassador. I mention this because of the unique
ability of military men to communicate with each other, irrespective
of nation or branch of service. I therefore strongly advocate
that military officers play a key role in negotiation of confidence-building
measures.
<P>
When the negotiation was finally over, the last meeting held,
and toasts appropriately drunk, my Soviet colleague approached
me. I had valued the meetings we had together. He had never lied
nor tried to deceive me. He, too, had found value in our relationship.
For he said something in the following lines: the agreement we
had worked on together is important, but it is perhaps even more
important to learn that it is possible for us (the Soviet Union)
to reach agreements with the Americans.
<P>
So, in spite of my early skepticism about the psychological aspect
of confidence-building, I was forced to admit that the relationships
which form as a result of the process do have a psychological
affect. It can best be expressed in terms of what the Germans
call <I>Feinbild</I> or image of an enemy. In the confidence-building
process the image of a potential adversary can change. While I
would still argue that security is the principal issue in confidence-building,
there is still a vital result when one's image of a potential
adversary takes on contours which more accurately reflect reality.
<P>
A swan is a beautiful bird. But it is really only good to look
at. A duck has virtues a swan does not possess; above all it is
a practical creature that serves man's practical needs. So it
is with confidence- and security- building measures. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
