</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2><B>AN OVERVIEW OF THE MIDDLE EAST PEACE PROCESS</B></H2>

<H2><B>Working Group on Arms Control and Regional Security</B>
</H2>

<P>
<B>Michael D. YAFFE, Ph.D</B>.
<P>
Foreign Affairs Officer, International Nuclear Affairs Division
<P>
Non-Proliferation and Regional Arms Control Bureau
<P>
United States Arms Control and Disarmament Agency
<P>
Washington, D.C.<HR>

<P>
The outcome of diplomatic negotiations is often determined as
much by the substantive aspect of the issues being discussed as
by the process and structures through which agreements are reached
or not reached. This phenomenon is a prevalent element of the
ongoing negotiations in the Middle East to obtain a just, durable
and comprehensive peace. As part of the Middle East Peace Process
(MEPP) begun in Madrid in October 1991, fifteen regional parties
(Algeria, Bahrain, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Kuwait, Mauritania,
Morocco, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Tunisia, United Arab Emirates,
Yemen and the Palestinians) have elected to participate in working
groups that comprise the multilateral track of the peace process.
These multilateral or regional talks, cosponsored by the United
States and Russia, have created a framework in which Israel could
join with Arab states in discussions on regional issues of mutual
concern. The talks complement and support -- but do not substitute
for -- negotiations on the separate bilateral tracks between Israel
and its immediate Arab neighbors of Jordan, Lebanon, Syria and
the Palestinians. While the bilateral tracks have attracted much
deserved public attention with the historic signing of the Declaration
of Principles between Israel and the Palestinians and a peace
treaty between Israel and Jordan, the multilaterals have been
the silent partner in the peace process. Highlighting the negotiating
process of the multilateral track provides insights into the pace
and types of decisions that may be reached in these talks.
<H4><B>1. Structure of the Multilateral Track</B></H4>

<P>
The multilaterals talks were founded on a functional approach
to international negotiation. Working groups were formed around
five issue areas which are or hold the potential of being sources
of conflict and cooperation in the region: water, economic development,
refugees, environment and security matters. The Arms Control and
Regional Security (ACRS) working group, the focus of this paper,
is the only such group devoted strictly to regional arms control
and security issues involving Israel and Arab states. Overseeing
the multilateral talks is a Steering Group comprised of the cosponsors,
Israel, Jordan, Egypt, the Palestinians, Saudi Arabia (representing
the states of the Gulf Cooperative Council), Tunisia (representing
the Maghreb), Japan, Canada, and the European Union. The Steering
Group guides and coordinates the working groups. Decisions by
the Steering Group and the five working groups are based on consensus,
a voting structure which has an inordinately strong influence
on negotiating dynamics. All groups, to date, have been meeting
in plenary semi-annually. The ACRS working group also holds a
wide assortment of intersessional activities such as workshops,
educational seminars, tours of arms control-related facilities
and paper preparation to stimulate discussion and negotiation
between its plenary sessions.
<P>
Over a score of extra-regional parties, representing countries
from around the world and organizations like the United Nations
and the European Union that have an interest in seeing a successful
conclusion to the talks, also participate in the multilaterals.
The role that each individual extra-regional party plays in the
process varies. Some simply offer suggestions at plenary sessions
on how the talks should proceed, some host events that may be
instrumental to negotiations, and some acting in the critical
role of mentors directing and promoting activities and discussions
on specific issues and topics in order to reach agreements on
particular confidence-building and arms control measures.
<H4><B>2. Stages of the Talks</B></H4>

<P>
Each working group has its own dynamic and pace of development.
In the ACRS, work on security issues has advanced through at least
four incremental stages. This is an evolving process. As such,
it is important to be mindful of the difficulty in generalizing
about the exact phase the negotiations have reached, especially
as some issues and relationships are more advanced than others
and that, at times, the talks may be exhibiting elements of all
four phases simultaneously.
<P>
In the past, Middle East states generally have sought to enhance
their security primarily through the national acquisition of military
arms and related resources while eschewing cooperative regional
arrangements and arms control agreements. Consequently, the first
phase of the ACRS working group was regarded as a period in which
the parties become familiar with the history and modalities of
arms control measures adopted in the Middle East and in other
regions. Another aspect of this phase is that it provides the
parties with opportunities to become familiar with one another
and with each others' security concerns. Parties have been submitting
papers on their long-term security goals and the principles by
which they approach the ACRS process (see, for example, Ambassador
Eytan Bentsur's contribution to this volume). This phase is also
notable for the historic visits by Israeli officials to Arab states
where they had never been welcomed before in order to attend ACRS
functions. Such visits can be attributable to the climate created
by the significant progress made in the bilateral tracks.
<P>
During the second stage, the parties seek to obtain consensus
on which confidence building and arms control measures should
be pursued initially and on concrete activities that can assist
the parties in understanding specific aspects involved in implementing
such measures, Toward this goal, a list of confidence-building
measures was compiled reflecting steps that have been adopted
throughout the world, and continue to collect suggestions for
activities from the working group parties as they arise in the
course of the ACRS process. Measures are identified as being ripe
for discussion for their potential applicability to the Middle
East while others
<P>
are left to be explored later. Essentially, measures are bifurcated
into two broad groups, conceptual and operational issues.
<P>
Items in the conceptual basket focus primarily on declaratory
statements on security and discussing abstract issues such as
military doctrine, elements involved in arms control negotiations
and security trends as well as concrete measures that are being
explored in order to ascertain their applicability to the region.
Egypt, for example, hosted a verification seminar which included
a visit to the Multilateral Force and Observers in the Sinai.
Austria hosted a seminar on declaratory measures and long-term
objectives for the region.
<P>
The operational basket contains measures which the parties agree
have greater potential applicability in the near term. In preparing
the parties to negotiate texts on prenotification of military
exercises and transmitting military data, Turkey held a workshop
on information exchange and the mechanics of reporting unusual
military activities. The Netherlands discussed with working group
participants the importance of telecommunications in managing
relations and introduced them to the Conference on Security and
Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) communications network. The Canadians
hosted a maritime measures workshop focusing on avoiding incident
at sea and cooperative search and rescue arrangements. A net result
of these events has been the development of a cadre of political
and military expert-level delegates who are versed in the details
of various arms control and confidence building measures.
<P>
The third stage encompasses further discussion of the various
national perspectives on security issues, actual negotiations
on texts of agreements and adoption of various measures. An important
objective during this stage has been to reach agreement on a statement
on principles and objectives of arms control and regional security.
On the operational side of the ledger, under the stewardship of
several extra-regional parties, Middle East participants have
engaged in negotiations to reach consensus on the texts to prevent
incidents at sea, to coordinate in search and rescue missions,
and on prenotification of certain military activities. The parties
have also
<P>
accepted to create a regional telecommunications network temporarily
using part of the CSCE network infrastructure in The Hague until
a permanent system can be located in the region. Negotiating these
texts is not regarded as indication that the parties am willing
to implement the agreements.
<P>
The fourth stage, and by no means the final stage, involves the
actual implementation of agreements and establishing venues in
the region for institutions that can support and contribute to
progress on arms control measures both before and after a full
peace is reached. Among the issues being discussed are permanent
sites for institutions such as regional security centers, an ACRS
data bank, and the communications network. As these institutions
are established and the various measures are implemented in the
region, the process will encompass elements of earlier phases
in which parties investigate new issues and areas where agreements
may be reached.
<H4><B>3. Challenges to the ACRS Negotiations</B></H4>

<P>
Each multilateral negotiation tends to take on an unique set of
challenges in trying to reach a consensus on issues by parties
that have diverse views, priorities, style and experience in diplomatic
interactions. The Arms Control and Regional Security working group,
with its own peculiar structure and processes, faces some special
challenges in advancing its work. The following list of challenges
is not meant to be comprehensive, but rather to illustrate some
specific problems and issues involved in the ACRS negotiating
process:
<P>
a) The peace process must strike a balance between talks in the
multilateral working groups and those of the bilateral track.
Negotiations in the bilateral track are critical to the success
of the multilaterals, especially as bilateral<B> </B>talks may
result in the participation in the<B> </B>ACRS by those currently
outside the working group. In this way, the two tracks can complement
each other in order to promote a comprehensive regional peace.
<P>
b) Extra-regional participates must be careful to remain neutral
during the negotiations, neither appearing to be imposing their
own solution on the parties or favoring a particular party. At
the same time, the co-sponsors and mentors need to keep pushing
the parties to achieve certain agreements while being mindful
of the constraints that may limit how far and fast the parties
are prepared to go.
<P>
c) As the regional parties develop an expertise in arms control
and confidence-building measures, it is important that they maintain
consistency in their delegations. Two problems that many states
experience in long-term negotiations are the constraints on resources
and the limited number of people available for multilateral negotiations,
especially when there are so many talks and related events occurring
simultaneously. Nevertheless, delegation consistency not only
helps to expedite negotiations by ensuring large and persistent
participation in the negotiations, but also avoids the need to
review previous understandings and agreements each time a new
delegation member becomes involved in the process.
<P>
d) With so many regional parties participating in the talks it
is important to ensure that all interests are being addressed
and that one set of security concerns such as those affecting
primarily the Levant region do not overshadow or minimize issues
of concern to the Maghreb and Gulf states.
<P>
e)<I> </I>The working group must balance the tempo and breadth
of its work in such a way as to maintain a broad range of confidence-building
and arms control measures under discussion to ensure that the
pace of negotiations on any one measure does not affect the advancement
of other measures.
<P>
f) Full representation by all important bureaucratic interests
in each regional delegation is critical to the successful outcome
of the negotiations. Diplomats must ensure that each security
related agreement they negotiate is supported by their military
and others with vested interests and military officials need to
ensure that the diplomats are aware of special issues that need
to be addressed in the negotiations.
<P>
g) As work in the peace process advances, the parties need to
ensure that their publics back home are sufficiently prepared
for their country's participation in specific security arrangements.
<H4><B>4. Track Two Events</B></H4>

<P>
Before leaving this discussion of the ACRS process, recognition
should be given to the important role that non-government organizations
have played in the peace process. Against the backdrop of the
formal negotiations are a host of non-official workshops and seminars,
known as &quot;Track Two&quot; events, sponsored by universities
and other interested institutions. These workshops have proven
valuable to the official diplomatic track inasmuch as they provide
informal settings for individuals from the region to explore in
off-the-record discussions new issues to be pursued and another
opportunity for old adversaries to comprehend the security concerns
of the other parties. Track Two workshops on threat perceptions,
confidence-building measures and arms control hold the potential
of generating ideas that can be carried back into the formal tracks.
At the same time, these meetings provide opportunities to expand
public support for the negotiations by allowing officials to interact
with non-government interested parties.
<H4><B>Conclusion</B></H4>

<P>
The ACRS working group has followed a simple set of guiding principles.
The process should be comprehensive, region-wide, incremental,
based on consensus decision-making and at no stage should it diminish
the security of any state or give any state a military advantage
over the others. It is equally important to bear in mind when
reviewing the work of the ACRS working group that it is only one
of five such groups comprising the multilateral track and that
it complements talks in the bilateral track. These parameters,
taken together with the unique political setting of the Middle
East, help to define the type of agreements that can be achieved
within the
<P>
ACRS and the working group's contribution to regional security
and stability.
<P>
Even though the MEPP is still relatively new, the process has
begun to bear fruit that is unrivaled by security negotiations
in other regions at a similar stage. We have experienced the rapid
erosion of hostility between Israel and its Arab neighbors. In
September 1993 Israel signed a declaration of principles with
the Palestinians. In October 1994, Jordan became the first Arab
state since Egypt in 1979 to sign a peace treaty with Israel.
The Arab League has agreed to relax its economic boycott of Israel.
Algeria, Morocco, Oman, Qatar and Tunisia agreed to establish
postal links with Israel. Also during late 1994, Tunisia and Morocco
agreed to open interest sections in Tel Aviv and Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin became the first Israeli head of government to visit
a GCC state, Oman; all signs that these states are preparing to
establish full diplomatic relations. These are all examples of
the commitment by the parties to the peace process and set the
stage for further advances in their common dialogue on arms control
and regional security. 
</BODY>

